thank you for the opportunity to have served our country during four of our nation's most critical and productive years
respectfully yours,
james h. webb jr
the dollar dropped in tokyo trading today and stock prices advanced for the ninth straight day
after opening at 129.27 yen, the dollar fell by midday to 128.65 and closed the day at 128.50, down 1.45 yen from monday`s close of 129.95
the dollar's fall was attributed to overnight setbacks in new york and london and strong selling pressure from foreign banks, dealers said
on the tokyo stock exchange, share prices closed higher at the end of tuesday's session, led by large-capital issues such as steels and heavy industrials
the nikkei stock average closed at 24,949.45 points, up 102.74 points, or 0.04 percent. volume in the first section was a moderately heavy 850 million shares, up from 830 million shares monday
there's nothing really big out there to push prices up or down, but it`s got to run out of steam sometime,'' said ron napier, vice president of salomon brothers, referring to the longest consecutive advance in stock prices since august
finance minister kiichi miyazawa told a news conference today that the higher prices on the stock exchange are the result of japan's sound economic fundamentals and optimism about a bright economic future
nine organizations, including the american academy of pediatrics and the national education association, are forming a coalition to lobby on behalf of children with aids
edward conner, a member of the pediatrics academy, noted in monday's announcement that about 80 percent of the known 839 cases of children with aids in the united states were born to mothers who are drug abusers themselves or sexual partners of drug abusers
if we could reach these prospective parents today, we could stop this expanding problem in nine months,'' he said at a press conference
rather than focus on a particular goal, representatives of the nine organizations said they would engage in a ``generic'' effort to make sure children are not forgotten as programs to combat aids are formulated and implemented
other members of the coalition: children's defense fund, american psychological association, national association of community health centers, child welfare league of america, american nurses association, national association of children's hospitals and related institutions and the western association of children's hospitals
state and local government workers received annual pay raises last year averaging 4.9 percent under collective bargaining contracts with public employee unions, according to the labor department
the pay increases were below the average 5.7 percent raises received by he same employees in 1986. but the workers still fared better last year than federal employees who got a 3 percent pay increase and private sector workers whose wages rose an average 3.3 percent, the department said monday
however, the bureau of labor statistics noted that union contracts in the public and private sectors differ significantly
state and local governments, for example, tend to have a higher proportion of professional and white-collar workers. union contracts in the private sector, on the other hand, often include lump-sum bonuses and cost-of-living adjustments excluded from the wage calculations and usually absent in the public sector
the figures showed that local government workers with wage increases averaging 5.3 percent outpaced state employees workers with an average 4.3 percent raise. fight</head>
the reagan administration's long and sometimes bumpy road to filling a vacant seat on the supreme court has came to an anti-climactic end as justice anthony m. kennedy spent his first day on the bench
four hours of subdued technical arguments in the hushed, crimson-draped courtroom monday were a sharp contrast to the noisy and partisan battles that preceded kennedy's feb. 3 confirmation by the senate
kennedy looked solemn as he entered the chamber, strode past the american flag, stood before the pale marble columns and took his seat at the end of the row of nine justices. that seat, on the far right as spectators face the court, is the traditional place for the high court's newest member
the former appellate judge from sacramento, calif., a man with a reputation for being deliberative and well prepared, didn't say a word until nearly an hour had elapsed. and then he asked only one question
kennedy's presence brought the court to full strength for the first time since justice lewis f. powell resigned in june
the producer of ``jeopardy'' has apologized to mayor joseph e. steineger jr. because a question on the television game show referred to the city as a suburb of kansas city, mo
but producer george vosburgh stopped short of conceding an error
we are taking kansas city, kansas, out of our definition of a suburb,'' said vosburgh, who sent a written apology to the mayor last week
we are not necessarily incorrect. ... we just will not refer to it that way in the future.''
the show intends to clear up the matter and other recent misunderstandings with an ``oops'' category in a future show
after hearing about the reference to his city on a december show, steineger wrote an indignant letter to the producer, saying kansas city, kan., was a city in its own right
steineger said he was satisfied, though still somewhat miffed
i guess when the mayor said they were wrong, they were wrong,'' he said. ``we certainly like to be recognized as our own city.''
slum dwellers gathered possessions from condemned homes and rescue workers searched mud and rubble for victims of four days of floods and mudslides in rio that have killed at least 75 people
civil defense spokewoman sonia hadid said monday that many poor people, who perch homes on the steep hillsides that jut up through this city of 5.6 million, were refusing to obey orders to abandon their shacks
they prefer to risk their lives than abandon their worldly goods,'' she said. officials warned that torrential rains that let up monday had loosened boulders and earth and said they expected more mudslides
get out while there's still time,'' mayor roberto saturnino braga told slum dwellers as civil defense officials condemned whole hillside communities
flash floods and mudslides have punished rio de janeiro state since feb. 2, killing at least 268 people and leaving more than 13,000 homeless
rains devastated the nearby mountain resort of petropolis during the first 10 days, briefly let up for carnival, then returned late friday to plague rio
the weather bureau said an antarctic cold front over rio dumped 5.1 inches of rain on saturday alone. normal rainfall for the month is 5.5 inches
roads turned into raging rivers that tossed cars and carried away shanties, rubbish and stones. the rains washed out city streets, power lines, knocked down large trees and filled homes with mud
in the wealthy santa teresa hillside district, a massive mudslide tumbled onto a three-story hospital wing, killing at least 11 elderly patients and staff. more victims were expected to be pulled from the thick mud
in the working-class abolicao district, firefighters continued their search for at least one more resident of a three-story building of six apartments built on a hillside that fell face forward late sunday
officials said 12 bodies were pulled from the concrete and twisted metal, while 16 dwellers were pulled out alive
three television networks broadcast appeals for donations of food, clothes, medicines and mattresses to aid the nearly 9,500 city residents rendered homeless by the inundation
the homeless were being housed in schools, churches and public buildings that have been converted into shelters
ms. hadid, the civil defense spokeswoman, said the death toll of 75 included only bodies that had reached the morgue
the final total certainly will be higher,'' she said
after months of preparation, pop star michael jackson was ``raring to go'' for tonight's first concert of his 13-city u.s. tour, his spokesman said
jackson spent monday night at kemper arena rehearsing and checking sound for the two kansas city shows, which are expected to draw about 33,000 people
jackson is confident about his tour, press manager lee solters said
he's a hard worker, a perfectionist,'' solters said. ``everybody is in tune with him. they all keep up with him and they all respect him for his professionalism.''
the 29-year-old jackson will perform here tonight and wednesday, before moving on to madison square garden in new york for concerts march 3-6
tickets for the shows here were virtually sold out, solters said, although some limited-view seats were still available. the kansas city star reported monday that some tickets were being sold for $200
the show requires 35 tons of equipment, which are carried in 11 48-foot-long trucks
jackson's 15-member troupe has seven musicians, four backup singers and four dancers. a 60-member crew works behind the scenes. about 70 local people have been hired as stagehands and security staff, said john friedmann, director of kemper arena
the show will include four video screens suspended from the ceiling, 72 speakers, nearly 3,000 lights and special effects
secretary of state joyce hazeltine says she doubts that today's weather will affect voter turnout, and she still expects about one-half the state's registered republicans and one-third of the democrats to vote in the presidential primary
the weather forecast calls for strong winds but no snow, she said
the secretary of state said the fact that vice president george bush withdrew from active competition in the south dakota primary will not affect republican voter turnout
how i see that. those who are for him are going to vote for him anyway. those who are angry with him for that are going to come out and vote for (bob) dole.'' supporters</head>
the chairman of rep. jack kemp's texas campaign is asking supporters of sen. bob dole and pat robertson to abandon their candidates and join the kemp campaign because of the refusal of dole and robertson to appear in a debate last week in dallas
bob holland, the kemp official, call the action by robertson and dole a snub of texas
by their failure to face george bush in one of his home states friday night, bob dole made clear that he has written off texas and pat robertson committed another serious blunder casting further doubts on his electability,'' holland said
the withdrawals left only kemp and bush to debate
we have had many disappointed former dole and robertson and for that matter (pete) du pont supporters calling us looking for a new home and we want them to know they are welcome to join us,'' holland said
du pont, former governor of delaware, withdrew last week as a candidate for the republican nomination
agriculture commissioner ward ``butch'' burnette said 32 calls from his department's phones to supporters of the presidential campaign of u.s. sen. albert gore jr. were made to discuss official business, not the democrat's race
burnette, gore's kentucky campaign chairman, and two of his aides involved in the campaign said the campaign may have come up, though
burnette said six calls to gore headquarters in arlington, va., were made to clarify news reports published locally jan. 19 about the tennessee senator's agriculture platform. the calls were made, however, jan. 12-14, according to the courier-journal
the newspaper reported in today's editions that more than 70 calls were made in december and january from state-government telephones to offices and supporters of gore
the total cost of the 73 calls was $58.97, not including tax
the day he was named gore's state chairman, burnette said, he issued a memo to employees telling them not to use state facilities on gore's behalf
a hand grenade slipped from the belt of a lebanese army officer and exploded today at a hospital in east beirut. police said the officer was killed and four visitors were injured
the grenade exploded in the morning in the visitors' lounge of the hayek hospital in the christian district of sin el-fil, a police spokesman said
first lt. issam rahmeh, who was visiting a patient, died instantly and four other visitors were injured, said the spokesman, who cannot be named in line with standing regulations
he said it had not been determined how the grenade slipped from rahmeh's belt. the army was investigating the incident
the american medical association, stressing that it opposes euthanasia, says first amendment rights should outweigh an order that it identify the author of a mercy-killing essay
citing the u.s. constitution and a state free-press law, the ama filed a motion monday in cook county circuit court to quash a subpoena from the state's attorney's office seeking the author's name
the essay, titled ``it's over, debbie,'' was written by a resident physician who described injecting a fatal dose of morphine into a 20-year-old woman dying of ovarian cancer. it was published in the journal of the american medical association's jan. 8 edition
jama's confidential sources are protected by the first amendment and by the illinois reporters privilege act,'' ama general counsel kirk johnson wrote in a statement accompanying the motion
as described in our motion, the debate and controversy which the publication has generated is exactly what the first amendment is all about
the ama supports the privilege asserted by dr. george lundberg,'' the journal's editor-in-chief, ``to protect jama's confidential sources, not withstanding that the ama opposes the practice of euthanasia and that ama believes the action described in the essay in unethical,'' johnson wrote
physicians and their organizations also have an ethical duty, however, embodied in the hippocratic oath, to teach education and inform their fellow physicians,'' he wrote. ``it is to fulfill this latter obligation that the ama publishes jama and gives it editorial independence.''
attorney newton minow, a former chairman of the federal communications commission who is helping johnson represent the ama, said he did not know whether the essay's author was aware of the controversy
lundberg has said he published the essay to spark debate over the issue of mercy killing
i expected a major reaction, but i didn't realize the extent to which the country was ready for an extraordinary response,'' lundberg said
we have clearly touched many raw nerves, and many people have been thinking about many of the diverse issues involved.''
he has said he believes the essay describes an actual event. but on monday, he said ``the account does have enough vagueness to welcome critical analysis as to whether it happened, or happened in this way.''
officials in the state's attorney's office have repeatedly declined to discuss the matter, as is routine during a continuing investigation
we're not confirming or denying that we're even looking into this,'' spokesman terry levin said monday
johnson said a subpoena was served a week ago today
retired marine corps brig. gen. charles banks, who was awarded the navy cross for heroism in the korean war, died of cancer. he was 73
banks, who died monday at st. francis memorial hospital, also served in world war ii. his combat service in that conflict included a tour with edson's raiders on guadalcanal
banks was awarded the navy cross for extreme bravery during the marine breakout from the chosin reservoir
banks, whose decorations also included the silver star, retired from the marines in 1959 and entered business. at the time of his death, he was vice president of the harper group, a san francisco-based freight-forwarding company
survivors include his wife, jane, of belvedere and their daughter, alexandra kennedy of soquel
the creators of a ``minicow'' produced near this northern town through cross-breeding and genetic engineering claim the smaller species can revolutionize cattle and milk production in the third world
the 27 animals grazing on a ranch at nearby tanleon are the product of 18 years and six generations of genetic manipulation. the smaller versions of the ox-like brazilian zebu or brahma species stand 3 feet and weigh 300 pounds
the experimenters began with a small pair of zebu that weighed more than a ton each and stood nearly 5 feet tall
each generation has become about eight inches shorter than the one before it,'' says angel castrillon, the local rancher who has conducted the minicow experiment since its start. ``we have created a genetic work that produces almost the same quantity of milk as a normal cow, occupies much less space and uses fewer resources,'' he told a visitor
people working on the project believe the mincows will enable many densely populated, land-poor countries to start or upgrade their cattle industries
ten minicows can graze on less than three acres of land, the area one normal cow generally requires. those 10 minicows produce 2,970 pounds of meat, about 330 pounds more than the one big cow would
horses and other animals have been reduced in size in other parts of the world, castrillon said. but, he said, ``what surprised us was that the minicows are producing three of four liters (about one gallon) of milk a day, compared to the six liters (about 1.5 gallons) that a normal cow produces.''
castrillon, whose ranch is in the fertile ``huasteca'' region of north central mexico, first proposed the idea to manuel berruecos, a geneticist at the national autonomous university of mexico, at a mexico city conference
the rancher said he suggested doing the opposite of what animal breeders traditionally do: instead of producing bigger and heavier specimens, why not make them smaller, on the model of the bonsai trees in japanese gardens?
unfortunately we have the theory and the prejudice that the bigger things are the better,'' berruecos said in an interview in mexico city. ``we want to make everything bigger, but the world isn't growing. our project may seem like science fiction, but we are close to a world that perhaps will have to adopt these (types of) measures.''
to achieve the smaller species, experimenters selected prospective breeding candidates with small heads and cross-bred to achieve smaller offspring
in the laboratory, berruecos works to weaken and eventually eliminate altogether large-growth genes in the herd's semen
berruecos, who holds a doctorate from the university of north carolina, claims that ``in terms of quality, our experience shows no difference in the milk or the meat.''
field specialists from west germany, japan and the united states are watching the experiments with interest. in fact, castrillon said one american offered $1 million to take over the research, an offer he said he rejected
castrillon's ranch is home to 15 adult minicows and a dozen offspring. another three are under care of the veterinary faculty at the national university
the minicows are gentle, but also very strong. they come close to you and strongly nudge your legs,'' said anabella castrillon, the rancher's wife
the researchers' next step?
we're planning to cross the tiny zebus with the jersey type, which is small and the best milk producer,'' castrillon said
he said he will continue cross-breeding until he produces the tiniest possible species with maximum productive efficiency
we're thinking that this species would be about 2 feet tall.''
religious broadcasters who lost financial support following last year's scandals and controversy face another potentially hard blow from the rev. jimmy swaggart's confession of sexual misconduct
my feeling is that there will be more damage, and the credibility of those of us in christian broadcasting will be hurt a little bit more,'' jerry rose, president of national religious broadcasters, said monday
this is not what we are about, and we have spent an inordinate amount of time dealing with these issues,'' said rose, who operates religious station wcfc-tv in chicago
swaggart, among the nation's most widely watched television preachers, stepped down from his pulpit sunday after confessing he had sinned against god and his family
officials with his church, the assemblies of god, said he had admitted to a long history of sexual problems and would be prohibited from preaching for a minimum of three months while he undergoes rehabilitation
mark demoss, a spokesman for the rev. jerry falwell, judged the damage to television ministries to be survivable
i look at the example of a gary hart moral failure _ that did not ruin the democratic party or other democratic candidates, but it did ruin gary hart,'' demoss said
it didn't work that way a year ago. some of the big ministries, including swaggart's, bled from the wounds inflicted by jim bakker's adultery and high living in the ptl ministry, and oral roberts' do-or-die appeal for $8 million
in the aftermath, no one sounded more cynical and disillusioned than swaggart. ``you can stay more holy a lot of times watching `miami vice' than watching so-called christian television,'' he said in one of his rousing sermons a year ago
a lot of people saw jimmy as a pacesetter for doing what needed to be done in the church, so in this case it is shocking,'' rose said
the rev. james robison, a tv evangelist who is seen on about 150 stations around the country, said the fear of criticism from swaggart and other preachers may have led bakker to hide his own problem, rather than address it
jim bakker told me himself, he said, `i wanted help, but i was so afraid of what would be said,''' robison said early today on abc's ``nightline.''
at cbn, whose operations include the christian broadcasting network and cbn university, spokesman benton miller declined to speculate on the impact from swaggart's problems
last year, however, he said contributions to cbn dropped 32.5 percent from april to october, and have remained flat. when cbn cut nearly 500 employees last summer, founder pat robertson blamed the controversies surrounding bakker and roberts
roberts, based in tulsa, okla., had said that god might ``call me home'' if he didn't raise $8 million by the end of march, the month of bakker's confession and resignation from ptl. cbn's fiscal year started april 1
we had to take the whole hit of that, plus the change in the talent mix for the 700 club, plus the drop in oil prices ... plus the recent october stock market plunge,'' miller said monday. ``all four of those factors hit us all at once.''
the change in the talent mix involved robertson's departure from the broadcast to seek the republican presidential nomination, and the resignation of co-host ben kinchlow. cbn cut 145 more employees in november, leaving a workforce of 1,174, though it has also managed to expand its television programming and launch a radio service, miller said
demoss said contributions to falwell's ministry had rebounded, but on monday, wpgh-tv in pittsburgh announced it was dropping falwell's program because he was $50,000 in arrears
oma bradner, who handles falwell's television accounts, said late monday a check was mailed on friday
swaggart had a larger audience _ 1,720,000 households per week last november _ than any other video evangelist, according to the arbitron rating service. the a.c. nielsen co. put swaggart's audience at 860,000 households, second to robert schuller's audience of 1,189,000 for the ``hour of power,'' but nielsen said swaggart was seen on the most stations, 286
arbitron reported that swaggart's audience had been 2,161,000 households last february, before the ptl and roberts controversies. between february and november, arbitron said, schuller's audience dropped from 1.7 million households to 1.4 million, roberts' from 1.15 million to 900,000, and falwell's ``old time gospel hour'' from 616,000 to 495,000
those figures are for broadcast audience only; most programs reach additional viewers on cable television
rose said swaggart's weekly broadcast would remain on his station at least until he sees what assemblies of god leaders decide to do
a fire slightly damaged the office of interior minister jose barrionuevo today, the ministry said. no injuries were reported
a ministry spokesman said the fire apparently was caused by an electrical short circuit in the second-floor office of the minister's personal secretary and spread to three adjacent offices
firefighters put out the fire in 15 minutes, the spokesman said
the interior ministry building is located near the central colombus square on the city's main north-south thoroughfare
barrionuevo was not in his office at the time the fire began, although members of his press office, security guards and cleaning help were
house prosecutors for gov. evan mecham's impeachment trial have submitted a list of 41 potential witnesses, including the governor and his brother, willard
but mecham's attorney murray miller wrote a letter monday saying he does not want to provide a witness list or to turn over any documentation yet
in a letter to chief justice frank gordon, who will preside over the trial that's scheduled to begin monday, miller said mecham believes that holding the senate trial before his criminal trial would violate his constitutional rights
he therefore does not wish to turn over any documentation or witnesses that he may call in his defense at this time,'' miller said
the governor's lawyer has indicated that he may go to court in an effort to get the senate trial delayed until after the criminal trial on charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan. that trial was delayed on monday until march 22
the house impeached mecham on feb. 5 and accused him of hiding the $350,000 loan, misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership, and trying to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat
the witness list submitted monday by the prosecution included many people who appeared before the house select committee on impeachment, including state department of public safety director ralph milstead and mecham campaign fundraiser bill long
also in the new list were people who did not testify before the house panel, including tempe developer barry wolfson, who provided the governor's $350,000 campaign loan. wolfson was subpoenaed on monday to provide documents and testify before the senate
mecham also was subpoenaed on monday to provide documents, according to house attorney paul eckstein
also on the list were donna carlson, the former mecham aide who was the subject of the alleged death threat, and former state official lee watkins, who is accused of making the threat
the list included an unidentified polygrapher who performed a lie-detector test on watkins to determine if he actually made the threat
all sides are scheduled to meet in a pretrial conference friday
smoke-free workplaces are becoming more common as employers listen to their workers' health concerns, according to a survey
the injurious effects of passive smoking have been well-publicized, and people object to working in that kind of environment,'' said victor lindquist, author of the 42nd annual northwestern university lindquist-endicott report
it seems to me that organizations are really trying to bend over to be accomodating to the non-smoker. there also were more firms spending money to help their employees stop smoking,'' lindquist said monday
his survey of 226 large and mid-sized companies found 70 percent restrict or are preparing to limit smoking in the workplace
on-the-job restrictions included permitting smoking only in designated areas, segregating workers into smoking and non-smoking areas, and equipping smokers with smokeless ashtrays
i was really surprised at the extent to which this had surfaced as a personnel issue,'' said lindquist said. ``today, smoking is pretty passe.''
lindquist said it was the first year he had asked companies about smoking policies in the survey, which began in 1945 and is used by thousands of corporations to establish starting salaries for college graduates and review personnel trends
the 1988 questionnaire drew responses from a cross-section of major industrial and geographic sectors. lindquist declined to identify any of the companies
in addition to the smoking regulations, the survey found:
_ 38 percent of companies conduct pre-employment testing for drug use and 8 percent said they would begin such testing in the next year
_ 2.2 percent plan to begin pre-employment testing for exposure to the aids virus by the end of the year
_ 1 percent said they will begin pre-employment genetic testing to screen for possible diseases
_ 66 percent said they provide guaranteed reinstatement to employees who take parental leave after having a child, and 20 percent provide payroll services that allow employees to have money deducted from paychecks that is designated to pay for day care and is tax-free
usg corp., a chicago-based maker of acoustical ceiling tile and thermal insulation, drew national headlines a year ago when it warned its 1,300 workers to quit smoking _ at work and at home _ or face possible firing
the survey found only one company that had completely banned on-the-job smoking, but several prohibited smoking in the private offices of corporate executives, said lindquist, northwestern's director of placement
although 70 percent restricted smoking or were planning to do so, just 34 percent said they discussed that policy with job applicants during interviews, he said
walker merryman, vice president of the tobacco institute, a washington-based lobbying group for the industry, said he couldn't comment on the survey's findings without details about the types, locations and identities of the companies surveyed
but he said the 70 percent finding ``is substantially higher than anything i've seen recently.''
for example, merryman said, he had seen a recent scientific, random-sample survey of businesses nationwide that found 36 percent with policies on smoking
the sex scandals surrounding two prominent assemblies of god ministers should not taint the more than 30,000 others in the church, of whom only a tiny number are ever disciplined, an official says
the evangelical church, which counts more than 16 million adherents worldwide and operates four colleges, is investigating the misconduct of its most popular television preacher, louisiana evangelist jimmy swaggart
on monday, a day after swaggart temporarily stepped down from his pulpit, church officials said he had admitted to a long history of sexual misconduct and would be prohibited from preaching for a minimum of three months while he undergoes rehabilitation
another prominent television evangelist, the ptl's jim bakker, lost his assemblies of god credentials last year amid charges of sexual misconduct. swaggart was said to have been active in uncovering that scandal and bakker accused him of plotting to take over ptl
those are the only two in our whole denomination that have that kind of recognition,'' church spokeswoman juleen turnage said monday. ``so people may feel that this is indicative of the assemblies of god denomination, and that is not true
we have over 30,000 credentialed ministers in the assemblies of god in the united states. at any given time, any given year, fewer than one-half of 1 percent are ever called into discipline.''
mrs. turnage said 12 areas of misconduct, ranging from doctrinal aberrations to moral failure, call for disciplinary action
swaggart's suspension and two-year rehabilitation program must be approved by the church's executive presbytery in springfield, according to the church's by-laws, she said
swaggart appeared before his congregation in baton rouge, la., on sunday to ask forgiveness from his family and church for an act he did not describe publicly. he said he would not return to his pulpit until the church investigation was completed
here is the text of a statement monday night by cecil janway, district superintendent of the assemblies of god, about the discipline recommended for evangelist jimmy swaggart:
we accept his confession of specific incidents of a moral failure. based on this detailed confession and the evidence we observed of true humility and repentance, we have offered him rehabilitation in accordance with the bylaws of the general council and louisiana district of the assemblies of god
brother swaggart has submitted to the terms of rehabilitation as follows:
1. brother swaggart will begin a two-year rehabilitation period effective immediately
2. brother swaggart will be required to refrain from preaching for a minimum of three months, except in fulfillment of present commitments involving foreign governments during that period
3. during the time of rehabilitation, brother swaggart will be relieved of his duties as co-pastor of family worship center, retaining the right to preach in the family worship center after the period described in paragraph 2
4. brother swaggart will receive counsel and supervision in weekly conferences with three members of the louisiana district presbytery during the period of rehabilitation
5. brother swaggart will submit quarterly written reports to the district superintendent and monthly written reports to his sectional presbyter
again, no doubt much speculation and rumor will find its way into the secular media. but, for the church, the body of christ, such speculation and rumor has no place
we urge brother swaggart and his associates to resist the request of those outside the church to respond to questions. brother swaggart has been in complete cooperation with the assemblies of god and has pledged to work within the structure of the church. superintendent says</head> with plaintiffs reax; picks up 10th graf pvs, `state attorney ...'</note>
the u.s. supreme court's rejection of a suit challenging what a tennessee fundamentalist group calls godless textbooks will enable schools to get on with teaching children, an education official says
we've been relieved of a lot of pressure, pressure that's been on our shoulders since 1983,'' robert cooper, hawkins county school superintendent, said monday
the lawsuit was filed that year by seven born-again christian families, who objected on religious grounds to the list of required reading textbooks for grades 1-8. the books included passages in ``the wizard of oz'' and ``cinderella,'' works by science fiction writer isaac asimov, hans christian andersen and anthropologist margaret mead
after a trial, u.s. district judge thomas hull ruled in 1986 that the families' religious freedom had been violated, awarded them $50,000 in damages and allowed their children to avoid the reading classes
but the 6th u.s. circuit court of appeals reversed that ruling and threw out the families' lawsuit
on monday, the high court dismissed the families' appeal of that decision
at this time we have no alternative other than to accept the supreme court ruling,'' said vicki frost, one of the plaintiffs
her husband, roger, said the high court's action left fundamentalists across the country persecuted
farley meade, another plaintiff, said: ``there are a lot of poor christian parents who can't send their children to religious schools. to me that's a sad day for religious freedom in america.''
the president of the organization that financed the lawsuit called the supreme court action ``the most coercive ruling in the history of religious liberty litigation.''
we are confident that this dreadful ruling will eventually be overturned,'' said beverly lahaye, president of concerned women of america, in a statement issued in washington, d.c
state attorney general w.j. michael cody praised the court action, saying, ``any alternative disposition would have been the cause of chaos in the school system.''
cooper said the protracted case did not particularly disturb the county's 6,800 public school students ``but as far as administrative personnel, school board members and even some teachers, it was very disruptive.'' he said making copies of records and testifying in court took time that could have been better used in teaching
the seven children involved in the lawsuit have long since transferred from to private schools, he said, adding that about 4,700 children in grades 1-8 were affected by the lawsuit
robert sharp, legal counsel for the state education department, said the case never interfered with the state's selection of approved textbooks or otherwise changed operation of the department
the one issue that could have caused turmoil was ... whether there would be other parents who would seek to `opt out' of reading programs in other schools,'' he said. ``none did.''
a u.s. military commander today charged north korea with destroying a civilian airliner to wreck the 1988 olympic games and accused communist officials of being ``criminals.''
rear admiral william t. pendley of the united nations command traded accusations and taunts with north korean military representatives over the destruction of the plane. the two sides also accused each other of fomenting tension and preparing for war
i want you to tell those who are responsible for killing 115 innocent civilians that their objective, to discourage the community of nations from coming to the seoul olympics, will not be met,'' pendley said
maj. gen. li tae ho, the chief north korean delegate, said the communist country had nothing to do with the attack. he charged that south korean military authorities destroyed the plane as part of a scheme to retain power and to discredit the north. ``you are stirring up confrontation and leading the situation on the peninsula to the brink of war,'' li warned
the united states, south korea and other nations have charged that north korea was behind the nov. 29 bombing of a korean air boeing 707 over the andaman sea with the loss of all 115 people on board. north korea has denied it had anything to do with the attack. the wreckage of the plane was never found
the charges were made at the first meeting of the military armistice commission since the loss of the plane. the panel polices the cease-fire that ended the korean war between north and south in 1953
the united nations command delegation presented a videotape of a televised confession made last month in seoul by kim hyon hui who said she was a north korean agent and that she destroyed the plane with a bomb as part of attempts to disrupt the olympic games that start in seoul in september
ms. kim rode on an early leg of the kal flight and she and a male companion took poison when they were detained in bahrain. the man later died
li and other north korean and chinese officials did not watch the tape and studiously stared at the ceiling or out of windows
pendley said the confession was damning evidence that the north could not refute. ``you thought you had committed the perfect crime, but, like all criminals, you made a mistake,'' he said
north korea has been demanding to co-host the olympic games. the international olympic committee and south korea have rejected the demand
the north korean delegation replied with a rambling accusation charging that the south korean government bombed the plane to frighten people into voting for the government in the dec. 16 elections
pendley rejected the north korean accusations and repeated a demand that those responsible for the attack be punished and north korea apologize for the incident. ``you should honestly admit this terrible act,'' he said
north korea called the military armistice commission meeting to demand the united states and south korea abandon plans for annual ``team spirit'' military exercises involving 200,000 men next month
it was the first military armistice commission meeting since october
the north korean delegates charged the exercises were preparations for an american nuclear attack and warned that the divided peninsula was being pushed toward war. ``you have nuclear war plans worked out,'' li charged
pendley dismissed the north korean accusations and said the exercises were lawful military activities intended to guarantee the safety of south korea. he said the united nations command had no intention of starting a war and posed no threat to north korea or peace in the region
team spirit exercises will continue as long as the threat of aggression exists,'' he said
the united states maintains 40,000 troops in south korea and heads the united nations command, which represents the 16 nations that fought under un auspices against north korea and china during the korean war
a man who fought city hall to keep his seven-tiered tree house in his back yard can continue to use the structure as long as he makes some safety improvements, city officials say
i feel just fine with all of this,'' mark tucker said after officials announced the outcome monday. ``my kids feel fine that they can play in their tree house.''
st. louis park officials had objected to the tree house last may, saying it was unsafe and exposed the city to possible lawsuits
the dispute was taken to hennepin county district court, where an agreement was reached during a hearing in minneapolis on feb. 5. judge daniel hart approved the compromise on feb. 8, ruling that tucker can continue to use the structure for his children and a few friends as long as the safety improvements are made
tucker, 38, gained national publicity during his fight over the tree house and for a pair of 10-day jail sentences he served in november 1987 and in january for housing code violations at minneapolis apartment buildings he owns
the city said the agreement states that only the five tucker children, who range from age 4 to 18, and up to four other people can use the tree house at any one time
tucker may not use the tree house as a business office anymore or hold any more open houses, such as one last year to solicit support in his fight with the city, the agreement said
the agreement requires tucker by june to provide the tree house ladder with safety cages and hand grips approved by a structural engineer. the structure must be inspected for safety every year and after unusually severe weather, such as winds in excess of 40 mph, heavy snowstorms and ice storms, the city said
gary kasparov leaned on the table, staring at the chess board. he scratched his head, studied some more and accepted a draw
eleven-year-old josh waitzkin smiled and shook the world champion's hand. this memory would last
well done,'' wrote kasparov as he autographed the boy's score sheet, which josh will frame
it was a heady day for all concerned monday as kasparov, the 24-year-old soviet hero, spent his first full day in the united states. and 59 even younger chess buffs got a chance to face the champ in a simultaneous exhibition in a bronx elementary school gymnasium
i was surprised at how long i stayed in _ 42 moves is a lot against the world champion,'' said benjamin shuldiner, a freckled 10-year-old who was checkmated two hours
kasparov, dapper in a gray-and-tan sweater, tan slacks and green scarf, arrived at the inner-city school smiling and joking, taking time to embrace curious students and pose for pictures
asked how he expected to do against the children _ a routine exhibition for any grandmaster _ he laughed
it is not a serious competition, it is a joke,'' he said in accented english. ``it's a special exhibition for children. ..
i will be happy if i am upset. if i am upset, they will be every happy, this is the main goal of the `simul,' to make people happy.''
his opponents managed two draws
when kasparov left, he resembled an american sports hero, working his way through a knot of admirers, signing autographs, posing for more pictures, shaking hands and ducking into a limousine
it's a great day for chess,'' said the champion. ``this is the beginning of the promotion of chess in the u.s.a.''
kasparov said such exhibitions to spark children's interest in the game are ``a very important tradition'' in chess
i think it is the duty of the world champion,'' he said. ``if we get a lot of boys and girls into chess, we can hope that in the nearest future we will find a new wave of talent.''
he'll spend five days in new york, playing two more exhibitions and meeting mayor edward koch on thursday
i have just seen the city from the window,'' he said. ``i'll try to find some time to see something amazing.''
he spent sunday evening at the manhattan chess club, where he played 24 games of speed chess, winning all but one, which he drew
he played blitz chess,'' said club president doug bellizzi. ``offhand, not serious games, with some very strong players. i saw two brilliant combinations. this is mozart, this is beethoven.''
or, as 14-year-old k.k. karanja said, ``it's like playing larry bird or michael jordan one-on-one.''
karanja, however, a former national elementary school champion, managed one of the two draws allowed by kasparov on monday. in most of the games, kasparov moved instantly, working his way around the large square of tables. at times _ against waitzkin, for instance _ he had to stop and think
i was pretty confident the whole way. i played a few inaccuracies,'' said waitzkin, a student at manhattan's exclusive dalton school
classes of students were led through the gym for a glimpse of kasparov
kasparov's opponents ranged in age from 7 to 15, and came from such disadvantaged neighborhoods as the south bronx, harlem, east new york and brownsville, as well as more affluent areas of manhattan
catherine w. ingold, the provost of gallaudet university in washington, d.c., has been named president of the american college in paris
the board of trustees chose ms. ingold on monday to replace daniel j. socolow, president for the past five years. she starts this summer
ms. ingold, 38, studied at the university of paris and received a doctorate in french from the university of virginia in 1979. she joined the staff of gallaudet university, a university for the deaf, in 1973, and became provost in 1986
the american college, founded in 1962, is a fully accredited four-year american university, with 1,000 students, half of them u.s. nationals
pierre salinger, the veteran abc news correspondent who is chairman of the american college board of trustees, said 125 candidates were considered during a six-month search
the ventura freeway's dubious claim to fame as the world's busiest piece of road is not only dubious _ it's false, say transportation officials. and some smog-choked motorists are unhappy about it
how did this happen? i appreciated its reputation even as i was caught in its snarls,'' said steve gediman, 26. ``it was worthwhile just sitting there because i was sort of participating in a global event.''
 the stretch of freeway, also known as route 101, through the san fernando valley may never have been the busiest, despite a listing that says so in the guinness book of world records, california department of transportation officials admitted monday
that's because counting monitors on two other freeway stretches were out of commission for nearly five years and human guesses calculating traffic flow there were much too low, said nick jones, an associate transportation engineer
aficionados of los angeles' fabled congestion should not despair, however. the busiest portion of freeway in the world has been determined to be the santa monica freeway not far away, jones said. coming in second is the san diego freeway
with the monitors fixed, new calculations show an average of 315,000 cars traveled on one stretch of the santa monica freeway every day during 1987, while 300,000 cars a day were logged on a portion of the san diego freeway, compared with only 277,000 on the ventura
any time you get over 250,000 cars per day, what's the difference?'' jones asked
ron sexton's reward for winning a school contest was nothing to snort at
sexton, a history teacher and wrestling coach at wilmington high school, came in first in a school project to raise money for children's hospital in columbus. his payoff _ he had to kiss a pig
he put his mouth where his money was in what was dubbed the ``squeal of fortune'' contest, laying a kiss on the snout of a sow during a pep rally last friday while the students and faculty of the high school watched
sexton won a contest in which students and teachers put money in gallon milk jugs as their way of choosing someone for the porcine pucker. there were 45 teachers up for votes, which cost 25 cents to cast, according to home economics teacher bonnie hansen
the contest raised $246.40. leader or higgins located, militia saying leader escaped southern lebanon, background on higgins abduction and videotape. adds byline. no pickup. ^by rodeina kenaan</note>
the nation's mainstream shiite moslem militia captured the three gunmen who kidnapped a u.s. marine officer in southern lebanon last week, security sources said today
the sources said the three gunmen are among dozens of suspects the amal militia rounded up while searching for lt. col. william r. higgins but that the man who masterminded the u.n observer's abduction remained at large
the gunmen, who were not identified, could not give their leader's whereabouts or say where higgins was being held, said the sources, who spoke on condition of not being further identified
reporters in southern lebanon last week reported that the amal militia had detained more than 40 suspects, but this was the first indication that the three gunmen were among those held
the same sources said today that at least two israeli soldiers were killed and several wounded when their armored patrol was ambushed by arab guerrillas in the southern lebanese village of braachit at sundown monday
it was not clear whether the ambush and kidnapping were related
higgins, 43, of danville, ky., was kidnapped south of the ancient port of tyre on wednesday. the security sources said the three gunmen were captured in a dragnet in the two days following the abduction
among the detainees are the three gunmen who seized col. higgins and forced him into the first getaway car,'' one source said
another three suspects who were being held monitored higgins' his movements before the abduction, the same source said
the source provided the information when asked for confirmation of an nbc news report that the three kidnappers had been captured
the gunmen were being held by amal in tyre and had been interrogated, but they were unable to provide useful information because their leader had kept them in the dark, the source said
the security source played down the significance of the gunmen's detention, saying the unidentified person who masterminded the kidnapping already had slipped out of south lebanon
the operation was a masterpiece from a professional standpoint,'' the source said. ``the mastermind used five identical brown volvo cars plus two additional getaway cars, a white peugeot and a red mercedes, in the abduction. the squad in each car did not know who was in the other car.''
the organization of the oppressed on earth, a pro-iranian shiite moslem group, released a videotape monday in which higgins recited its demands for his release, including an israeli pullout from a border zone in south lebanon
the organization charged that higgins was a cia spy. u.s. and u.n. officials denied the claim
higgins heads a 76-man u.n. observer group drawn from 16 nations that monitors border violations of a 1949 armistice signed by lebanon and israel
the group was attached to the 5,800-strong united nations interim force in lebanon in 1978, when the nine-nation force was deployed to keep peace on the lebanon-israel border
timur goksel, the force spokesman, said the search continued for higgins today in the tyre region, 50 miles south of beirut
goksel said 20 officers of higgins' observer group have been withdrawn to u.n. posts along the israeli border
the kidnapping increased friction between shiite forces vying for dominance in southern lebanon
it pitted the moderate amal, which is backed by syria and is trying to rescue higgins, against the extremist hezbollah, or party of god, which is loyal to iran and has declared support for the kidnappers, calling higgins a ``filthy american.'' hezbollah is believed to be an umbrella for groups holding most of the 25 foreigners missing in lebanon
amal's spokesmen say a total of 42 fundamentalists have been rounded up in the tyre region since higgins' abduction. hezbollah claims more than 150 fundamentalists were arrested by the amal militia
higgins is the ninth american missing after being kidnapped in lebanon since march 1985. the other foreign hostages are four frenchmen, three britons, two west germans, a swede, a norwegian, an italian, an irishman, an indian and two unidentified men
the longest-held hostage is terry a. anderson, chief middle east correspondent of the associated press, who was kidnapped march 16, 1985
