an unemployed handyman visiting his old neighborhood was chased by a furious, crack-crazed mob and fatally shot after he was accused of being an undercover narcotics agent, police said
daniel t. foster, 30, was shot as he fled from the jeering crowd, according to a published report monday
these people were so afraid that he was there to take their dope away that they killed him on the spot,'' police inspector earl sanders told the san francisco examiner
they killed him because he was a stranger. it wasn't his neighborhood anymore,'' sanders said
foster once lived in the hunters point district but left the city in 1978 to move to virginia, authorities said. he returned to san francisco only a few weeks before his death
just after midnight jan. 22, foster got off a bus in his old neighborhood, where he was going to visit his sister, and found himself in the crowd of about 20 men and women. some of them, police said, were high on crack cocaine, a potent and dangerous form of the drug
the same crowd had just fought police and forced officers to retreat under a barrage of rocks and bottles, investigators said
they were full of crack, and at least one of them had a gun,'' said sanders' partner, inspector napoleon hendrix. ``foster stepped right into it.''
when foster began walking toward his sister's apartment, people in the crowd ``asked him if he was a cop,'' said sanders
he told them `no' and kept walking. then they asked him if he was from sunnydale (the turf of a rival gang), but when he said `no,' someone in the crowd said he was lying. then, they began to chase him,'' he said
foster ran down the block and had nearly reached the corner when someone in the crowd fired a pistol at least four times, police said. foster was hit once in the back and was pronounced dead at san francisco general hospital
his killer has not been found, authorities said
the home he came back to was not the same one he left,'' sanders said. ``crack cocaine had claimed his friends. as near as we can tell, he never touched the stuff, but in the end, it got him, too.'' 1955.'' to add background on commemoration. pickup 3rd graf pvs, ``austrian television...</note>
the government's plan to have president kurt waldheim address a ceremony marking the 50th anniversary of austria's annexation by nazi germany is becoming a major point of dispute
german troops marched into the country nearly 50 years ago, officially linking this alpine nation with adolf hitler's third reich. austria did not become independent again until 1955
austrians are marking the annexation _ called the anschluss in german _ as a time of reflection on a troubled period when throngs cheered hitler, jews were harassed and resistance fighters executed
austrian television and radio, along with many of the country's newspapers, are giving much attention to the march 11 commemoration. the issue is especially sensitive because of the widely held opinion in austria that the country was a ``victim'' of the third reich
now, with waldheim under fire for his role as a first lieutenant in the german army in the balkans during world war ii, it is increasingly uncertain what the bickering coalition government will do on the march 11 anniversary
many austrian socialists have made it clear they are against the ceremony during which the 69-year-old waldheim is scheduled to deliver a speech
i have misgivings about this event,'' fred sinowatz, the socialist party chief and former chancellor, told reporters at a news conference monday after a meeting of the party's leadership suggested that waldheim should step down
the socialists, senior partner in the government, adopted a resolution saying a report on waldheim's wartime record released earlier this month has ``badly shaken the president's moral authority at home and abroad.''
it has become obvious that ... waldheim ... cannot realize the most important aims he has set for himself, that is to promote domestic peace in austria and to increase austria's prestige in the world,'' the resolution said
the leadership at the meeting, which included chancellor franz vranitzky, stopped short of asking for waldheim's resignation
the report on waldheim's wartime record presented no evidence that would clearly back allegations that he committed wartime atrocities, but it left open the question of whether he was guilty of any crime
the report, written by an international panel of historians, said he was ``in close proximity'' to some nazi atrocities in the balkans, knew they were going on and made no attempt ot prevent them
it also said waldheim concealed his wartime past and tried to make it seem harmless once he could no longer hide it
waldheim has denied any wrongdoing
instead of a commemoration ceremony, sinowatz called for reflection of ``what happened on march 11, 1938, and what must be done so that such a thing never happens again.''
but deputy chancellor alois mock, a leader of the conservative people's party, the junior member in the coalition government, rejected the idea of scrapping the ceremony and the waldheim speech in vienna's hofburg palace
that's a suggestion that will never be accepted by the people's party,'' said mock, waldheim's most vigilant public defender, at a separate news conference monday where he spoke on behalf of the party
fritz koenig, another people's party leader, urged a suspension of the political debate until after the nation commemorates the anniversary
i think that after the ceremonies on march 11, there must be a discussion on how to achieve greater cooperation ... among the federal president, the government and the parliament,'' koenig said on behalf of the party
newspapers are giving the dispute prominent play:
with increasing frequency, there are suggestions that the government should simply call off the planned commemoration ceremonies for march 11,'' the conservative die presse said in its lead story monday
a day earlier, economics minister robert graf, a people's party member, became the latest of several politicians to make such a suggestion
he told a roundtable tv discussion that he had made the suggestion ``out of concern about further polarization.''
on account of waldheim, the 1938 commemorations are on shaky ground,'' the socialist az tabloid of vienna said in a front-page headling on monday
the socialists and the people's party made plans for the hofburg ceremony before the historians' report on waldheim's wartime past was issued
waldheim was the conservative candidate in the presidential election. he became president with 53.6 percent of the votes in a june 8, 1986 runoff. his term is scheduled to end in 1992
in austria the president is head of state, a largerly ceremonial position. vranitzky runs the government
he tried and tried and tried through prayer and fasting and everything he could do to lick it and it beat him.'' _ the rev. glen cole, describing what he said was tv evangelist jimmy swaggart's account of his struggle against a sexual obsession
