cholera has infected 51 people in northeastern thailand and killed a 7-year-old girl, a health official said today
dr. chin yuwachit, public health chief of udon thai province, said the disease has been brought under control since cases were first reported in several districts on feb. 8. eleven victims remain hospitalized, he said
cholera is prevalent in areas in asia where public sanitation is poor. the acute infectious disease is caused by a bacteria found in fecal-contaminated food and water. its main symptom is severe diarrhea. immediate comment on report.</note>
guerrillas using rocket-propelled grenades ambushed an israeli armored patrol in south lebanon, killing two soldiers and wounding several others, security sources said today
the sources, speaking on condition they not be identified further, said the patrol of one tank and an armored personnel carrier was ambushed near the village of braachit at sundown monday
both vehicles were raked with rocket-propelled grenades that set off a chain of ammunition explosions in the tank,'' said one source. ``no one could have escaped alive from the burning tank.''
the source said there were several other serious casualties in addition to the two fatalities in the ambush, but no specific figures were available
the source said the guerrillas were either shiite moslem fundamentalists or pro-syrian leftists. both groups operate in that area. the source said there was not yet enough information available to be more specific
the israeli army had no immediate comment on the reported attack
braachit is five miles west of israel's border in an area where an israeli ``security zone'' overlaps with the area of operations of the u.n. interim force in lebanon, known as unifil
the scene is about seven miles east of the area where unifil troops and shiite moslem amal militiamen have been searching for u.s. marine lt. col. william r. higgins. higgins, 43, of danville, ky., was kidnapped south of the port of tyre last wednesday. talks. trims thereafter to tighten. no pickup. ^by m.h. ahn</note>
kim young-sam and rival opposition leader kim dae-jung met today to discuss merging their two parties in time for the parliamentary elections, but they only agreed to discuss the issue again
the surprise, two-hour private meeting was proposed by kim young-sam after he emerged today from two weeks of near seclusion and told reporters a merger would ensure an opposition victory in the balloting expected be held in april
kim dae-jung, president of the party for peace and democracy, immediately agreed to the meeting, which was held at a seoul hotel
we will do our best to make the opposition merger successful at any cost,'' kim young-sam said afterward. kim dae-jung said he was not as optimistic. no specific date was set for another meeting
repeated efforts to reunite the two parties have failed and several rounds of talks in recent weeks have not produced any progress. neither party indicated today that the situation had changed
on feb. 8, kim young-sam resigned as president of the reunification democratic party, purportedly to help reunite the opposition before the national assembly elections
the meeting was the two kims' first since oct. 29, when they split in disagreement over which of them should run as the opposition candidate in the dec. 16 presidential elections. each insisted on running, giving government party candidate roh tae-woo victory despite roh's failure to win a plurality
after the defeat, the two kims came under strong pressure to retire from politics. many people accused them of putting personal ambition ahead of their avowed campaign goals of ending military rule
when he quit as president of his party, kim young-sam said he had expected the rival opposition groups could agree on a merger
kim young-sam today said he believed that ``the merger of the opposition bloc is the only way to crush the ruling democratic justice party's plot to perpetuate its rule and revive democracy in this country. so, it must be achieved with the people's power.''
he said the new cabinet formed by roh, who is to take office thursday, is merely an extension of that of outgoing president chun doo-hwan. the new cabinet includes several key holdovers from chun's administration
kim young-sam said he had a ``great deal of doubt about roh's implementing democratic reforms.'' roh, a former general like chun, has pledged to an end to the long tradition of authoritarianism in south korea
the governing and opposition parties, which have been squabbling over the number of lawmakers to be elected from each district, have failed to rewrite the election law and to set an exact date for the national assembly election
a former police officer convicted of torturing a 17-year-old boy with a 50,000-volt stun gun was sentenced to two years in prison by a judge who called his action ``a gross betrayal of public trust.''
former huntington park police officer william lustig jr., 32, was convicted in december of one count of felony assault under color of authority because of the methods used during questioning of jaime ramirez. another former officer, robert rodriguez, 27, was found guilty of aiding and abetting in the crime
superior court judge michael berg on monday sentenced lustig to two years in state prison and rodriguez to six months in county jail as a condition of three years' probation
in our society, a suspect in police custody has the right to be free from torture,'' berg said. ``these acts constituted a gross betrayal of the public trust.''
it's an embarrassment to everyone in the community, this type of behavior,'' said deputy district attorney james koller
ramirez, who attended the hearing with his parents, said of the sentencing: ``i think it's fair. it's the law.'' he has filed a $10 million federal lawsuit claiming his civil rights were violated during the nov. 30, 1986, incident
in december, jurors convicted the two former officers of using a 50,000-volt electric stun gun similar to a cattle prod to torture ramirez, who had been arrested for questioning about stereo components he was carrying as he walked along a street in huntington park, a los angeles suburb
ramirez testified during the trial that lustig used the stun gun to burn his thighs through his clothing several times during interrogation
lustig's attorney, richard levine, said his client's actions ``were not criminally motivated'' and he has endured enough punishment through the public humiliation he has had to withstand
lustig had a ``misplaced belief that the ends justify the means in a criminal investigation,'' levine said.the attorney said he did not know whether he would file an appeal
rodriguez's lawyer, william hadden, said he would appeal, and the judge agreed to stay rodriguez's sentence pending the outcome, setting bail at $3,000. ^by tom sharp</byline>
conspiracy charges against a woman whose boyfriend parachuted to his death with 77 pounds of cocaine strapped to his body were dropped at the request of the prosecution
the motion to dismiss the charges against rebecca sharp, 32, of lexington, ky., was filed friday by assistant u.s. attorney james r. dedrick and approved without comment monday by u.s. district judge james h. jarvis
dedrick declined to meet with a reporter or return telephone calls monday. his motion to dismiss the charges came a week after he lost a battle to use against ms. sharp statements she made to a government undercover agent
the trial of ms. sharp, a paralegal, on charges of conspiring with former lexington narcotics officer andrew thornton ii to import cocaine and to distribute the drug had been set to begin march 1
dedrick's motion asked that the charges be dismissed without prejudice, which allows him to seek another indictment
rebecca was very happy over that, as you might imagine,'' her attorney, w. thomas dillard iii, said of the dismissal of charges. ``hopefully, that will be the end of it.''
dedrick's motion did not specify why he wanted the charges dismissed, and dillard said he would not care to speculate, but it seemed likely that the ruling disallowing ms. sharp's statements was a direct cause
those statements were suppressed, meaning they could not be used as evidence against her, on feb. 12 by u.s. magistrate robert p. murrian
murrian ruled the statements ``were made in a situation so inherently coercive that they must be considered as involuntary and compelled'' because the undercover agent posed as a representative of violent colombian drug dealers who wanted either their cocaine or their $12 million
thornton's body was found on a knoxville driveway the morning of sept. 11, 1985. he carried bags with 77 pounds of cocaine in them, and federal authorities have linked him to some 200 pounds of the drug found in duffel bags scattered across northern georgia
a few days after thornton's death, kieran kobell, a special agent with the federal drug enforcement agency, visited ms. sharp in lexington
kobell, using an alias, and a government informant now listed as a fugitive took ms. sharp on a car ride during which, kobell said, she revealed an intimate knowledge of the cocaine-smuggling operation and promised the deal would go through even if she had to kill somebody
during testimony in the suppression hearing, kobell said he did not force ms. sharp to say anything during the car ride. however, murrian also noted that kobell threatened both ms. sharp and her attorney in kentucky, fred partin, in a telephone call to the lawyer the next day, according to partin's testimony at the suppression hearing
nine police officers taken hostage during a violent clash with separatist rebels were freed today, and members of the dominant conservative party demanded that the separatist faction be outlawed on this french-ruled island
about 100 protesters battled french gendarmes at a hospital construction site on the east coast city of poindimie, holding nine officers for about 13 hours before releasing them. officials said 17 officers were injured during the fracas
authorities who spoke on condition of anonymity said all the protesters involved escaped arrest
the gendarmerie, a police force under the french military, said in a statement that at least 20 people were injured by sticks or stones in the battle and four police cars set on fire
the rally for caledonia in the republic, a local party with close links to french premier jacques chirac's rally for the republic party, adopted a resolution today calling on overseas territories minister bernard pons to dissolve the separatist kanak socialist national liberation front
dissolution would make the party illegal. the resolution also called for party leaders responsible for the clash to be expelled from the island
yewene yewene, a separatist leader, said the resolution showed ``a logic of intolerance, a policy of contempt and a desire to humiliate the kanak people.''
yewene said the protesters did not object to the building of a hospital, but not at the site chosen, which he said was vital to the local tieti tribe
the kanak group supports independence for new caledonia, a territory of 145,000 people about 1,100 miles east of australia
in a referendum last september, a majority voted against independence. the kanak front boycotted the election, saying immigrants who arrived in new caledonia in the past three years should not have been eligible to vote
kanaks make up 42.6 percent of the population and europeans 37.1 percent. other nationalities make up the rest
regional elections, which the separatists say they will boycott, are scheduled for march. helms, made inquiry</note>
sen. jesse helms is asking the cia to investigate charges that the agency provided personal data to panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega about helms and sen. edward m. kennedy
in a letter to cia director william webster, helms said he had received reports that the cia had provided similar information on other senators to officials in other foreign countries
the north carolina republican said maintenance of files on members of congress would be ``illegal and improper.'' the transfer of such information to another government would ``call into question the integrity'' of u.s. intelligence institutions, helms wrote
the letter, a copy of which was made available to the associated press on monday, was sent to webster following testimony by jose blandon, a former noriega associate turned critic of panama's defense chief
blandon, testifying before a senate subcommittee on feb. 9, said the cia passed to noriega data about helms, kennedy, d-mass., and two of their aides. the senators have been among noriega's strongest critics on capitol hill, citing allegations of noriega's involvement in drug trafficking
at the time of blandon's testimony, the cia said it ``categorically denies'' his allegations
a cia spokeswoman, sharon foster, had no comment monday on helms' letter except to say that communications from members of congress are confidential but are taken seriously and responded to
blandon's testimony reinforced the notion that the cia had maintained close ties with noriega despite strong evidence dating back several years that he was involved in drug trafficking activities
two federal grand juries have indicted noriega on drug related charges
kennedy has said it was ``unconscionable that the cia knew about noriega's drug trafficking activities and continued to work with him for such a long time, but it is even worse to think that the cia would provide information about noriega's leading american critics to the general himself.''
blandon spent monday at u.s. district court with prosecutors investigating the iran-contra affair. although no details were provided, blandon presumably was questioned about his testimony that noriega agreed to provide training for nicaraguan contras after receiving a request from former white house aide lt. col. oliver l. north in 1985
helms, in a separate letter to fbi director william sessions, asked if the agency had ever passed on data about members of congress or their staffs to the cia and whether it had engaged in wiretaps or surveillance on him or members of his staff
in his letter to the cia's webster, helms asked whether the cia had maintained information on members of congress or their staffs and whether such information was ever passed on to any official of a foreign government, specifically the panamanian defense forces
helms indicated he was skeptical about the cia's denial, contending that it made an inquiry afterward to cia field offices and to the heads of u.s. agencies involved in national security issues as to whether the denial was accurate
ms. foster of the cia said she was unable to comment on that allegation
helms asked webster not to rely on cia files because the information alleged to have been passed on may have gone through a ``back channel'' without files being maintained
it is imperative that an internal investigation be conducted and all employees in contact with panamanian government or military officials be questioned,'' helms wrote. details from news conference in brussels. picks up 5th graf, `the garrisoning ...' subs grafs 11-13 pvs, bgng, `also today .. ., with 6 grafs to update with details of travel plans, comments on star wars. picks up 14th graf, `on human ...' edits to tighten.</note>
secretary of state george p. shultz left moscow today without a firm timetable for a soviet pullout from afghanistan, but u.s. intelligence sources said the red army is taking initial steps to leave
soviet troops are retreating to defensive positions and dependents are being withdrawn, a solid sign the soldiers will not be far behind, a senior u.s. official said
in addition, soldiers in the 115,000-man soviet force are not being replaced when they complete their tours of duty, said the official, who briefed reporters on shultz's flight to brussels on condition of anonymity
shultz said monday at the end of two days of talks in moscow that he did not have ``the slightest doubt'' the red army would depart. and after briefing nato officials in brussels today, he reaffirmed his expectation the soviets would quit afghanistan
but he evidently did not get a specific timetable from soviet communist party general secretary mikhail s. gorbachev or soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze
the garrisoning of soviet troops and departure of dependents is ``solid evidence'' the eight-year military intervention in afghanistan will soon end, the u.s. official said
on feb. 8, gorbachev offered to begin the pullout may 15 if pakistan and afghanistan reach a settlement by march 15 in negotiations due to resume in geneva next week. he said the withdrawal could be achieved within 10 months
the soviets have, however, accused pakistan of obstructing a settlement by insisting an interim coalition government be created in kabul to prevent the protracted civil strife islamabad says would otherwise ensue
shultz has said such a government could facilitate the troop withdrawal and return of about 3 million refugees from pakistan. but another senior u.s. official said washington does not endorse pakistan's position. referring to the anticipated withdrawal, the official told reporters: ``we wouldn't want to miss the bus. we've been trying to get the soviets out for years.''
gorbachev has said moscow would not make the composition of the government it leaves behind a condition of withdrawal
shultz stopped at nato headquarters in brussels today to brief the western allies, who were especially interested in the steps taken on arms control
from brusssels, shultz was flying back to washington for a 26-hour respite before heading for the middle east try to push arabs and israelis into negotiations
i don't think many people give me much chance,'' shultz said with a smile. but, he added, ``even if the chances are small, it's worthwhile trying.''
also today, shevardnadze left moscow for prague, czechoslovakia, to brief warsaw pact foreign ministers, the soviet news agency tass said
on monday, u.s. and soviet negotiators were directed to prepare within a month three draft agreements for a treaty to reduce long-range, or strategic, nuclear weapons by 30 percent to 50 percent. such missiles have a range of more than 3,400 miles
the drafts will deal with verifying compliance with the cutbacks, disposing the weapons, and exchange of information. they are to be ready for the next shultz-shevardnadze meeting, in washington on march 22-23
shultz told reporters in brussels that the two sides were still far apart on the u.s. strategic defense initiative. ``i think we moved it a little bit in moscow, maybe imperceptibly,'' he said of the disagreement over the u.s. program to develop a space-based defense against ballistic missiles
on human rights, shultz persuaded the soviets to drop for the rest of the year, at least, a requirement that jews who want to emigrate have a close relative living abroad
a senior u.s. official, who demanded anonymity, said about 90 percent of jews who have applied for exit visas do not have close relatives in israel
in the past several months, the official said, the soviets for the first time provided the united states with figures on applications waiting to be processed. on feb. 1, he said, there were 1,042 on file
soviets who have performed work considered by the government to be of vital national importance or that involved classified information are routinely denied exit visas
shultz told a news conference in moscow on monday that he gave a ``good mark'' to the two-day talks with shevardnadze, that they had moved the two sides closer to a strategic arms agreement and a spring summit in moscow
no specific date for a fourth summit between president reagan and gorbachev was agreed to, but shevardnadze told reporters monday that both sides want the summit in late may or early june
defense minister dmitri t. yazov said monday the soviets will begin withdrawing shorter-range ss-12 missiles from east germany and czechoslovakia late this month as a ``display of good will.''
the missiles must be eliminated under the intermediate-range arms pact signed in december. such missiles have a range of about 300 to 3,000 miles
a dutch tourist who was believed to have died in a hotel fire that killed five other people has been found alive, the official bulgarian news agency said today
the news agency bta said 37 people from britain, the soviet union, west germany, the netherlands, greece and denmark were injured in the blaze in the ski resort of borovets, 22 miles southeast of sofia
on monday, bta reported six people were killed in the fire, but today the agency said one man, from the netherlands, ``has since been discovered in good condition.'' it did not elaborate
according to bta and the sas insurance organization in the dutch city of arnhem, the dead tourists included two dutch women, identified only as ms. ever van den berg and mrs. stekelenburg. two other victims have not been identified and the fifth was identified as a bulgarian tourist, roumen roussev
of the 37 injured, bta said 17 were british, four soviet, five west german, seven greek, two danish and two dutch
bta said preliminary reports suggest the fire started on the ground floor and then quickly spread to the first and second floors of the hotel, which was made of wood
nineteen people were undergoing treatment at the pirogov emergency aid institute in sofia, bta repoted, adding two of them were in ``severe'' condition
the other injured tourists are at another hospital in the bulgarian capital and in a hospital in the town of samokov, the agency said
the cost of living the high life in new york rose last year at more than twice the rate of the consumer price index, with beluga caviar showing the most increase, according to a champagne producer's survey
whereas the cpi rose 4.4 percent last year, the life of luxury in the nation's most expensive big city went up 9 percent, according to the ``moet index.''
the survey has been compiled since 1983 by moet and chandon champagne
largest increases included: 14.7 percent for 30 grams of beluga caviar, up from $29 in 1986 to $33.25 last year; 11.7 percent for a wash, cut and blow dry at a top hair salon, from $60 to $67; and 10 percent for a day's maid service, from $80 to $88
luxuries with lower price hikes included: 3 percent for a round trip new york-paris flight on the concorde, up from $4,296 to $4,424; 4.8 percent for a full-length mink coat, from $15,750 to $16,500; and 5.3 percent for a limousine rental, from $38 an hour to $40 an hour
it was the fourth consecutive year the moet index exceeded the cpi. in 1986, the index rose 6.1 percent, while the cpi rose only 1.9 percent
cbs plans to launch a late-night talk show with ``wheel of fortune'' host pat sajak next season that would compete with nbc's ``the tonight show starring johnny carson.''
meanwhile in new york, nbc announced monday it is launching ``later with bob costas'' in august, a half-hour talk show that will follow ``late night with david letterman.''
the sajak show means cancellation of the network's late-night lineup of action shows and music, said a source at cbs. the shows are expected to remain on the air until at least september, said the source, who is close to the productions and spoke on condition of anonymity
they include the original series ``adderly,'' ``night heat,'' ``diamonds'' and ``top of the pops'' and reruns of ``hunter.''
at least 20 percent of the cbs affiliates are not carrying the late-night shows,'' the source said. ``cbs is turning to sajak in hopes of finding a format all its affiliates will stay with.''
sajak is host of ``wheel of fortune,'' the most successful syndicated show ever
cbs entertainment president kim lemasters said recently he wanted the network to increase its late-night visibility with a talk show and confirmed that the network was talking with sajak. sajak also discussed the possibility of a cbs talk show recently when he was a guest on nbc's ``late night.''
the costas show would be a half-hour addition to nbc's schedule, following ``late night.'' costas is a sportscaster with nbc, but his show would feature interviews with people ``from all walks of life,'' nbc said
the show will originate from new york, except in the summer when it will be based in costas' hometown of st. louis
sajak, host of both the nbc daytime version and syndicated nighttime version of ``wheel of fortune,'' is expected to leave the daytime show sometime this year, though he will stay with the nighttime show, said betsy vorce, a spokeswoman for king world, which distributes ``wheel'' for syndication
a 16-year-old boy has been arrested in the deaths of his parents, whose bodies were found buried in a shallow grave in the family's back yard, authorities said
a neighbor told police that the boy's father had recently shown him a drawing by his son depicting a man with an ax in his head. the boy reportedly told his father, ``that's what i feel like doing to you.''
the bodies of peter and karen overhand were discovered about midnight sunday by police who went to the residence to check out confidential information they had received
mitchell overhand, 16, the couple's only child, was being held at the juvenile detention center, the bernalillo county sheriff's department said. a second 16-year-old youth, whose name was withheld, also was taken into custody. no charges have been brought against the two
the overhands, who were believed to be in their mid-30s to 40s, were killed between 3 a.m. and 4 a.m. thursday, probably while they slept, said sheriff's capt. dan houston
an autopsy indicated peter overhand was shot with a .38-caliber handgun, houston said. an autopsy had not been completed on mrs. overhand monday night, but houston said she also appeared to have been shot
four handguns were seized as evidence, but authorities would not say where they were found or to whom they belonged
james bradley, a neighbor, said mitchell overhand told friends his parents were in california for the weekend attending his grandfather's funeral
sheriff's department spokeswoman ronni crago said police received information that ``something of a suspicious nature'' had happened at the overhand home in a subdivision on albuquerque's west mesa
police obtained a search warrant and found the bodies, she said
c.d. youngblood, who lives next door to the overhands, said peter overhand spoke to him often about problems he was having with mitchell
overhand, youngblood said, recently told him of finding a drawing in the garbage depicting a man with an ax in his head. when peter overhand confronted his son with the drawing, the younger overhand said, ``that's what i feel like doing to you,'' youngblood recalled
mitchell overhand, bradley said, spent the weekend with friends and had attended a party friday night at an albuquerque hotel. he said the boy also had invited a number of friends to his home over the weekend
youngblood also said peter overhand told him his son hated him so much, ``he wouldn't be surprised if he tried to kill him.'' pickup.</note>
a member of the senate armed services committee said today that the resignation of navy secretary james h. webb will force congress to take a closer look at the pentagon budget and the future size of the navy
i think what his resignation will do will cause us to look at our commitments,'' sen. william cohen, r-maine, said on ``cbs this morning.'' ``can we, in fact, afford to keep the commitment that we've made without spending the money necessary to put out a fleet to do it?''
the senator later added that webb's decision ``may spur very critical analysis of exactly where we're going with the defense budget.''
webb, in announcing his resignation monday, said he quit because defense secretary frank c. carlucci made budget decisions that mean the target of a 600-ship navy will never be met
the resignation ... may be right for him but a bit premature for us,'' cohen said. ``after all, secretary carlucci has to come before capitol hill, present the budget
we might disagree. we might agree with secretary webb that perhaps the allocation of the cuts should not have come out of shipbuilding, perhaps they should come out of some other service or some other way of achieving those cuts,'' cohen said
in 1981, president reagan promised to build the navy to a total of 600 deployable ships from the 450 the service had at that time
the navy was given large increases for shipbuilding as part of the record military spending buildup in reagan's first term. although overall defense spending has slowed sharply during the last three years, navy shipbuilding continued to grow, although more slowly
navy officials had said they would meet the target by next fall, but carlucci ordered the service to mothball 16 aging frigates, leaving it with 580 ships
the defense secretary ordered the cuts as part of a package of $33 billion worth of reductions carlucci had to find under an agreement reached by reagan and the democratic-controlled congress to cut federal spending
sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., said monday that webb's decision ``has obviously launched an important new stage of the debate about pentagon priorities and the size and type of navy we need.''
sen. carl levin, d-mich., said, ``i never believed that there was anything magic about the number 600.''
while carlucci ordered 16 older ships cut, the navy's budget includes money for 17 new ships. among them are one missile-firing submarine, two more 688-class attack subs, the first of a new class of ``seawolf'' attack subs, and three destroyers
carlucci declined to respond monday to webb's criticism, but he noted last week that he had to make ``tough choices'' in cutting the budget
speed skater bonnie blair set a world record while becoming america's second gold medal winner at the winter olympics
blair's time of 39.10 seconds in monday night's 500-meter race nipped the record set minutes earlier by her east german archrival christa rothenburger
i think i just got it on guts,'' blair said
on saturday, brian boitano of california won a gold medal in figure skating. u.s. athletes also have won one silver and one bronze medal
rothenburger lowered her own world record by 0.27 second, skating in the second pair in the women's 500 meters and finishing in 39.12. two pairs later, blair, of champaign, ill., trimmed an additional 0.02 second off the mark, winning the gold in 39.10. karin kania of east germany won the bronze
the soviet union leads with seven golds, and east germany has six
china's economy grew by a robust 9.4 percent in 1987, but rising prices caused by high consumer demand lowered living standards for one out of five city dwellers, the state statistics bureau said today
china's gross national product for the year was $295 billion, ranking it seventh in the world. the report said industrial output was up 16.5 percent, while agriculture output increased 4.7 percent
the bureau, in an annual report, said china's 200 million urban dwellers made an average of $248 last year, up 10.6 percent before inflation. its 800 million peasants averaged $125 each, up 5.3 percent
but zhang zhongqi, director of the bureau's comprehensive statistics department, also said at a news conference that a nationwide survey showed 21 percent of urban households had less to spend last year because of an 8.8 percent rise in the cost of living index
he said retail prices rose 7.3 percent nationwide, compared to about 6 percent rise in 1986. in the cities, however, inflation hit 9.1 percent
he said the main factor was the inability of the nation's producers, particularly of food and consumer goods, to meet the growing demands of a more affluent society
meat, poultry and egg prices climbed 16.5 percent, and fresh vegetables and aquatic products rose about 17 percent. pork and sugar were rationed for the first time in decades in many cities because farmers, discouraged by rising prices for raw materials, cut back production
wage earners who received no salary raises and retirees on fixed incomes suffered the most from the price spiral, he said
zhang said the government was trying to overcome supply-demand imbalances by promoting production of non-staple commodities, controlling excessive investment that has led to an overheated economy and subsidizing some prices where consumers and producers are particularly hard hit
he said 10 percent of china's urban residents were economically distressed, defined as having an annual income of less than $108
in rural areas, 8.2 percent, or about 60 million people, were under the poverty line of $54 a year. zhang said poor people in the countryside fell from 80 million in 1986, but he gave no comparative figures for the urban poor
zhang said unemployment hovered around 3 percent in 1987. he said underemployment _ millions of workers in factories and offices with little or nothing to do _ was an even more serious problem
the chinese government has acknowledged that inflation, unemployment and income disparities are all problems that china will have to live with as it adjusts from a rigid central planning system to a state-controlled but increasingly decentralized market economy
among the strong points were the nation's foreign trade, with exports rising 27.8 percent to $39.5 billion. the trade deficit fell from $12 billion in 1986 to $3.7 billion last year
it said new foreign investment in 1987 totalled $7.57 billion, up 4.3 percent, of which $5.33 billion was from borrowing and $2.4 billion from direct investment
the vampire,'' a painting by norwegian artist edvard munch that was insured for $2.3 million, was stolen today, the munch museum reported
curator arne eggum said thieves broke through a ground floor window of the museum and fled with the picture, which depicts a woman with her mouth on a man's neck
after the museum alarm sounded, the theft was quickly discovered and reported to the police by a caretaker who lives in the museum building,'' he said
wheel tracks outside the building indicated the culprits fled in a small car, he told ntb news agency. police said border checkpoints were alerted
the vampire'' was one of three paintings with the same theme rendered by munch in 1893 and 1894. a second painting also is in the museum and a third is in goteborg, sweden
munch, who died in 1944, bequeathed his private collection of his art to the city of oslo, including 1,100 paintings, 4,500 drawings and 18,000 prints
the munch museum has had several unresolved thefts since it opened in 1963, and experts have called for improved security
florida citrus growers have filed suit in federal court to prevent texas from enforcing its emergency quarantine of the fruit
the suit called the feb. 11 quarantine unconstitutional and invalid
texas agriculture commissioner jim hightower said he had ordered the 30-day quarantine on fruits and plants to protect texas' $65 million-a-year citrus industry from the canker which had infected some florida citrus groves
the u.s. department of agriculture, hightower charged, had bowed to pressure from florida growers earlier this month when it lifted a ban on shipments of florida citrus to other citrus-producing states. the ban was imposed in 1984 following an outbreak of citrus canker in florida
the suit by non-profit florida citrus mutual and tuxedo fruit co., a citrus grower and shipper, alleged that texas' quarantine would cost the florida citrus industry millions of dollars
the florida petition, which seeks a preliminary injunction, said an amended quarantine in florida permits interstate movement of fruit from florida under certain rigorous federal standards
max woodfin, spokesman for the texas department of agriculture, said texas agriculture officials were prepared to defend the quarantine in ``any peaceful forum available.''
woodfin noted that a public hearing has been scheduled for thursday in mcallen. testimony is expected from florida, california, arizona, louisiana and u.s. department of agriculture officials, as well as texas producers and experts on citrus disease
weinberger reax; picks up 8th graf pvs: the united..
caspar weinberger received an honorary knighthood from queen elizabeth ii today, the highest royal honor britain has bestowed on an american
the brief, private ceremony at buckingham palace didn't mean the former u.s. defense secretary would become sir caspar. that accolade is reserved for the queen's own subjects. but it was britain's way of saying thanks to an exceptionally good friend
asked why he got the knighthood, weinberger modestly replied: ``i haven't the faintest idea.''
but the announcement feb. 1 cited his ``outstanding and invaluable contribution'' to anglo-american defense cooperation, and his ``unfailing support and assistance'' during the 1982 falkland islands war between britain and argentina
the 70-year-old weinberger, who counts winston churchill among his heroes, did not have to kneel before the queen as a commoner and be tapped on both shoulders with a sword, as is the custom for british subjects
her majesty was nice enough just to present it to me.'' he said, adding: ``i'm very honored, very pleased, and still very astonished.''
he received a red ribbon with the badge of the order of the british empire, and a separate silver star signifying the title knight grand cross _ the highest order of chivalry for a foreigner
it means he can now call himself caspar weinberger gbe
weinberger, wearing a gray suit, was accompanied by his wife, jane, and foreign secretary sir geoffrey howe, who had recommended him for the honor
the 25-minute ceremony was held without reporters or photographers present in the small, blue-walled queen's audience room where the 61-year-old monarch often receives official visitors
she was very gracious as always, and very generous in her remarks,'' weinberger told reporters afterward. he politely avoided mentioning what they discussed
he carried his new insignia in a blue presentation box which he opened for photographers just before driving away to a luncheon hosted by u.s. ambassador charles h. price ii
when weinberger's award was announced, reporters asked him whether he was ready to be called ``sir cap.'' he replied: ``good god, no. our constitution has some harsh words about titles. but i really am flattered.''
asked after the ceremony whether he was now more of an anglophile, he replied: ``well, it's hard to be not.''
weinberger retired nov. 5 after nearly seven years as president reagan's defense chief
the united states provided critical intelligence and logistical support to britain during its 74-day campaign to oust argentina's invasion force from the british-ruled south atlantic islands. weinberger insisted monday that his role was ``a comparatively modest, small one.''
buckingham palace said only a very few of the 55 other americans who have received honorary knighthoods were made gbes. the most famous americans who have received honorary knighthoods were made knights of the british empire or kbes, a lower order of chivalry
they include former secretary of state dean rusk, industrialist henry ford iii, philanthropists paul mellon and john paul getty ii, actors douglas fairbanks jr. and sidney poitier, former sen. j. william fulbright, d-ark., and food magnate henry j. heinz ii
american-born violinist yehudi menuhin also received an honorary kbe, but his award was changed to a full knighthood after he gained dual british-u.s. citizenship in 1985, and he is now known as ``sir yehudi.''
weinberger has longstanding links with britain and has visited often, finding strong support from prime minister margaret thatcher for reagan's military buildup at home and his drive to modernize nato and keep it unified
the anglo-american relationship, he said, is ``critically important'' to the western alliance
weinberger gave up an invitation to the white house last november to make his debut as a british television commentator on the treaty eliminating medium- and shorter-range nuclear missiles, which he helped secure _ and had some candid assessments of the soviet leadership
last month, he was appointed a distinguished visiting professor at edinburgh university, where he will spend four weeks this summer participating in a special project investigating the interplay among technology, communications and the humanities
weinberger often cites churchill, especially the late prime minister's early warnings in the 1930s that europe must rearm in response to the growing military threat from germany
weinberger says he sees ``some rather deadly parallels'' today, and warned monday that nato must remain strong ``to deal with increasing soviet threats.''
the cuban government plans to release a significant number of political prisoners in an effort to block a formal united nations investigation of human rights in cuba, u.s. officials say
fidel castro will ``release thousands of political prisoners mixed in with common prisoners'' to persuade member nations to vote down the american proposal for the u.n. investigation, said armando valladares, chief of the u.s. delegation to the u.n. human rights commission in geneva
a spokesman for a cuban delegation in geneva was quoted today by the fort lauderdale news-sun sentinel as saying a major announcement would be made in cuba on wednesday, but he would not elaborate
a state department official who closely follows cuban affairs said the ``thousands'' suggested by valladares, who spent 22 years in cuban prisons, may be overly optimistic, but a good chance exists the cubans will free enough prisoners to make the action appear significant
even if it is for cosmetic purposes, we love it,'' said the official, who asked not to be identified. ``we're talking about human lives here. even if a release is done cynically, people are still out of prison.''
the united states placed a similar resolution before the u.n. human rights commission's annual session last year. it failed by one vote on a procedural motion 19 to 18, with five nations abstaining. the state department again expects a close vote
although the resolution does not condemn cuba's human rights record, a u.n. investigation of human rights practices on the communist island would be politically embarrassing to castro
estimates of cuban political prisoners range from as few as 500 to as many as 10,000. the state department official said castro himself has acknowledged holding 1,000 to 2,000 such prisoners. scandal, charge of `dirty tricks' against bush campaign; picks up 9th graf pvs, bgng, `two weeks.'</note>
republican presidential hopeful pat robertson said today that charges of jimmy swaggart's sexual misconduct had been known for a few months, but somebody planned the scandal to embarrass him before the super tuesday elections
swaggart, a television evangelist accused of sexual misconduct, was ordered monday by the hierarchy of his church in baton rouge, la., to limit his preaching and enter counseling
robertson, who bristles at the label of former television evangelist, said today that evidence showing that swaggart had been involved with prostitutes had ``lied dormant since last october.''
it ``stretches the imagination and stretches credulity'' that it came two weeks ``before the most important primary in the nation,'' the republican candidate said during a news conference in columbia. a round of primaries and caucuses will be held super tuesday, march 8, in 20 states
nothing happens to people by accident,'' robertson said in an interview monday with the anderson, s.c., independent-mail. ``it is kind of funny this came up two weeks before the most important primaries in the nation. people probably wonder what went on
i think somebody had something to do with it,'' said robertson. ``somebody else planned all these things, i am afraid.''
asked again today whether he had any evidence to show that the scandal broke just before super tuesday, robertson replied: ``i have no knowledge. it's certainly a coincidence.''
on monday, robertson offered no proof of his contention, and declined to say to whom he was referring. however, in the same interview he accused the campaign of vice president george bush of ``dirty politics'' and ``trickery'' directed at him
a bush campaign official, asked about the remarks, said robertson had apparently adopted a new campaign strategy of ``making bizarre statements in order to make news.''
to suggest that we had something to do with (the swaggart affair) borders on the outlandish,'' said jay morgan, bush's deputy southern political director, in a telephone interview from his home in atlanta
robertson repeated his charge today that the bush campaign plans ``dirty tricks'' in south carolina, saying he was told that the vice president's campaign plans to run some television ads ``dealing with religious bigotry in the few days before the (south carolina primary) elections.''
bush campaign ad director sid rogich said today the only ad running in south carolina is a biographical commercial
two weeks ago, robertson scolded nbc anchor tom brokaw, who interviewed him live on the night of the iowa caucuses, for referring to him as a former television evangelist
robertson, who founded the christian broadcasting network and for years hosted its flagship program ``the 700 club,'' says he wants to be described as a former religious broadcaster, or a television businessman
earlier monday, robertson had said swaggart's troubles were ``unfortunate,'' but had nothing to do with him
he said the swaggart case will have ``no more effect on me than gary hart'' had on other candidates, referring to hart's problems following reports of his relationship with a miami model. hart dropped out of the presidential race in may but rejoined it in december
it (the swaggart controversy) will not affect me because it has nothing whatsoever to do with me,'' robertson told the anderson newspaper. ``but i want to tell people to ask george bush what he thinks about all this
i have been told of bush's dirty tricks and i expect to see them in south carolina,'' he said. ``his campaign will use every kind of dirty trick against me because this state is important and i have a lot of support and george bush knows that.''
south carolina holds its primary march 5, three days before 20 states, mainly in the south, hold primaries and caucuses
the fbi today denied it had conducted a political investigation of anti-reagan activists, saying it had information that members of the targeted group planned or discussed disrupting the 1984 republican convention and shutting down a public utility
the fbi's executive assistant director, oliver b. revell, came before a senate panel to defend the probe of the committee in solidarity with the people of el salvador. the probe was ended without any charges being filed
the group has said it was investigated because it opposes president reagan's central america policies
documents previously released in the march 1985-june 1985 probe show that fbi agents and informants sent to spy on cispes collected so much information on peaceful protest activities that bureau headquarters was worried that the investigation had gone too far
the documents, released under the freedom of information act, have shown that while the investigation was targeted at cispes, the files eventually included information on hundreds of other individuals and groups, ranging from roman catholic nuns to union leaders who opposed reagan policies
in defending the probe, revell told the senate intelligence committee that in addition to possible violence, cispes was involved in circulating forged u.s. documents and had strong ties to the u.s. communist party
some have insinuated that this investigation was politically motivated as many individuals associated with cispes were opposed to reagan administration policies in central america,'' revell said. ``nothing could be further from the truth
we did find indications that some cispes members were at least discussing and planning violence. our investigtions uncovered one cispes member who was tasked to determine response times of emergency services in a major american city; another cispes member stated he had developed a system to shut down a public utility in a major midwestern city; as well as plans to violently disrupt the 1984 republican convention.''
the bureau initiated the investigation under foreign intelligence and counter-intelligence guidelines, designed to protect the united states against crimes such as espionage and terrorism, in which foreign powers or groups are involved
these guidelines allow the fbi to focus more on politically oriented groups and their missions than on specific crimes that are planned or carried out. because of this wider latitude, some lawmakers and the american civil liberties union warn that it is easy to cross the line and investigate free speech and peaceful assembly
fbi director william s. sessions said the investigation in this case ``was predicated on information received from several sources that certain leaders and key members of cispes were involved in covertly furnishing funds and materials to a foreign terrorist organization.'' the group was identified as the fmln, the group fighting a war against the u.s.-backed government of el salvador
jerry berman, chief legislative counsel for the american civil liberties union, said the investigation should have started under the most strict guidelines, those for general criminal investigations
these investigations can only begin ``when facts or circumstances reasonably indicate that a federal crime has been, is being, or will be committed.'' if the crime has already been committed, the probe focuses on who committed the act and on securing evidence
the fbi is given greater leeway for a domestic ``intelligence'' investigation, which can focus on groups in the united states trying ``to further political or social goals through activities that involve criminal violence.''
the bureau did not place the cispes investigation under either the intelligence or general guidelines, but under the foreign intelligence and counter-intelligence rules that involve participation by foreign entities
these rules remain largely classified, but officials familiar with them say they provide the widest latitude among the different sets of guidelines
on july 26, 1984 _ some 16 months after the investigation began _ fbi headquarters sent 32 field offices a message that suggested some of them were going beyond the guidelines
some offices have reported information recently regarding political statements and political lobbying by cispes or cispes affiliates,'' it said. ``supervisors in recipient offices must carefully monitor this and related investigations and asset operations within your respective divisions to ensure appropriate direction, targeting and reporting.''
but messages from the field showed that bureaus were still confused
in august 1984 the denver office told headquarters, ``the field is still not sure of how much seemingly legitimate political activity can be monitored.''
and prior to the july directive, fbi headquarters received messages like this one from cincinnati: ``the bureau is requested to furnish cincinnati with guidelines regarding investigation of captioned matter, vis-a-vis religious organizations _ specifically the roman catholic church.''
rep. don edwards, d-calif., chairman of the house judiciary civil rights subcommittee, said he does not fault the fbi for starting the investigation under foreign intelligence guidelines, but for ``a management problem'' in not shutting it down much sooner
we want it narrow, and stopped when criminal conduct is not found,'' he said in an interview. ``the cispes investigation went on for years and there was no criminal conduct. somebody should have blown the whistle.''
berman, of the aclu, said the field offices became ``a vacuum cleaner for collection of first amendment activity.''
they never began to narrow it,'' he said. ``they ended up sweeping up the first amendment activity and broadly targeting cispes all over the country.'' now reporting poland sent its deputy foreign minister, sted foreign minister. no pickup.</note>
