panamanian officials detained 25 u.s. military personnel here for two hours and then released them without filing charges, a u.s. embassy spokesman said today
but a top panamanian military official denied the personnel were detained, and said police officers only briefly stopped them to check for drivers' licenses
the u.s. embassy spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, told the asociated press that panamanian officials detained the 25 troops as they were driving monday to u.s. military installations located in the former panama canal zone
most of the troops were driving motorcycles but two were in cars and one was walking, the spokesman said. panamanian officials released all 25 after two hours without charges, the embassy official said
col. leonidas macias, chief of police for the defense forces of panama, denied police had detained the u.s. personnel. macias said local police momentarily stopped them to ask for drivers' licenses and to remind them that u.s. troops are prohibited from wearing their uniforms outside the former canal zone
relations between panama and the united states have been strained since last june, when protests started here against the leadership of gen. manuel antonio noriega, chief of the defense forces and the power behind the civilian government. kabul</head>
the afghan guerrilla alliance today announced a plan to form a coalition cabinet that would replace the communist government of president najib and ensure the withdrawal of soviet troops from afghanistan
western diplomats in kabul, meanwhile, reported a bomb went off in the soviet embassy compound, indicating the guerrillas are intensifying their attacks in the capital
the seven-party islamic unity of afghan mujahedeen announced the plan in a statement telexed from the pakistani border city of peshawar. it stipulates that afghanistan would have a 28-member cabinet to replace najib's peoples democratic party of afghanistan
the statement said the government would be made up of 14 ministers from among the guerrilla leadership, seven representatives from among the 3 million afghan refugees in pakistan and ``seven moslems presently living in kabul.''
earlier, guerrilla leaders said these ``moslems'' would include non-communists in the kabul administration who have not committed serious offenses ``against the people'' during the eight-year war
the proposal, which would allow the guerrillas to control the afghan government, was not expected to be accepted by the soviets or the current administration in kabul
diplomatic sources said today that moslem guerrillas have stepped up attacks in kabul, where communist officials and soviet advisers reportedly are preparing to leave
western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said at least 18 explosions were heard during the past week in the afghan capital, including one in the soviet embassy compound and one near radio afghanistan
one source said a bomb inside the soviet compound feb. 19 caused some injuries, but there were no further details
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev announced early this month that the red army could begin pulling its 115,000 troops out of afghanistan by may 15 if kabul and islamabad sign a u.n.-sponsored accord by mid-march
a new round of indirect talks between islamabad and kabul is scheduled for march 2 at geneva. pakistan insists an accord should be linked to an agreed plan on formation of a transitional government
islamabad and the guerrillas are pushing this point because they fear an outbreak of fighting between various afghan groups and the communists if no government is in power
the soviets, however, disagree, charging that such an insistance on setting up an interim government is obstructing soviet plans to withdraw
guerrilla leaders have rejected any power-sharing with the current kabul officials and today's statement from peshawar backed up that position
the statement said a shoora-ali or supreme council would also be formed to oversee the cabinet. it would consist of the leaders of the seven-party alliance and would provide ``joint leadership during the interim period.''
the insurgents said the ``broad-based transitional government will represent all sections of the afghan nation.''
the alliance said there would be a consultative council of 75 members consisting of two members from each of afghanistan's 28 provinces and 19 members from among moslem religious scholars, intellectuals and technocrats. the council would frame the interim laws to administer the country until an elected constituent assembly writes a constitution
the country would adopt the name, the islamic state of afghanistan, ``wherein the koran ... will be supreme,'' the statement added. `authorities say ....'</note>
a police crackdown on street gangs has been applauded by some black leaders tired of the violence that claimed 300 lives last year, but the arrest of an off-duty black officer also raises the question of harassment
black and hispanic leaders accused police of largely ignoring the gang violence until a woman bystander was killed jan. 30 in street-gang crossfire in an upscale neighborhood
but two weeks after the shooting, an off-duty black policeman from a blue-collar suburb was arrested by los angeles police as he stood on a street corner in the same neighborhood, accompanied by six black youths. the officer said his group was conducting an informal ``sting'' operation to investigate alleged harassment by city police
both the arrest and the killing of 27-year-old karen toshima occurred in westwood village, a theater and restaurant district that soaring housing prices have turned into a relatively wealthy neighborhood
authorities say there were more than 300 gang-related murders in los angeles county in 1987 and the rate is increasing. but gang violence usually is confined to the predominantly black and hispanic southside neighborhoods of the nation's second-largest city where turf battles between drug dealers have led to drive-by shootings
five people were killed and five others were injured in gang shootings last weekend even as police staged a crackdown. deputy chief glenn levant, newly appointed as the city's anti-gang czar, said the more than 50 arrests were part of a strategy to prevent murders by taking gang members out of circulation
children playing in parks and a 67-year-old woman sitting in a wheelchair have been killed when gang hitmen missed their targets
and that's not the way it should be. we should be able to live normally,'' said barbara thomas, spokeswoman for the south central organizing committee, which says it represents thousands of black families
city councilman nate holden, who is black and represents a largely black district, said the yearning for more police protection crosses racial lines
i've had white people complain about the gangs. they all just want to feel secure in their community and their homes,'' he said
at the same time, the sting by sgt. don jackson of the hawthorne police department called into question the racial sensitivity of the los angeles police
none of those kids did anything except stand on that corner and be black _ and that was enough,'' said jackson, who was released on his recognizance after being arrested on a misdemeanor charge of resisting an officer
the police department defended the arrest of jackson and frisking of the others, saying the group, dressed like gang members, was blocking the sidewalk and refused to move
the question of police harassment is among the issues being considered as the city moves ahead with a plan to hire 150 more officers, increasing the force to its largest strength ever, 7,500 officers
police chief darryl gates on monday declined to say anything about how he will deploy his forces until after a march 8 hearing of the city's advisory police commission
mayor tom bradley, as he approved the new hiring last week, said the additional forces would help ``return this city to a drug-free, gang-free atmosphere.''
john p. kenney, a criminologist and former police commission member, said more police officers is not the answer. ``it wouldn't solve the problem. it would for a few days or for a few weeks. then you get complaints of overpolicing and harassing,'' he said
historically, there's a resentment to an excessive show of force,'' said garrett capune, professor of criminology at the university of southern california. ``it has a racist overtone, you know, there seems to be more crime because there's more officers. it becomes a sort of self-fulfilling prophecy.''
but holden replied: ``these guys can sit in some classroom and think what it's supposed to be like. but they haven't seen the real world. i resent them. let them come into the black community and see what it's like.''
hundreds of southside residents demonstrated at police headquarters after extra officers were deployed in westwood this month, primarily at the request of merchants who were afraid their business would be hurt by news of the gang shooting
minority activists later publicized a study by the independent public administration service in virginia that appeared to show police responded more slowly to crimes in poor areas
the police department on friday released a letter from the principal author of the report stating that it had been widely misinterpreted. the letter said the study concluded the department takes too long to respond to emergencies, but that geographical differences are not significant
a british soldier ordered jailed for life for killing a belfast roman catholic has been freed and returned to his regiment after serving only three years in prison, the army said today
the disclosure came amid anglo-irish tensions following the killing of a catholic man on sunday by a british soldier and the irish government's decision to conduct its own investigation of the slaying, which occurred in northern ireland
the announcement that the convicted killer, pvt. ian richard thain, was back in uniform, although not in northern ireland, provoked sharp reactions from leaders of the province's catholic minority. at the same time, leaders of northern ireland's protestant majority were angered by dublin's announcement that it will probe sunday's killing
thain was jailed for the fatal shooting of thomas reilly, road manager of the pop group bananarama, on aug. 9, 1983. thain claimed in court that he fired because riots were going on and he believed reilly was about to pull a gun on him
but the judge found him ``deliberately untruthful'' and said he did not believe thain truly feared reilly was about to shoot at him. thain was the first soldier sentenced to life imprisonment for actions in northern ireland
an army statement said thain was then 18 and ``while the army in no way condones his action, we consider the incident to have been a tragic error of judgment made by a young man in very difficult circumstances.''
the home office said thain was released on a life license, a form of parole whereby he can be reimprisoned ``should his behavior give rise to concern.'' it said he was freed after a review by the state parole board
sinn fein, the legal political wing of the outlawed irish republican army, said thain's release showed there was no justice in northern ireland. the victim's father, jim reilly, said: ``i'm very, very shocked and distressed. i can't believe this has happened.''
meanwhile, the irish government sent deputy police commissioner eugene crowley to monaghan, on the border with northern ireland, to launch an investigation into sunday's shooting of 23-year-old aidan mcanespie
mcanespie was killed by a bullet from an army observation tower at a checkpoint near aughnacloy, half a mile from the frontier in county tyrone
relatives said he was walking to a weekly gaelic football game and had passed through the checkpoint when he was shot
mcanespie was a sinn fein supporter, and his former parish priest said he was harassed whenever he passed through the checkpoint. press association, the british news agency, said the soldier who fired at mcanespie told his interrogators it was an accident. the soldier is in military custody
the irish move was seen as a calculated slight to britain, since its police force in the province was conducting an inquiry. british authorities stressed that the irish investigation would be confined to ireland's side of the border
the european court of justice today voided a 1985 european economic community law banning the marketing of hormone-treated meat in the 12-nation trade bloc
the eec high court said the common market states had not followed correct procedures when they enacted the ban, which was passed by a written procedure that required unanimity
denmark and britain had opposed the ban and the british took the issue to court
the ban on the use of cattle-fattening hormones took effect jan. 1 for meat produced in the eec. it was to take effect in january 1989 for imported beef
the united states has called the ban an unfair trade practice and threatened retaliation. it also disputed the contention of eec consumer groups that there was enough scientific evidence to show that the hormones posed a human health threat
proponents ontended the ban did not discriminate against the united states because it applied to all nations, including those of the eec
u.s. beef exports to the eec total about $130 million a year
a judge has ordered a quick trial of a lawsuit that could affect whether an 11-year-old boy with leukemia lives or dies
the suit was filed by the boy's father, jim lacina of geneva, to regain health insurance coverage he contends was mistakenly canceled
doctors say the boy, jamie, needs a bone marrow transplant by march 15 to survive more than a few months. but the fred hutchinson cancer research center, the seattle hospital that could treat the boy, requires patients to have insurance coverage or $100,000 in hand before it will perform the procedure, said hospital spokeswoman susan edmonds
cuyahoga county common pleas judge carl j. character declined monday to decide the case without a jury, but set a jury trial date for monday so a verdict could be issued in time for jamie to get the treatment
we've definitely advanced this case more than a year,'' character said. ``they (the lacinas) came in and indicated the condition of the young man had become more critical. ... hopefully it can be resolved in a timely fashion.''
lacina says chemotherapy no longer is an effective treatment for his son
in the lawsuit, filed in 1986, lacina said nationwide life insurance co. of columbus terminated his health insurance without notifying him
a nine-year agent for nationwide, lacina lost his job in 1983 because of company cutbacks. attorneys for both sides agree that he paid to continue his policy after he lost his job
lacina's attorney, gerald jeppe, told character that lacina didn't receive a copy of his policy, a notice that his premium was due, or a termination notice in late 1983. he asked the judge to rule in lacina's favor without a jury trial
jeppe said lacina is applying for medicaid while he awaits a decision on the case. meanwhile, a fund for the boy has been established at a bank, he said
nationwide's attorney, edward e. duncan, told character that the company mailed lacina the documents in question. a jury should decide whether lacina received them, he said
the facts of this case are indeed tragic. a little boy through no fault of his own may be denied care,'' duncan said. ``the long and the short of it is whether mr. lacina is telling the truth when he says he didn't receive either of those letters or that policy.''
duncan said nationwide will prove at the trial that lacina's behavior was inconsistent for a man who thought he had health insurance coverage. lacina ran up large hospital bills for his son and filed for bankruptcy, duncan said
the lawsuit wasn't filed until the summer of 1986,'' duncan said. ``what was mr. lacina doing between 1983 and 1986 with these hospital bills if he had coverage?''
jeppe declined to discuss the case aside from the comments he made in court. 02-23 0504</first> spokesman for state health commissioner as saying her comments to newspaper were misunderstood and that she still opposes needle exchange. picks up in 8th graf, `a proposal ...'</note>
boston mayor raymond flynn has written to city councilors seeking approval of an experimental sterile needle exchange for drug addicts in hopes of curbing the spread of aids
flynn said addicts, their sex partners and their babies ``are the fastest growing group of aids victims,'' and that conventional anti-drug measures ``do not go far enough in the short term'' to curb the spread of acquired immune deficiency syndrome
dr. george a. lamb, the city's director of clinical and community health services, was prepared to outline the proposed program at a closed meeting this morning at city hall, according to the boston globe. he recently toured several european cities to examine needle distribution programs
addicts could enter the program on their own or by referral, lamb said
flynn is seeking approval by the city council of a home rule petition to the legislature, the newspaper said. the move would bypass any applicable state laws against possession of hypodermic syringes by drug addicts or against dispensing such equipment to drug addicts
gov. michael s. dukakis has opposed any needle exchange program, as had state public health commissioner deborah prothrow-stith
the globe quoted prothrow-stith as suggesting monday night that if the state wanted to consider ``something really radical,'' it could supply addicts not only with sterile needles but also with heroin
but department of public health spokesman john stobierski said today the comment ``was in no way a policy recommendation or proposal,'' but was made by the commissioner in explaining why she believed the needle exchange proposal was ``very, very wrong.''
in a statement today, prothrow-stith said the department remains opposed to a needle exchange for iv drug users'' and that the state should continue to concentrate on drug treatment and rehabilitation programs
a proposal by new york city to supply a small number of addicts with clean needles on an experimental basis awaits formal approval from the state health commissioner, dr. david axelrod, who had opposed the idea but said last month that he would approve it
new york wants to supply 200 to 400 addicts with syringes. the recipients would have to turn in used needles to get fresh ones. the needles would be tested for aids and to ensure that they weren't shared
although the test period would last a year, the city's health commissioner, dr. stephen joseph, has said he expected solid indications of success or failure within six months
aids is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. it is spread through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring
a dog named tootsie awakened her master with a whine and led him outside to a snowdrift, where he found his 90-year-old mother curled up in her nightgown
ethelyn preston, who has alzheimer's disease, was listed in stable condition today at swedish medical center in suburban englewood, where she is being treated for a broken right arm and cuts
if tootsie hadn't notified me, she would have died,'' said roy preston, mrs. preston's 58-year-old son, who lives with her
preston said his 3{-year-old boxer woke him up friday morning, ``whining, like she wanted to tell me something,'' he said. ``then she ran right out to the back yard.''
he followed the dog and found his mother lying on her right side, slightly curled up in a snowdrift near the back door. she was wearing a nightgown and was barefoot
when i saw her there, i was frantic,'' her son said. ``i couldn't lift her. her body was stiff. she was all dead weight from lying out in the cold.''
she had been outside about 15 minutes, he said
preston got help from a neighbor and an ambulance
when the ambulance arrived, tootsie pitched in again
she was running back and forth from where she (ethelyn preston) was and the ambulance,'' her son said. ``it seemed like she (tootsie) wanted to tell them where my mother was.''
preston said his mother probably was trying to get to the bathroom, next to her bedroom, when she lost her way and ended up in the yard
he said he will hire round-the-clock supervision for her when she gets home from the hospital. 2nd graf pvs, it is. edits throughout to conform.</note>
the united states will be able to provide military help to nato allies despite the new u.s.-soviet treaty banning medium-range nuclear weapons from europe, the chief u.s. negotiator for the pact told a senate committee today
if it is not prohibited by the treaty, we can do it,'' maynard glitman told the senate armed services committee
glitman was testifying about the effect of article 14, a provision which says that neither side shall do anything, now or in the future, to undercut the pact
sen. dan quayle, r-ind., told glitman that ``i'm concerned about article 14'' because it might limit future u.s. aid to nato nations
the provision is a standard clause added to other treaties which simply restates the intention of both nations to abide by the pact, glitman said
the treaty spells out in great detail what each side cannot do and anything is permitted if it is not prohibited, said glitman
for example, said glitman, the treaty doesn't ban the transfer of u.s. technology to nato nations such as great britain to develop ground-launched cruise missiles. those u.s. missiles will be banned by the treaty but the british could go ahead and build their own, he said
glitman said u.s. negotiators resisted soviet efforts to block u.s. help for nato. ``we knew their goal was to find a way to put a brake on nato activities,'' he said
president reagan pledged today that the united states will do its part to ensure that the nato alliance remains strong, saying in an address broadcast to europe that ``our destiny is coupled with yours.''
in the address, which came a week before a nato summit meeting, reagan reaffirmed the alliance agreement that an attack on any member nation is an attack against all of them. ``simply put, an attack on munich is the same as an attack on chicago,'' he said
glitman's testimony was part of a detailed examination of the pact, a line-by-line scrutiny which legislators said was necessary to avoid possible conflicts with future administrations over the treaty's meaning
it is very regrettable that we have to go through this,'' armed services committee chairman sam nunn, d-ga., said monday to glitman
nunn and other democrats noted that the scrutiny arises from congressional distrust of the executive branch, a skepticism born of the fight over the meaning of an earlier treaty
nunn noted the state department had delivered 31 volumes of records about how u.s.-soviet negotiators reached the intermediate-range nuclear forces pact signed by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev
committee staffers spent 300 hours reviewing only three volumes of records that preceded the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty, nunn said
the armed services panel is one of three senate committees examining the inf treaty. ratification by the full senate is expected but the votes will be delayed until after nunn's committee finishes it close examination, nunn told his colleagues monday
ratification would require a two-thirds vote
the distrust arose from a dispute between the democratic-controlled congress and the reagan administration over the meaning of the abm pact, particularly how it would affect reagan's star wars missile-defense research program
the existing ``narrow'' interpretation of the abm pact would ban some tests of the strategic defense initiative, as star wars is formally known. but reagan has asserted that his administration has the right to unilaterally move to a ``broad'' view of the pact that would permit sdi tests
nunn led a congressional fight to block the move to a ``broad'' view of the abm pact and promised to delay the inf ratification until the administration promised that current testimony on the inf pact was ``authoritative.''
administration officials had argued that the 1973 executive branch testimony on the abm pact wasn't ``authoritative.''
nunn told glitman that committee staff members had drawn up 135 questions, many of them technical, about possible ambiguities in the treaty
two other democrats on the committee supported nunn's decision to scrutinize the inf pact
sen. john glenn, d-ohio, said, ``i'm sorry there was a reinterpretation of the abm treaty that made this necessary.'' sen. james exon, d-neb., said, ``it's sad we have to go through the exercise we're going through here.''
meantime, dr. edward teller, the physicist who is considered the father of both sdi and the hydrogen bomb, supported the treaty in testimony before the foreign relations committee
teller noted that he deeply distrusts the soviets and said, ``my personal approach (to the treaty) is careful, doubtful, yet positive.''
teller termed the fights over the meaning of the treaty ``senseless debates.''
new york _ a 70-year-old man reputed to be the underboss of the gambino crime family has been sentenced to 15 years in prison and fined $820,000 for a racketeering conviction
u.s. district judge jack b. weinstein said monday he sentenced joseph armone to prison despite his age because he was convinced the defendant was a high-ranking member of the crime family
weinstein also cited armone's lengthy criminal record, which he said began when the defendant was 15 years old
armone, of brooklyn, was convicted dec. 22 of racketeering conspiracy involving extortion, bribery and illegal interstate travel to commit bribery
he was jailed after his conviction when he refused to renounce any organized crime ties, a condition for his release from detention
he had faced a maximum sentence of 20 years for the most serious charge, racketeering
one of the bribery charges accused armone and a co-defendant, joseph n. gallo, of plotting to give a $20,000 bribe so that gallo's son would be transferred from a state prison to a federal prison, where presumably he would receive better treatment. the plot was unsuccessful
gallo, 76, the reputed former consigliere of the gambino family, was sentenced earlier this month to 10 years in prison and fined $300,000 for his racketeering conviction. weinstein stayed the sentence pending appeal
two other co-defendants were also sentenced monday. anthony vitta, 49, of queens, a reputed gambino soldier, was given a 10-year prison sentence and fined $250,000. vitta was convicted of racketeering conspiracy, loansharking and other charges
salvatore migliorisi, 49, of brooklyn, was sentenced to three years in jail and fined $25,000 for his extortion and obstruction of justice conviction
the four defendants were among 16 people with alleged ties to the gambino family who were indicted in june 1986
of the 16 defendants, 11 have now been convicted or have pleaded guilty, two were acquitted, charges against one defendant were dismissed, another defendant is missing and believed dead, and one is awaiting trial
armone faces additional federal charges of extortion and racketeering in fort lauderdale, fla., where he and 12 other people with alleged ties to the gambino family were named last month in a 22-count indictment
a criminal suspect's rights are not violated when a witness who is unable to identify the suspect in court testifies about an earlier identification of the accused, the supreme court ruled today
the justices, voting 6-2, ordered the reinstatement of the conviction of a california prison inmate in the beating of a prison guard who suffered memory loss because of the attack
justice antonin scalia, in his opinion for the court, said a defendant's right to cross-examine his accusers is not violated by admission of a prior, out-of-court identification statement from a witness who is unable to explain in court the basis for the identification
scalia said defense lawyers have ample power to attack the credibility of such witnesses when they take the stand
the weapons available to impugn the witness's statement when memory loss is asserted will of course not always achieve success,'' scalia said. ``but successful cross-examination is not the constitutional guarantee.''
the decision is a victory for the reagan administration, which urged the court to reinstate the federal conviction of james joseph owens for assault with intent to murder john foster, a guard at a federal prison in lompoc, calif
owens, a prisoner there at the time of the attack, was sentenced to an additional 20 years for the assault
the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals overturned owens' assault conviction on grounds he was denied the right to cross-examine foster effectively
foster was attacked on april 12, 1982, with a metal pipe. he suffered numerous injuries to his head, face, arms and hands
on may 5, 1982, shortly before he was released from a hospital, foster told an fbi agent that owens had attacked him. foster also picked owens' photograph from several mug shots
but at the trial, foster said he was unable to recall who assaulted him or whether he actually saw his assailant. he did testify that he remembered identifying owens when questioned in the hospital by the fbi agent but said he no longer remembered why he said owens was the assailant
the 9th circuit court said foster may have been influenced by visitors who spoke with him during his hospital stay
three inmates testified that owens was the attacker. there also was evidence that owens attended a meeting the day before the assault of the moorish science temple of america, a prison religious group that discussed attacking foster
in a dissenting opinion today, justice william j. brennan said the high court ruling ``reduces the right of confrontation to a purely procedural protection, and a markedly hollow one at that.''
he was joined by justice thurgood marshall
justice anthony m. kennedy, who became a member of the court thursday, did not take part in the decision
the case is u.s. vs. owens, 86-877. weekly and the british journal of psychiatry are two different publications.</note>
a young mentally ill man egged into a suicide attempt by his mother apparently cured his phobia of germs and obsession for handwashing by shooting himself in the head, doctors said
the .22-caliber slug destroyed the section of the brain responsible for his disabling obsessive-compulsive behavior without causing any other brain damage to the man, a straight-a student, his doctor said
the afflicted man tried to kill himself five years ago, when he was 19, said psychiatrist leslie solyom of shaughnessy hospital in vancouver, british columbia
victims of the disorder typically have an inexplicable compulsion to repeat activities over and over
the man, identified only as george in a report in physician's weekly and the british journal of psychiatry, washed his hands hundreds of times a day and took frequent showers, solyom said. the behavior forced him to drop out of school and quit his job
solyom treated george for more than a year before he attempted suicide
george was also very depressed and told his mother that his life was so wretched that he would rather die,'' solyom said. ``parents of obsessive-compulsives, particularly mothers, often have cruel streaks,'' he said
she said, `so look george, if your life is so wretched, just go and shoot yourself.' so george went to the basement, stuck a .22-caliber rifle in his mouth and pulled the trigger.''
the bullet lodged in the left front lobe of the brain. surgeons removed it, but could not get out all the fragments
when he was transferred to our hospital three weeks later, he had hardly any compulsions left,'' solyom said
after brain surgery to remove the bullet he showed no signs of his former obsession, the doctor said. he returned to school, got a new job and is now in his second year of college, having retained the same iq as he had before the illness struck, solyom said
monday's edition of physician's weekly wryly described the failed suicide attempt as ``successful radical surgery.''
the story was also reported in today's editions of the los angeles times
the idea that a man could blow out part of his frontal lobe and have his pathological symptoms cured is quite remarkable, but it is not beyond belief,'' said psychiatrist thomas ballantine of massachusetts general hospital in boston
what made the case so very interesting was that we had measured iq and done a lot of other tests before the suicide attempt,'' solyom said. ``afterward, we compared results and he had not lost anything. we used very sensitive tests to measure brain damage and could find none.''
new research indicates that as much as 3 percent of the u.s. population displays some obsessive-compulsive behavior, according to psychiatrist michael jenike of harvard university
conventional psychotherapy is useless in such victims, jenike said. the disorder is most effectively treated with a combination of antidepressant drugs and behavioral therapy
as a last resort, neurosurgeons will occasionally remove part of the left front lobe of the brain, where the obsessive behavior is thought to originate. the operation is probably performed between 10 and 30 times per year in the united states, ballantine said, with mixed results
time is running out for long-term illegal aliens to apply for amnesty under a yearlong program, u.s. attorney general edwin meese warned
the deadline for applications under the legalization program is may 4, and meese said monday there probably won't be an extension
we have 73 days, and that's plenty of time for anybody who is eligible to get their application in,'' meese said at a news conference at a san diego neighborhood ins office. he refused to discuss topics other than immigration
the immigration reform and control act of 1986 allows aliens who have lived continuously in the united states since 1981 or before to apply for residency with the immigration and naturalization service
my hope in being here today is to dramatize both the importance of the process, the desire of the u.s. government to confer legalization on everybody who is eligible, and to urge everyone in the category to apply as soon as possible,'' meese said
meese, who oversees the ins as the nation's top domestic law enforcement official, refused to comment on israeli foreign minister shimon peres' recent assertion that he wrote the attorney general in 1985 about a controversial iraqi oil pipeline project
i'm here to talk about immigration today, and that's the only topic that's appropriate,'' meese said
immigration officials have made ``tremendous strides'' in handling amnesty applications from nearly 1.3 million people nationwide, said meese, who called the program one of the justice department's key activities
the attorney general handed temporary residency cards to eight aliens who now must wait 18 months before completing the legalization process
the supreme court today limited the job protection for government workers fired for lacking security clearances
by a 5-3 vote, the justices agreed with the reagan administration that the merit systems protection board lacks authority to decide whether the denial of security clearance is justified
justice harry a. blackmun, writing for the court, said, ``it should be obvious that no one has a right to a security clearance.''
he said judgments about who should receive clearance ``must be made by those with the necessary expertise in protecting classified information'' and he said the board lacks that expertise
the court ruled against thomas e. egan, who was hired in 1981 as a laborer at the trident naval refit facility in bremerton, wash., on the condition he subsequently receive a security clearance
the facility is used to test and repair trident submarines. all jobs at the facility require security clerance
when he was denied the clearance because of two past criminal convictions, egan was fired in 1983
egan challenged the firing in an appeal to the merit systems protection board, which was created by the civil service reform act of 1978 to protect federal civilian employees from unfair disciplinary treatement
the board concluded that it lacked the authority to review egan's case. but a federal appeals court here overturned the board's decision and sent egan's case back to the board for further study
the reagan administration argued that the appeals court ruling threatened the government's ability to protect national security
dissenting today were justices byron r. white, william j. brennan and thurgood marshall
white, writing for the three, said the government's interest in protecting its secrets would not be jeopardized by granting egan a hearing before the review board
the majority's decision frustrated ... congressional intent by denying any meaningful hearing to employees such as (egan) who are discharged on national security grounds,'' he said
justice anthony m. kennedy, who joined the high court thursday, did not take part in today's decision
in other action, the court:
_ ruled that a criminal suspect's rights are not violated when a witness who is unable to identify the suspect in court testifies about an earlier identification of the accused
the justices, voting 6-2, ordered the reinstatement of the conviction of a california prison inmate in the beating of a prison guard who suffered memory loss because of the attack
_ ruled unanimously that businesses may not be sued in federal court for refusing to contribute to multi-employer union pension funds after a collective bargaining agreement expires
in an 8-0 ruling, the court rejected reagan administration arguments that barring lawsuits in such cases could undermine the solvency of the multi-employer pension plans
the security case is navy vs. egan, 86-1552
the marine corps has charged two women officers with ``fraternization and indecent acts'' with other female troops at the training base here, a spokesman said
maj. robert w. mclean, public affairs officer at the marine corps recruit depot at parris island, said a sergeant and a captain in the fourth recruit training battalion were charged friday with violations of several articles under the uniform code of military justice
he said charges against other women are being considered
an article 32 hearing, which is similar to a grand jury hearing, has been scheduled for next week,'' mclean said. ``the purpose of this hearing is to inquire into the allegations and charges and recommend disposition.''
the spokesman said the hearing could result in a recommendation for court-martial, administrative action or a recommendation that the charges be dropped
charged were capt. judy a. gretch, administrative officer for the battalion, who has been in the marines since 1981, and sgt. mary p. kile, a former drill instructor who has been in the marines since 1983, mclean said
earlier this month, the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled the army's ban on homosexual soldiers unconstitutional
but mclean said the charges are not affected by the ruling
they are not being charged with lesbianism, but with indecent acts,'' he said
capt. joanne schilling, a public information officer for marine corps headquarters in washington, said monday the corps' policy on homosexuality is the same as that of the department of defense
the uniform code states that homosexuality is ``incompatible with military service,'' and that certain overt acts are prohibited
the marines do not knowingly enlist people who are homosexual, and the type of action they take against marines who are found to be homosexual is left up to the commanding officer, said lt. col. john shotwell. it can range from an administrative discharge, under honorable conditions, to court-martial, which can include a military prison sentence
three women who said they were being investigated told the state newspaper of columbia that the marine corps had planned to court-martial or discharge as many as 10 women who train female recruits. none of the women interviewed by the state were charged friday
the women, who spoke to the newspaper on the condition they not be identified, said they and others have been accused of homosexuality, sodomy and fraternization but have not yet been formally charged. they said they are not homosexual
parris island is one of two boot camps in the country where recruits are sent for an 11-week basic training program, and the only one to which women are sent
of the 200,000 marines, roughly 10,000 are women, officials said. it deprives.</note>
a new york city law aimed at forcing some large private clubs to admit women and racial minorities as members violates ``the fundamental right of our citizens ... to choose who their friends will be,'' the supreme court was told today
alan mansfield, a lawyer for the new york state clubs association, said the city's method _ not its objective _ was based on ``a fundamentally incorrect analysis of the freedom to associate.''
the court's decision, expected by july, could carry an impact well beyond new york's borders. at least five other major cities have similar ordinances
peter l. zimroth, chief lawyer for new york city, argued that mansfield's clients have fabricated a constitutional case
it's their burden to show there are real clubs out there that would get hurt, and they haven't,'' zimroth said
both mansfield and zimroth had their arguments repeatedly interrupted with questions from the justices, including justice anthony m. kennedy, who joined the court last thursday and only recently resigned from a men-only club
kennedy appeared particularly interested in the fact that the city law exempts some clubs, such as the american legion and the protective order of elks
justice harry a. blackmun, who also recently resigned from a male-only club, did not ask a question during the 60-minute session
at one point, justice thurgood marshall suggested that the city law may be a valid attempt to battle bias, pointedly telling mansfield, ``you want to torpedo it.''
the city law exempts ``distinctly private organizations'' from its anti-bias requirements
but it deprives non-religious groups of that designation if they have more than 400 members, provide regular meal service and regularly receive payment of member dues from non-members such as employers
similar ordinances were enacted recently in buffalo, chicago, detroit, los angeles and san francisco
new york's highest court upheld the law, rejecting arguments that it unconstitutionally creates an irrefutable presumption that such organizations are not truly private
in previous rulings, the supreme court has ruled that states, through their public accommodations laws, may force the u.s. jaycees and rotary international to admit women as members
in ruling unanimously in the rotary case last may, the justices suggested that numerous other male-only or female-only private organizations may have to comply with laws requiring equal access to public accommodations
after assessing may's ruling, kiwanis international voted to end its men-only tradition and allow its 8,200 clubs worldwide to admit women
the new york state club association is composed of about 125 private clubs and associations. many of its groups are male-only or are organized along national origin or other ethnic lines
its challenge of the new york city law has been supported in the supreme court by, among others, the benevolent and protective order of elks, the loyal order of moose, the improved order of red men and the club managers association of america
the city law was defended by, among others, the u.s. conference of mayors, the council of state governments, the national association of counties, the national league of cities, the american civil liberties union and the american bar association
kennedy, the court's newest justice, was criticized during his recent senate confirmation hearings for his past membership in exclusive private clubs
kennedy quit san francisco's all-male, all-white olympic club, after he was mentioned as a possible supreme court nominee. he had been a member since 1962
he quit the all-male sutter club in his hometown of sacramento, calif., eight years ago
blackmun recently quit the cosmos club in washington, d.c., where he had held a longtime membership. the club bars women from becoming members
the case is new york state club association vs. new york city, 86-1836
a 32-year-old woman was reported missing today from a bahamas-bound cruise ship, and the coast guard sent a jet and a cutter to search for the woman
the husband of cheryl wainscott of woodstock, ga., told the captain of the carnivale that he last saw his wife at 12:30 a.m. today when she went for a walk, said coast guard petty officer joe dye
the husband said his wife had been depressed, dye said
the cruise ship radioed the coast guard at about 9 a.m. today. a falcon jet and the 95-foot cutter cape current were immediately dispatched to search an area 70 miles northeast of miami, near great isaac light, dye said
the 640-foot, miami-based carnivale is owned by carnival cruise lines. it routinely makes three- to four-day trips to the bahamas. it set sail for nassau at 4 p.m. monday on one of those voyages, said company spokesman tim gallagher
a 26-year-old pipe fitter was arrested in connection with a series of 19 sexual attacks in the san diego area blamed on a ``bolder-than-most'' rapist, police said
alvin ray quarles was arrested monday at a motel staked out by police, said officer brian monahan of the suburban national city police department
quarles was questioned by investigators at san diego police headquarters for several hours and booked into the county jail, said san diego police spokeswoman linda zweig
the series of rapes and burglaries began 14 months ago. the attacker was dubbed ``bolder-than-most'' because of the audacity of his demands and because he frequently attacked women when they were with a boyfriend or husband
quarles was charged in the investigation of two rapes and six robberies and burglaries, zweig said. the investigation is continuing and more charges may be filed, she said
quarles was arrested about 5 a.m. monday after a police detective spotted him peeking in windows and checking doors of the motel, police said, adding that a 13-inch kitchen knife was found hidden under his shirt
the arrest came an hour after a man forced his way into a room at a motel in east san diego where two elderly women were sleeping and robbed the women but did not assault them
at least 16 of the sexual assaults occurred in san diego, half of them at small motels
selection of the site to house the planned $4.4 billion ``super collider'' atom smasher has been delayed from july until late in the year, energy secretary john herrington told congress today
i would guess a preferred site would be selected in november or december,'' herrington told the interior subcommittee of the house appropriations committee
he was answering a question on whether the site would be chosen before or after the committee acts on the department's request for $363 million in construction funds for the fiscal year beginning oct. 1
i don't see us making the decision'' before the committee must act, herrington said
but he said there was little risk in appropriating the money before site selection since ``there is nothing new in the technology.''
outside the hearing room, spokesman phil keif said ``they need more time,'' but the department still hoped to hold to its original schedule of confirming the selection in january 1989
the eagerly sought scientific installation would probe the secrets of matter by whirling beams of protons into each other at an energy 20 times what is available with current machines
the most powerful current machine is the accelerator at batavia, ill. not far from the chicago district of subcommittee chairman rep. sidney yates, d-ill
yates asked herrington to comment on a newspaper report of a study from a local group claiming that locating the new machine next to the batavia installation would save the government $3.3 billion over the years through savings on components, buildings, computer programs and other facilities. but herrington said he was unfamiliar with the study
illinois, texas, arizona, colorado, michigan, tennessee and north carolina remain in the competition to house the collider
federal agents have given city police officials the names of 18 miami officers, including that of a former assistant police chief, in the latest move in an ongoing investigation of corruption in the department
since 1985, about 75 miami officers have been arrested, suspended or fired for a variety of misdeeds, from homicide to cocaine possession to prostitution and drunken driving
police chief clarence dickson has predicted that as many as 100 officers, nearly 10 percent of the force, could be involved in some level of corruption
alfredo bared, whose name was on the list fbi agents gave to miami police internal security detectives monday, is the highest-ranking person whose conduct is under scrutiny
in 26 years in the miami police department, i never did anything illegal,'' he said monday night. ``i can tell you that _ 100 percent. al bared did not do anything wrong, be it civilly, criminally, ethically or whatever.''
none of the 18 has been relieved of duty, police said monday. bared, 49, resigned in 1986
although police and the fbi have refused to discuss specific allegations, the miami herald reported that unidentified sources said they all involve drugs. 11th graf pvs, the latest</note>
former tv evangelist pat robertson is borrowing heavily going into the critical super tuesday primaries, taking out a massive $5.5 million loan for his presidential campaign, financial reports show
robertson ended january with $5.5 million in the bank, but his campaign had $6 million in debts as he far outspent any other candidate on the super tuesday contests involving 20 states on march 8
rival gop contenders george bush and bob dole, on the other hand, remained in good shape
bush, the overall fund-raising leader, ended january with $9.2 million in cash on hand and $811,029 in obligations, while dole had $4.2 million and $654,269 in bills to pay, their latest financial statements show
neither had any loans outstanding, but the other gop contender, rep. jack kemp of new york, took out $750,000 in loans to get through the iowa and new hampshire contests this month
among democratic candidates, money leader michael dukakis had the most cash available, $4 million
besides his loan, robertson reported contributions of $1.3 million during january. his report also listed as receipts the $6.5 million in federal matching funds that he applied for but had said he might not use
robertson had said he was philosophically opposed to the public financing system and his staff said he would only use matching funds if he needed to stay competitive
robertson's campaign did not return calls monday night to answer questions about the loan, by far the biggest borrowing of any campaign for the 1988 election
robertson paid off a short-term loan of $1.5 million that his attorney has said was secured with his matching funds, hisreport showed
the latest financial reports were due at the federal election commission on saturday, but robertson's was not filed until late monday
it showed that the new loan was taken out in january from sovran bank in chesapeake, va., at an interest rate of prime plus 1 percent and was due to be repaid on feb. 28
the sizable expenditures on this month's iowa and new hampshire contests and subsequent spending toward super tuesday are not reflected in the new reports, which cover the period through jan. 31
robertson has spent more than any other candidate against the overall spending ceiling which is set by election law at $27 million for the primary season. he reported spending $17.6 million against the cap
bush, conversely, while raising more money than any other candidate, has been watching his budget and has spent the least of any republican contender against the cap
he reported spending $10.7 million against the ceiling, compared with kemp's $12.8 million and dole's $13.5 million
robertson also spent the most of any campaign in a single state _ $1 million in texas, compared with bush's $335,743 and dole's $81,645
wealthy campaigns must keep from spending too much early in the campaign, because they could leave themselves unable to spend money on later contests without going over the limit
on the democratic side, none of the candidates approached the cap, with dukakis spending the most at $7.8 million
the massachusetts governor also had the biggest democratic bank account at the beginning of this month, $4 million with $511,789 in bills to pay, while the next nearest democrat, sen. al gore jr. of tennessee, had $2 million with $84,248 in obligations
sen. paul simon, d-ill., borrowed $523,674 in january and ended the month with a $691,069 debt and only $401,176 in the bank. he raised $534,259 in contributions for the month, $1.9 million in matching funds, and $523,674 in loans
rep. richard gephardt, d-mo., entered february with $820,260 in debts and $172,477 in cash on hand. he collected $212,702 in contributions and $1.9 million in matching funds during january
aides for both gephardt and simon have said that fund-raising picked up this month and that they have whittled down their debts
gore had ignored iowa to concentrate on the super tuesday states, but he raised very little money during the time the other candidates were campaigning hard in iowa and new hampshire
he collected only $180,746 in contributions during january, in addition to the $1.8 million in matching funds he got, his report showed
dukakis raised $804,839 in contributions and got $3.5 million matching funds
democratic contender jesse jackson reported raising $610,036 in donations, plus $598,021 in matching funds during january, ending the month with $509,978 in cash on hand and $354,881 in obligations
former colorado sen. gary hart ended the month with $615,547 in cash on hand and $24,484 in debts after collecting $70,303 in contributions and $937,325 in matching funds
kemp continued a hand-to-mouth campaign, ending january with a debt of $1.3 million after raising $1 million for the month. however, his political director, charlie black, said the debt would be wiped out when kemp's federal mathching funds come in this month
he insisted the campaign is not in financial trouble, saying a heavy mail solicitation program and fund-raising events are reaping about $400,000 a week
dole raised $1.2 million in contributions for january and got $5.6 in matching funds, while bush collected $767,892 privately and got $6.4 million in matching funds
most candidates got very large matching fund payments in january because that was the first months the money was released, and the sums were based on the candidates' fund raising for all preceding months
candidates can get matching funds from the federal treasury for each contribution of $250 or less that they raise in private funds. the matching fund is supported by the $1 checkoff on individual income tax returns
the supreme court, rejecting claims by private landowners, ruled today that the state of mississippi owns thousands of acres of oil- and gas-rich land near the state's gulf coast
by a 5-3 vote, the justices said states may claim title to land beneath waters subject to the tie's influence _ and not only land under navigable waters
the ebb and flow of the tide, not navigability, determines the state's ownership, said justice byron r. white for the court
states have interests in lands beneath tidal waters which have nothing to do with navigation,'' white said. those interests range from protecting fishing to setting aside submerged land for reclamation for urban expansion, he said
it would be odd to acknowledge such diverse uses of public trust tidelands and then suggest that the sole measure of the expanse of such lands is the navigability of the waters over them,'' white said
the court rejected an appeal by private landowners and companies that included phillips petroleum and a partnership called cinque bambini
they challenged the state's claim to some 2,400 acres of undeveloped property in hancock county, miss
the mississippi supreme court ruled in 1986 that the state has control over the land based on a grant from the federal government when mississippi became a state in 1817
the private landowners and companies based their claims on spanish land grants of 1813
the state leased 600 acres of the land to saga petroleum u.s. inc. in 1977 for oil and gas exploration
the mississippi court said the state's title extends to all land subject to tidal influence, inland to the mean high water mark
the lands in question underly non-navigable bayous and streams several miles north of the gulf coast. they are influenced by the tide since they are affected by the ebb and flow of an adjacent navigable river that flows into the gulf
dissenting today were justices sandra day o'connor, john paul stevens and antonin scalia
o'connor, writing for the three, said today's ruling will break ``a chain of title that reaches back more than 150 years'' and ``will disrupt the settled expectations of landowners not only in mississippi but every coastal state.''
justice anthony m. kennedy, who joined the court on thursday, did not take part in the decision
the case is phillips petroleum vs. mississippi, 86-870. from new york post interview with ms. giancana.</note>
people magazine paid judith campbell exner $50,000 for interviews in which she claimed to have served as a courier and contact for president kennedy and a chicago mobster, the author of the article says
kitty kelley said monday that she and exner, who claims to have arranged at least 10 meetings between kennedy and mafia boss sam giancana in the early 1960s, split a fee of ``about $100,000.''
parts of exner's story were questioned today by giancana's daughter antoinette, the author of ``mafia princess.''
ms. giancana said on ``cbs this morning'' that she never met exner but knew that she was her father's girlfriend. and she said that her father wanted to help in the alleged assassination plot against cuban leader fidel castro
but she said that as far as she knew, her father never spoke to kennedy during his time in the white house
he always told us about people he'd been with and met,'' she told the new york post in an interview. ``but not once did he say anything about meeeting kennedy. i'm sure dad would have said something.''
moreover, ``my father had an utter contempt for the kennedys. why would he ever want to meet with jfk in the white house or anywhere else?'' she said on the cbs program
ms. giancana said her father did not need kennedy's help, but that kennedy needed giancana's help in chicago while he was running for president
she told cbs it was possible that kennedy asked exner to go to giancana and ask for help, ``but how, probably, i really don't know.''
questioning exner's account that giancana gave her a note to deliver to kennedy, ms. giancana said her father did not put things in writing. ``the man had at least a little class. he never put anything in writing where they could bring it up or show it from the day he had written it.''
kelley said she first arranged to talk to exner about kennedy and giancana in 1983, but plans fell through after exner demanded at the last minute to be paid
i told her, `i don't pay for interviews. don't you just want to be honest and tell the truth?''' kelley recalled. ``but i didn't get the story because i wouldn't pay. this time, people did it.''
kelley said payment was justified now because exner has terminal cancer and ``the story is a little piece of history.''
elizabeth wagner, publicity manager at people, said the magazine had no comment on the fee
columnist liz smith reported in her column in today's new york daily news that she put kelley and exner together. smith said she did not pursue exner's story herself because ``for exner's sake, i couldn't afford to
she is suffering from terminal cancer, she needs the money to live out her days and pay medical bills, and only a magazine like people can pay the big bucks needed to offer up such a story.''
in a 1975 appearance before the senate intelligence committee, exner said she had an 18-month affair with kennedy before and after he entered the white house, and that she later had an affair with giancana. but she said she knew of no ties between the two, and that kennedy never knew of her friendship with giancana, which predated her affair with kennedy
in an interview monday on abc's ``good morning america,'' exner said she changed her story because ``things have changed dramatically for me. i've had two bouts with cancer and i've just had my lung removed and i've been given a fairly short length of time (to live.) and i was being very uncomfortable with not being able to tell the truth.''
in 1975, ``i was afraid for my life so i was afraid to tell the truth,'' she said. ``my husband and i made a very coscious decision not to tell the story.''
exner said she witnessed one of the giancana-kennedy meetings, and that she carried envelopes on many occasions between kennedy and giancana and johnny roselli, giancana's lieutenant in las vegas, nev., and southern california. she said giancana once told her he had met kennedy in the white house
kelley said kennedy apparently wanted mob assistance to win the presidency in 1960, and later to eliminate cuban leader fidel castro
giancana was murdered in 1975, roselli a year later
kelley said exner produced airplane tickets, hotel bills and appointment books from 1960 through 1962 to support her story. white house telephone logs show she had more than 70 conversations with kennedy
jeff smith, spokesman for sen. edward kennedy, d-mass., said, ``there has been no comment and there probably will not be a comment'' from the kennedy family
g. robert blakey, a professor of law at the university of notre dame and an expert on organized crime, said he found exner's story ``incredible.''
the president of the united states dealing directly with a mobster and no one knowing around him knowing about it?'' he asked
blakey, a former justice department lawyer who worked for the house committee that investigated kennedy's assassination, said congressional investigators in the 1970s verified exner's reports of her affair with kennedy
but, he said, ``my judgment was that she gave all the information she had at that time.'' pvs, swiss oilman. edits throughout to shorten.</note>
president reagan stands behind attorney general edwin meese iii in the face of disclosure of a memo to meese about payments to israeli officials ``which would be denied everywhere,'' the white house said today
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater was questioned by reporters about the memo, which was disclosed on monday. lawyers for meese said the memo gave no reason to conclude that the attorney general knew of any plans to bribe israeli officials
ed meese has been a friend and adviser (of the president) for years and years going back to california,'' fitzwater said. ````he knows him to be a man of integrity and he stands behind him.''
the memo from longtime meese friend e. robert wallach described a plan to funnel a portion of some $650 million-$700 million from an iraqi pipeline project to the israeli labor party of then-prime minister shimon peres
the wallach-meese memo is the focal point of a criminal investigation of the attorney general. at issue is whether meese knew of a possibly improper payment plan involving the israeli political party and, if so, why he did nothing about it
fitzwater turned aside most questions about the case, saying it was inappropriate to comment while it was under investigation by the independent counsel
asked whether reagan wanted meese to remain as attorney general, fitzwater said, ``absolutely. he's a good man who does good work.''
the president has full confidence in the attorney general and we don't have any comment on the documents or the case,'' the spokesman said
swiss oilman bruce rappaport was a partner in the proposed pipeline and wallach was his lawyer. backers of the project were seeking assurances that israel would not bomb the $1 billion pipeline, which was to run through iraq and jordan
wallach's sept. 25, 1985, memo to meese said that rappaport had confirmed with peres that ``israel will receive somewhere between $65-$70 million a year for ten years out of the conclusion of this project.''
what was also indicated to me, and which would be denied everywhere, is that a portion of those funds will go directly to labor,'' said the two-page memo which wallach marked ``personal &amp; confidential _ for your eyes, only.''
meese's lawyers released the memo monday, along with a handwritten note from peres to meese in which the israeli leader said of the pipeline project: ``i would go a long way to help it out. but then discretion is demanded on our part.''
peres said today that israel never opposed laying an iraqi pipeline through jordan, ``so why would anyone need to use bribes?''
the foreign minister told reporters as he toured a west bank city that ``no new documents were published that cause me concern and i have nothing to say.''
but he added, ``we all agree that we favor the laying of the pipeline. so why would anyone need to use bribes? nobody said he (meese) gave the labor party anything or proposed anything to the labor party.''
peres, who had initially denied that he had written a letter to the u.s. attorney general, said sunday that he used the highly unusual diplomatic channel of going through meese ``because i was approached by people who told me that the attorney general will deal with it.''
in his letter to meese, peres said ``i have asked my friend bruce (rappaport) and bob (wallach) to let you know the whole story and i shall depend on your judgment about the best way to handle this matter.''
peres denies he was offered a bribe or anything of value in connection with the pipeline project
independent counsel james mckay, who has been investigating the attorney general since last may 11, is trying to determine whether meese violated the foreign corrupt practices act. that law prohibits u.s. citizens from bribing foreign officials and gives the attorney general responsibility for enforcing the ban
in releasing the memo, one of meese's lawyers, nathan lewin, said in a lengthy statement that ``no one can fairly infer that mr. meese or anyone else reading the document should have understood that there was a `bribe' or `payoff' scheme to obtain the israeli labor party's support for the pipeline project.''
the words `which would be denied everywhere' did not imply illegality of any kind,'' lewin added
the fact that rappaport intended to provide large amounts of financial support to the labor party, or that through some other governmental arrangement the labor party would be receiving indirectly some of the project's proceeds, could cause political embarrassment in israel and was obviously not a matter to be publicized,'' the statement said
mr. wallach frequently used colorful phrases suggesting intrigue and secrecy in his memoranda, even on subjects that were patently innocuous.''
lewin said ``the most reasonable inference'' is that ``bruce rappaport, who had been a substantial financial supporter of the labor party, would be sharing the large amounts of money he would receive as a result of the `oil lifter rights' he held with the government of israel and with the labor party.''
the oil lifter rights placed rappaport in control of the actual production and sale of the oil. in return, rappaport was to make available to israel substantial amounts of the oil generated from the pipeline
iraq eventually backed out of the pipeline project and it was not built
meese has said he doesn't recall reading the reference in the wallach memo to payments to peres' political party. meese declined to comment on the newly released documents at a news conference monday in san diego, calif., where he was attending a meeting of u.s. attorneys
meese's lawyers said they decided to release the material because ``speculation in the media ... has so greatly exceeded reasonable bounds that the usual policy of confidentiality gives the public a misleading impression.''
the documents reveal that wallach was urging meese to take an active role in the project
in a second wallach-meese memo released monday, wallach hinted that meese might speak to secretary of state george shultz about the project and that the involvement of then-national security adviser robert mcfarlane was needed
i know it goes without saying that a discussion of this subject with the president would be most desired, and i would think most effective,'' said wallach
meese's lawyers said the attorney general ``took none of the initiatives suggested by mr. wallach.'' in a note to peres dated oct. 7, 1985, meese referred peres to mcfarlane, saying shultz had removed himself from the matter because he had worked for bechtel group inc., which was planning to build the project. river reservoirs</head>
the supreme court, in a victory for three midwestern states, today limited the secretary of the interior's authority to allocate water stored in missouri river basin reservoirs
the justices ruled unanimously that the interior secretary exceeded his authority when in 1982 he approved a contract authorizing energy transportation systems inc. (etsi) to take water from lake oahe in south dakota for a coal slurry pipeline project
the court, in an opinion written by justice byron r. white, said the 8th u.s. circuit court of appeals was correct when in 1986 it ruled that the secretary lacks the power to allocate for industrial use water stored in the river basin reservoirs
the reservoirs are not reclamation projects as defined by a 1944 federal flood control law giving the interior department power to regulate reclamation and irrigation projects, white said
agreeing with the 8th circuit court, white said the army corps of engineers was given primary authority over flood control and navigation under the 1944 act. federal officials had to get permission from the corps of engineers before removing water from lake oahe in 1982, white said
the decision is a victory for officials in missouri, iowa and nebraska, three states in the lower missouri river basin. those states had blocked the now-scraped pipeline project
as envisioned by the interior department, etsi would have moved lake oahe water to wyoming, where it would have been mixed with locally mined coal. the slurry then would have been piped for use in coal-fired steam generating power plants in the southeast
three states in the upper missouri river basin _ north and south dakota and wyoming _ opposed the 8th circuit court's ruling and had supported the reagan administration and etsi. the upper basin states said the appeals court ruling deprived them of using water within their boundaries
when the case was aired before the justices last november, one lawyer portrayed it as a dispute ``between upper and lower basin states.''
the case is etsi pipeline project vs. missouri, 86-939 and 86-941. for senator; original version moved in advance</note>
spring is right around the corner and that can only mean one thing: car dealers putting on an extra push for sales
well, ok, there are other signs of spring, among them the arrival of the first seed catalog, followed by robins and other birds to munch the seeds. but sales by auto dealerships are right up there
the average new car costs more than $12,000 and is generally the second most costly purchase made by americans. and when that much money is involved, some time and effort is called for to get the most for the money
as with most things, be prepared. car salesmen have a lot more practice at selling than most people do at buying, and allowing them to push you into a hasty decision can be a costly error
think in advance about what kind of car you want and how much you can afford to pay, and make a trip to a library to check books and magazines on new car features and prices
shopping around is important to get prices from various dealers, and make notes of the base cost they cite and the extra costs for options plus any dealer charges and other costs
if the car you want isn't available consider ordering one. it may take longer, but you can avoid paying for a lot of options you don't want
and insist on negotiating on the price. check with consumers union, publisher of consumer reports magazine, for car prices. for a charge, cu will provide a printout on any type of auto, citing the dealer's actual cost for the car and options. knowing this information can give you a real negotiating edge
the federal trade commission has put together a new car buying guide for shoppers, which includes a handy worksheet for shoppers to compare prices and options they want. copies of the ``new car buying guide'' are available at no charge from the public reference branch, federal trade commission, 6th street and pennsylvania ave., washington, d.c., 20580
a variety of auto-related booklets are also available from the consumer information center, pueblo, colo., 81009. these include ``buying a used car,' item 440t, 50 cents; ``a consumer's guide to vehicle leasing,'' item 441t, 50 cents, and ``cost of owning and operating autos and vans,'' item 442t, 50 cents
the ftc's new car guide includes a helpful list of price terms that you should know when negotiating. these include:
invoice price: the manufacturer's initial charge to the dealer. this is usually higher than the dealer's final cost because dealers often receive rebates, allowances, discounts and incentive awards. the invoice price always includes freight (also known as destination and delivery). if you are buying a car based on the invoice price, be sure freight is not added to the sales contract
base price: the cost of the car without options, but including the standard equipment, factory warranty and freight
monroney sticker price: this is the price on the label attached to the car window and is required by law. it shows the base price, the manufacturers installed options with the manufacturer suggested retail price, the manufacturer's transportation charge and the fuel economy. this label may not be removed by anyone other than the buyer
the monroney sticker price was named for the late sen. mike monroney, d-okla., who sponsored the legislation requiring it
dealer sticker price: usually on a supplemental sticker, this is the monroney sticker price plus the suggested retail price of dealer-installed options, additional dealer markup, additional dealer profit, dealer preparation and undercoating
congressional auditors said today a very preliminary survey indicates taxpayers are getting correct responses only 61 percent of the time when they telephone tax questions to the internal revenue service
however, the general accounting office, which conducted the survey, acknowledged that it is so incomplete that the results may not be valid
irs commissioner lawrence b. gibbs told a house ways and means subcommittee that a much more thorough check, by the irs itself, has found telephone ``assistors'' are giving the correct answer 74.8 percent of the time
we are obviously not satisfied with answering three out of four questions correctly at this time,'' gibbs said. ``we are not, however, totally surprised by our figures . ... the large number of tax law changes this year was bound to challenge our assistors despite our training and planning efforts.''
the commissioner noted that it is not just irs employees who are having trouble finding all the correct answers. he cited a survey of 50 tax professionals who came up with 50 different answers when asked by money magazine to calculate the taxes owed by a hypothetical family
gibbs noted that the 74.8-percent accuracy rate by irs telephone answerers this year compares with a 79-percent mark in a gao survey last year, before most provisions of the landmark 1986 tax overhaul had taken effect
jennie s. stathis, associate director of the gao, an investigative arm of congress, told the subcommittee that ``under the circumstances, we believe irs did a good job in trying to prepare its employees and the taxpaying public for the 1988 filing season.''
she said auditors found that 84 percent of taxpayers who visited irs walk-in facilities for help with their tax returns were satisfied with the assistance and that 74 percent received help within 15 minutes
however, ms. stathis said, the gao found ``the need for irs to improve the accuracy of telephone assistor responses to assure that returns are completed accurately and processed timely
she ackowledged that the gao, in checking the accuracy of irs telephone assistors, had made only 224 calls over six days, and said the results were so preliminary that they could not be projected as an accurate sampling. those calls produced correct responses 61 percent of the time, although 4 percent were not complete
the gao survey is continuing, as is the irs' own effort to check how its employees are doing. in contrast, the irs finding of 74.8 percent accuracy is based on more than 5,000 calls. suspect's id, charges; subs 9th graf, `the man ...,' with 2 grafs to udpate with comment from hostage, delete outdated material.</note>
a drifter shot two plainclothes policemen with one of their guns in a struggle on a downtown street, then took refuge in an office building where he held six hostages before surrendering, police said
police officer ed gorrell, 33, was shot in the head and was in serious condition today after surgery at brooke army medical center, hospital spokesman staff sgt. king lance said
officer onofre serna, 26, suffered a graze to the chest area and was in stable condition at medical center hospital, hospital spokeswoman ruby salazar said
the suspect, identified as david johnson, 28, was charged with two counts of attempted capital murder and was in bexar county jail in lieu of $1 million bond, said police spokesman sgt. paul buske
after the scuffle monday night with the policemen, the gunman ran into a nearby office building and took the hostages, buske said
the officers stopped the individual ... and a struggle ensued. one of the officers lost his weapon. (the suspect) picked up the weapon and several shots were fired,'' buske said
police chief william gibson said the man made no demands when he took the hostages. gibson said he didn't know immediately why the officers stopped him
the gunman fled into the travis park plaza building, took two people hostage on one floor, released them, and then took three other people hostage on the third floor. the three escaped when the gunman walked into another area to take a sixth hostage, buske said
the gunman surrendered to police shortly before 10 p.m., about an hour after he released the last hostage, following talks with police negotiators, said buske
he seemed disoriented at first, despondent, that he had gotten framed,'' hostage jerry renaud said today. ``he said he wasn't there to hurt us. he said he just needed a place to hide out for the night.''
the man was described as a street person by city manager lou fox
my understanding is he (the gunman) had some mental problems and it's your typical downtown problem that we've been faced with,'' fox said
gorrell and serna were part of a downtown foot patrol aimed at deterring street crime; buske described the patrol as effective in combating downtown muggings
last month, a mentally ill homeless man shot and killed a dallas police officer in a downtown parking lot. the killing touched off a wave of public support for police when dallas police chief billy prince blamed some city council members for creating an atmosphere that led to the shooting by criticizing police
a group of legislators has nominated the overseas radio service of the british broadcasting corp. for this year's nobel peace prize
bbc chairman marmaduke hussey announced the nomination of the corporation's external services on tuesday. the bbc said there are at least 100 other nominations from around the world for this year's prize
the nobel peace prize normally is awarded to individuals, but the london-based human rights group amnesty international received it in 1977
the bbc's overseas radio services are headed by the flagship english-language bbc world service and broadcast in 37 languages to an estimated world audience of 120 million
the 22 house of commons legislators, who come from different parties, said in their letter to the oslo-based nobel peace prize committee the nomination was in recognition of the bbc's 55 years of international broadcasting
police arrested 75 people suspected of illegal drug trafficking in this northern city, authorities said tuesday
police chief umberto lucchese said the sweep was made at dawn sunday. he said warrants had also been issued to 27 people already in jail, while police were unable to track down seven others to serve the warrants
police said those arrested were suspected of involvement in small or medium-size drug operations
they said sunday's operation had no connection with the seizure last week of 187 pounds of nearly pure heroin found in two garages in a village just outside verona. police arrested three men in that case
the house foreign affairs committee today approved a resolution of support for el salvador's upcoming elections, but only after lawmakers expressed reservations about the country's human rights record
on a voice vote, the panel approved a resolution noting el salvador's efforts since 1979 to establish a constitutional system that institutionalizes an electoral process, and recognizing the large turnout in 1984 for the election of president jose napoleon duarte, despite threats of violence
the resolution, sent to the full house for a vote, ``expresses confidence that the people of el salvador will reject efforts to disrupt the election'' scheduled for march 20 to select national legislators and local officials
past elections have been plagued by threats of disruption and warnings to voters not to participate made by the leftist farabundo marti national liberation front, which is waging a guerrilla war against the duarte government
the bill was watered down slightly after rep. ted weiss, d-n.y., objected to phrasing flatly stating that el salvador has achieved a system ``which respects human liberties.'' the bill was changed to say only that the country has ``sought to'' establish such a system
give them a little credit for trying, ted,'' said committee chairman dante fascell, d-fla
weiss referred to reports that rightist death squads have resumed their activities in recent months, and noted that the country's judicial system has failed to live up to u.s. hopes
a west german living in denmark applied for political asylum after bonn requested his extradition for neo-nazi activity, a justice ministry spokesman said tuesday
thies christophersen, 70, applied for asylum on the grounds of ``political persecution'' in west germany, said spokesman clas nilas. ``we are presently considering the case according to normal procedures.''
west german authorities submitted an extradition request two weeks ago for christophersen, who has lived in denmark for two years
christophersen has published works saying there were no gas chambers in the nazi concentration camps, no mass murders and no medical experiments on humans
such material is outlawed in west germany, but not in denmark. the justice ministry, however, has expressed willingness to meet the extradition request
christophersen owns a publishing company in the town of kollund just north of the west german border that produces nazi literature. his residence and work permit was extended for five years in september
a federal judge ruled today that a confession by a suspected lebanese shiite terrorist that he had led the 1985 hijacking of a jordanian airliner was illegally obtained by the fbi
u.s. district judge barrington d. parker, who sharply criticized the fbi's interrogation, suppressed the oral and written confessions that fawaz younis made to federal agents following his sept. 13, 1987, arrest in the mediterranean after he was lured aboard an fbi-chartered yacht off cyprus
younis, a former member of the shiite amal militia, is scheduled to stand trial march 22 on charges he had led the june 11, 1985, hijacking of a royal jordanian airliner from beirut international airport
the plane was flown to several points in the mediterranean and destroyed by explosives the next day after passengers and crew were taken off the jetliner
parker ruled that fractures younis suffered on both wrists when he was slammed to the deck of the yacht by fbi agents, plus seasickness, made it impossible for him to waive rationally his rights against self-incrimination
the judge also noted that the fbi deliberately kept younis aboard a navy ammunition ship for four days during which he underwent ``relentless interrogation.''
the defendant's will was overborne by the interrogation and his capacity for self-determination was critically impaired,'' the judge said
the judge sharply criticized the fbi for taking four days to transport younis from the yacht where he was seized to an aircraft carrier from which he was flown to washington for arraignment before a federal magistrate
the slow voyage across the mediterranean appeared to serve only the government's purposes _ ample time to educe a confession. this was a clear abuse of the obligation to bring the defendant before a judiciali officer immediately following his arrest,'' parker said
justice department spokesman patrick korten said the agency had no immediate comment on parker's decision
federal prosecutors have other evidence against younis, including a videotape of him reading a statement to reporters before the plane was blown up at the beirut airport
two americans who were aboard the plane when it was stormed by five gunmen carrying ak-47 assault rifles have identified younis as leader of the hijackers
in addition, the prosecutors will be able to use the testimony of jamal hamdan, a friend of younis who lured him to the fbi-chartered yacht off cyprus on the pretext of completing a drug deal
parker found that younis ``was in an extremely weakened physical condition at the very time when he was explained his rights. in an uncertain physical condition, in an oppressive environment, and subject to relentless interrogation, younis lacked the will necessary to voluntarily waive his rights.''
the judge noted that ``the government had deliberately scheduled four days for the voyage across the mediterranean; four days which younis would be subjected to constant questioning by agents.''
while ruling the confession was illegally obtained, parker dismissed a defense motion that younis's arrest was illegal
here, at a glance, are the methods for picking delegates from south dakota to attend the 1988 democratic and republican national conventions this summer
method: caucus
date: saturday, march 12
presidential filing deadline: tuesday, december 29, 1987
non-binding presidential primary: tuesday, february 23
candidates filed: bruce babbitt, michael dukakis, richard gephardt, albert gore, gary hart, jesse jackson, paul simon
pledged delegates: 15
super delegates: 4
total delegates: 19
delegates allocated: saturday, march 12
selection of delegates: saturday, march 12 and saturday, april 23
south dakota democrats choose pledged national convention delegates through a one-tiered caucus system put in place after the national party determined the state's presidential primary was being held in violation of the rules
the primary on feb. 23 will be a non-binding ``beauty contest,'' although state party officials said they would feel bound by honor _ if not by rules _ to honor the wishes of the voters in awarding national convention delegates to presidential candidates
south dakota, which has just one congressional district, will choose 10 congressional-district delegates at a statewide caucus to be held in mitchell on march 12. the party has been compelled to provide bus transportation to any democrat needing a ride to the caucus
the state's remaining five pledged national convention delegates will be picked by the state committee on april 23 and will be allocated among presidential candidates in proportion to the results of march 12 caucus
method: primary
date: tuesday, february 23
presidential filing deadline: tuesday, december 29, 1987
candidates filed: george bush, bob dole, jack kemp, pat robertson, pete du pont, alexander haig
delegates: 18
