a white supremacist group considered dumping enough cyanide to kill 440,000 people into the water supplies of new york or washington, d.c., to create civil unrest, the group's former leader testified
james b. ellison, a key prosecution witnesses in the trial of 10 men accused of plotting the violent overthrow of the government, said one of the defendants, robert miles, gave him a 30-gallon barrel of cyanide and declared:
the ones who would be killed would not really matter. it would be a good cleansing.''
ellison also testified that in 1983, members of a white supremacist group he led had participated in a murder, robberies and attempts to blow up utility facilities
ellison is serving 20 years for racketeering and weapons violations committed when he led the arkansas-based religious-military group, called the covenant, the sword and the arm of the lord. he was arrested in 1985 after a four-day standoff
ellison, 47, said monday he agreed to cooperate with prosecutors after the government agreed to relocate and give new identities to the two women he considers to be his wives and to his nine children
miles and nine others are charged with conspiracy to overthrow the government by force. the government alleges that they and four others on trial, including aryan nations leader richard butler, espouse white supremacist goals or belong to white supremacist groups
those four, and one of the accused conspirators, are charged with plotting to kill a federal judge and an fbi agent. two are also accused of interstate transportation of stolen money. all the defendants face maximum sentences of 20 years in prison and $20,000 fines on each charge if convicted
returning to the witness stand today, ellison said that richard wayne snell, a member of his group, murdered william stumpp on nov. 11, 1983, in the robbery of a pawn shop that stumpp operated in texarkana, ark
this is what they were doing at that time,'' ellison said, referring to occasional forays involving robberies and attempts to disrupt utilities
ellison said he asked snell later why snell had killed stumpp
he said that he was an evil man, he was a jew, and that he just needed to die,'' ellison testified
snell, one of the defendants in the case, is on death row in arkansas for the murder of stumpp, and is serving a sentence of life without parole for the 1984 slaying of state trooper louis bryant
ellison said the robberies were undertaken because of an agreement made in 1983 at hayden lake, idaho, by himself and leaders of other white-supremacist groups to take action designed to bring down the government so that an all-white state could be established in the nation's northwest
in his testimony monday, ellison described how defendants william wade and his son ray wade solicited the group's help to find and kill u.s. district judge h. franklin waters and fbi special agent jack knox, both of fayetteville
he said the wades wanted to avenge the slaying of a fugitive tax protester, gordon kahl, who was killed along with an arkansas sheriff in a 1983 shootout with federal authorities at a house on land owned by william wade
knox helped prosecute people who harbored kahl, and waters presided over the trial
ellison said ray wade urged that local officials involved in kahl's death ``be hanged publicly from the lamp post there in smithville.''
the idea, ellison said, was to make an example of them so that other officials would not take similar actions
ellison testified that miles, 63, of cohoctah, mich., gave him the barrel of cyanide after ellison participated in a survivalist conference in dearborn, mich., in 1981. ellison said he also received some chemicals to make explosives and rocket propellant
he said he was wary of transporting it, but miles told him, ``you might need it sometime. it will kill a lot of people.'' the government says the cyanide was enough to kill 440,000 people
ellison testified that he, miles and defendants louis ray beam jr., 41, of houston and butler, 69, of hayden lake, idaho, discussed in 1983 using the cyanide to poison the water supplies of new york or washington, d.c., in an attempt to create public unrest and show the government was powerless. wheels; subs penultimate graf, `even though...' to correct that wallach a spokesman sted sponsor of toyota trucks; also moved for pms.</note>
eli wallach has deemed barbra streisand nuts
not exactly. but as dr. herbert a. morrison in the movie, ``nuts,'' wallach portrays a psychiatrist who is truly convinced that claudia draper, a former call girl accused of murder, is insane and therefore must be locked away. streisand, as draper, believes otherwise
as a heavy i am not well liked in the movie,'' wallach said. ``but i approached the character with the conviction that he is a professional and he made this diagnosis based on years of experience. the more this girl rants and raves, the more i am convinced of my diagnosis.''
the consummate professional, wallach has brought to the screen more than 40 years of acting experience
you know, originally i prepared for a teaching career, but due to several circumstances i missed the exam,'' he said. ``so i decided to do what i most wanted to do and that was to act.''
he began his career with a scholarship to the neighborhood playhouse in new york and made his first appearance in the equity library production of tennessee williams' ``this property is condemned.''
this became an important turning point in wallach's life, for the only other performer in the show happened to be the actress, anne jackson, who later became his wife
wallach made his broadway debut in 1945 in ``skydrift'' a short-lived production. but soon thereafter, he was cast in the broadway production of ``mister roberts,'' which starred henry fonda and ran for two years
he then went on to receive a tony award for tennesse williams' ``the rose tattoo.''
it's a shame that shows have become so expensive here in new york, because we would have less problems if everybody were able to go to the theater _ rich, poor, black, white, minorities _ everbody,'' he said
theater is not a luxury but a necessity, for theater helps people understand the human condition.''
this belief in the power of theater to reach out to people has led wallach through many plays in his long career, including ``camino real,'' ``henry viii,'' ``antony and cleopatra,'' ``waltz of the toreadors,'' ``luv'' and ``the teahouse of the august moon.''
wallach's movie career began with elia kazan's debut as a director in ``baby doll'' in 1956, for which he won britain's highest film acting honor
i used to sneer at the screen,'' wallach said, ``then i realized how hard it is
a movie has many layers _ the director wields the baton and i play the instrument. although it's a lot of hard work, i have fun and that's important
let me tell you this,'' he continued. ``the most important things in life are the right partner and your work. if you find a lifelong partner and you love your work, you are a most fortunate person.''
the 72-year-old wallach has indeed been fortunate. he and jackson have raised two daughters and a son. he has also appeared in aproximately 50 motion pictures since ``baby doll.'' he is most recognized for his role in the spaghetti western, ``the good, the bad and the ugly.''
people all over the world still come up to me on the streets and mention that movie with clint eastwood,'' he said
his other films include ``the magnificent seven,'' ``the misfits,'' ``how the west was won,'' ``cinderella liberty,'' ``the deep'' and ``tough guys.''
his most recent tv appearances include ``the executioner's song'' and an hbo movie, ``the impossible spy.''
even though he's busy with films and television _ he's also a spokesman for toyota trucks _ he still manages to keep one foot in the theater
i am like a farmer who rotates his crops, i always allocate a certain period of my time to go back to my roots _ the theater.''
president yoweri museveni reshuffled his cabinet for the second time since coming to power in 1986 and created three new posts for deputy prime ministers, radio uganda reported tuesday
the state-owned radio gave no reason for the shake-up, in which museveni kept on all 44 ministers, but transferred 32 of them to new posts
among those receiving new portfolios was stanislas okurut, the former minister of culture, sports and youth, who has not been heard from since his kidnapping two months ago by rebels in eastern uganda. okurut was named minister of labor
the new deputy prime ministers are former minister of state eriya kategaya, former foreign affairs minister paul ssemogerere, and former minister of internal affairs abubakar mayanja. samson kisekka retained his post as prime minister
museveni seized power in this east african nation in january 1986 after leading a five-year bush war. his first cabinet reshuffle was in november 1986
the week's campaign marked something of a break between new hampshire's intensive leadoff primary a week ago and the highly visible southern contests ahead
but for dole, it marked an opportunity to demonstrate strength on the heels of his new hampshire loss, and he taunted the vice president for not competing
i don't know where george bush is,'' he said in duluth. ``we're going to send him a map of minnesota so at least he gets a little idea where it is.''
but bush's aides wanted no part of two states so close to iowa, where the vice president finished a humbling third in caucuses two weeks ago. instead the vice president spent his time in south carolina, which votes on march 5, and in several super tuesday states
dole enjoyed the support of sen. larry pressler and gov. george mickelson and was a prohibitive favorite in south dakota
he looked for a boost from minnesota, as well, but sounded less confident of a victory there
party officials said minnesota was tailor-made for a robertson surprise, noting his earlier success in organizational contests such as iowa, where he finished a surprising second, and in hawaii, which he won. robertson also was well known in the state because his one-time television program was viewed widely
kemp, his candidacy on the ropes after a weak third place finish in new hampshire, purchased television advertising at the last minute in south dakota. his aides conceded in advance that minnesota looked like a lost cause because of robertson's presumed strength
among the democrats, new hampshire primary winner dukakis dreamed of a two-state sweep midwestern sweep that would clearly establish him as a candidate with national appeal
his rivals said he spent a fortune organizing minnesota, leaving gephardt, jackson and simon in his wake
south dakota was another story _ and a heated one
gephardt, anxious for a victory, aired television commercials attacking the governor. the missouri congressman also won the endorsement of sen. tom daschle, and rushed a commercial onto the air trumpeting the news
dukakis responded with a late radio advertisement responding to the attacks and pointing out that gephardt accepts political action committee campaign funds
gore also invested in television advertising in south dakota to redeem his earlier declaration that he needed to demonstrate strength outside the south
despite his initial statement that he needed a win this week to stay in the race, simon changed course and vowed to fight for the ``heart and soul'' of the democratic party until the convention. his aides conceded no victories were likely in either minnesota or south dakota
jackson made little effort in south dakota, but worked hard in minnesota in hopes of matching his double-digit showing in the iowa caucuses next door
hart said in advance he would stay in the race no matter where he finished
british travelers will no longer need a visa to visit the united states next year, officials of both countries said tuesday
the decision soothes a long-standing british irritation, since britain does not require u.s. visitors to have similar visas
officials said the change is part of a pilot program to drop visa requirements for eight countries, beginning with britain and japan. they would not identify the other six
there are a number of technical issues to be settled but we hope the new arrangement can come into force at the turn of the year,'' said a spokesman for britain's foreign office, speaking anonymously in keeping with british custom
a u.s. embassy official said less than 2 percent of british and japanese visitors cause problems on u.s. visits, such as abusing the length of stay
when the program is implemented, british travelers will be required to have only a valid passport and a return ticket and can stay in the united states for a maximum of 90 days. they will still be required to apply for a visa to work or live in the united states
the u.s. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, that last year the embassy issued 690,000 non-immigrant visas to britons. he said the number of british visitors was even higher because some traveled on multiple-entry visas
this year, the embassy expects to process 900,000 such visas, he said. contempt, picking up 7th graf pvs, `on monday ...</note>
a four-day sickout by 110 providence firefighters ended today when the firefighters returned to work after being threatened with contempt of court
but 35 of the firefighters were cited with contempt anyway by superior court judge americo campanella because they did not show up in court monday to explain why they were absent over the weekend
campanella said there was no evidence that the firefighters had not acted in concert to stay off the job in violation of a back-to-work order issued saturday by another judge. he said he would decide on penalties at a later time
the city had asked for the contempt citations even though the sickout was over in order to prevent something similar from happening in the future, said city labor attorney vincent ragosta jr. state law prohibits public safety employees from striking
everything's back to normal,'' fire chief michael f. moise said today
eighty-seven firefighters who reported for duty friday evening were kept on the job during the sickout over a contract dispute. no major fires occurred in the city during the four-day period
on monday, campanella postponed a hearing after ragosta and leo j. miller, president of the providence firefighters union, indicated that relatively few members of the union had been notified of the temporary restraining order issued by another superior court judge at the city's request saturday
miller testified he was only able to reach about half the 50 firefighters scheduled to work sunday
ragosta said the city served notices of the restraining order on 129 firefighters. another 36 were notified of monday's contempt hearing
the union represents 450 of the city's total uniformed force of 479
the dispute apparently concerns language in a contract ratified by firefighters in december that the city has yet to sign
miller asserts the city is trying to renege on a provision that calls for an officer to be placed in charge of each rescue unit. union members also complain that promises to replace worn-out or damaged equipment like boots, helmets and firecoats have not been fulfilled
all but one of the 51 firefighters scheduled to report for work at 8 a.m. saturday called in sick, moise testified monday. sixty others called in sick for the shift that was supposed to begin at 6 a.m. sunday, moise said
gov. evan mecham is as stubborn as a mule and can't govern the state, former sen. barry goldwater said today as he became honorary chairman man of john rhodes' republican gubernatorial bid
goldwater, who backed mecham, a fellow republican, during the 1986 campaign, said at a news conference today that the endorsement was a mistake
he screwed up too much ... he turned out wrong,'' goldwater told reporters
you look back over all the governors that we've had in this state,'' said the senator, who has been considered the patriarch of the arizona gop. ``we''ve had some darn good ones and we've had some mediocre ones, but it took us a long time to get a really bad one.''
nonetheless, goldwater said mecham will be difficult to beat in the may 17 recall election because he still has a strong core of support despite the governor's indictment on criminal charges and upcoming impeachment trial
rhodes, a former 30-year congressman, will face mecham and democrat carolyn warner in the recall vote
goldwater contended mecham was too wrapped up in defending himself against the impeachment and criminal charges during recent months to spend much time governing the state
mecham gave up the acting governorship to democrat rose mofford when he was impeached on feb. 5. his senate trial is scheduled to begin monday on charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan, misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership, and trying to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official
even if he could solve his legal problems, however, goldwater said he does not believe mecham can govern the state
he is a very obstinate man,'' goldwater said. ``i used to drive mules and he's a lot like a mule.''
goldwater said he doesn't see much difference between rhodes and mrs. warner, except that he believes rhodes has more experience
hank williams jr., country music's rowdy outlaw, and gentle ex-frycook and grammy nominee randy travis swept today's academy of country music nominations
williams, last year's acm entertainer of the year, and travis, who swept the awards show in 1987 with four trophies, will face each other in entertainer of the year, top male vocalist, single song, album and video categories
the surprise was the poor showing of the multiple grammy nominee ``trio'' album, which got the academy's best album nomination but no other mention for singers dolly parton, linda ronstadt and emmylou harris
williams led with six nominations. travis had five and gentleman cowboy george strait had four, including top male vocalist, single, song and album nominations
other multiple nominees included perennial favorite alabama and newcomers k.t. oslin and ricky van shelton with three each, and the bellamy brothers, crystal gayle, the judds, reba mcentire and restless heart with two apiece
the nominees were announced during a news conference at the hollywood roosevelt hotel. ballots go into the mail to about 2,500 academy members this week, and finalists will be announced during a nationally televised two-hour nbc-tv special march 21 from knott's berry farm in buena park
the show will be hosted by williams and miss mcentire
in addition to williams and travis in the entertainer of the year category are alabama, miss mcentire and willie nelson
in the male vocalist category, williams, travis and strait are joined by ronnie milsap and steve wariner
female vocalist contenders include rosanne cash, miss gayle, miss mcentire, tanya tucker and kathy mattea
miss gayle is also in the top vocal duet category with gary morris. other contenders are foster &amp; lloyd, sweethearts of the rodeo, the bellamy brothers and the judds
the top vocal group category includes alabama, exile, highway 101, restless heart and the oakridge boys
williams' ``born to boogie'' lp got him nominations for best single, song and album of the year. travis' ``forever and ever, amen'' got nods for best single and song and his lp ``always and forever'' got him an album of the year nomination
also in the top album category is ``heart land'' by the judds and ``oceanfront property'' by strait
other top single contenders are strait's ``all my ex's live in texas,'' restless heart's ``i'll still be loving you,'' and van shelton's ``somebody lied.''
other best song nominees are miss oslin's ``80's ladies'' and van shelton's ``somebody lied.''
in the best new artist category, female contenders include miss oslin, nanci griffith, libby hurley, k.d. lang and dana mcvicker. male nominees are van shelton, larry boone, marty haggard, lyle lovett, and jo-el sonnier
in the video category, which is voted by the academy's board of directors, contenders include miss oslin's ``80's ladies,'' travis' ``forever and ever, amen,'' williams' ``my name is bo cephus,'' the bellamy brothers' ``santa fe,'' dwight yoakam's ``little sister'' and alabama's ``tartop.''
indian troops shot and killed 20 tamil civilians tuesday after four soldiers died in a ambush by tamil rebels, sri lankan military officials said
the civilians were killed after an indian army officer and three soldiers died in the ambush in kuthukudiuppu, a northeastern village in the mullaitivu district about 173 miles northeast of colombo, the officials said
the sri lankan officials could not be identified in accordance with briefing rules
a spokeswoman for the indian high commission, or embassy, denied any tamil civilians were killed. she said the body of one tamil rebel was recovered and at least 10 more rebels were believed killed
authorities clamped an indefinite curfew on the district after the violence broke out, the sri lankan officials said. they said there were reports of heavy air activity by indian troops
more than 45,000 indian troops are stationed in sri lanka to disarm tamil militants opposed to a peace accord signed last july, which grants some autonomy to minority tamils. the tamils constitute 18 percent of sri lanka's 16 million people
tamils say they are discriminated against by the majority sinhalese, who control the government and the army
the most powerful tamil rebel group, the liberation tigers of tamil eelam, has been battling indian troops since last october in the northern and eastern provinces, where most of the tamils live
also on tuesday, sinhalese extremists stabbed a police constable and a security officer guarding an injured sinhalese militant inside the colombo general hospital, a police spokesman said. he said both victims were in serious condition
the attackers are believed to be members of the people's liberation front, an ultra-nationalist organization of the majority sinhalese people that also opposes the peace accord. they escaped with their injured comrade
on monday, liberation front members raided a sri lankan army camp northeast of colombo, killing two soldiers. the attackers escaped with two chinese-made t-56 automatic rifles and 120 rounds of ammunition
the group has vowed to kill anyone who supports the indian-sri lankan accord, claiming it grants too many concessions to the tamils. sinhalese extremists already have killed more than 150 people since the accord was signed
last year, attackers believed to be members of the liberation front killed a popular sri lankan film stars and politician, vijaya kumaranatunga, who supported the peace pact. with dnc has ended and to include material on second vote being compiled on caucus night.</note>
here, at a glance, are the methods for picking delegates from minnesota to attend the 1988 democratic and republican national conventions this summer
method: caucus
date: tuesday, february 23
presidential filing deadline: none
pledged delegates: 78
super delegates: 9
total delegates: 87
delegates allocated: tuesday, february 23
selection of delegates: sunday, may 1 and sunday, june 12
minnesota democrats plan to pick national convention delegates through a four-tier caucus-convention system, beginning with precinct caucuses on feb 23. the precinct caucuses will elect delegates to the county conventions, which elect delegates to the congressional district and state conventions
under an agreement reached with the national party, the results of the presidential preference vote at the precinct caucuses will not be tabulated until march 8. this was to end a confrontation over the state's insistence on holding its leadoff event on feb. 23, two weeks earlier than allowed by national party rules
the two sides remained at odds until a few weeks ago over a plan by minnesota's secretary of state to compile a poll of the presidential preferences of delegates elected to the county conventions. the state democratic party has agreed it would lend no help to conducting the poll on precinct caucus night. those figures, which technically have no binding effect, were to be gathered by thousands of volunteers recruited by the secretary of state
the state's 51 pledged national convention delegates from congressional districts will be chosen and allocated at the congressional district conventions scheduled for april 29-may 1
the rest of the state's 27 pledged delegates will be chosen and allocated among presidential candidates at the state party convention june 10-12
former vice president walter mondale, the democratic presidential nominee in 1984, automatically will be seated as a delegate because of his position as a former party leader
method: caucus
date: tuesday, february 23
presidential filing deadline: none
delegates: 31
delegates allocated: friday, april 15 and thursday, june 16
selection of delegates: friday, april 15 and thursday, june 16
minnesota republicans begin the four-step process of picking national convention delegates with precinct caucuses on feb. 23
participants in the caucuses elect delegates to county conventions to be held between march 5-26. these conventions pick delegates to the congressional district conventions to be held between april 15-may 7; and to the state convention to be held june 16-18
the eight congressional district conventions each will choose three delegates to the national convention. the state convention will choose minnesota's remaining seven delegates at-large
minnesota gop rules do not require that participants in the state caucuses or conventions bind themselves to any presidential candidate
officials have a big selling job to do in this improverished town if 30 families are to get new homes, the mayor says
the families living in old shacks, rusting trailers and leaning houses on tchula's north side are to get new homes in about a year, but mayor david cotten says it is going to be hard to convince some that officials are trying to improve their quality of life and not swindle them
they're scared and you can't blame them,'' cotten said. ``the most devastating thing to fight is ignorance.''
cotten and u.s. rep. mike espy were on hand monday for a ground-breaking ceremony on the site of a burned-out house in the middle of a four-block strip targeted for revitalization
we're going to be tearing these down,'' cotten said of the stretch of homes. ``but this a drop in the bucket. we want to change the face of tchula. we want everyone to be a homeowner.''
when farmworkers are idle, unemployment in the central mississippi town of 2,000 can reach 85 percent, cotten said. poor housing conditions are easily visible from the road
with a $695,832 community development block grant _ federal money allocated by the state _ city and state officials are to begin razing some homes in march and refurbishing others. in place of the homes to be torn down, 30 new single-family dwellings will be built
residents who already own their land and homes will get the new homes free, and renters will have a chance to buy homes through low-interest programs, cotten said
the city also will use the money to pay half the rent of displaced homeowners during the renovations
lillie may brooks, 67, who lives alone in a home just a few feet from where ground was broken for the first new house, was suspicious of the plans
this house belongs to me and i don't want my house torn down,'' said brooks as she sat on her porch. ``this house suits me all right.''
another resident, jesse riley, watched curiously from the road while officials spoke
can they really take someone's home?'' he asked a bystander. ``it's nice but i don't see why they should take people's property.''
the mayor said many will change their minds as they understand the program
we have a lot of people here with no education,'' cotten said. ``there are many who think you're going to steal their land.''   
energy secretary john herrington told a house subcommittee tuesday he had been dealt a low blow by interior secretary donald p. hodel through hodel's interpretation of why herrington opposes one of hodel's ideas
herrington recommended that the panel not consider hodel's request for funds for what he called the ``frivolous'' idea of removing the o'shaughnessy dam in hetch hetchy valley in california's yosemite national park and draining the reservoir behind the dam
the dam provides three-quarters of san francisco's water. the city earns about $38 million a year selling water and electricity from the reservoir
rep. sidney yates, d-ill., chairman of the house appropriations interior subcommittee, said he found hodel's idea ``strange,'' and he had been ``shocked if not surprised'' that hodel proposed it last year
yates read the opening paragraph of a news article about the feud between the two cabinet secretaries describing hodel's belief that herrington was opposing removal of the dam because herrington was concerned about what it would do to his job prospects in california
that's a low blow, isn't it?'' yates said
it really is,'' herrington replied
what about this job you're going to get?'' yates asked
i don't know who fabricated that,'' herrington said
hodel has said the hetch hetchy valley, filled by the reservoir from 1913 to 1923, could relieve some of the visitor pressure on yosemite valley, which attracts more than 2 million people a year. he has said the project could not be begun for years, but is asking for $600,000 in his budget for further studies
yates asked herrington, ``your recommendation to this committee would be not to consider an appropriation which would result in a change in the status of hetch hetchy?''
herrington replied, ``that's my recommendation.''
as energy secretary, i am concerned about destroying an infrastructure that produces a substantial amount of electricity,'' he added
the generating capacity _ about 150 megawatts _ eventually will have to be replaced, ``and i just don't think enough thought has been given to the economic consequences,'' herrington said
herrington said his department estimated that removal of the dam and restoration of the valley could cost $5 billion to $6 billion, ``a lot of money for a frivolous idea.''
here, at a glance, are highlights of actions taken tuesday by the supreme court

security clearances

the court limited the job protection for government workers fired for lacking security clearances
by a 5-3 vote, the justices agreed with the reagan administration that the merit systems protection board lacks authority to decide whether the denial of security clearance is justified
the case is navy vs. egan, 86-1552

criminal identification

the court ruled that a criminal suspect's rights are not violated when a witness who is unable to identify the suspect in court testifies about an earlier identification of the accused
the justices, voting 6-2, ordered the reinstatement of the conviction of a california prison inmate in the beating of a prison guard who suffered memory loss because of the attack
the case is u.s. vs. owens, 86-877

pension funds

the court ruled that businesses may not be sued in federal court for refusing to contribute to multi-employer union pension funds after a collective bargaining agreement expires
in an 8-0 ruling, the court rejected reagan administration arguments that barring lawsuits in such cases could undermine the solvency of the multi-employer pension plans
the case is welfare trust fund vs. advanced lightweight concrete, 85-2079

gulf coast

the court, rejecting claims by private landowners, ruled that the state of mississippi owns thousands of acres of oil- and gas-rich land near the state's gulf coast
by a 5-3 vote, the justices said states may claim title to land beneath waters subject to the tie's influence _ and not only land under navigable waters
the case is phillips petroleum vs. mississippi, 86-870

missouri river basin

the court, in a victory for three midwestern states, today limited the secretary of the interior's authority to allocate water stored in missouri river basin reservoirs
the justices ruled unanimously that the interior secretary exceeded his authority when in 1982 he approved a contract authorizing energy transportation systems inc. (etsi) to take water from lake oahe in south dakota for a coal slurry pipeline project
the case is etsi pipeline project vs. missouri, 86-939 and 86-941
afghan insurgents announced plans tuesday to replace the communist regime with an islamic government, which they said would promote peace and ensure the safe withdrawal of soviet troops from afghanistan
the guerrilla alliance said the civil war would not end until such a government was established to guide the way to a nation called ``the islamic state of afghanistan.''
president najib responded that a new government should be formed after the soviets withdraw, and is a matter for ``afghans alone.''
kabul radio quoted najib as saying: ``no one can direct the afghans on this ... or give their views.''
his comments appeared to reflect the government's position that the issue of a coalition government should be settled within afghanistan, not by guerrilla leaders in neighboring pakistan
afghan guerrillas began fighting after a communist coup in april 1978 and soviet soldiers entered the country in december 1979. an estimated 115,000 now are in the country helping fight the insurgents
on feb. 8, soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev offered to begin withdrawing troops may 15 if pakistan and afghanistan reach agreement by march 15 in u.n.-sponsored negotiations that resume in geneva next week. he said the pullout could be accompalished in 10 months
islamic unity, an alliance of seven guerrilla groups, announced its plans for a government in a statement telexed from the border city of peshawar, pakistan, calling for a 28-member cabinet to replace najib's government
it said the government would consist of 14 ministers from the guerrilla leadership, seven representatives of afghan refugees and ``seven moslems presently living in kabul.''
insurgent leaders have said the moslems in kabul would include non-communists in the current administration who have not been closely involved in the war
in a separate statement, alliance leader yunis khalis said: ``as long as a single communist remains in power in kabul, the regime will have to face the mujahedeen resistance. until we have established an islamic government, we will never lay down our arms.''
about 3.5 million afghan refugees live in pakistan. most are in border cities and camps that serve as bases and supply points for the guerrillas known as mujahedeen, or holy warriors
the alliance statement said a ``supreme council'' would be the government's highest body and oversee the cabinet. its members would be leaders of the seven-party alliance based in pakistan, who would provide ``joint leadership during the interim period'' after moving to kabul
this government is proposed to replace the present regime in kabul before the signing of the geneva accords under the auspices of the united nations,'' and would ``represent all sections of the afghan nation,'' the announcement said
it said the chief cabinet minister also would be the head of state, but it did not say who would hold the post or name proposed cabinet members
another organ of government would be a consultative council of 75 members _ two from each of the 28 provinces and 19 moslem religious scholars, intellectuals and technocrats, the statement said. it said the council would make interim laws to apply until a new constitution was written
provincial councils would be in charge of regional affairs
the statement said an independent election commission would supervise the election of a constituent assembly immediately after the soviet withdrawal
in ``the islamic state of afghanistan,'' the statement said, ``the koran and sunnah (teachings and practices of the prophet mohammed) will be supreme.'' it said the country would be governed by an elected head of state and legislative assembly
a federal judge has ordered an investigation into why a doctor waited two months to disclose that one of three hemophiliac brothers exposed to the aids virus had been diagnosed with aids-related complex
u.s. district judge elizabeth kovachevich said in a court order monday that she has ``grave concerns'' with dr. jerry barbosa's statements to the press that he withheld the diagnosis out of respect for the privacy of the family of clifford and louise ray
in a medical report filed feb. 12, barbosa said ricky, 11 and the oldest of the brothers, was diagnosed with arc, aids-related complex
barbosa, a physician at all children's hospital in st. petersburg, told the st. petersburg times that he knew of the diagnosis in december but didn't report it out of concern for the rays' privacy, the times said tuesday
i left out a number of things on purpose,'' the times quoted the doctor as saying
in her order, ms. kovachevich asked a magistrate to find out what the doctor told a times reporter and who was aware of barbosa's ``intentional omissions from the medical reports and when they were aware of the omissions.''
in addition, she said she wanted to know whether attorneys told the court any contradictory medical information and whether an independent doctor should be appointed
last august, the judge ordered the desoto county school board to reinstate the three ray boys _ ricky, robert and randy. the brothers, all hemophiliacs, were barred from class after they tested positive for antibodies associated with acquired immune deficiency syndrome
during a hearing last summer, doctors said the boys probably were contaminated through plasma products used to clot their blood and showed no symptoms of having the disease
the aids virus can remain dormant for years. arc is found when the virus causes a set of symptoms that usually are considered a precursor to aids
barbosa said in his feb. 12 report that ricky's condition appeared to be stable. the boy has been treated with azt, an anti-aids drug
the ray boys' medical records are supposed to be on public file as a condition of the august injunction that returned them to school. the family, however, fled desoto county a week after classes began because of a parental boycott, bomb threats that emptied the school and a deliberate blaze that destoyed their home
they now live in sarasota, where the boys enrolled in school without objection from school officials, although some parents objected
aids is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. it is spread through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring
u.s. ambassador to ireland margaret heckler prayed at the churchyard where her grandparents are buried and visited the cottage where her father lived before he emigrated to the united states
the visit by mrs. heckler was supposed to be a secret, but people in ballysteen, a village of 200 people near the river shannon 14 miles west of limerick, found out in time to spruce up the ancestral cottage
in the tiny two-bedroom house, mrs. heckler, who has been ambassador to ireland for two years, found a loaf of home-baked bread, scones and tea laid out on the table by the villagers
limerick county council chairman paddy sheehy, who happens to be mrs. heckler's cousin, greeted her when she arrived, and the local folk music band regaled her with songs of welcome
it's a moment i've long waited to cherish,'' said mrs. heckler, 56. ``it's fascinating to see the country roads where my family once walked and to see the hills where they probably once roamed.''
mrs. heckler, a former congresswoman from massachusetts, served as the federal secretary for health and human services before being posted to dublin in january 1986
american rock star tina turner arrived here tuesday for two performances this week, accompanied by an eight-piece band and 10 tons of equipment
turner, with four grammy and two american music awards to her credit, said that she plans to concentrate on acting, which means she can't keep traveling at the same time
however, the 48-year-old singer said, she will try to satisfy her rock fans by continuing to do recordings and television specials
motherhood makes amy irving pine to play the title role in ``the taming of the shrew,'' the actress says in the march issue of vogue
since i had (3-year-old) max, my work has changed. there's less naivete to it,'' said irving, 34. ``i'm not being sent the sweet young thing parts any more.''
now, she wants to conquer a roster of illustrious roles. ``i want to play the shrew, all the shaw women. i want to do a st. joan,'' she said
when ms. irving is working, her husband, director steven spielberg, stays home with their son. when spielberg is on location, the family goes with him.  
faye dunaway, divorced from british photographer terry o'neill and back in new york after living for several years in england, says she's found new satisfaction in living alone
i am happier now than i've ever been, more centered on who i am and what i want to do, and much less dependent on whoever's around and whatever their opinions are,'' the actress says in an interview in the march issue of vogue magazine
her return to america came with the movie ``barfly,'' a film about the life of writer charles bukowski and shot in seedy locations around los angeles
speaking of her role, played opposite mickey rourke, she says, ``i found myself at a place in my life, and there was wanda at the same place
that's what i want _ to connect in my work with who i actually am. god knows i've had a lot of artifice,'' she says. ``i don't want to play any larger-than-life monsters, grotesques. i don't want to play any more queens.''
miss dunaway, who lives with her 7-year-old son, said she's not ready to make any long-term commitments in her private life
britain's princess anne met with president yoweri museveni and visited hospitals and health clinics tuesday, hours after arriving on the start of a 12-day swing through east africa
the 37-year-old princess, queen elizabeth ii's only daughter, is visiting hospitals and clinics in uganda, mozambique and somalia established by the save the children fund
the princess, who has been president of the international charity since 1971, is the first member of britain's royal family to visit this former british colony in 23 years
former defense secretary caspar weinberger became an honorary knight tuesday, joining the illustrious ranks of the defenders of queen elizabeth ii's realm
the queen herself bestowed the medals on weinberger in a simple ceremony at buckingham palace, but it doesn't mean he can call himself ``sir caspar.'' ``caspar weinberger gbe'' will have to do
in recommending him for the highest royal honor britain gives to foreigners, prime minister margaret thatcher's government was thanking weinberger for his defense of british interests, especially during the 1982 falkland islands war with argentina, when washington provided britain with crucial intelligence and logistics support
but the unassuming weinberger professed amazement at the accolade. when a reporter asked why he thought he had received it, he replied: ``i haven't the faintest idea.''
weinberger skipped the pomp and pageantry of a public investiture at buckingham palace, in which the queen would have placed a ribbon of medals over his head before an audience of hundreds
instead, he chose a 25-minute private audience with the queen attended only by his wife, jane, and foreign secretary sir geoffrey howe, who had recommended him for the honorary knighthood
as a foreigner, weinberger didn't have to bow or scrape before the queen
her majesty was nice enough just to present it to me,'' he said, pointing to the blue box he was holding
weinberger opened it for photographers, showing them the gold cross of the order of the british empire and the silver star of a knight grand cross, the highest order of chivalry for a foreigner. he did not put them on
i'm very honored, very pleased and still very astonished,'' said weinberger, who retired nov. 5 after nearly seven years as president reagan's defense chief
when the award was announced on feb. 1, reporters asked 70-year-old weinberger whether he was ready to be called ``sir cap.'' he replied: ``good god, no! our constitution has some harsh words about titles. but i really am flattered.''
actually, the title of ``sir'' is reserved for british subjects
weinberger was the 56th american to receive an honorary knighthood but only the second to receive a gbe. the other knight grand cross was awarded in 1976 to hugh bullock, president and chairman of pilgrims of the usa, an anglo-american friendship society
other americans who have been made knights of the british empire, a lower rank of chivalry, include president dwight d. eisenhower, former secretary of state dean rusk, industrialist henry ford ii, philanthropists paul mellon and john paul getty ii, actors douglas fairbanks jr. and sidney poitier and former sen. j. william fulbright, d-ark., who headed the senate foreign relations committee
the foreign office said weinberger was being knighted for his ``outstanding and invaluable contribution'' to anglo-american defense cooperation, especially his ``unfailing support and assistance'' during britain's 74-day campaign to oust argentina's invasion force from the falklands
weinberger refused to say whether the queen had spoken about the falklands or defense. ``she was very gracious as always and very generous in her remarks,'' he said, without elaborating
the private meeting took place in the queen's audience room, where the 61-year-old monarch has weekly talks with mrs. thatcher and occasionally meets other officials. it contains a piano and the blue walls are filled with paintings including two canalettos and two gainsboroughs
weinberger, who counts winston churchill among his heroes, has longstanding ties to britain
he made his debut as a british television commentator in december, when the treaty which he helped secure eliminating shorter- and medium-range missiles was signed, and he will be spending four weeks this summer as a distinguished visiting professor at edinburgh university
asked whether the honorary knighthood had made him more of an anglophile, weinberger replied: ``well, it's hard to be not.''
he then drove off with his wife to celebrate at a luncheon given by u.s. ambassador charles price ii
a judge has temporarily blocked enforcement in new york state of a federal regulation denying funds to family planning agencies that make abortion referrals
u.s. district court judge lewis stanton granted attorney general robert abrams a temporary injunction friday in its attempt to block the government from cutting funds to agencies that tell clients where they can obtain abortions
the regulation, issued earlier this year to cover title x of the public health services act of 1970, also is being challenged in other states. it was supposed to take effect march 3
city health commissioner dr. stephen joseph has called the regulation ``the worst set of federal guidelines i've seen in 25 years'' and said it would ``spread the aids virus in our community'' by barring women with aids from having abortions
the u.s.-soviet treaty eliminating medium-range nuclear missiles from europe won't hurt u.s. efforts to provide high-tech military help to nato, the chief u.s. negotiator said tuesday
this treaty does not prohibit the transfer of technology,'' maynard glitman testified before the senate armed services committee
glitman's detailed analysis was part of a thorough examination of the pact signed 10 weeks ago by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev. the treaty will eliminate all nuclear-tipped missiles with ranges of about 300 to 3,000 miles
committee members say the detailed scrutiny is needed because of disputes about the meaning of past treaties, particularly the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty
the current treaty is being considered by the senate amid a fight between the democratic-controlled congress and the reagan administration over the precise meaning of the 1972 pact and whether it banned futuristic weapons such as those being developed under the strategic defense initiative
article 14 of the intermediate-range nuclear forces (inf) treaty says neither side shall do anything, now or in the future, to undercut the pact
sen. dan quayle, r-ind., told glitman that ``i'm concerned about article 14'' because it might limit future u.s. help to other nato nations
if we don't spell out what the future obligations are,'' said quayle, ``down the road i can foresee some problems ... now is the time to give us as much running room as possible in the future for our technology.''
but glitman took the opposite approach, noting that the treaty is extremely specific in spelling out prohibited weapons, along with their components
if it is not prohibited by the treaty, we can do it,'' said glitman. later, he added that ``we're best protected by stating what we cannot do.''
glitman said the voluminous negotiating record is the best defense against future disputes about what is, and is not, covered by the treaty
he opposed suggestions by quayle and other senators that some type of amendment is needed to clarify article 14
the section is a standard clause which has been added to other treaties and it simply restates the intention of both nations to abide by the pact, glitman said
glitman cited one method in which he said u.s. aid to nato would not be affected. the treaty bans cruise missiles, he said, but it doesn't block the transfer of u.s. technology to nato nations such as great britain to develop cruise missiles
glitman said the u.s. negotiating team resisted soviet efforts to block u.s. help for nato. ``we knew their goal was to find a way to put a brake on nato activities,'' he said
reagan promised tuesday that the united states will do its part to ensure that the nato alliance remains strong, saying in an address broadcast to europe that ``our destiny is coupled with yours.''
in the address, which came a week before a nato summit meeting, reagan reaffirmed the alliance agreement that an attack on any member nation is an attack against all of them. ``simply put, an attack on munich is the same as an attack on chicago,'' he said. last 5 grafs pvs to trim.</note>
a top fbi official admitted today that some agents came ``very close'' to conducting a political investigation of anti-reagan activists, but denied they intended to do so or received any instructions from the reagan administration
oliver b. revell, executive assistant director, told a senate panel there were legitimate reasons to investigate the committee in solidarity with the people of el salvador, including possible links with salvadoran-based terrorists, and discussions by cispes members of committing violent acts
the investigation was closed down without any charges being filed, and the bureau has now begun an investigation of its agents' conduct. cispes has said it was investigated because it opposes president reagan's central america policies
several members of the senate intelligence committee told revell they remained skeptical of the fbi information that triggered the investigation in march 1983 and fueled it until it closed in june 1985
sen. arlen specter, r-pa., the former district attorney of philadelphia, said he has ``grave questions'' about revell's justifications, adding ``you have to proceed on the basis of tangible hard facts and evidence'' _ which he indicated were lacking in this case
revell, noting this was a terrorism investigation, testily replied that if the fbi always waited ``until there was tangible evidence, you would have been picking up the pieces of the bombs.''
documents previously released in the probe show that fbi agents and informants sent to spy on cispes collected so much information on peaceful protest activities that bureau headquarters was worried that the investigation had gone too far
the documents, released under the freedom of information act, have shown that while the investigation was targeted at cispes, the files eventually included information on hundreds of other individuals and groups, ranging from roman catholic nuns to union leaders who opposed reagan policies
revell said that more than a year after the investigation began, top fbi officials warned field offices about investigating legitimate political activity, beause they ``sensed'' the conduct of some agents was ``very close to the line.''
we may have seen some wavering over that line,'' he said, but maintained that the investigation was legitimate under the fbi's foreign intelligence and counter-intelligence guidelines
he flatly denied that the administration ever tried to influence the investigation, commenting, ``there's been absolutely no contact by anyone in the administration concerning tasking, opening or closing of the investigation.''
in defending the probe, revell testified that in addition to possible violence, cispes was involved in circulating forged u.s. documents and had strong ties to the u.s. communist party
some have insinuated that this investigation was politically motivated as many individuals associated with cispes were opposed to reagan administration policies in central america,'' revell said. ``nothing could be further from the truth
we did find indications that some cispes members were at least discussing and planning violence. our investigtions uncovered one cispes member who was tasked to determine response times of emergency services in a major american city; another cispes member stated he had developed a system to shut down a public utility in a major midwestern city; as well as plans to violently disrupt the 1984 republican convention.''
the bureau initiated the investigation under foreign intelligence and counter-intelligence guidelines, designed to protect the united states against crimes such as espionage and terrorism, in which foreign powers or groups are involved
these guidelines allow the fbi to focus more on politically oriented groups and their missions than on specific crimes that are planned or carried out. because of this wider latitude, some lawmakers and the american civil liberties union warn that it is easy to cross the line and investigate free speech and peaceful assembly
fbi director william s. sessions said the investigation in this case ``was predicated on information received from several sources that certain leaders and key members of cispes were involved in covertly furnishing funds and materials to a foreign terrorist organization.'' the group was identified as the fmln, the group fighting a war against the u.s.-backed government of el salvador
jerry berman, chief legislative counsel for the american civil liberties union, said the investigation should have started under the most strict guidelines, those for general criminal investigations
these investigations can only begin ``when facts or circumstances reasonably indicate that a federal crime has been, is being, or will be committed.'' if the crime has already been committed, the probe focuses on who committed the act and on securing evidence
the fbi is given greater leeway for a domestic ``intelligence'' investigation, which can focus on groups in the united states trying ``to further political or social goals through activities that involve criminal violence.''
the bureau did not place the cispes investigation under either the intelligence or general guidelines, but under the foreign intelligence and counter-intelligence rules that involve participation by foreign entities
these rules remain largely classified, but officials familiar with them say they provide the widest latitude among the different sets of guidelines
on july 26, 1984 _ some 16 months after the investigation began _ fbi headquarters sent 32 field offices a message that suggested some of them were going beyond the guidelines
some offices have reported information recently regarding political statements and political lobbying by cispes or cispes affiliates,'' it said. ``supervisors in recipient offices must carefully monitor this and related investigations and asset operations within your respective divisions to ensure appropriate direction, targeting and reporting.''
but messages from the field showed that bureaus were still confused
in august 1984 the denver office told headquarters, ``the field is still not sure of how much seemingly legitimate political activity can be monitored.''
marijuana and small traces of cocaine and methamphetamine were detected in the system of an amtrak switchman who fled his post after a washington-to-boston train derailment, officials said tuesday
thomas connor, 30, of aldan, pa., tested positive for marijuana in his blood and urine, the federal railroad administration said after receiving results from the center for human toxicology at the university of utah
in addition, there was evidence of cocaine and methamphetamine in connor's urine, but the levels were so low that the fra declined to even say they represented a ``positive'' finding under normal circumstances
connor, who has since resigned, was on duty in a control tower when the train struck a work vehicle in chester, pa., near philadelphia, injuring 25 people on the train. officials said he left his post after realizing he had failed to take the train off a stretch of track undergoing maintenance
connor did not submit to blood or urine tests until more than 72 hours after the accident. for that reason, the fra said it instructed the laboratory to test the specimens to seek the ``smallest detectable amount,'' even if it fell below the normal reporting range
fra administrator john riley said the case illustrated the importance of urine and blood tests being conducted on members of train crews involved in major accidents. that program was struck down two weeks ago by the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals, and the reagan administration is appealing
 under the provisions of the recent 9th circuit decision, it is unlikely that we could have performed these tests. neither we nor the national transportation safety board would have the benefit of the information the tests were able to provide,'' riley said
arthur donato, connor's attorney, was said to be in a meeting and unavailable for comment tuesday
marijuana can remain in the system and be detected for as long as 30 days after use. cocaine and amphetamines have much shorter detection ranges _ roughly two to five days and two to seven days, respectively
the tests found connor had 89 nanograms per mililiter of marijuana in his urine. a nanogram is one billionth of a gram. it normally takes a finding of at least 20 nanograms per mililiter to confirm the presence of the drug
fra spokesman bill loftus declined to interpret the findings, but said they will be considered in investigations of the accident by his agency and the ntsb
this does not determine what level may have been in his system at the time of the accident. it does not determine impairment. it does not determine cause,'' loftus said
an assistant conductor on the amtrak train also tested positive for marijuana, but he was not believed to have had played any role in the accident, the fra said
