the national governors' association voted after a spirited debate today to support the u.s.-canada free trade agreement despite fears that some state industries could suffer
the vote was 30 to 5, with the governors of kentucky, michigan, north dakota, west virginia and wyoming in the minority
the governors also adopted policies urging the federal government to take action on child care, including a ``modest'' commitment of funds to help poor working families
the fight against the resolution supporting the free trade agreement was led by wyoming gov. michael sullivan, who charged that american energy producers, fisheries, precious metal miners and others ``are left at a disadvantage.''
we can express our support for free trade without endorsing the agreement,'' sullivan said. he said it was premature and governors should wait until their next meeting in august to take a stand
but wisconsin gov. tommy thompson replied, ``i don't like the beer, you don't like the energy, governor sullivan, but how are we going to have some input'' in the senate ratification debate
an aide to the wisconsin governor explained that some american brewers have licensees in canada, but wisconsin's heilemann's does not and could be left at a disadvantage
but thompson said it would be ``a terrible mistake'' to spurn the agreement
illinois gov. james r. thompson said that if the governors did not put aside ``partisanship and parochial fears for the greater good of the country'' on this issue, ``then i have to say my voice would be a little softer'' when he asked congress to lay aside politics in dealing with the deficit or welfare reform
the governors, who were concluding their three-day winter meeting, did add an amendment to their resolution offered by gov. garrey e. carruthers of new mexico which said: ``the governors have significant concerns about issues created or not fully resolved by the agreement and ask to be consulted as the implementing legislation or other measures are developed to ameliorate these problems. the administration should enter into additional negotiations to address inequities regarding subsidies.''
the governors adopted a policy two years ago supporting the u.s.-canada free trade negotiations. the new policy says the governors' support ``is contingent upon canada and the u.s. doing nothing'' before the final treaty ratification to jeopardize or undermine ``the spirit and benefits of the free trade agreement.''
the governor of guam, joseph ada, expressed concern that u.s. territories were left out of the initial agreement
the governors of hawaii and maine abstained from the vote, which did not include all the state leaders, because of their concerns about the agreement, which was signed by president reagan and canadian prime minister brian mulroney on jan. 2. the agreement, which must be ratified by congress and the canadian parliament, would eliminate all tariffs between the two countries by 1999. it also would set up a new tribunal to settle future trade disputes
forty-four governors signed a letter urging the senate to pass a welfare reform bill this year and the governors also asked congress to extend through 1992 their right to issue mortgage revenue bonds. a provision in the 1986 tax reform law forbids their issuing new mortgage revenue bonds after 1988
on monday the governors went to the white house to hear president reagan make a pitch for a no-frills, $1.1 billion republican alternative to the $4.3 billion house-passed version of welfare reform. he also cautioned them to ``tread carefully'' on the issue of child care
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, a democratic presidential hopeful, called reagan's speech a disappointment. he said the president should have joined the governors' call for passage of new york sen. daniel patrick moynihan's welfare reform bill in the senate
reagan instead said he still strongly supports the less costly republican alternative that the house rejected two months ago, which would give states more flexibility in running their welfare programs. unlike the democratic bill passed by the house, it would not provide any big increase in aid to families with dependent children
the governors' policy on child care calls for the public and private sectors to work in concert on the problem, and says that despite the deficit, ``the governors believe that the federal government should begin to take action to improve child care.''
