disabled americans express greater interest in politics than other citizens, but they register and vote at a rate considerably lower than the general public, says a survey released tuesday
our findings suggest that barriers, either external or internal or both, prevent many disabled americans from converting their exceptionally high political interest into actual electoral activity,'' said humphrey taylor, president of louis harris and associates, which conducted the poll
the telephone poll of 536 disabled people nationwide found that 53 percent said they follow government and public affairs most of the time
in comparison, only 26 percent of all u.s. adults pay attention to politics much of the time, according to a 1984 national election study by the university of michigan
during the 1984 presidential campaign, 46 percent of the disabled americans were ``very much interested'' in the contest compared with 35 percent of all adults, according to the new survey, conducted in june and july 1987 by louis harris and associates
however, the interest did not translate into equal levels of registration and voting,
disabled people registered at a rate that is six points lower than the general population and voted at a rate that 12 points lower, the poll said
the most common barrier cited for disabled people was lack of transportation and difficulty in getting to the polls, problems noted by 29 percent of the respondents. twenty-one percent said it was difficult to stand or walk
the survey had a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percent
taylor said he expects the number of disabled voters to increase as states comply with federal law to make areas accessible to the nation's approximately 35 million disabled
the survey defined disabled as people with a health problem that prevented them from working, attending school or participating in other activities; people with a physical disability such as blindness, or people who considered themselves disabled
the announcement of the survey results coincided with the start of the national organization on disability's public service campaign to encourage the disabled to register to vote
the campaign included magazine ads featuring photos of former texas rep. barbara jordan and presidential press secretary james brady, and the words, ``we're here promoting voter registration for the 1988 elections.''
the ad also carries a toll-free number for registration information: 1-800-248-able
one-minute television spots also promote the hotline number
leaders of austria's three main political parties called tuesday for a reconsideration of plans to have president kurt waldheim address a ceremony on the 50th anniversary of austria's annexation by nazi germany
the debate over the solemn ceremony march 11 is the latest round in the international controversy surrounding waldheim and his role in the german army under adolf hitler
several high-ranking politicians have suggested the event should be called off, saying a waldheim speech is not the way for the country to reflect on the atrocities of the nazi era
none of the officials tuesday called for a cancellation and none said that waldheim should be barred from speaking. still, it was clear that the politicians were not satisfied with the structure of the ceremony as it stands
waldheim has consistently denied that he committed wrongdoing as a first lieutenant serving in the german army in the balkans in world war ii
an international historians' commission report released earlier this month left open the question of whether waldheim committed nazi wartime atrocities
however, the report said waldheim was ``in close proximity'' to nazi atrocities in the balkans, knew they were going on and made no attempt ot stop them. it also said waldheim concealed his wartime past
the commission, which started work in 1987, was formed after the u.s. government placed waldheim on a ``watch list'' of undesirable aliens, effectively barring him from the united states
at a joint news conference tuesday, the parliamentary leaders of the conservative people's party, the socialists and the rightist-oriented freedom party said organizers should rethink plans for the cermony which include a waldheim speech
parliament president leopold gratz, a socialist, said it is not a question of canceling the ceremony. but he emphasized a meeting of the organizers is needed ``because high officials have gone public with their questioning of the sense of the planned official ceremony.''
several thousand protesters are expected to gather outside the hofburg palace, where the ceremony is set to take place, to demonstrate against waldheim and demand his resignation
protesters, many of them opposed to waldheim, also have promised to flood heroes' square next to the hofburg on march 12, the day after the scheduled waldheim speech
gerulf stix, parliamentary leader of the freedom party, also called tuesday for a rethinking of the commemoration plans, while the tiny greens party has called for its scrapping altogether
several other political leaders also have expressed their reservations
i have misgivings about this event,'' socialist party chief fred sinowatz told reporters at a news conference monday
the former chancellor called, instead, for reflection of ``what happened on march 11, 1938 and what must be done so that such a thing never happens again.''
german troops marched into austria nearly 50 years ago, officially linking this alpine nation with hitler's third reich
austrians are marking the annexation, called the anschluss in german, as a time of reflection on the troubled past
austrian television and radio, along with many of the country's newspapers, have started programs leading up to the march 11 commemoration date. there also are films and exhibitions
u.s. ambassador to ireland margaret heckler prayed at the churchyard where her grandparents are buried and visited the cottage where her father lived before he emigrated to the united states
the visit by mrs. heckler was supposed to be a secret, but people in ballysteen, a village of 200 people near the river shannon 14 miles west of limerick, found out in time to spruce up the ancestral cottage
in the tiny two-bedroom house, mrs. heckler, who has been ambassador to ireland for two years, found a loaf of home-baked bread, scones and tea laid out on the table by the villagers
limerick county council chairman paddy sheehy, who happens to be mrs. heckler's cousin, greeted her when she arrived, and the local folk music band regaled her with songs of welcome
it's a moment i've long waited to cherish,'' said mrs. heckler, 56. ``it's fascinating to see the country roads where my family once walked and to see the hills where they probably once roamed.''
mrs. heckler, a former congresswoman from massachusetts, served as the federal secretary for health and human services before being posted to dublin in january 1986
american rock star tina turner arrived here tuesday for two performances this week, accompanied by an eight-piece band and 10 tons of equipment
turner, with four grammy and two american music awards to her credit, said that she plans to concentrate on acting, which means she can't keep traveling at the same time
however, the 48-year-old singer said, she will try to satisfy her rock fans by continuing to do recordings and television specials
motherhood makes amy irving pine to play the title role in ``the taming of the shrew,'' the actress says in the march issue of vogue
since i had (3-year-old) max, my work has changed. there's less naivete to it,'' said irving, 34. ``i'm not being sent the sweet young thing parts any more.''
now, she wants to conquer a roster of illustrious roles. ``i want to play the shrew, all the shaw women. i want to do a st. joan,'' she said
when ms. irving is working, her husband, director steven spielberg, stays home with their son. when spielberg is on location, the family goes with him
faye dunaway, divorced from british photographer terry o'neill and back in new york after living for several years in england, says she's found new satisfaction in living alone
i am happier now than i've ever been, more centered on who i am and what i want to do, and much less dependent on whoever's around and whatever their opinions are,'' the actress says in an interview in the march issue of vogue magazine
her return to america came with the movie ``barfly,'' a film about the life of writer charles bukowski and shot in seedy locations around los angeles
speaking of her role, played opposite mickey rourke, she says, ``i found myself at a place in my life, and there was wanda at the same place
that's what i want _ to connect in my work with who i actually am. god knows i've had a lot of artifice,'' she says. ``i don't want to play any larger-than-life monsters, grotesques. i don't want to play any more queens.''
miss dunaway, who lives with her 7-year-old son, said she's not ready to make any long-term commitments in her private life
britain's princess anne met with president yoweri museveni and visited hospitals and health clinics tuesday, hours after arriving on the start of a 12-day swing through east africa
the 37-year-old princess, queen elizabeth ii's only daughter, is visiting hospitals and clinics in uganda, mozambique and somalia established by the save the children fund
the princess, who has been president of the international charity since 1971, is the first member of britain's royal family to visit this former british colony in 23 years. patients</head>
doctors, dentists and other health-care workers can face penalties under the city's civil rights laws if they refuse to treat people with aids, an administrative law judge has ruled
judge william kirchgaessner, in a 17-page decision handed down monday, said that the city human rights commission's ban against discrimination in public accommodations included health-care services
the ruling in the case of john campanella, who was diagnosed as having aids two years ago, clears the way for him to file a complaint with the commission against his dentist, dr. david hurwitz. hurwitz had sent campanella a letter a year ago saying he would no longer treat campanella because of the disease
this ruling puts all health-care workers in the city, including dentists, doctors and nurses, on notice that they cannot refuse to treat people with aids,'' said lisa bloom, an attorney who represented campanella
arnold weiss, hurwitz's attorney, had filed a motion to dismiss the complaint, arguing that the commission did not have ``the authority to call a professional office a place of public accommodation.''
weiss declined to comment monday on the ruling, saying he had not yet read it, or to say whether it would be appealed
no date has been set for a hearing on campanella's complaint, ms. bloom said
aids is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. it is spread through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring
soviet president andrei gromyko was welcomed tuesday by his hungarian counterpart karoly nemeth at the beginning of a five-day visit to this reform-minded but economically stagnant soviet ally
the only official business on the calendar of the former longtime soviet foreign minister, who became soviet president three years ago, was the signing of an agreement establishing a hungarian cultural center in moscow
but a hungarian official said privately that gromyko and hungarian leaders could be expected to discuss ``everything'' about relations between the two countries
the visit officially was to mark the 40th anniversary of the feb. 18, 1948, mutual assistance pact between the two countries. and on thursday, gromyko is to give a major address to the hungarian parliament
gromyko, 78, was accompanied by a large soviet delegation, including deputy foreign minister vadim loginov and victor karpov, head of the soviet writers union. the soviets are staying until saturday morning
in a brief but ornate welcoming ceremony in the square in front of the parliament building situated along the danube, gromyko inspected an honor guard of troops and listened to a military band play the anthems of the two nations
he and nemeth then departed, presumably for private talks. representatives of the soviet delegation were to meet with reporters in the evening
the government newspaper in a banner headline across its front page tuesday said, ``we greet with sincere respect and friendship comrade andrei gromyko.''
the newspaper, magyar hirlap, noted that it was gromyko's first state trip abroad since assuming the presidency of the supreme soviet in 1985 after his long career as soviet foreign minister
the reason he chose hungary, the newspaper said, may be ``that our own efforts and initiatives are being recognized'' and that ``soviet bodies are showing a well-meaning interest in our country.''
hungary under party chief janos kadar has been a leader of economic and political reform among soviet bloc nations, and its policies in many ways parallel the changes advocated in the soviet union by mikhail s. gorbachev
but the economic success of hungary in the 1960s and '70s has given way to stagnation in the 1980s
hungarians are facing double-digit inflation and a foreign debt burden of $16 billion for a country of only 10.6 million people, the highest per capita debt in the east bloc
the economic problems and the question mark hanging over the nation as it waits the eventual retirement of kadar, who will be 76 in may, are seen as two possible topics that would come up during the gromyko visit
kadar has been general secretary of the hungarian socialist workers (communist) party since 1956
officials of the christian broadcasting network said tuesday it will stop showing ``the jimmy swaggart telecast'' while the assemblies of god minister is under church-supervised probation
cbn will air, this coming sunday, a piece we did on reverend swaggart's service last sunday,'' said benton miller, a cbn spokesman. ``after that point, we will not be airing any swaggart programming during the probation.''
swaggart, a baton rouge, la., televangelist, told his congregation sunday that he had sinned but gave no specifics following allegations of sexual misconduct
the louisiana presbytery of the assemblies of god voted monday to bar him from preaching for three months and have him undergo two years of rehabilitation. the national presbytery will make the final decision
miller said cbn would decide after the three-month probation whether to resume carrying the program
pat robertson, founder of cbn and a republican presidential aspirant, said monday that the weekend revelations about swaggart were planned by parties unknown to embarrass his campaign. robertson offered no proof to back up his allegations
the red sorghum field'' _ an epic film about seduction and war in china _ won the best-picture award tuesday at the 38th berlin film festival
the best-director prize went to canadian norman jewison for his romantic comedy ``moonstruck,'' and holly hunter was named best actress for her portrayal of an ambitious tv producer in ``broadcast news.''
joerg pose and manfred moeck shared the best-actor honors for their work in the east german entry ``bear ye one another's burden.''
twenty films from 15 countries competed for top prize at the festival, considered europe's second-most prestigious movie competition next to the cannes film festival
the red sorghum field,'' the first feature for director zhang yimou, is set in a remote province of china during the late 1920s and early 1930s. it tells the story of a young married girl who is seduced by a distillery worker and bears his child. her life is then engulfed by the japanese invasion of china
this is the first time that a chinese film has received such a great honor in europe,'' zhang said. ``i am especially happy for my friends and co-workers.''
zhang, who studied at the beijing film institute, won the best acting award at the 1987 tokyo film festival for his role in the film ``the old well.'' he belongs to a new generation of chinese movie-makers whose films examine sexuality and human emotion more realistically than past chinese films
this generation of movie-makers was very young when the cultural revolution broke out in china,'' zhang told the ap
they are the young people who experienced the cultural revolution for 10 years,'' he said. ``because of this special experience, they have an unusual point of view. they are more-future-minded, they have different expectations. they want to break with china of the past and represent the modern chinese society.''
moviegoers packed west berlin theaters during the 12-day festival, and many films were sold out several hours before their showing. long lines of people waited to buy tickets for ``broadcast news'' and ``wall street.''
the festival was to end tuesday night with a showing of steven spielberg's ``empire of the sun,'' which was not an entry in the competition
the supreme court, in a defeat for private landowners, on tuesday buttressed the power of states to control inland and coastal property affected by shifting tides
in a 5-3 ruling involving mississippi's claim to 42 acres of underwater land, the justices hotly disputed the effect of the decision
the dissenters said it threatens private property in every coastal state in the nation
but justice byron r. white, writing for the majority, said, ``we are doubtful that this ruling will do more than confirm the prevailing understanding. our ruling today will not upset titles in all coastal states.''
the ruling, involving oil- and gas-rich land near mississippi's gulf coast, said states own land beneath waters subject to the tide's influence _ and not only land under navigable waters
the ebb and flow of the tide, not navigability, determines the state's ownership as long as it previously has not relinquished a public trust claim to the tidelands, white said
states have interests in lands beneath tidal waters which have nothing to do with navigation,'' he said. those purposes range from protecting fishing to setting aside submerged land for reclamation for urban expansion, he said
it would be odd to acknowledge such diverse uses of public trust tidelands and then suggest that the sole measure of the expanse of such lands is the navigability of the waters over them,'' white said
he said tuesday's ruling is in line with longstanding tradition giving states control over tidelands
the court rejected an appeal by private landowners and companies that included phillips petroleum and a partnership called cinque bambini
the private interests challenged mississippi's claim to some 2,400 acres of undeveloped property in hancock county. lower courts granted most of the land to the private companies
but the courts said the state owns 42 acres underlying the north branch of bayou lacroix and 11 small drainage systems, about five miles from the gulf. the state leased the land to saga petroleum u.s. inc. in 1977 for oil and gas exploration
the mississippi supreme court in 1986 upheld the state's ownership of the land based on a grant from the federal government when mississippi became a state in 1817
the state court said the state's title extends to all land subject to tidal influence, inland to the mean high water mark
the mississippi land is influenced by the tide since it is affected by the ebb and flow of an adjacent navigable river that flows into the gulf
the private landowners and companies traced their claims to the underwater land back to spanish land grants of 1813
in a dissenting opinion tuesday, justice sandra day o'connor said the ruling could have sweeping impact
the court holds today that the public trust includes not only tidewaters along the ocean shore, but also discrete bodies of water that are influenced by the tide but far removed from the ocean or any navigable tidal water,'' she said
breaking a chain of title that reaches back more than 150 years, the court today announces a rule that will disrupt the settled expectations of landowners not only in mississippi but in every coastal state.''
o'connor was joined by justices john paul stevens and antonin scalia
in other decisions, the court:
_limited the job protection for government workers fired for lacking security clearances. in a 5-3 ruling involving a fired laborer at a navy installation in washington state, the court agreed with the reagan administration that the merit systems protection board lacks authority to decide whether denials of security clearance are justified
_said, 6-2 in a california case, that a criminal suspect's rights are not violated when a witness who is unable to identify the suspect in court testifies about an earlier identification of the accused
_in a victory for the states of missouri, iowa and nebraska, unanimously limited the authority of the interior secretary to allocate water stored in missouri river basin reservoirs
_unanimously ruled in a case from california that businesses may not be sued in federal court for refusing to contribute to multi-employer union benefit funds after a collective bargaining agreement expires
justice anthony m. kennedy, who joined the court last thursday, did not take part in any of the decisions
a 21-year-old white man ``taught to hate black people'' was sentenced tuesday to perform 200 hours of community service for the naacp after he admitted chasing two blacks with a baseball bat
cook county circuit judge stuart nudelman said he hoped that by working with blacks, james kalafut would overcome his prejudice
he has been taught to hate black people for some reason,'' nudelman said after the sentencing. ``i'm trying to put him in an environment where he can perhaps do some good and learn something about the people he thinks he hates and perhaps learn that his feelings are misguided.''
kalafut was charged aug. 16 after he and other whites brandishing baseball bats, throwing bottles and shouting racial slurs chased two blacks from a transit stop in gage park, a predominantly white neighborhood on chicago's southwest side
the plumbing company laborer could have been sentenced to a year in prison on his plea of guilty to aggravated assault and ethnic intimidation, the judge said
kalafut's brother, larry, is serving a six-year prison term after pleading guilty to firebombing the home of a black family who had moved into gage park, said barry silver, james' attorney
silver said the order for his client to work for national association for the advancement of colored people is ``a good sentence given the fxhat he's basically pleaded guilty to hating a minority group.''
by being with black people, he will have a chance to learn they are no different than he is except that the color of their skin is different. i think that is an important lesson for anyone to learn, especially someone who has been involved in this kind of activity,'' silver said
the attorney said james kalafut, who declined to be interviewed, was willing to give the sentence a try but was ``concerned about his own personal safety when he is in the neighborhood of the naacp,'' located on chicago's south side
he also said kalafut was concerned about being rejected by naacp officials and being ``made the scapegoat in a sort of reverse discrimination.''
the naacp plans to work hard to make sure that doesn't happen, said edward mcclellan, president of the group's south side branch
certainly we don't presume there are only white racists or what have you,'' mcclellan said. ``racism can be engendered by anyone inclined to that sort of prejudice.''
he said it wasn't the civil-rights group's job to punish kalafut. he also said he wasn't sure what type of work the group would ask him to perform
i can only hope his attitude is such that he's willing to come here and pay his debt to society,'' mcclellan said. ``i would hope that he would have some positive reflections from this experience that maybe he's been hating the wrong thing.''
nudelman said that trying to help kalafut overcome his prejudice made more sense than sentencing him to jail, ``where he won't learn anything except more hatred.''
but the judge warned, ``if he screws up and doesn't do what he's supposed to, he'll come back before me and i'll sentence him to jail.''
abc took the gold for its coverage of the winter olympics, winning the week, moving into the lead in the february sweeps and taking over second place for the season, ahead of cbs
olympics events took six places among the top 20 shows, forcing nbc into second place for the week ending feb. 21 and for the sweeps, which help determine the rates local stations charge advertisers
the opening chapter of nbc's much-ballyhooed miniseries ``noble house'' ended up 16th. however, it did beat out abc's olympics coverage for sunday night as well as the cbs movie ``bring me the head of dobie gillis.''
coverage of the olympics in calgary, canada, gave abc its first weekly victory since super bowl week, ending jan. 31. its only other first place for the season was during the world series, the week ending oct. 25
abc's coverage of the tuesday night events were first in the ratings. nbc's ``the cosby show'' was second and abc's saturday coverage was third. wednesday's coverage was seventh and thursday's was ninth
abc won the a.c. nielsen co. ratings for the week with an average of 19.4. nbc was second with 15.0 and cbs was third with 12.8. the rating is the percentage of the nation's 88.6 million households with television
the new season-to-date ratings: nbc 16.3, abc 13.8, cbs 13.6
the top 10 shows were: abc's tuesday olympics, nbc's ``the cosby show,'' abc's saturday olympics, nbc's ``a different world,'' cbs' ``60 minutes,'' nbc's ``cheers,'' abc's wednesday olympics, cbs' ``murder, she wrote,'' abc's thursday olympics, and nbc's ``family ties'' and ``alf,'' tied for 10th
abc's evening news show, benefiting from the olympics viewership, remained ahead of its rivals with a rating of 12.0. cbs was second with 11.1 and nbc third with 10.0
the lowest-rated network show was cbs' ``48 hours: campaign trail.'' here are the five bottom shows in descending order: cbs' ``houston knights,'' cbs' ``ringling brothers circus: 20th anniversary of the clown college,'' cbs' ``west 57th street,'' nbc's ``decision: 88, new hampshire,'' and cbs' ``48 hours: campaign trail.''
meanwhile, the fox broadcasting co. was also enjoying good ratings for its sunday night shows. ``21 jump street'' had its highest rating to date with 6.6, which would place it ahead of three network shows. ``married with children'' got a 5.7 rating, its highest ever. that would place it higher than the two bottom network shows. ``werewolf'' got its highest rating ever in its 8 o'clock time period, 5.1, which would give it a tie with the network's' lowest-rated show
adel ali massoud said tuesday that when soldiers took him to the mediterranean beach near his home here, beat him and buried him in the sand, they told him: ``don't think you are going to return alive.''
the 18-year-old youth and a gaza lawyer want to take the army to court over the brutality massoud says was inflicted on him. it is the second time this month palestinians have reported being buried alive by soldiers
the israeli army says it is investigating both incidents
they took me to the beach'' about a mile and a half away, massoud said. ``they attached me to a jeep and dragged me behind it through the sand and the water.''
massoud said he saw another youth on the beach, whom he identified as saleh hamad, receiving the same treatement
they put sand in my mouth and covered me with sand, then they covered me up, using their hands,'' he said
the youth said he did not know how deeply he was buried, but the weight on his chest was very heavy and he lost consciousness
the next thing i remember, i was in the hospital,'' he said
lying under a blanket on a mattress spread on the floor of his spare home in the khan yunis refugee camp, the young palestinian recounted how israeli soldiers burst into his home at 4 a.m. feb. 14
they used ladders to climb over the wall'' into the tiny courtyard in front of the house, massoud said
as family members and neighbors began to gather in the small room, he said: ``i was sleeping, here, like this. i suddenly saw soldiers. they shined a strong light in my face. they started to beat me with sticks.''
the youth said the soldiers put a chain around his neck to raise him to his feet, beat him to the ground and used the chain to raise him again
aisha ali massoud, 40, mother of adel and nine other children, said the soldiers also entered her room. she said about 15 entered the one-story house
ms. massoud said soldiers also grabbed her 10-year-old son sami, and one of them stuck a gun in sami's mouth
i grabbed for him, and they hit me here,'' she said, pointing to a fading mark on her forehead
she said neighbors told her later the soldiers had raided many houses in the neighborhood, a maze of winding, narrow alleys. they were looking for teen-aged boys, she said, but her son adel was the only one in the area
after the soldiers took adel to the beach, buried him in the sand and left, families living near the beach rescued him
of course i'm angry,'' he said. ``this is no way to treat people. they told me on the road, on the way to the beach, `don't think you are going to return alive.'''
on feb. 5, soldiers grabbed four palestinian youths and covered them up with a bulldozer in the village of kfar salem, near nablus, 40 miles north of jerusalem. the army detained two soldiers in the case, but the investigation is continuing
gaza attorney mohammed abu shaaban wants to press the case in the supreme court in jerusalem
i think we will have some problems because he and his family will be afraid,'' shaaban said. ``the military police have threatened people in other cases.''
the medical report at khan yunis' nasser hospital indicate the youth was treated in the emergency room but suffered only bruises. x-rays showed no broken bones. a doctor, speaking on condition of anonymity, said massoud's family refused to allow him to be admitted for fear the army would come for him
we aren't going to court for justice,'' shaaban said. ``we are going to court because we know all the newspapers will talk about it. that's useful. but we know we'll never get justice.''
the boy's father, ali mohammed massoud, said he too wants to push the case in the courts, but is afraid
if we go to court, the next day they will come and beat him,'' the father said. ``maybe, after it is in the press, i'll discuss it with the lawyer. ``if it makes trouble for us, we won't do it.'' warsaw pact briefing in prague; subs 17th graf ``the secretary ...'' to make shevardnadze reference conform.</note>
secretary of state george p. shultz said tuesday the soviet union has made a ``very clear'' commitment to withdraw its troops from afghanistan, even though no firm timetable has been announced
u.s. sources said the red army had begun preparations to leave. soviet soldiers were sent to afghanistan in december 1979 and an estimated 115,000 are in the country helping the communist government fight moslem insurgents
north atlantic treaty organization officials who attended a closed meeting with shultz described him as hopeful of a soviet withdrawal, but said he did not mention specific evidence that preparations were under way
shultz told reporters, when asked why he was optimistic about soviet intentions: ``their statements are very clear and very public and unequivocal, unadorned.''
a senior u.s. official, briefing reporters on condition of anonymity, said soviet troops are taking up defensive positions and dependents are being sent home. he said this was ``solid evidence'' that the soviet military intervention would end soon
the official also said soviet soldiers are not being replaced when they finish tours of duty. he spoke on shultz's flight to brussels from two days of talks in moscow
while shultz was in brussels, the kremlin's warsaw pact colleagues were briefed on the moscow talks by eduard a. shevardnadze, the soviet foreign minister
after a 2{-hour meeting with the nato allies, shultz flew to washington to prepare for a trip wednesday to the middle east, where he will meet with arab and israeli leaders about efforts to revive peace negotiations
in his remarks to reporters, shultz said he had encountered ``intense skepticism'' about the chances of a breakthrough on middle east negotiations, but the united states has ``a few ideas'' that could help end the deadlock. he was not more specific
i believe that if there are chances, even if the chances are small, it's worthwhile trying,'' he said. ``you can't be too afraid of failing.''
europeans who attended the nato meeting said the allies praised shultz and the reagan administration for making an effort on middle east peace
there was the feeling expressed that of course the situation appears deadlocked, but that nonetheless it would be worth trying now,'' one said, on condition that his name not be given
shultz said a complete soviet withdrawal from afghanistan would boost prospects for resolving other regional issues
i certainly have the sense ... that they do regard their presence in afghanistan as counterproductive at this point and they would like to leave,'' he said
on feb. 8, soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev offered to begin the withdrawal may 15 if pakistan and afghanistan reach agreement by march 15 in u.n.-sponsored negotiations that resume in geneva next week. he said the pullout could be accomplished in 10 months
kremlin officials have accused pakistan of obstructing a settlement by insisting an interim government be created in kabul to prevent protracted civil strife. about 3.5 million afghan refugees have fled to neighboring pakistan, which is eager for a solution
shultz told the nato allies the soviets decided to withdraw because they realized they could not defeat the guerrillas, who get much of their support from the united states
the secretary also reported progress on arms control in his moscow talks with gorbachev and shevardnadze
on monday, u.s. and soviet negotiators were directed to prepare within a month three draft agreements for a treaty to reduce long-range, or strategic, nuclear weapons by 30 percent to 50 percent
draft accords on verification, disposing of weapons and exchange of information are to be ready for the next shultz-shevardnadze meeting, march 22-23 in washington. the goal is for gorbachev and president reagan to sign the final treaty at a summit in moscow late this spring
cities may not promote equal opportunity by imposing blanket restrictions that force private clubs to admit women and racial minorities as members, the supreme court was told tuesday
alan mansfield, a lawyer for the new york state clubs association, said such a new york city law violates ``the fundamental right of our citizens ... to choose who their friends will be.''
but peter l. zimroth, the city's chief lawyer, said the clubs affected by the law are not intimate associations but bastions of the ``old-boy'' network where business deals are consummated
citing the example of the 10,003-member new york athletic club, zimroth asked the justices, ``can you imagine someone saying `here are 10,002 of my most intimate friends.'''
the court seemed to be confused by the widely varying views expressed by mansfield and zimroth about the law and a ruling by new york's highest state court upholding it
the justices' decision, expected by july, could carry an impact well beyond new york's borders. at least five other major cities _ buffalo, chicago, detroit, los angeles and san francisco _ have enacted similar ordinances recently
the new york city law banning discrimination by public accommodations exempts ``distinctly private organizations.''
but it deprives non-religious groups of that designation if they have more than 400 members, provide regular meal service and regularly get their members' dues paid by non-members such as the members' employers
mansfield said the city law wrongly treats any organization that meets the three criteria as non-private. ``three prongs and you're out,'' he said. ``this law incorporates a fundamentally incorrect analysis of the freedom to associate.''
mansfield said each club affected by the law should have a chance to prove that, even if it meets each of the three criteria, it is a truly private entity
zimroth said no such club has come forward. ``i don't think this is a real case,'' he said. ``the city council wasn't talking about hypothetical clubs. it was talking about real clubs.''
both lawyers were interrupted repeatedly by questions from the bench during the 60-minute argument session
justice anthony m. kennedy, who joined the court last thursday and only recently resigned from a men-only, whites-only club in san francisco, appeared troubled by the fact that the law also exempts certain ``benevolent orders'' such as the masons, loyal order of moose, protective order of elks and the knights of columbus
mansfield argued that treating various private organizations differently violates equal-protection guarantees
zimroth said new york city officials were not concerned about such organizations being used as extensions of the business office
justice harry a. blackmun, who recently resigned from a men-only club in the nation's capital, did not ask a question
one of the more animated exchanges occurred when justice thurgood marshall suggested that the challenged law was a valid civil rights measure and then said to mansfield, ``you want to torpedo it.''
the u.n. command rejected north korean charges tuesday it is building up forces for a nuclear attack and it demanded the communist nation admit it ordered the bombing of a civilian airliner
the united nations command dismissed a north korean demand that the united states and south korea call off joint military exercises, called ``team spirit.'' it accused north korea of fomenting tension on the divided korean peninsula and trying to sabotage the 1988 olympic games in seoul
the united states maintains 40,000 troops in south korea and heads the command, which represents the 16 nations that fought under u.n. auspices against north korea and china during the korean war
don't miscalculate ... the will of the world to react, with appropriate action, to continued barbaric acts of terrorism which result in the deaths of innocent people,'' said u.s. rear adm. william t. pendley, the chief u.n. command delegate
pendley demanded north korea punish those involved in the bombing last november of a south korean airliner and apologize to the world. all 115 people aboard the korean air jet were killed when it blew up nov. 29 over the andaman sea near burma
chief north korean delegate maj. gen. li tae ho said pyongyang had nothing to do with the attack and charged south korea with destroying the plane in a scheme to retain power and discredit the north
the charges were made at the first meeting of the military armistice commission since the loss of the plane. the commission polices the ceasefire that ended the korean war between north and south in 1953
north korea called the meeting to demand the united states and south korea abandon the annual ``team spirit'' exercises that start next month, charging the exercises were preparations for an american nuclear attack
you have nuclear war plans worked out,'' li charged
pendley dismissed the north korean accusations and said the exercises were lawful military activities intended to guarantee the safety of south korea
the u.n. command's delegation presented a videotape of a televised confession last month in seoul by kim hyon hui, a woman who claimed she was a north korean agent and destroyed the plane to disrupt the olympic games that start in seoul in september
ms. kim, who rode an early leg of the kal flight, took poison along with a male companion when they were detained in bahrain. the man died but she recovered
pendley said the confession was damning evidence that the north could not refute. ``you thought you had committed the perfect crime, but, like all criminals, you made a mistake,'' he said
north korea has been demanding to be a co-host of the olympic games. the international olympic committee and south korea have rejected the demand
while hundreds of university of massachusetts students discussed racism in class, a small group at neighboring hampshire college on tuesday occupied a dormitory office to protest racial attitudes at that elite school
the takeover came nearly a week after the end of a six-day occupation of a university of massachusetts building by more than 100 people protesting racial violence on campus
that occupation ended when protesters reached an agreement with the chancellor, joseph duffey, which included increased hiring of minority faculty and staff
penny premdas, a spokeswoman for the hampshire group, students of underrepresented cultures, said up to 40 students occupied the office of the dakin house dormitory, a traditional meeting place for minority students, at 8 a.m. to work on a list of demands, including that an office in the dormitory be converted into a third world cultural center
we have been to the administration several times over the past three years with our demands and concerns and nothing has been done,'' said ms. premdas, who is black. ``it's been all lip service. it seemed this was the only way to get something done.''
unlike the university of massachusetts, which has been the scene of attacks on blacks, ``we have never had any blatant physical harassment here,'' ms. premdas said. ``it has all been emotional and mental and institutional.''
a dakin house resident, marston chickering, said the occupation was ``particularly hard at this school, which has an image of being politically correct and aware.''
no one's ever satisfied at this school,'' said karen bagninm, a freshman from new york city who lives across the yard from dakin. ``everyone's always feeling belittled or discriminated against. if it's not minorities, it's females ... this is what they (the protesters) feel they have to do to get attention.''
about 100 of the 1,100 undergraduate students at the private college are minorities, said petez gluckler, a spokesman for the administration
a consultant hired by the school last year to investigate racial attitudes on campus is preparing his final report, gluckler said
the school planned to provide the protesters with food and sleeping bags, said hampshire spokeswoman lee wicks
hundreds of students at the 25,000-student university of massachusetts campus across town from hampshire attended class discussions on racism on tuesday
at least 35 classes were devoted to the topic in response to a call by the graduate student association to boycott all classes tuesday and wednesday in lieu of forums on racism, said school spokeswoman jeanne hopkins
duffey had warned in a statement against students boycotting classes and had suggested that racism discussions be held in classes. wars</head>
william l. ball iii, president reagan's new choice to pilot the navy through the shoals of pentagon budget cutbacks, was described tuesday as savvy coalition builder with years of experience at the white house and capitol hill
all of us who know him here at the white house know that the navy is getting a strong advocate and a strong fighter,'' white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said in announcing reagan's decision to nominate ball
ball, a stocky, 39-year-old who has served as the president's chief lobbyist on capitol hill since 1986, was tapped tuesday to succeed james h. webb as secretary of the navy
webb abruptly handed in his resignation monday after accusing defense secretary frank c. carlucci of scuttling administration dreams for a 600-ship navy
fitzwater, a long-time friend of ball's, described him as ``the kind of guy who knows how to build coalitions and work with people. ... he has a great love and respect for the navy and he knows how to get things done.''
the spokesman said webb's resignation had caught the administration by surprise, but that ball was easily recognized as a top candidate for the job due to naval, congressional and white house experience
he's a known quantity. everyone instantly recognized him as the perfect choice,'' fitzwater said
the spokesman said ball earned carlucci's respect in the wake of the iran-contra affair, when the legislative liaison helped the former national security adviser forge a new relationship with congress and its intelligence oversight committees. ball also worked with carlucci on the formulation of the latest budget policies, fitzwater said
he earned frank's respect. ... he knows intimately the problems frank is facing,'' the spokesman observed
fitzwater said the south carolina native has a ``wry sense of humor'' and ``is personable and savvy'' when it comes to working with congress and the military
he should have no problems,'' the spokesman predicted
prior to working in the white house, ball was assistant secretary of state for legislative and intergovernmental affairs
in 1981, he served as the chief clerk of the senate armed services committee. earlier, he had worked as the administrative assistant for former sens. herman talmadge, d-ga., and john tower, r-texas
ball was commissioned as a regular officer in the navy in 1969 and served three years aboard the guided missile destroyer uss sellers, followed by three years of service in the department of the navy
he graduated from the georgia institute of technology with a degree in industrial management
ball is married to the former patricia adkins of memphis, tenn., and has two daughters
people's court'' judge joseph wapner's word is the law on television, but not necessarily off camera, where the popular show's lawyers have agreed to pay a $2,500 settlement to a man the judge ruled against
the show's producers said the $2,500, awarded to 72-year-old former mr. america rex ravelle, marked the first time the judge has settled out of court with someone who has sued over a tv decision
the judge's decision was so bad it was unbelievable,'' said ravelle, who had sought $2,000 in back rent and return of a bedroom set he said was taken by a woman he evicted from his house
ravelle said in a recent interview that he was set up to look like a bully and a buffoon and then wapner ruled against him for dramatic effect when the show was taped dec. 4, 1985
i was instructed to project my voice and assert myself, while the defendant was submissive and scarcely audible,'' ravelle said. ``this obvious ploy clearly established me as the big, macho villain.''
wapner said he couldn't recall ravelle's case and was unaware of the settlement, but added he tries to be fair to all people on the show
i try to be fair, and our track record is there,'' said wapner, former presiding judge of los angeles superior court. ``i try to make sure that each side gets a fair shot.''
ravelle, who had sued the show for $1 million, agreed to drop the suit in exchange for the settlement last week
of approximately 2,000 small claims cases wapner has heard during the show's seven years, ravelle is one of only three disgruntled litigants to sue, said james b. pollock, vice president for ralph edwards productions, the show's producer. he is the only one to win a settlement, pollock added
participants on ``people's court'' are selected from among those who file for damages in small claims courts in 36 southern california localities. since files are open to the public, researchers can read cases and get in touch with those filing claims. those selected after phone interviews appear for personal interviews and are selected by producers for the program
all participants volunteer to take part and sign papers making it legally binding under california's law on arbitration. wapner has a private arbitration practice
the executive staff of the u.s. bureau of prisons has decided federal inmates should not have the privilege of begetting children through artificial insemination
if such a police were allowed, the government believes ``that numerous other inmates from regular prison institutions of all security levels would desire to beget children,'' according to the government's response filed monday in the case of a federal prisoner
the response was filed monday in the case of steven james goodwin, 31, a prisoner in the medical center for federal prisoners in springfield
goodwin had filed a lawsuit against the government and received a favorable ruling from u.s. magistrate james england. the judge recommended in november that u.s. district judge william r. collison rule that the bureau's lack of a policy on artificial insemination isn't a constitutionally sufficient reason to prohibit the procedure
goodwin had asked in his lawsuit that doctors be allowed to collect his sperm at the prison so it could be frozen and sent to his wife's doctor in st. louis
the executive staff of the bureau met earlier this month to consider a policy on the issue, assistant u.s. attorney david c. jones said in the government's response
if the procedure were allowed in one case, all 48 federal prisons would be affected. the prisons either would have to develop collecting, handling and storage procedures for semen, or private medical personnel would have to be allowed into the institutions, jones said
as result, the response said, the bureau believes the situation could be extremely costly or create substantial security risks
the government disagreed with england's ruling that begetting or bearing children is a fundamental right that survives incarceration. actually, begetting or bearing children is one of the many rights that is restricted by imprisonment, jones said
goodwin is serving a 14-year sentence on a charge of conspiracy to distribute cocaine
eighty-seven firefighters who had been on duty for more than three days were sent home tuesday as colleagues ended a sickout and returned to work under threats of contempt of court citations
more than 100 firefighters called in sick saturday, sunday and monday, despite a judge's order saturday that they report for duty
thirty-three firefighters who defied the order were held in contempt tuesday by another judge, americo campanella of superior court, for failure to show up in court to explain why they were absent
the firefighters had been served notice by the city to appear in court on monday
campanella's ruling stunned attorneys for local 799 of the international association of firefighters. they told campanella it was their impression he only wanted union president leo j. miller and secretary-treasurer richard kless in court
attorney harry j. hoopis said he thought his representation of the union membership as a whole, as well as miller's, was good enough to constitute the presence of the absent members
campanella, who continued the hearing on the status of the rest of the firefighters who called in sick, said he would decide later what penalty to assess against the 33
mayor joseph r. paolino urged that no jail time be imposed. however, the city continued to press for contempt citations, even though the sickout ended with the start of tuesday's day shift, to prevent something similar from happening in the future, according to city labor attorney vincent ragosta jr
the sickout, which the city is trying to prove is an illegal job action by municipal employees, cost the city about $84,000 in overtime and related expenses, estimated fire chief michael f. moise
it also meant a long haul for firefighters who went to work at 6 p.m. friday. moise kept them on duty through the sickout, but they went home tuesday
the sickout apparently stemmed from a dispute over language in a contract ratified by firefighters in december but yet to be approved by the city council
miller contends the city is trying to renege on a provision that calls for an officer to be placed in charge of each rescue unit. union members also say the city is not replacing worn-out or damaged equipment as promised
then-fbi director william webster was kept unaware of problems with a probe of anti-reagan activists, even when it became clear that some agents were investigating legitimate protest activities, a top agency official said tuesday
oliver b. revell, executive assistant fbi director, also told the senate intelligence committee that no one in the administration told the bureau to conduct the investigation
revell's testimony offered the first in-depth look at the fbi's investigations of the committee in solidarity with the people of el salvador, or cispes, which began in 1981 and ended in 1985. leaders of cispes maintain that the inquiries were politically motivated, but revell denied that charge
nothing could be further from the truth,'' he said. ``we have investigated a number of groups on the other side of the political spectrum. ..
the focus of the fbi investigations has been and is criminality, or the collection of intelligence which will keep our nation and citizens safe from terrorism,'' he said
at another point, revell said, ``i have no knowledge of any political taskings by anyone in the reagan administration of the fbi's cispes investigation.''
no criminal charges ever have been filed against cispes or any of its members
several members of the committee told revell they remained skeptical of the fbi information that triggered the investigation of cispes
sen. arlen specter, r-pa., said he had ``grave questions'' about revell's justifications, adding, ``you have to proceed on the basis of tangible hard facts and evidence'' _ which he indicated were lacking in this case
but revell noted that it was a terrorism investigation, and added that if the fbi always waited ``until there was tangible evidence, you would have been picking up the pieces of the bombs.''
earlier, specter asked revell the extent of webster's involvement in the cispes probe
he was aware of several cables sent to him for informational purposes,'' revell said. ``he did not authorize any of the activities. the supervision was at the sectional level.''
revell added that it is impossible for the fbi director to keep up with all the investigations the bureau conducts. however, he did say that in the wake of revelations about the conduct of the cispes case, ``we have taken interim steps to increase the level of review'' of sensitive probes
webster, who now directs the cia, has had no public comment on the investigation
sen. william cohen, r-maine, vice chairman of the intelligence panel, joined specter in criticizing the fbi probe
it is apparent that whatever the rationale for its initiation, it resulted in the fbi subjecting many americans and u.s. organizations to various types of scrutiny without any basis other than the exercise of their first amendment rights,'' cohen said
he later asked revell why the fbi headquarters had to send a memo on july 26, 1984, cautioning the field offices against reporting legitimate political activities by cispes
revell replied that the memo was sent because top fbi officials ``sensed'' the conduct of some agents was ``very close to the line.''
we may have seen some wavering over that line,'' he said, but he maintained that the investigation was legitimate under the fbi's foreign intelligence and counterintelligence guidelines
revell said the fbi opened its investigation into cispes on sept. 3, 1981, after the justice department requested the bureau examine whether the group was supplying money and material to leftist rebels in el salvador and therefore was required to register under the foreign agents registration act
revell described that probe as ``just a records check,'' and it was closed in february 1982
a little more than a year later, on march 30, 1983, the counterterrorism section at the fbi authorized a new investigation of cispes. this probe, revell said, was into whether members of cispes were ``engaged in international terrorism, activities in preparation therefor, or knowingly aiding and abetting the terrorists in el salvador and other countries in the conduct of international terrorist activities.''
that investigation continued for more than two years, during which time, revell said, ``we did find indications that some cispes members were at least discussing and planning violence.''
he cited an instance of a cispes member given the job of determining response times of emergency services in a major american city, another of a cispes member saying he had developed a system to shut down a public utility in a major midwestern city and a third of discussion of plans to disrupt the 1984 republican convention in dallas
angela sanbrano, executive director of cispes, who attended the intelligence committee hearing, denied afterward that any of the charges were true. she suggested that the comments about possible violent activities might have been made by someone ``planted'' at cispes meetings
revell said the fbi closed the investigation in june 1985 ``when we found there was insufficient evidence to continue the investigation.''
he said ``part of the reason for that was the disinformation and misinformation supplied to us'' by frank varelli, who told a house subcommittee last year hat he was paid by the fbi to infiltrate the dallas chapter of cispes and told the bureau what it wanted to hear
revell said earlier that the dallas fbi agent who directed varelli was investigated for ``mishandling documents, funds and direction.''
varelli has sued the fbi in an attempt to get pay he claims he is owed for his work
orders to u.s. factories for ``big ticket'' durable goods fell 2.8 percent in january, the biggest decline in a year, reflecting sharp drops in demand for aircraft and primary metals, the government reported tuesday
the commerce department said that orders for durable goods fell to a seasonally adjusted $112.23 billion last month, a drop of $3.28 billion from december
the steep decline, only the third setback in the past 13 months, followed a big december advance of 4.1 percent, the strongest rise since march
analysts said the january setback reflected a return to more normal levels of demand in both aircraft and primary metals, two categories which had seen unusually big advances in december
both the reagan administration and federal reserve chairman alan greenspan noted that the overall decline also masked pockets of strength, particularly in non-defense capital goods
the numbers that were released on durable goods, if one subtracts some of the temporary fluctuations, were really quite strong,'' greenspan said during an appearance before a house banking subcommittee
many economists are predicting that growth will slow in the first half of 1988 because of an unusually high buildup of unsold inventories which occurred at the end of 1987. but greenspan said he did not think this slowdown would deteriorate into a recession, in part because of the strength being shown in manufacturing
while we envisage sluggish growth for the period immediately ahead, there just are very few signs that we're about to tilt over'' into a recession, greenspan said
at the white house, presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said that the administration continues to believe that the trend in manufacturing ``is still healthy.''
the administration is forecasting that half of overall growth this year will come from rising factory production
private economists said they were not alarmed by the january setback, which was the biggest drop since an 8 percent fall in january 1987. they pointed to a 1.6 percent increase in orders for non-defense capital goods, the category which reflects business plans to expand production facilities
that is an encouraging sign that businessmen are not backing off from their investment plans,'' said david wyss, an economist with data resources inc., of lexington, mass
even with the setback last month, new orders were still 15.5 percent ahead of a year ago, reflecting the strong export demand caused by the decline in the value of the dollar
demand in transportation industries fell by 12.4 percent to $27.21 billion last month following an 8.6 percent advance in december, a surge which was attributed primarily to new aircraft orders placed with the boeing co. of seattle
orders for primary metals fell 15.5 percent to $10.19 billion after having shot up 10.5 percent in december. analysts said that the big december jump in orders came because of fears of pending price increases
demand for military hardware fell 12.1 percent in january to $7.86 billion
orders for electrical machinery rose 5.5 percent in january while demand for non-electrical machinery rose 5.8 percent
shipments of durable goods fell 3.3 percent to $109.26 billion following a 4.3 percent increase in december
israel's parliament on tuesday elected irish-born chaim herzog to a second five-year term as the country's president
eighty-two members of the 120-member knesset, or parliament, voted to re-elect herzog, who was unopposed. two voted against him and 18 did not vote, israel radio reported. other members were not present
the office of president is a largely ceremonial one in israel and the president has no formal party affiliation
i heartily thank the members of israeli knesset for their trust and their vote and (i) accept the knesset's decision with appreciation and gratitude,'' he said on israel radio. ``i am proud to serve the people.''
herzog, 69, was first elected to the post in march 1983
his first term in office was marked by a controversial decision to pardon shin bet security agents, including the former head of the service, avraham shalom, who were found guilty of lying in court about the beating deaths of two captured palestinian hijackers
herzog was criticized for the decision, but won praise when he took a strong moral stand against a ring of jewish terrorists jailed for crimes against arabs. he rejected a call from right-wing israelis to pardon all of them, although he did lessen the sentences of some
herzog was also praised for his behind-the-scenes efforts to end an election stalemate in september 1984 between shimon peres' centrist labor party and yitzhak shamir's conservative likud bloc. his efforts contributed to the forming of israel's unusual coalition government
herzog headed israel's military intelligence from 1959 to 1962. in 1967, he became the first military governor of the occupied west bank, captured by israel from jordan in that year's middle east war. he also served as israel's ambassador at the united nations from 1975 to 1978
a british soldier sentenced to life in prison for slaying a belfast catholic has been released from jail and returned to his regiment after only three years in prison, the army said tuesday
pvt. ian richard thain was not, however, returned to active service in northern ireland
an army statement tuesday said thain killed the man when he was 18
while the army in no way condones his action, we consider the incident to have been a tragic error of judgment made by a young man in very difficult circumstances,'' the statement said
the rev. denis faul, a roman catholic priest and human rights campaigner in northern ireland, said he had no objection to the release, but asked why similar clemency could not be shown to civilians serving life sentences for actions committed in their youth
sinn fein, the legal political wing of the outlawed irish republican army, claimed thain's release showed there was no justice in northern ireland
i'm very, very shocked and distressed. i can't believe this has happened,'' said the victim's father, jim reilly
the announcement of thain's release came amid new tension between britain and ireland
on sunday, a catholic was killed by a british soldier in northern ireland. the irish government announced it would undertake its own investigation of the slaying, even though the incident occurred in northern ireland outside dublin's jurisdiction
the irish move was seen as a calculated slight to britain, since its police force has already announced its own inquiry and the soldier has been placed in military custody
sunday's shooting of 23-year-old aidan mcanespie occurred near aughnacloy, half a mile from the frontier in county tyrone
mcanespie was killed by a bullet from an army observation tower at a checkpoint as he walked to a football match
mcanespie was a sinn fein supporter, and his former parish priest said he was harassed whenever he passed through the checkpoint. press association, the british news agency, said the soldier who fired at mcanespie told his interrogators it was an accident
thain was convicted of killing thomas reilly, road manager of the pop group bananarama, on aug. 9, 1983. he claimed in court that he fired because he believed reilly was about to pull a gun on him
the judge found thain ``deliberately untruthful.'' the private was the first soldier sentenced to life imprisonment for actions in northern ireland
thain was released on a life license, a form of parole whereby he can be reimprisoned ``should his behavior give rise to concern,'' the home office said
it said he was freed after a review by the state parole board
anglo-irish relations are already under strain on a series of issues including disputes over the extradition of ira suspects and british anti-terrorism laws which dublin sees as discriminatory toward ulster catholics
the worst tension, however, is being generated by britain's announcement last month that it will not prosecute northern ireland police officers involved in the shooting of six unarmed catholics in three incidents in 1982, despite evidence of a police conspiracy to pervert the course of justice
a memo to attorney general edwin meese iii from his friend e. robert wallach broached a proposal to bolster israel's moderate labor party against the rival likud bloc
in his september 1985 memo, made public monday, wallach stressed the need to encourage soviet leaders to allow greater jewish emigration to israel because russian jews, once they are voters in israel, tend to support the labor party
israel contends that 400,000 jews want to emigrate from the soviet union _ enough to make a difference in an israeli election, if all were allowed to resettle in israel
wallach's idea was based on the assumption that israel would call early elections no later than march 1986, but it is unclear whether an influx of russian jews could have brought about a labor victory. no election was held, and in october 1986, then-prime minister shimon peres switched jobs with foreign minister yitzhak shamir in a power-sharing arrangement
there is a need to provide israel with a increasing flow of ashkenazi jews to help balance the influx of sephardic-oriental jews who have a natural affinity and affiliation with likud,'' wallach wrote
from the standpoint of american interests, the advantage is evident,'' he added without elaboration
ashkenazi jews are those whose origins are in europe, while sephardic jews came from asia and africa. voter breakdown shows that sephardim, who constitute some 60 percent of israel's 3.5 million jewish population, tend to support likud more than they do labor
u.s. leaders in the past have said privately they feel more comfortable with labor, which exhibits greater willingness to cede lands to israel's arab neighbors in return for a peace settlement. likud is more hardline, refusing any territorial concessions
but publicly, the united states has consistently veered away from taking any stand that could be viewed as interference in internal israeli politics
the wallach-meese memo is the focal point of a criminal investigation of the attorney general. at issue is whether meese knew, from reading the memo, of a plan to pay a bribe to the labor party, and, if so, why he did nothing about it
wallach wrote that his business associate, israeli-born oilman bruce rappaport, had commissioned several public opinion polls that indicated a ``high probability'' of early elections and growing support for labor
rappaport, who resides in switzerland and is a generous contributor to the labor party, confirmed an arrangement with peres that israel would receive some $700 million over 10 years from the pipeline that would pass near the israeli border on its way from iraq to the red sea port of aqaba
what was also indicated to me ... is that a portion of those fund will go directly to labor,'' wallach wrote
the emigration issue, as outlined by wallach, revolves around soviet leader mikhail gorbachev's promise to peres to consider increasing emigration levels if the jews went directly to israel rather than to the united states, wallach said
the united states has refused to take any stand in support of direct soviet emigration to israel, saying it was up to the jews to decide where they want to live. exchange</head>
mayor raymond flynn sought the approval of the city council on tuesday for an experiment to provide sterile needles to drug addicts in an effort to curb the spread of aids
drug-users would make periodic visits to facilities yet to be established for the program and would get up to seven marked needles each time, depending on how many they returned from the previous visit
when entering the program, addicts would be offered a place, if available, at a drug treatment center. rejected offers would be renewed periodically
no one initiative to contain the virus can be the answer, other than finding a vaccine or a cure for the disease itself,'' said flynn, in a prepared statement at a closed morning meeting attended by city councilors
conventional anti-drug measures ``do not go far enough in the short term'' to curb the spread of aids, he said
addicts, their sex partners and their babies ``are the fastest growing group of aids victims,'' flynn said
among the 1,230 massachusetts aids cases reported so far, about 20 percent have involved intravenous drug users. more than 25 percent of boston's estimated 14,000 intravenous drug addicts are thought to be infected with the virus already, state officials said
council president christopher iannella is expected to assign the measure to a council committee for review at the council meeting wednesday, according to flynn spokesman arthur jones
flynn also is seeking city council's approval of a petition to the state legislature to by-pass state laws against possession of hypodermic syringes by drug addicts or against dispensing such equipment to drug addicts
reaction was mixed among city councilors. some like councilor david scondras, said after the meeting tuesday that he backed the plan because ``my instincts tell me this is a medical crisis and (politicians) should not stand in the way of what a doctor prescribes for a patient.''
councilor james kelly said he has ``strong objections.''
first, i don't think the city should be giving the appearance that we're condoning drug use, which we clearly are,'' said kelly. ``second, i don't think it'll work.''
gov. michael s. dukakis has opposed any needle exchange program and so does state public health commissioner deborah prothrow-stith
i don't think we ought to be encouraging people to shoot up with heroin. i am against it,'' dukakis told a news conference tuesday. ``if we can get people into methadone maintenance programs, needles cease to be a factor. and that is a much, much better to deal with this, in addition to treatment.''
last month, the state of new york announced a plan to distribute free needles to drug addicts in new york city
acquired immune deficiency syndrome, which has no known cure, has been found to be spread through sharing of infected intravenous needles as well as through sexual contact. it damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer
as of jan. 4, the centers for disease control in atlanta had received reports of 50,265 americans with aids, 28,149 of whom had died
a delta air lines jetliner bound from boston to salt lake city made an emergency landing tuesday at o'hare international airport after the flight crew shut down one engine, a federal aviation official said
delta flight 235, a boeing 757 flying from boston to salt lake city with 127 people on board, made an unscheduled landing at o'hare at 9:22 a.m. cst, said marjorie kriz, a spokeswoman for the federal aviation administration
no injuries were reported, she said. the jetliner landed safely and taxied on its own to a terminal, she said
they're designed to fly on one engine,'' ms. kriz said
the plane's 120 passengers and seven crew members remained on board while repairs were made, and the craft left for salt lake about 11:20 a.m., said delta spokeswoman christa anderson
the crew shut down the engine as a precaution because an indicator gauge showed low oil pressure, said a delta official reached at the company's marketing office in suburban schaumburg
the official, who declined to be identified, said that the incident would not be termed an emergency landing and that the passengers were never in danger
the active-duty strength of the nation's military services in january was virtually unchanged from the previous month but more than 12,000 below the same period last year, the pentagon said tuesday
as of jan. 31, the army, navy, marine corps and air force had 2,167,378 men and women on active duty, up 767 from dec. 31 figure
that combined total represents a decrease of 12,023, however, compared with the jan. 31, 1987, tally. the armed services reported active-duty strength of 2,179,401 a year ago
it is not unusual for military strength to swing up and down on a monthly basis during the year, primarily because of differences in the flow of new recruits. the strength totals are expected to vary even more widely than normal this year, though, because the pentagon is reducing its active-duty strength in a budget-cutting move
according to the latest ``military strength'' assessment, two of the four armed services reported declines in personnel in january from december
the marine corps reported 198,243 men and women on active duty, down 194 from december. the air force reported 604,574, down 755
the army had an active-duty strength of 778,835 as of jan. 31, up 1,155 from december. and the navy reported 585,726 on active duty last month, up 561 from december
western nations are luring away tens of thousands of poland's most skilled professionals, causing a costly ``brain drain'' of its best and brightest young people, the government charged tuesday
government spokesman jerzy urban said the west is cashing in on poland's costly investment in education and threatening to prolong his country's economic crisis
he said more than 500,000 poles emigrated to the west between 1983 and 1987, including nearly 60,000 university graduates. the losses include 19,000 engineers, 5,500 physicians, 4,800 economists and 4,000 scientists
there is a brain drain in the western emigration policy'' that makes it difficult for unskilled workers to remain abroad but which ``eagerly retains experts in demanded specialties,'' urban said
the rich west, which is criticizing socialism, is sucking from poland a part of socialism's achievement,'' he said. ``we are suffering these losses in favor of countries which in general ... are very reluctant to undertake economic cooperation with poland which would back our reforms.''
the educations of the doctors and engineers who have fled the country between 1983 and 1987 is about $100 million, urban said
urban's comments, read from a text at the beginning of his weekly news conference, mirrored charges made in november by soviet leader mikhail gorbachev
in an interview with nbc news, gorbachev replied to a question on the soviet policy toward jewish emigration by saying u.s. officials are trying to solve their problems by ``organizing a brain drain from the soviet union.''
urban did not specify what steps the government might take to stem the wave of emigration, saying he was only appealing to all poles to express their views on a problem ``for which there is no simple remedy.''
urban did say that western countries should take the consequences of the brain drain into consideration ``in balancing mutal economic relations and commitments,'' an apparent reference to poland's efforts to obtain new economic credits and a favorable debt payment rescheduling from its western creditors
urban's remarks reflect growing concern in the country to the large numbers of young professionals fleeing the country's economic crisis for greener pastures in the united states, west germany, italy and france, among other countries
last month, a joint government and roman catholic church commission expressed concern about what it called an ``alarming phenomenon'' and called for measures to convince young poles that they can satisfy their aspirations in their native country
official newspapers have printed articles about emigration, including letters from young professionals explaining why they want to leave. government polls have shown that more than half poland's youth would like to stay in the west to work for two years or more
emigration has grown since the lifting of martial law in 1983, when the government liberalized regulations for obtaining a passport to travel abroad. urban said poles made 4.2 million trips to western countries from 1983-87
he said those staying abroad were motivated by economic rather than political reasons, describing their attitude as ``mean-spirited ... turning the back on the homeland instead of working in favor of improving living conditions.''
but he added the government did not intend to withdraw from its liberalized passport policy
some soviet bloc countries, such as romania, have demanded that would-be emigres repay the cost of their education before departing
from 1983 to 1987, urban said, 58,500 people emigrated legally from poland, including 5,000 university graduates
another 117,000 people, including 16,500 university graduates, traveled to the west on business or tourist trips and then stayed permanently abroad without consent of polish authorities
he said 328,000 people, including 38,000 with university degrees, extended their stay abroad, although many were expected to return to poland, he said
bruce smart, the commerce department's top trade official since mid-1985, is resigning to return to the private sector, officials announced monday
commerce secretary c. william verity said the departure resulted from a ``difference of management styles'' between the two men
smart had been one of the leading candidates to become commerce secretary when malcolm baldrige was killed in a horse riding accident last summer. however, president reagan chose verity for the job. verity took office on oct. 19
smart had served as undersecretary for international affairs since july 1985. he reportedly had been in line to take over the no. 2 job at the commerce department as the deputy secretary, which became vacant with the departure earlier this month of clarence brown
however, in his statement, verity said, ``a difference of management styles developed between bruce smart and myself and i asked him to agree to have his name withdrawn for the position of deputy secretary.''
verity said he asked smart to continue in the trade job but that smart had declined
smart's office said he was not commenting on the announcement
a commerce department spokesman said no decision had been made on the exact date of smart's departure. the spokesman said smart did not have a specific job yet in the private sector
state prosecutors said monday they won't seek criminal charges against contractors of an apartment building that collapsed during construction in bridgeport last year, killing 28 workers
chief state's attorney john kelly and bridgeport state's attorney donald browne said investigators determined that the cause of the collapse ``did not involve intentional criminal conduct on the part of any contractor involved in the construction.''
while investigators have disclosed the most probable cause of the building collapse, we do not believe that they have demonstrated either a gross deviation from a reasonable person's standard of conduct or that the prosecution could demonstrate responsibility for criminally negligent homicide beyond a reasonable doubt,'' the prosecutors said in a statement
richard bieder, an attorney representing families of some collapse victims, said authorities probably don't know all there is to know about the accident because some people with information may not have come forward
my experience is that more of them with information will begin singing like canaries as the pressures (of lawsuits) mount,'' he said
i think there's more behind this story,'' echoed anthony petta, general manager of the waterbury foundation co. inc., which was a concrete subcontractor for the l'ambiance project and lost 11 workers in the accident. ``who knows what will happen after all of the court proceedings?''
l'ambiance plaza, a multi-story apartment complex in bridgeport's downtown, was being built in the lift-slab method. in that method, huge concrete floor slabs are poured and allowed to harden in a stack on the ground before they are jacked into place on steel columns
federal authorities concluded the april 23, 1987, collapse was triggered when a small bracket that was part of the lifting system bent under pressure
the national bureau of standards concluded that builders failed to conduct stress-analysis tests to find out if the lifting brackets, steel pieces measuring about 4 by 12 inches, could hold up the concrete slabs
the labor department assessed a record $5.1 million in fines against five companies for violations at the apartment complex. the heaviest fines went to tpmi-maycomber, a joint venture of tpm international of darien and b.h. maycomber of boston, which was the primary contractor and project manager, and texstar contruction co. of san antonio, texas
the decision announced monday by kelly and browne affects only state prosecution
a regional administrator for the u.s. occupational safety and health administration, john miles, said recently he has recommended federal criminal charges be filed as a result of the collapse. the federal review process could take months
joe egan, business agent for ironworkers local 424, which lost seven men in the collapse, said he couldn't understand the state prosecutors' decision
if there has to be criminal intent, than most manslaughter cases would have to be thrown out of court,'' egan said
bridgeport mayor thomas w. bucci declined to comment on monday's announcement except to say, ``they (kelly and browne) are both excellent prosecutors and i'm not going to second guess their decision in this matter.''
in a lawsuit filed oct. 28 by the victims' families, the city was accused of negligence in issuing a building permit for l'ambiance plaza and in inspecting construction of the building
david turlington, a lawyer for texstar construction co. of san antonio, texas, said connecticut's decision verifies ``that ... the cause of the disaster has not been determined and texstar continues to dispute the findings by the national bureau of standards and osha.''
they had the goods on bucky. even if he'd had an alibi, he wasn't in a position to tell anyone about it
but when hamilton county sessions court judge h.l. smith handed down his sentence monday, maybe he took into account this was bucky's first offense. and that he was only 3 years old. and also that he was a deer
bucky is a white-tailed buck judged too tame to survive in the wild after being illegally raised on a farm since he was a fawn. smith ordered him to spend the rest of his life in chattanooga's warner park zoo
the sentence satisfied hershel bradshaw, a 70-year-old birchwood, tenn., man who had taken care of the deer since its mother and another fawn were accidentally killed by a combine he was operating
bradshaw was concerned that tennessee wildlife resources agency officials wanted to destroy the seven-point buck
for a while, they were talking about taking it out in the woods and shooting it,'' he said. ``i just don't think that would have been right.''
bradshaw's attorney, bob moon, said his client was charged with illegally taking and possessing a class iv animal. wildlife officials were told about the deer by a group of hunters who became angry when bradshaw would not let them shoot the animal, which was caged, moon said
tennessee law prohibits anyone except ``zoos and transient circus acts'' from possessing or displaying a class of wildlife that includes such as white-tailed deer, black bears, bobcats and wild turkeys
the judge said he had no intention of fining bradshaw
now that michigan's 150th birthday is over, the state office in charge of the bash has to figure out what to do with nearly 10,000 birthday cards and letters
many were placed by staff of the sesquicentennial office in a large laundry hamper, but some can't be filed away so easily
for example, there is the 150-pound, 4-foot by 4-foot ceramic tile state map, a joint venture of detroit's vernor primary school and pewabic pottery
there also are 28 6- by 4-foot birthday cards sent in by michigan shopping malls, some of them bearing more than 9,000 signatures
some communities sent in birthday scrolls up to 20 feet long and signed by hundreds of residents. most of the cards are hand made. many are from kindergartens and elementary schools, but there's even one from ``all of us at the eaton county jail.''
the state's 18-month-long celebration of its 150th birthday ended jan. 26
things are popping out on the farm, thanks to a jump in consumption of the fluffy white snack americans devour by the ton each year
production of popcorn statewide has doubled since the early 1980s when the last official estimate was made, said john unger, statistician for the illinois agricultural statistic service in springfield
consumption of popcorn has increased with the popularity of microwave ovens,'' unger said. ``the price of popcorn is up, and i think some farmers see it as an alternative crop that will make them a little more money.''
scott talbott of manito is hoping to take advantage of the popcorn craze. he and his father, gnile, grow up to 800 acres of popcorn each year near this town of 1,900 located 20 miles south of peoria
unger estimated illinois farmers grow upwards of 35,000 acres of popcorn each year, more than double the 15,000 acres reported in 1981 in the last census
indiana leads the nation, with about 53,000 acres of popcorn, and nebraska and ohio rank about even with illinois
deirdre flynn, spokeswoman for the popcorn institute in chicago, said industry sales started climbing in 1984, and a reported 700 million pounds were sold in 1986
u.s. and soviet diplomats will have a tough time meeting a one-month deadline for drafting portions of a treaty to slash superpower nuclear arsenals, government and private experts said tuesday
the aspects of the agreements that they have agreed to draft within 30 days are important, but they are appendages to the main treaty,'' said albert carnesdale, a former arms control negotiator now at harvard university
and another former negotiator, james hackett of the conservative heritage foundation in washington, cautioned that ``the best way to get a bad agreement is to give your negotiators a deadline. thirty days is an incredibly short time for an agreement that should take years to negotiate.''
both the soviets and americans would have to make major changes in their bargaining positions to produce an agreement before a summit planned for moscow in late may or early june, said carnesdale, hackett and administration sources who spoke on condition of anonymity
secretary of state george p. shultz and his soviet counterpart eduard a. shevardnadze set the 30-day deadline at their meeting in moscow on monday, directing their staffs to reach draft agreements dealing with verifying compliance with the cutbacks, disposing the weapons, and exchange of information
shultz and shevardnadze meet again in washington on march 22-23. defense secretary frank c. carlucci and soviet defense minister dmitri yazov are also scheduled to discuss the issues at a meeting in bern, switzerland, on march 16-17
the foreign ministers announced no major breakthroughs in the strategic arms reduction talks (start), which president reagan and soviet leader mikhail gorbachev have agreed should cut superpower nuclear arsenals to 6,000 warheads, a reduction of 30 percent to 50 percent, depending on how the weapons are counted
among the major points of disagreement are a u.s. proposal to limit the number of soviet land-based intercontinental ballistic missiles (icbm's) to 3,300, no more than 1,630 of which can be on rockets carrying seven or more warheads. and the soviets are demanding limits on the number of cruise missiles aboard submarines and aircraft
one administration source said, ``it's going to be tough to get a deal unless the two sides agree to mix and match,'' the formula adopted in the second strategic arms limitation treaty, signed in 1979. that pact set overall limits on warhead levels but did not achieve the limits on land-based soviet icbm's that the administration has been seeking under start
some analysts believe that no start deal is possible unless the superpowers reach agreement on the degree to which the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty limits the testing of weapons developed under reagan's strategic defense initiative
however, congress has barred the administration from spending any money through next september on tests that would break the abm pact, and u.s. experts believe that enthusiasm for star wars will wane after reagan leaves office
star wars is probably a moot point,'' said an administration source
a spokesman at the soviet embassy, boris malkhov, said tuesday that ``we are confident that technical obstacles can be overcome. we have the political will, and we think that president reagan does, also,'' to produce a start accord before the summit
