editor's note: bryan brumley writes on national security issues from washington
post-operative trembling endured by half the 25 million people who undergo surgery each year results from the use of anesthetics, not from decreased body temperature as had been assumed, according to a new study
the finding could lead to improved treatments to prevent the unpleasant and uncontrollable tremors that in some cases resemble a seizure and can be dangerous to patients, researchers said tuesday
we now know that a very dramatic side effect of surgery has been misinterpreted for more than 35 years,'' said daniel i. sessler, assistant professor of anesthesia at the university of california-san francisco and head of the study
sessler, along with researchers at ucla and the university of minnesota, compared electrical signals produced in the muscles during normal shivering to those in nine women recovering from anesthetic after surgery. they found the post-surgical tremors were not related to body temperature, but matched tremors produced in people with severed spinal cords
anesthetic, they found, wears off in the spine while the brain remains asleep, essentially disconnecting the spine from the brain's chemical messages
if the patient's skin gets cold, triggering shaking, the brain cannot signal the muscle reflex to stop, sessler said. after about 15 minutes, when the brain wakes up, the tremor stops, he said
people have been trying to do something for years about post-surgical tremors, but generally without success because they have been treating it as a thermo-regulatory problem,'' said sessler, who reported the finding at last year's meeting of the international anesthesia research society. the study will be published in the journal anesthesiology this year
dr. richard stein, vice president of the american society of anesthesiologists, said the finding will not drastically alter current practice at hospitals, which already use lamps or blankets once tremors begin
but according to sessler, warming the skin with infrared heating lamps or even something as simple as a hair dryer while the patient is still asleep should prevent the tremors altogether
infrared heating lamps are used empirically in some hospitals and have already been shown to work ...,'' said sessler. ``but most don't treat this except with blankets. routinely keeping the patient warm would prevent this, even a modest increase in the warming system.''
the shaking, which can occur with almost all general anesthetics in use today, can raise the patient's heart rate and blood pressure, in addition to pulling apart incisions and damaging teeth, sessler said
stein differed with sessler's estimate that half of all surgical patients experience some tremors, from mild to severe. he said such cases are rare and are usually not serious
the condition is most common among patients treated in cold operating rooms, such as those receiving hip or knee replacement, he said. orthopedic surgeons keep the temperature at around 62 degrees because of the heavy gowns they must wear and the air conditioning system, both designed to prevent infection, he said
in a separate study, sessler's research team disproved another assumption _ that surgery patients lose all ability to control body temperature. anesthetics do not eliminate control but instead lower the threshold for cold. the regulatory reaction occurs, but at a much lower body temperature than normal, they found
selection of a site for the $4.4 billion ``super collider'' atom smasher will be delayed by up to four months to prepare a draft environmental impact statement before, instead of after, the choice, the energy department said tuesday
word of the delay, from july to november or december, came in budget questioning of secretary john herrington before the interior subcommittee of the house appropriations committee
he was asked whether he would pick the site before or after the committee acts on his request for $363 million in construction funds for the fiscal year starting oct. 1
i don't see us making the decision'' before the committee must act, herrington said. ``i would guess a preferred site would be selected in november or december.''
the department has planned for more than a year to chose the final site in july and confirm it in january, subject to preparation of an environmental impact statement
department spokesman jeff sherwood said later that doe now believes it is better to do more work on the environmental impact statement and complete a draft covering all possible sites before chosing the final site
that will be on the street and people will be able to comment on it, and we'll have the benefit of the comments in choosing the fon to delay announcement of a final site recommendation
the longer you go in with this project without getting the funding committed, the more risk there is it won't get funded,'' blanchard said at the national governors' association winter meeting in washington. ``the more you narrow down the site selection, the less likely congress is to fund it.''
if congress builds it, the superconducting super collider will investigate exotic scientific theories of the origin of matter by whirling beams of protons into each other at an energy 20 times greater than what is now possible
believed to be the largest scientific instrument ever built, state governments are anxious to win the contest for the 53-miles-around tunnel because it will create 3,000 jobs and have an annual operating budget of $270 million
besides michigan, illinois, texas, arizona, colorado, tennessee and north carolina remain in the competition to build the collider
a two-pack-a-day woman who said she smokes just to annoy her husband was ordered not to light up in front of him or their three children and to confine her smoking to one room of their house, according to court papers made public tuesday
the court order, from state supreme court justice ralph diamond, says elizabeth roofeh, 41, of kings point on long island, can be held in contempt if she breaks the rules
mrs. roofeh's husband, jahanshah, a non-smoking orthopedic surgeon, went to court in an attempt to get his wife to stop smoking around the family
he claimed she had made a promise to that effect when they married in 1976. she said she broke the promise in 1984 only because of stress after suffering a stroke
she filed for divorce last may from her iranian-born husband, whom she called ``an ayatollah.''
i smoke just to annoy him,'' mrs. roofeh said last year. ``i'll quit when i get him out of the house.''
in the suit, roofeh claimed his wife's habit was ``offensive and detrimental to the health of the children,'' aged 6, 7, and 9
the husband had argued that smoking was as bad as punching or spitting and asked for an order of protection, but diamond said such orders are designed to protect family members from domestic violence and would be too severe a remedy
instead, he ordered that she never smoke in front of her husband or children and never smoke at home except in the family's small tv room
mrs. roofeh said tuesday that the ruling, dated monday, was ``nothing new.''
she said she had already been refraining from smoking in front of the children and confining her smoking to the tv room
in an affidavit, she had agreed that smoking is ``detrimental to the health of the smoker and those who passively inhale the smoker's smoke.''
constance navesky, a spokeswoman for the judge, said extensive research into state law had not found any similar ruling
the sisters of kidnapped marine lt. col. william higgins said he appeared well on a tape released monday by his lebanese extremist kidnappers
he looks good, considering what he's been through in the last few weeks, but he is under a lot of stress,'' said his sister, mary fisher, of the jefferson county suburb of okolona
it's strange to be seeing this. it's something you think can never happen to you,'' said another sister, linda lee miller of memphis, tenn., who is visiting mrs. fisher
on the scratchy tape, higgins, who was born in danville, ky., and grew up in nearby garrard county, read a list of demands that had to be met in order to obtain his release, including withdrawal by israel from its border ``security zone'' in south lebanon
higgins, 43, head of a united nations observer force in lebanon, was kidnapped last wednesday as he drove alone in a jeep on the higihway south of tyre, about 50 miles from beirut
a group calling itself the organization of the oppressed on earth, which claimed responsibility for the abduction, released the 70-second tape
i don't believe he thought it could happen to him. i believe he thought he was safe,'' mrs. fisher said of her brother
both mrs. fisher and mrs. miller said their brother would not want the united states to give in to the kidnappers' demands
he would want them to take a hard line, not give in to them, to stand up for the rights that the u.s. believes in,'' mrs. miller said
while both sisters said they were glad to see that their brother was alive, they realized it could be a long wait. currently, there are eight other americans being held hostage in lebanon, for as long as nearly three years
he wouldn't want us to just stop our lives because he's in this situation,'' mrs. fisher said
mrs. fisher said she would like to be able to get word to her brother of the death of their father, william higgins sr. the elder higgins died thursday, the day after his son's abduction, without knowing what had happened to the marine
mrs. fisher said she also had a message for her brother's kidnappers
please let him come home. please release him.'' when younis arrested, insert one graf after 9th graf pvs, bgng: ``the slow''; picks up 10th graf pvs, bgng: younis' ``capacity</note>
the fbi illegally obtained a suspected shiite lebanese terrorist's confession to leading a 1985 airplane hijacking during ``relentless interrogation'' that violated his rights, a judge ruled tuesday
u.s. district judge barrington d. parker suppressed oral and written confessions that fawaz younis gave to agents after he was lured aboard an fbi-chartered yacht in the mediterranean last sept. 13
parker ruled the statements were inadmissable as evidence because younis was denied his constitutional protection against self-incrimination and his right to legal counsel during four days of questioning aboard a navy ship in the mediterranean
somehere along the way, in its zeal and determination to indict and prosecute an alleged hostage-taker and hijacker under recent congressional enactments, and in securing fawaz younis' written confession, the fbi failed to comply fully with constitutional restraints and predecential supreme court decisions,'' parker said in a 47-page opinion
law enforcement agencies must follow the letter and the spirit of the law, even though the accused is not a citizen of the united states,'' parker said. the fbi ``failed to do so in september 1987 when it interrogated the defendant.''
younis was arrested when a friend who had become a government informant lured him onto an fbi-chartered yacht with the prospect of making a drug deal. prosecutors say they have a videotape and other statements from witnesses that place younis at the scene of the june 11, 1985, hijacking of a royal jordanian jetliner from beirut international airport
he is scheduled to go to trial march 22 before parker on charges that he led hijacking, during which the plane was blown up after passengers and crew were taken off the aircraft
although parker declined to rule that the arrest was illegal, he concluded that the fbi deliberately kept younis aboard the uss butte for four days to obtain a confession in ``a clear abuse of the obligation to bring the defendant before a judicial officer immediately following his arrest.''
the slow voyage across the mediterranean appeared to serve only the government's purposes _ ample time to educe a confession,'' parker said. ``that deliberate action coupled with the lengthy and relentless interrogation was all to the defendant's prejudice and detriment.''
the fbi launched its plan to abduct younis early last year under the direction of oliver revell, the bureau's executive assistant director, who witnessed the arrest and was aboard the butte for part of its four-day voyage, according to testimony
younis' ``capacity for self-determination was critically impaired'' by seasickness and throbbing pain from wrists that were fractured when agents slammed him to the deck of the yacht, skunk kilo, following his arrest, parker said
the judge noted that the fbi kept younis in windowless, overheated room aboard the ammunition ship as it steamed slowly from waters off cyprus to a rendezvous with the uss saratoga four days later. younis was then flown from the carrier to andrews air force base, md
the defendant had been advised of his rights to remain silent once during his interrogation, but ``in an uncertain physical condition, in an oppressive environment, and subject to relentless interrogation, younis lacked the will necessary to voluntarily waive his rights,'' parker said
we are reviewing the decision carefully within our office and with our colleagues in the department of justice,'' timothy j. reardon iii, principal assistant u.s. attorney, said in a statement. fbi spokeswoman susan schnitzer said the bureau would not comment on the decision
parker also criticized the ship's doctors for providing inadequate medical treatment and ``negligent diagnosis'' despite younis' ``constant complaints'' about the pain
younis was given ice packs but his wrists were not x-rayed and put into casts until after he was flown to washington
parker said he was ``extremely troubled'' by the fbi's failure to provide younis with a defense lawyer ``despite the meticulous detail of operation goldenrod'' _ the fbi's code-name for the effort
if the fbi could arrange to have a medical surgical team of five doctors and several tons of medical equipment aboard the butte, would it have been too difficult to arrange for a competent and detached attorney?''
besides the confession, prosecutors also have the testimony of two americans who identified younis as one of five men who boarded the plane with ak-47 assault rifles. they also have the testimony of jamal hamdan, younis' one-time friend who had several conversations with him about the hijacking
in addition, prosecutors have a videotape of younis reading a statement to reporters before the plane was blown up in the background
the state supreme court on tuesday declared west virginia's $1.49 billion budget unconstitutional because it contains a deficit, and the state auditor's office said all state spending would cease immediately
we've got to quit everything right now,'' said don adams, chief clerk for auditor glen gainer
adams said no further expenditures of state money can be made until the $26 million deficit in the current budget is corrected
there was a unanimous reaction of shock at the decision, which had been pending for months
the governor has been saying it's unconstitutional since june. i'm sure he'll be interested to hear that,'' said gov. arch moore's press aide, john price
moore was in washington at a governor's conference tuesday and could not immediately be reached for comment
the court ruled in a 3-2 decision, in an opinion written by justice darrell mcgraw, did not tell gov. arch moore and the legislature what to do about the unconstitutional budget
 ... we presume the governor and legislature will do their duties,'' mcgraw wrote
the decision resulted from a lawsuit brought by the west virginia education association last year that challenged cuts in funding for education. the association did not seek to have the budget declared unconstitutional but asked that moore be forced to call a special session to address the problem
in his response, moore did not contest the allegations and said the legislature budgeted $26 million more than he had said would be available in revenues. he said the document was unconstitutionally out of balance
the state constitution's requires ``that the estimate of revenue and the budgeted appropriation be in balance so as not to create a deficit.''
but the high court said it refused to tell the legislature and the governor what they should do to correct the problem and rejected the education association's request that a special legislative session be ordered
it said the branches of government are equal and the court presumes that the executive and legislative branches will do what they are supposed to do
the national park service affirmed the dream of a former boy scout tuesday by dedicating a national trail he conceived to show tourists landmarks that illustrate the rich history of blacks in the nation's capital
the black history national recreation trail winds from a 179-year-old cemetery in the exclusive georgetown neighborhood to the home of 19th century black leader frederick douglass in the city's poor anacostia section
the trail is a continued and living legacy to the achievements of black americans,'' said willard andre hutt, 27, who started the drive for the trail as his eagle scout project in 1979
dedicated to the memory of late black historian carter g. woodson, the tour through washington is part of a series of national park service trails, such as the appalachian trail, that represent periods in american history
the trail includes such landmarks as lincoln park on capitol hill; the downtown home of educator and presidential advisor mary mcleod bethune; the metropolitan african methodist episcopal church, the first ame in washington, created in 1822 when a group of dissatisfied blacks broke away from a predominantly white church; howard university, founded after the civil war to provide higher education to blacks; and the preserved home of abolitionist douglass
interior secretary donald hodel, urging tourists to visit the sites, wrote in a letter that the trail ``will surely contribute to an increasing awareness of the vitality and rich history of the black community in washington d.c.''
our young people need to see these sites,'' mayor marion barry jr. said at a dedication ceremony. ``they need to understand we didn't get to where we are because of who we are, but because of the struggle of these people.'' becoming law</head> ... ''</note>
two republicans said tuesday their $375 million child care improvement bill is far more likely to become law than a multibillion-dollar alternative sponsored by democrats
it's closer to what the president is going to sign than anything else on the table or under discussion,'' said rep. nancy johnson, r-conn., house sponsor of the gop bill. ``it is practical. it is realistic. it is doable.''
the plan sponsored by johnson and sen. orrin hatch, r-utah, relies on state regulation and private initiatives. the $2.5 billion democratic proposal requires federal regulation and, among other things, provides more direct aid to low-income families
there's no way they can get that past a democrat president, let alone this president,'' hatch said
hatch said he would have to ``sit down and negotiate'' with sen. christopher dodd, d-conn., sponsor of the democratic bill in the senate. he predicted no child care bill would pass unless it comes close to what he has proposed
but dodd said he and hatch already have had ``numerous conversations'' about the two child care proposals, with little to show for them
i frankly feel that under any of the presidential candidates, i would fare better with my child care proposal than under this administration,'' dodd said. ``so unless i sense that sen. hatch and others are willing to move more in our direction to really target low- and moderate-income families, i am going to be unwilling to necessarily reach a compromise this year.''
hatch initially introduced his bill last year, saying conservatives had to take a leadership role in resolving the child care problems faced by many working families. he reintroduced it tuesday with some refinements and johnson's companion measure in the house
the bill provides $250 million for state grants to projects designed to improve or expand child care or make it more affordable, $100 million for liability pools that any licensed provider could join and $25 million for capital improvements to regulated day care homes
in addition it would limit provider liability, give tax credits to employers with on-site child care and offer a double tax exemption to families in which a parent stayed home for six months to care for a newborn. the break would be worth about $500 to $600 to the average family
though some experts have said state regulation of day care is inconsistent and in some cases very poor, johnson said that would change because the bill requires state regulation and will stimulate debate
when that debate becomes public ... it results in good standards,'' she said
johnson also said the bill would decrease the incidence of ``underground'' providers because it addresses the liability problem and simplifies taxes for family day care providers
if you don't deal with those disincentives, you're not going to bring people into the regulated system,'' she said
the national governors' association, meanwhile, urged the federal government tuesday to take action on child care, including a ``modest'' commitment of funds to help poor working families
the governors, ending their three-day winter meeting in washington, called for the public and private sectors to work in concert on the problem, and said that despite the deficit, ``the federal government should begin to take action to improve child care.''
but president reagan on monday cautioned the governors to ``tread carefully'' on the issue of child care
maybe it's my conservative bent, but i can't help but feel uneasy sometimes'' about proposals to seek government solutions to such problems, reagan said
hatch and johnson described their bill as bipartisan, although most democrats are supporting the dodd bill, introduced in the house by rep. dale kildee, d-mich
proponents of the democratic measure say a strong federal role is needed to unify and strengthen the current piecemeal system and to give the private sector a framework in which to invest
only 5 percent of employers currently offer day care services or direct financial aid to pay for them
eds: deletes `a' in 7th graf `the government' to make spelling nagorno-karabakhskaya
thousands of people marched in soviet armenia on tuesday to demand control of territory assigned to another republic, dramatically illustrating tensions among the nation's 100 nationalities
demonstrations in yerevan, capital of the southern soviet republic, followed protests in the disputed area, a small mountainous region just north of turkey
a former political prisoner said from yerevan that the protesters want the small area _ part of the neighboring republic of azerbaidzhan _ to be made part of the republic of armenia because many armenians live there
other problems between different nationalities have led to demonstrations in the republics of kazakhstan, estonia, lithuania and latvia
nationalist demonstrations have increased since mikhail s. gorbachev gained power in march 1985 and adopted a policy of ``glasnost,'' or openness on selected social issues. on feb. 10, he said developing a nationalities policy is ``the most vital, fundamental issue of our society.''
dissidents in moscow said tuesday at least 100,000 demonstrators took to the streets in yerevan, but a participant claimed later the number was 200,000. in either case, it appeared to be one of the largest unofficial gatherings ever reported in the soviet union
the government acknowledged ``breaching of public order'' took place in the the disputed area, nagorno-karabakhskaya, and said the territorial demands were against the public interest
tamara grigoryants, a moscow dissident whose husband is armenian, said the disputed area in the caucasus was given to neighboring azerbaidzhan in the early 1920s although most of its inhabitants are armenian
paruyr ayrikyan, a 38-year-old former political prisoner, said in a telephone interview from yerevan that protests began late monday and continued tuesday. yerevan is 1,100 miles south of moscow
no one slept all night,'' he said. ``we gathered at the opera house at about 11 p.m. and stayed out demonstrating until 5 a.m. about 200,000 people massed outside the council of ministers, the central committee headquarters and the supreme soviet.''
about one-third of armenia's 3.3 million people live in yerevan
ayrikyan led an underground armenian nationalist group called the national unification party and was jailed for 17 years beginning in 1969. he said he now is chairman of a nationalist group called alliance for national determination
earlier this month, he said, the nagorno-karabakhskaya government council asked that the region be made part of armenia, citing the constitutional guarantee of the right of self-determination. the communist party central committee rejected the request, and demonstrations followed in nagorno-karabakhskaya and yerevan, ayrikyan said
soldiers brought in tanks to quell protests in nagorno-karabakhskaya and rumors circulated that some demonstrators were killed, he said
the government made its comment through the official news agency tass, and the dispatch was read later on the national evening news program
breaching of public order was provoked as a result of irresponsible calls by extremist individuals,'' tass said of events in nagorno-karabakhsaya
it said the central committee ``holds that the actions and demands directed at revising the existing national and territorial structure contradict the interests of the working people in soviet azerbaidzhan and armenia and damages inter-ethnic relations.''
the central committee urged residents ``not to yield to provocations by nationalist elements'' and said all measures would be taken to ``safeguard public order,'' tass reported. it did not give the number of demonstrators or say what actions were taken to stop the protest
alexander ogorodnikov, a former political prisoner who lives in moscow, said demonstrators in yerevan chanted the slogan, ``one nation, one republic!''
karen s. demirchyan, the armenian communist party chief, went on television monday night asking people to be calm, but thousands gathered outside the opera whistled and jeered, ogorodnikov and ayrikyan said
police followed the demonstrators as they marched through yerevan but did not detain or harrass the protesters, ayrikyan said
he added that rumors were circulating of authorities sending martial arts experts to the city to cause disorder and provide police with a pretext for intervention
problems of nationalities gained prominence last summer in the baltic republics, and there were street demonstrations in latvia, lithuania and estonia to mark the anniversary of a secret german-soviet agreement that led to the soviet takeover of the three countries in 1940
on feb. 16 in vilnius, the capital of lithuania, there was a heavy presence of police patrolling the streets and squares in an apparent move to prevent any demonstrations on the 70th anniversary of lithuanian independence
estonian dissidents plan more protests wednesday
in the central asian republic of kazakhstan, at least 3,000 people rioted dec. 17-18, 1986, in the capital alma ata to protest appointment of an ethnic russian to replace a kazakh as the republic's party leader
network news stories on vice president george bush were generally negative before the iowa republican caucuses but became much more favorable after his poor showing there, a media analyst said tuesday
there were 157 on-air evaluations of bush as a candidate on evening newscasts from jan. 1 to feb. 16, said robert lichter, who has been logging and analyzing television coverage of all the contenders since early last year
from jan. 1 to feb. 8, before bush's third-place iowa finish, 61 percent of the evaluations were negative. from feb. 9 through feb. 16, between the iowa and new hamphire contests, only 34 percent of the evaluations were negative
lichter called the trend ``a dramatic upturn'' that illustrates the media tendency to treat front-runners more critically than the rest of the pack
as bush's prospects dim ... suddenly for the first time in this campaign he starts to get good press,'' lichter said
part of the shift involved the virtual disappearance of stories about bush's role in the iran-contra affair, lichter said. before the iowa caucuses feb. 8, there were twice as many stories about iran-contra as there were about any other policy issue. then iran-contra ``dropped from sight,'' he said
lichter showed snippets of pre-iowa campaign coverage that included several pointed comments from bush's chief rival, senate minority leader bob dole of kansas
in one nightly news clip, dole said bush never said anything at leadership meetings. ``i don't know, maybe he was just holding back,'' he said. in another, dole said he had ``a record of leadership. ... i can't help it if he (bush) can't provide any.''
after the iowa caucuses, sample clips showed barbara bush calling her husband ``wiser and smarter'' than the other candidates. nbc correspondent tom pettit said bush was ``not a quitter. he's a very determined man.'' and a new hampshire truck driver told an interviewer that bush ``seems a lot taller and sterner than i thought he would be.''
lichter said most positive comments come from candidates and their families while negative ones come from others in the race. the trend worked to the disadvantage of democrats because they kept picking on each other _ particularly during debates, he said
sample clips of the democrats included some acerbic comments on the so-called massachusetts miracle touted by gov. michael dukakis as evidence of his successful economic policies
i went to divinity school and they have a tougher definition of the word miracle,'' sen. albert gore, d-tenn., said during one debate
rep. dick gephardt and sen. paul simon provided many instances of democratic sniping picked up by network news. among the clips:
it is legitimate for me to say where are you going? who is the real dick gephardt?'' said simon, defending an anti-gephardt television ad
i asked sen. simon to take those ads off television,'' gephardt said. ``and if he doesn't, he should take off his bow tie because he's just another politician.''
lichter said abc and nbc coverage of bush stayed just about the same after bush's confrontation with dan rather on cbs. but bush's positive evaluations on cbs dropped sharply from about 50 percent to 27 percent after the set-to, lichter said
lichter said the negative cbs coverage may have been ``one blip'' attributable to ``a lot of anger'' over the incident. he said bush stories on cbs since iowa are in the same ballpark as other networks _ about 60 percent positive
horse-race'' comments about a candidate's chances were not included in the tallies of positive and negative evaluations. comments that were counted came from candidates, their families and aides, network correspondents, independent experts and others
lichter is a fellow at the american enterprise institute and co-director of the center for media and policy studies. besides tracking network news coverage of the candidates, he is also monitoring election-year political humor on the johnny carson and david letterman shows
federal monitors of state-run family assistance programs should penalize only those states with excessive rates of overpayments, a congressional study said tuesday
moreover, the report by the nationa research council said the current federal monitoring system should be replaced with one that measures state efforts to accomplish the social purposes of the programs rather than just financial accountability
recommendations of the panel, an operating arm of the national academy of sciences, are based on an 18-month study ordered by congress
the new report focuses on aid to families with dependent children and medicaid. a similar report issued last may concentrated on the food stamp program
the underlying call for different ways of measuring effectiveness applied to all three programs, which account for about 40 percent of total federal spending on the poor
nevada is the only state that has escaped sanctions that are expected to total $3 billion by 1989. nearly all of the 49 states facing sanctions are appealing and some are challenging them in court
intended to deter overpayment errors in the three programs, penalties are imposed if a state's error rate exceeds 5 percent of its food stamp payments and 3 percent of its afdc and medicaid payments
the panel endorsed the concept of imposing sanctions for improperly run programs, but said the overpayment error rate should not be the sole criteria of a state's performance
it said the present monitoring system does not provide the ``detailed data that are needed for identifying and correctioning problems at the service-delivery level.''
because of uncertainties in the available information, sanctions should be limited to ``extremely bad performers'' until a more comprehensive method of measuring performance is developed, the panel said
it said federal officials should measure the states against each other, rather than the present absolute gauge, and penalize only those with ``excessively large'' error rates
however, the report did not specify a cutoff point as being ``exessively large'' and said, ``there is no absolutely reliable way of determining, say, the 10 states with the highest error rates.''
massachusetts and wisconsin receieved top scores tuesday in a ranking of state environmental protection programs by an advocacy group, the fund for renewable energy and the environment
the two states received 45 points out of a possible 60 in the group's subjective assessments of programs in six areas: surface water protection, pesticide control, highway safety, land use planning, indoor pollution and pollution from energy production and use
not far behind in the rankings were california and new jersey with 44 points each and connecticut with 43. at the bottom of the list were nevada, oklahoma and texas with 19 points, arkansas and mississippi with 17 and wyoming with 15
in the separate areas, the group put these states first: north carolina in surface water protection; california in pesticide protection; oregon in land use planning; new jersey in combating indoor pollution; maryland in highway safety; and massachusetts in energy pollution control
in an introduction to the report, denis hayes, chairman of the fund, said, ``slowly, the environmental community has come to recognize that our responsibility is not discharged simply by passing sweeping legislation. ... the real success must be won in the trenches
the purpose of this study is to share information on how the battle is going in the trenches.''
this is the second report from the fund. last year's examined outdoor air pollution, soil conservation, solid waste and recycling, hazardous waste management, groundwater protection and renewable energy and conservation. the fund said it plans to look at each area every three years
the rankings tried to account for the existence of state legislation, the scope of programs, financing, monitoring and enforcement and indications of progress
the report singled out massachusetts, which imposed $697,000 in penalties for water pollution under a new state program
among other points, the report said:
_arkansas, idaho, indiana, louisiana, maryland, minnesota, ohio and washington ``have more than one-fifth of the major municipal public treatment works in significant non-compliance'' with their water pollution discharge permits
_most states rely on local government zoning ordinances for controls on land use, and statewide programs were found only in oregon, florida, vermont, colorado, hawaii and new jersey
_forty-two states have passed laws limiting smoking in public places, and 22 states and more than 200 local governments restrict smoking to some degree on the job
_though not one of the traditional environmental issues, ``highways are one of our most dangerous daily environments,'' and ``the automobile is also the machine with the single greatest impact on our environment,'' accounting for half of air pollution. 02-23 0841</first> ...'' to update with hopkins comments.</note>
the army announced tuesday it intends to build incinerators at eight ammunition depots around the country to destroy old chemical weapons because it doesn't want to risk moving the munitions
i think we could do it either way,'' said james r. ambrose, the under secretary of the army and the official who made the final decision
but it is my judgment in rendering this decision that it is much more sensible in every respect, and far less complex and i think on the whole ... less risky, to do it where it is
we think we can exercise much better control on a combined federal reservation than we can transporting this stuff over many states and through cities and the like,'' he said
ambrose's decision was hardly a surprise. the army has favored on-site destruction of its old chemical stocks ever since it began studying the matter more than two years ago, and just last december released an environmental impact study supporting that approach
some members of congress, however, including rep. larry j. hopkins, r-ky., have contested the army's plans, saying the service hasn't demonstrated the safety of incinerating chemical weapons at storage depots located near population centers
hopkins said tuesday he was not surprised by ambrose's decision, but thought the army had reneged on an earlier agreement to conduct a more ``site-specific'' study of each depot
in my view, on-site incineration is unsafe and unthinkable in madison county, ky.,'' hopkins said. ``we have the most amount of population and the least amount of chemicals.''
the service is now constructing a prototype incineration plant on johnston atoll in the pacific ocean _ where another chemical weapons depot is maintained _ to demonstrate the safety of the destruction process, ambrose noted
we think these plants are extremely safe,'' he said at a pentagon briefing. ``we think the safety is greatly in excess of that required by any of the known rules and laws.''
the army's no. 2 civilian leader said the service now hopes to begin building the eight incineration plants by 1989 or 1990, but conceded that timetable could be slowed by litigation or by congress
while ambrose said he was comfortable with his decision, he said he fully expects to see lawsuits challenging the move
i've had even some people i won't identify assure me that they'll sue me either way,'' he said to laughter
the army's stockpile of so-called unitary chemical weapons, in which shells and bombs are filled with a variety of nerve gases and poisons such as mustard gas, is now on average more than 25 years old. although the army won't say how large the stockpile is _ citing secrecy classifications _ published estimates have ranged from 25,000 tons to 40,000 tons
the weapons are stored at the aberdeen proving ground, md.; anniston army depot, ala.; lexington-blue grass army depot, ky.; newport army ammunition plant, ind.; pine bluff arsenal, ark.; pueblo army depot, colo.; tooele army depot, utah, and umatilla army depot, ore
the army is under orders from congress to begin destroying the old stock as it begins producing a new type of chemical weapon considered to be more safe. those new ``binary'' weapons are made with two harmless chemicals that are kept separate until after the artillery round or rocket is fired, mixing then to form a lethal gas
ambrose said tuesday he had closely studied the army environmental impact study before accepting its rejection of four alternatives to on-site incineration
those alternatives included transporting the weapons by rail for destruction at plants to be built at tooele and anniston; transporting by rail to a single national disposal center at tooele; airlifting the lexington and aberdeen weapons to tooele for destruction, with on-site destruction at the other locations, and continued storage at the current sites
these devices are there,'' ambrose said. ``they've been there for some time. they will not go away. they should be gotten rid of. they will not turn into something completely harmless by themselves
i have simply concluded that the ability to control (transportation) actions and to take the necessary precautions in large-scale movements ... is just much more of a formidable, complex and uncertain task than to keep these materials under close control at these locations and to perform the incineration there.''
the army could probably save about $200 million if it built a single large incineration plant instead of eight small ones, but the risk of large-scale movement of the weapons is not worth it, ambrose added
if all goes well, ambrose said it would cost between $2 billion and $2.5 billion to dispose of the old weapons and that the job could be completed by 1996 or 1997. it would then take another year or so to dismantle the eight incineration plants, he said. term</head> mccloskey's first election but his second; subs penultimate graf to correct number of votes cast in 1984 election to 230,000, sted 260,00.</note>
connecticut attorney general joseph i. lieberman announced monday he will challenge maverick republican sen. lowell p. weicker jr.'s bid for re-election, while democratic rep. frank mccloskey of indiana _ who won re-election in 1984 in a disputed recount _ said he would seek a fourth term
and in augusta, maine, longtime congressional aide edward s. ``ted'' o'meara said he would run for the gop nomination in the 1st congressional district, challenging l.l. bean heiress linda bean-jones in a primary. the seat is held by democrat joseph e. brennan, the former governor
lieberman, 45, a democratic former state senator who ran unsuccessfully for congress in 1980, attacked weicker for using the senate as ``a debating society'' for his own agenda
weicker, 56, who announced his candidacy for a fourth term earlier this month, has made a name for himself as a liberal republican, frequently at odds with his party and president. he has championed constitutional issues and civil rights and worked against school prayer and balanced budget amendments
the candidates will be determined at state party conventions this summer. so far, weicker is unopposed and lieberman has only token opposition from gary johnson, who describes himself as a veterans' rights advocate
mccloskey said he expected another tough campaign in the 8th congressional district, which is situated in southwestern indiana. in 1984, mccloskey won by just four votes in a hotly disputed recount after a race with republican candidate rick mcintyre of bedford in which more than 230,000 votes were cast
so far, two republicans have filed to challenge mccloskey _ john smith, a bloomington businessman, and john myers, an odon newspaper publisher. workers told they could be laid off, sted would be. picks up 13th graf pvs, `the international ...'; a longer version moved on the business wire.</note>
flight attendants at northwest airlines have voted overwhelmingly to strike the airline this weekend unless a contract dispute over wages and benefits is resolved, a union official said monday
jeff musto, a spokesman for teamsters local 2747 representing 6,500 northwest attendants, said 94.4 percent of the more than 5,000 attendants participating voted to strike saturday. strike authorization required a two-thirds majority
the strike authorization of 94.4 percent reflects the deplorable state of labor relations at northwest airlines,'' musto said at a news conference, reading a statement prepared by the local
northwest airlines labor relations does not comprehend the severity of the labor situation at this carrier,'' the statement read
northwest spokesman redmond tyler said he was not surprised by the strike vote and said the airline expected to continue operating most of its flights if a strike occurred
meanwhile monday, the teamsters union at pan am corp. threatened to disrupt the airline over a contract impasse but stopped short of calling a strike
the strike deadline for the union, which represents 4,500 pan am baggage handlers, reservations clerks and other ground personnel, passed at 12:01 a.m. sunday. no negotiations were scheduled for monday
teamsters officials said they would use tactics such as sending baggage to the wrong airports and canceling reservations
tyler said northwest officials and the union would hold a negotiating session tuesday ``with the cooperation of the national mediation board and we continue to remain optimistic that our contract will be resolved.''
the two sides have not negotiated since the national mediation board released them from mandatory negotiations last month, when they deadlocked over wages, fringe benefits and work rules. a 30-day cooling-off period ends at 12:01 a.m. est saturday, at which time the attendants may strike and northwest may impose a new contract
about 2,000 northwest managers are qualified to be flight attendants and would be used during a strike, according to the airline, which also advertised earlier this month for flight attendants
but northwest last week told 5,300 mechanics and baggage handlers they could be laid off if the flight attendants went on strike
the international association of machinists, which represents 20,000 ground workers at northwest, and the pilots' union have not said if they would honor a strike by the flight attendants
in the last strike against northwest, the machinists union walked out for 27 days in may 1982
northwest merged with the minneapolis-based republic airlines in 1986 and the company and its major unions have been involved in talks on new contracts ever since
many former republic employees are paid less than their northwest counterparts, a cause of friction between labor and management
northwest's latest proposal to the teamsters offers immediate elimination of pay gaps between former northwest and former republic flight attendants and deals with the other areas of disagreement
the proposed five-year agreement calls for pay increases for former republic flight attendants ranging from 17 percent to 26 percent, according to terry erskine, northwest's vice president of labor relations. senior flight attendants earn about $35,000 annually; starting pay is about $15,000 a year, he said
but musto said monday that ``even though it does show a pay raise for the republic people, the end result would be a pay cut if you put a dollars and cents figure on things being taken away form the republic people.''
musto said the proposal would mean less vacation pay and, ``in the long run, you would get less retirement benefits.'' cleanup</head> to update with comment from occidental, other reaction, picking up 8th graf, `curtin's ruling...'. subs graf 10, `occidental, formerly...', to include history of occidental acquisition of company</note>
a federal judge ruled tuesday that occidental chemical corp. is liable for the cost _ estimated at more than $250 million _ of cleaning up the love canal landfill that became synonymous with environmental disaster
after nine years of deliberations, u.s. district judge john curtin said occidental produced the wastes and stored them in a way that would eventually result in toxic leakage
it is beyond dispute that occ's disposal practices were at least partially responsible for the release, or threatened release, of the chemicals from the love canal landfill,'' curtin said
curtin said occidental's liability would be determined in further court proceedings involving claims against occidental by other parties, including the state of new york and some residents. previous estimates have ranged above $250 million
frank ashley, a spokesman for occidental petroleum corp., the parent of occidental chemical, said the company would appeal
although we believe we are protected by insurance, we intend further to protect our rights by appeal from this extraordinary decision,'' ashley said
at last someobo~ has been assigned some responsibility,'' said sister marjeen hoffmann, director of the ecumenical task force which has been an advocate for people in the love canal neighborhood
this is what we've been waiting for,'' she said
lois gibbs, a former love canal resident who now runs the citizen's clearing house for hazardous wastes in alexandria, va., said she hopes the company will be found liable for the full $250 million. ``that will at least make them blink,'' gibbs said
roger j. marzulla, acting assistant attorney general in charge of the justice department's land and natural resources division, said the ruling shows occidental ``cannot insulate itself from liability by blaming others.''
curtin's ruling upholds the federal comprehensive environmental response, compensation and liability act of 1980, which the judge said was designed to compel the waste disposal industry ``to correct its past mistakes and to provide a solution for the dangers posed by inactive abandoned waste sites.''
the law was passed 27 years after occidental yielded ownership of the landfill, transferring it to the niagara falls school board
occidental, formerly hooker chemical and plastic co., contended that it was not responsible for the site after 1953 when it sold the property to the school board, which built a school on the grounds. occidental petroleum had acquired hooker in 1968 and changed the name to occidental chemical
occidental said the construction broke a clay seal on the dump and allowed the chemicals to leach into the environment. the company acknowledged dumping 20,000 tons of chemical wastes into the canal during the late 1940s and early 1950s
martin littlefield, assistant u.s. attorney for the buffalo district, said the decision was ``a great victory for the state because it means companies are indeed responsible for what they've done in years past.''
littlefield said occidental would be liable for the ``bottom line'' on the cleanup costs. he said, however, the ruling allows occidental to sue other parties the chemical giant contends should share the responsibility
nunzio loverdi, president of the love canal environmental action committee, said, ``i think occidental should accept the decision and not take action against the city and school board because if it does we will all suffer. we want to get on with our lives and put this behind us.''
ten years ago, love canal became synonymous with environmental disaster when state officials ordered an evacuation of children and pregnant women from the area because of leaking chemicals. president carter designated the 10-block site as a federal emergency area in 1978
the federal environmental protection agency began the suit against the company in 1979
during the next two years, 728 families were evacuated. many of those were among the 1,300 former residents who accepted a $20 million damage settlement from occidental in 1984
today, there are some 175 families awaiting the results of a state habitability study to decide whether they can return to their homes
occidental has since proposed construction of a multimillion-dollar incinerator complex and offered to destroy dioxin-contaminated wastes. the offer marks the first time since the federal and state governments took over the cleanup in 1979 that the company has proposed any direct action or involvement in cleanup measures
occidental officials are scheuled to make a formal proposal at a meeting march 2 in washington at the u.s. environmental protection agency. graf bgng ``but he said ... ''</note>
former secretary of state henry a. kissinger grudgingly supported senate ratification of the new u.s. soviet medium-range arms reduction agreement on tuesday, saying it never should have been agreed to in its present form
but kissinger said the treaty should be approved without crippling amendments because failure to do so would ``magnify all difficulties'' within the nato alliance
the removal of american intermediate range missiles (from europe) is now irreversible,'' because of the pressures of european public opinion and other factors, kissinger told the senate foreign relations committee
because of that, he said, defeat of the treaty in the senate ``would generate a crisis in the atlantic alliance which in the end would almost certainly lead to the unilateral withdrawal of u.s. missiles from europe and undermine the cohesion of the alliance.''
my concerns cannot be removed by the refusal of the senate to ratify the agreement,'' kissinger said. ``failure to ratify ... cannot cure its defects
meanwhile, because they had ``manuevered themselves into a position where they think they now have no choice but to stand by proposals they never thought would be agreed to in the first place.''
the treaty is the result of nato's 1979 ``dual-track'' decision to deploy u.s. weapons to counter soviet ss-20 medium-range missiles while at the same time negotiating their removal
they felt the obligation to imply that these weapons were there for arms control purposes and were therefore open to negotiation,'' kissinger said of the european political leaders
kissinger said he believes the treaty is flawed because it will not reduce in any significant way the ability of the soviet union to devastate europe with other nuclear weapons and because it substantially reduces the ability of the united states to retaliate with nuclear weapons based in europe
nuclear deterrence in europe will now rely primarily on weapons based in the united states and kissinger said that creates ``a psychological and political imbalance,'' especially when weighed against soviet superiority in conventional forces
but he said rejection of the treaty would severely undermine confidence in american leadership, demoralize the alliance, and ignite neutralism
sen. david boren, d-okla., chairman of the intelligence committee, said his committee has ``high confidence'' in the ability of the united states to verify soviet compliance with the treaty
but ``there's a very big question mark about our ability to verify'' a separate treaty providing deep cuts in long-range nuclear weapons, boren said in an interview
the problem there is one of money, not technical ability,'' he explained. ``we have the capability, but the administration has to come forward and propose a budget plan to pay for it.''
the intelligence committee has been holding closed-door hearings for three weeks about verification capabilities
in his testimony, glitman provided a detailed analysis as part of the senate's thorough examination of the pact signed 10 weeks ago by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev. the treaty will eliminate all nuclear-tipped missiles with ranges of about 300 to 3,000 miles
armed services committee members say the detailed scrutiny is needed because of disputes about the meaning of past treaties, particularly the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty
the current treaty is being considered by the senate amid a fight between the democratic-controlled congress and the reagan administration over the precise meaning of the 1972 pact and whether it banned futuristic weapons such as those being developed under the strategic defense initiative
article 14 of the intermediate-range nuclear forces (inf) treaty says neither side shall do anything, now or in the future, to undercut the pact
sen. dan quayle, r-ind., told glitman that ``i'm concerned about article 14'' because it might limit future u.s. help to other nato nations
if we don't spell out what the future obligations are,'' said quayle, ``down the road i can foresee some problems ... now is the time to give us as much running room as possible in the future for our technology.''
but glitman took the opposite approach, noting that the treaty is extremely specific in spelling out prohibited weapons, along with their components
if it is not prohibited by the treaty, we can do it,'' said glitman. later, he added that ``we're best protected by stating what we cannot do.''
glitman cited one method in which he said u.s. aid to nato would not be affected. the treaty bans cruise missiles, he said, but it doesn't block the transfer of u.s. technology to nato nations such as great britain to develop cruise missiles
glitman said the u.s. negotiating team resisted soviet efforts to block u.s. help for nato. ``we knew their goal was to find a way to put a brake on nato activities,'' he said
reagan promised tuesday that the united states will do its part to ensure that the nato alliance remains strong, saying in an address broadcast to europe that ``our destiny is coupled with yours.''
in the address, which came a week before a nato summit meeting, reagan reaffirmed the alliance agreement that an attack on any member nation is an attack against all of them. ``simply put, an attack on munich is the same as an attack on chicago,'' he said. secretary</head> after 13th graf pvs, bgng: fitzwater said; picks up 14th graf pvs, bgng: `it is</note>
president reagan on tuesday picked a veteran capitol hill infighter, william l. ball iii, to step into a simmering dispute over pentagon budget cuts as his new secretary of the navy
the white house said the president will nominate ball, a former capitol hill aide who has been chief lobbyist for both the state department and the white house, to succeed james webb, who resigned as navy secretary on monday with a blast at secretary of defense frank c. carlucci
we look to will ball to continue working aggressively for a strong u.s. navy,'' white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said, noting webb's charge that carlucci had needlessly sacrificed the administration's goal of a 600-ship fleet
fitzwater said the administration still seeks a 600-vessel navy, but now expects that the goal will be reached in fiscal year 1992, more than two years after reagan leaves office, rather than in fiscal 1989 as originally planned
the budget restructuring under way at the pentagon now is a difficult and painful process,'' fitzwater said. ``secretary carlucci is doing an admirable job. he's quite capable and suitable to the task, and he's carrying out thepresident's policies in that regard.''
of ball, he said, ``all of us who kfw him here at t z/e house know that the navy is getting a strong advocate and a strong fighter both on the hill as well as in any of the other courts of public opinion around the country.''
ball, 39, a soft-spoken southerner who came to washington as an aide to former sen. herman talmadge, d-ga., has a reputation for skill at the behind-the-scenes compromises and maneuvers needed to steer legislation through congress
webb, on the other hand, was more noted for outspoken advocacy of such controversial positions as his criticism of the service academies' admission of women and his ruling that the navy would no longer accommodate officers who want to play professional sports
ball has been assistant to the president for legislative affairs since february 1986. before that he had been assistant secretary of state for legislative and intergovernmental affairs. from 1981 to 1985 he was administrative assistant to`hen sen. john tower, r-texas, serving also as chief clerk of the senate armed services committee in 1981. he was talmadge's administrative assistant in 1978
a native of south carolina, he is a graduate of the georgia institute of technology and was a regular officer in the navy from 1969 to 1975
as secretary of the navy, ball will oversee approximately 584,000 navy personnel and 199,000 marines
he will be succeeded at the white house by a deputy, alan kranowicz, who has been primarily responsible for white house lobbying efforts in the house. kranowicz served as chief of staff to former rep. tom loeffler, r-texas, while loeffler was in congress
fitzwater said webb ``did the honorable thing'' in resigning when he could no longer support the president's policies. he said webb's service was ``distinguished and the president appreciates it very much.''
later the white house released a letter from reagan to webb accepting the resignation ``with regret'' and saying, ``as your service to this administration comes to a close, i want to thank you for the selflessness and loyalty that you have always personified.''
defense department spokesman dan howard said, ``the pentagon is very pleased that someone with such positive credentials has been named so quickly.''
it is a painful restructuring they are having to go through to absorb some of those reductions in spending levels,'' the presidential spokesman said. ``the president has been a strong advocate of the military and has worked hard to build it up over many years and feels that pain no less than anyone else.''
the budget cuts being carried out by carlucci, the former white house national security adviser who succeeded caspar w. weinberger at the pentagon late last year, result from a compromise reached by reagan with the democratic-controlled congress
in his budget message delivered last thursday to congress, reagan said he had kept his part of the bargain and expected them to keep their part by appropriating the full amount agreed upon for pentagon spending
ball's nomination requires confirmation by the senate. he is expected to have little difficulty since the nomination will be reviewed by the senate armed services committee, many of whose members know him as a former aide to the panel and to tower, who is a former member and chairman
in announcing his resignation monday, webb charged that carlucci had instructed him to deny news stories reporting that it was the defense department, not the navy, that wanted to mothball ships
he also said carlucci needed to ``spend a lot more time with the top leaders in this building (the pentagon),'' but instead had been ``spending a lot of time with the state department and a lot of time on the hill.''
carlucci declined to respond, saying only that he had learned of webb's resignation with ``regret.''
pat robertson suggested on tuesday that political motivations lay behind the timing of sexual-misconduct allegations against tv evangelist jimmy swaggart, and he also accused george bush's campaign of planning religiously bigoted television commercials
he provided no evidence to support his accusation on the timing of the swaggart story, and he declined to say who might be behind any such effort. however, he said the vice president's campaign was the only one in the gop presidential race that has been engaging in ``dirty tricks.''
robertson's comments brought heated denials from bush~ others in the vice president's campaign
asked about robertson's charge during a campaign stop in st. louis, bush challenged him to ``prove it.''
later, in london, ky., bush was asked if he could say his campaign had no connection with the timing of the swaggart story
that's a hundred percent accurate,'' he replied
bush said he saw no reason anyway to connect the swaggart story with robertson, himself a former television evangelist
i don't think it's fair to burden pat robertson with something with jimmy swaggert. i don't think that's fair play,'' bush said. ``on the other hand, if he accuses me of something, i'm perfectly prepared to defend us.''
in washington, south carolina gov. carroll campbell, bush's state campaign chairman, said, ``if somebody makes a specific charge then they certainly ought to have to come forward with some proof. i think it's a rather ridiculous charge myself.''
robertson said evidence indicating swaggart had been involved with prostitutes had lain ``dormant since last october.''
it ``stretches the imagination and stretches credulity'' that revelations of such allegations came two weeks ``before the most important primary in the nation,'' the republican candidate said during a news conference. he was referring to the primaries and caucuses that 20 states will hold on march 8, known as super tuesday
i think somebody had something to do with it,'' said robertson. ``somebody else planned all these things, i am afraid.''
he also said bush's campaign was guilty of dirty tricks against him and was planning more in the form of advertisements before the super tuesday primaries
they will attack my religious beliefs and practices and i'm going to call them before it happens,'' robertson said
bush officials said that accusation wasn't true
robertson declined to say what led him to make the charge
