a space agency engineer who pressed for a delay in the launch of the ill-fated space shuttle challenger started work monday at the private aerospace company that built the shuttle booster rocket
judson a. lovingood, 51, joined several other top-ranking officials in leaving the marshall space flight center since the seven crew members died in the challenger explosion two years ago
lovingood retired saturday from the national aeronautics and space administration, where he had worked for 25 years, instead of taking an assignment at nasa headquarters in washington as deputy director of systems engineering and analysis for the shuttle program
he elected to retire in lieu of accepting the assignment for economic and other reasons,'' said a marshall spokesman, dave drachlis. ``dr. lovingood has said that he has worked on the shuttle since 1969. the challenger accident has exacted a great personal toll and he felt it was time for a change.''
lovingood's new job is technical director of morton thiokol
he said through a thiokol spokeswoman that he will be responsible for ``overseeing some technical activities'' at the huntsville division of morton thiokol, whose main shuttle plant is in utah. his activities were not specified, but he said the company's huntsville operation has little connection with the shuttle program
lovingood was deputy manager of the shuttle projects office at marshall when morton thiokol engineers recommended against launching the shuttle in cold weather at cape canaveral on jan. 28, 1986
i was contacted about 4:30 that afternoon (jan. 27) by a guy from the cape,'' lovingood said
a point was being made and the point being that i heard that thiokol people were recommending that we not launch,'' he said. ``i felt like with a recommendation like that that we shouldn't launch, period.''
a presidential commission that investigated the disaster concluded that the decision-making process prior to the launch was flawed, with the views of morton thiokol engineers overruled and critical concerns not relayed to top nasa levels, where officials were pushing for a launch
the commission said flawed o-rings in the booster rocket allowed hot gases to leak through to the external fuel tank
pat robertson's campaign lawyer contended tuesday that the campaign has not used the $6.5 million it received in federal matching funds even though its financial report shows it has less than that on hand
the matching funds were used to secure a $5.5 million loan during january, said campaign attorney marion harrison, but he added that the campaign does not consider that was using the money
the matching funds are 100 percent in an escrow account,'' and none has been spent, harrison said in a telephone interview
when asked why the campaign's financial statement filed with the federal election commission showed $5.5 million in cash on hand, $1 million less than the matching funds he said were in the bank, harrison said he did not prepare the report and could not explain it
campaign aides did not return calls monday and tuesday to answer questions about the report
whether or not the robertson campaign has accepted the matching funds is significant because presidential candidates who are declared eligible for such funds must abide by spending limits under federal regulations
the robertson campaign contends that it does not have to abide by the limits unless it actually uses the money, and considers that although it put the funds into its bank, it still has the option of sending the money back and bypassing the spending limts, said harrison
that will be our contention if we decide not to accept them,'' harrison said. ``it's a decision that hasn't been made yet.''
fec spokesman fred eiland said, ``that's sort of a dubious argument, but the commission would have to answer that.''
he noted that candidates must sign an agreement to abide by the spending limits even before they actually get the matching funds
the spending cap issue is more important for robertson than for any other presidential candidate because he is by far the closest to the limit
the cap is $23 million for the primary season plus another 20 percent, or $4.6 million, allowed for fund-raising expenses
as of the end of january, robertson reported spending $17.6 million against the $23 million cap, plus $4.3 million against the fund-raising cap
those figures did not include february's spending toward the iowa and new hampshire contests, tuesday's south dakota and minnesota contests or the super tuesday primaries in 20 states on march 8
harrison said the $5.5 million loan from sovran bank in virginia was secured, but neither he nor the bank's regional executive officer, earl slattum, would disclose what collateral was required
the loan was bigger by far than any taken out by the other candidates
election law requires that banks treat presidential campaign loans in the normal course of business, with no special considerations applied
slattum cited customer privacy considerations and refused to divulge any information about robertson's loan, the bank's general lending practices, or even the cities included in the region slattum heads
slattum and harrison also declined to give the date the loan was taken out although fec spokesman eiland said that is required on the disclosure reports. the report listed the date only as january 1988
robertson also used his matching funds to secure a $1.5 million loan in december from sovran bank. that loan was paid back on jan. 10
robertson reported spending during january of $7.9 million, more than any other presidential campaign, and ended the month with $5.5 million in cash on hand and $6 million in outstanding debts
a new election system in which people vote for candidates by lining up behind them led to one death and widespread charges of fraud, kenya newspapers reported tuesday
the purpose of monday night's voting was to choose parliamentary candidates for kenya african national union of president daniel arap moi, kenya's only legal political party
john matere keriri, who was assistant transport minister but failed in his nomination bid, called the vote ``an absolute sham, a fraud not an election.''
keriri and a few other losing candidates claimed they or their agents were arrested and harassed by partisan officials the night before the monday vote and that several agents were barred from polling stations
one man identified as a keriri supporter died and two other people were hospitalized in the northern kirinyaga district, where violence was used to keep some people from voting, newspapers reported
the elections marked the party's first test of the new system and a much-criticized regulation that allows nominees with more than 70 percent of the vote to enter parliament unopposed
at least 30 candidates received more than 70 percent
church leaders, lawyers and a few politicians have called the line-forming system as intimidating and said the 70-percent rule disenfranchizes non-party members
under the new system, voters lined up behind candidates and officials took a head count
government officials contend the new system will prevent corruption and give the party rank and file a greater voice. candidates previously were chosen by the party chairman, secretary-general and treasurer
preliminary results indicated poor turnouts in many constituencies. the standard, an independent nairobi newspaper, reported hundreds of eligible voters milled outside some voting locations and only a few lined up to vote
it appeared more people came as spectators than as voters,'' it said
anglican bishop david gitari accused election officials of trying to rig the ballots. he said the election official at one polling station refused to count heads when more people lined up behind keriri than behind his opponent
official tallies were expected later this week in the week
presidential nominations are due saturday but no-one is expected to challenge moi. he has held the office since the death of the first president, jomo kenyatta, a decade ago
sen. jesse helms, r-n.c., said tuesday that most u.s. intelligence agences now believe the soviet union is hiding hundreds of potent medium-range missiles in europe. the reagan administration said his assertion is incorrect
helms, commenting as the senate foreign relations committee continued its examination of the new treaty banning all medium-range missiles in europe, has repeatedly said estimates from the defense intelligence agency indicate the existence of at least 300 more ss-20 missiles than those declared by the soviets
the senator, who opposes the treaty, said on tuesday he now has been told a majority of u.s. intelligence agencies support that view
but sen. claiborne pell, d-ri., the committee chairman, read an administration statement denying that
the statement called the helms assertion incorrect, and added: ``the majority of the national intelligence community does not support the view the soviets have withheld a number of ss-20s.''
the statement said that all data on the number of such weapons will be reviewed when the soviets submit an updated report on their medium-range missile force after the new treaty is ratified by the senate
that report will be verified by on-site inspection, the statement said
it said that cia director william webster, ``speaking for the entire intelligence community, has said the (submitted) soviet data ... `falls within (u.s.) intelligence estimates.'''
the ss-20 is a mobile, highly accurate, medium-range missile, each of which carries three nuclear warheads. background on role of assistant judges, wheel, picking up 7th graf pvs, `the charges...'.</note>
a former county assistant judge who was the focus of misconduct charges against three state supreme court justices has been convicted of lying under oath
a vermont district court jury found former chittenden county assistant judge jane wheel guilty late monday after more than six hours of deliberations, said court spokeswoman harriett eitapence
an attorney for wheel, found guilty of three counts of lying under oath, said he would try to have the verdict set aside
wheel, 55, was charged in october 1986 for her actions during an inquest earlier that year into allegations that she had padded her paycheck
the prosecution maintained she lied when asked if she had altered court files to indicate that she was sitting in court on days she actually was elsewhere. judges are paid for time spent hearing cases
assistant judges in vermont are elected lay people, while regular judges are lawyers appointed by the governor. wheel was a high school english teacher until her election in 1974 and had long been active in democratic politics
lay judges, who make up the state's superior court system, hear mostly civil cases, although before court reorganization several years ago they also often heard criminal cases
the charges against wheel, who was defeated in a september 1986 election, rocked the state's judiciary because of her association with three vermont supreme court justices
misconduct charges were filed in january 1987 by the judicial conduct board against wheel, former supreme court justices william hill and thomas hayes, and justice ernest gibson iii, accusing them of using their influence to help wheel while she was under investgation by the attorney general's office in the paycheck-padding case
hayes died last year, and charges against gibson were dropped. wheel and hill await proceedings before the conduct board
the board is slated to take up 12 counts against hill on march 7
one of the misconduct counts alleges that hill berated an employee of the chittenden county superior court when she walked into a room and saw wheel's arms around hill
another alleges that wheel's friendship with hill was so open that an employee of the court called hill at home and warned him that unless he altered his behavior in front of wheel it could do serious damage to his reputation
another charge alleges that hill talked improperly outside the courtroom with wheel about a case that had been tried in her court and was being appealed before him at the supreme court level
during the trial, assistant attorney general david suntag portrayed wheel as someone who had been caught in a web of lies and deceit as she signed her name to the court folders to cover up the fact she had hardly sat in court on cases for a year
she lied under oath, and no amount of talking about lots of other things and no amount of changing stories ... can change that,'' suntag told the jury
wheel's attorney, richard davis, said he would move to have monday's verdict set aside on grounds that the evidence did not support a guilty finding
during the trial, which began jan. 25, davis had argued that wheel was the victim of a vendetta by court personnel
wheel faces a maximum penalty of 15 years in jail and a $10,000 fine for each of the three counts. no sentencing date had been set
snow fell tuesday from michigan to new york, while rain dampened areas from the gulf coast to new england
clear to partly cloudy skies prevailed west of the mississippi river
snow fell in southeastern kentucky, west virginia, and western sections of pennsylvania and new york, mixed with rain across parts of northern new england and central new york
heavier snowfall tuesday morning included 6 inches at coopers rock state park in west virginia; 5 inches in laurel village, pa.; and 3 inches at somerset, pa., and chalke hill, pa
snow showers dusted the michigan shore of lake superior between marquette and sault ste. marie
rain was scattered from southern new england across southeastern new york and eastern pennsylvania, and the tennessee valley, and fell in portions of the central gulf coast and central florida
gale warnings were posted along the new england coast, where winds were clocked at 20 to 35 mph. winds of 20 to 35 mph also were common from the northern plains to the upper great lakes, resulting in sub-zero wind chill readings
ice jams prompted flood warnings along streams near buffalo, n.y
temperatures at 2 p.m. est ranged from 9 degrees at yellowstone park, wyo., to 84 degrees at homestead, fla. the morning low was 14 below zero at gunnison, colo
wednesday's forecast called for sunny skies over most of the nation, with snow showers in parts of the great lakes region and a few rain showers in the florida peninsula
high temperatures were expected to reach the 20s and 30s from wyoming and colorado across the northern half of the plains, the middle-mississippi valley, the great lakes and the ohio valley to new england; the 60s in much of california, southern new mexico, southern texas, northern florida and southern georgia; the 70s and low 80s in the desert southwest and southern and central florida; and the 40s or 50s elsewhere
yugoslavia denied tuesday that it had granted political asylum to the son of former egyptian president gamal abdel nasser, who is wanted for terrorism in egypt
in a statement read to the associated press over the telephone, a yugoslav foreign ministry spokesman also denied that khaled abdel nasser is a permanent resident of belgrade
it is true that he periodically visits yugoslavia like any visitor who has a tourist visa,'' said the spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity
nasser and 19 others were indicted in egypt last week in connection with four shooting attacks on israeli and u.s. diplomats and embassy workers in cairo between 1984 and 1987. two israelis died and six israelis and two americans were wounded in the shootings
nasser, 38, and 10 other defendants face possible death sentences. the other nine could receive life sentences
arab reports said nasser had been living in belgrade with his family for four months and that yugoslavia granted him political asylum
we want to emphasize that he has never asked for nor was granted political asylm'' in yugoslavia, said the statement. ``he (nasser) is not engaged in any political activity in yugoslavia.''
the spokesman said that nasser possesses a multiple-entry tourist visa given to all those who have diplomatic passports
he has an egyptian diplomatic passport,'' he added
cairo newspapers reported that authorities in yugoslavia had been notified that nasser is a fugitive sought by interpol, the international criminal police organization
the daily al-akhbar also said ahmad el-khawaga, a defense attorney and head of the egyptian bar association, went to belgrade to bring nasser back from exile
yugoslavia's late leader josip broz tito was a co-founder of the non-aligned movement with gamal abdel nasser. egypt and yugoslavia have no extradition treaty
an israeli tank was attacked while on patrol in south lebanon, and two israeli soldiers were killed and two wounded, the military command announced tuesday
lebanese security sources said earlier tuesday that guerrillas using rocket-propelled grenades ambushed an israeli armored patrol consisting of one tank and one armored personnel carrier near the south lebanese village of braachit, killing two soldiers and wounding others
the israeli army announcement said the tank was hit by an explosive device at 6 p.m. monday near braachit, six miles north of the israeli border in israel's self-designed security zone in south lebanon
the explosive device was activated and as a result of that, two soldiers were killed and two others suffered light wounds and were rescued,'' the brief announcement said. it said israeli soldiers launched a search in the area
the announcement gave no details. the military command did not explain why the announcement was delayed for over 24 hours
the israeli fatalities in south lebanon were the first this year
both vehicles were raked with rocket-propelled grenades that set off a chain of ammunition explosions in the tank. no one could have escaped alive from the burning tank,'' said one of the lebanese sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity
he said the guerrillas were either shiite moslem fundamentalists or pro-syrian leftists. both groups operate in that area
israel created its six- to 10-mile-wide security zone when it withdrew the bulk of its troops from lebanon in june 1985, ending a three-year occupation
the zone is patrolled by about 1,000 israeli soldiers assisted by about 1,000 militiamen from the mostly christian south lebanon army, which is trained and backed by israel
st-jean, quebec (ap) _ andre bissonnette, who was dismissed from the federal cabinet after news reports linked him to a questionable land deal, was acquitted tuesday of four charges of fraud, breach of trust and conspiracy
normand ouellette, bissonnette's close friend and political associate, was convicted of one count of fraud but acquitted of one charge of breach of trust, one count of conspiracy to commit fraud and one count of conspiracy to commit breach of trust
charges were filed after a series of sales that tripled the price of a piece of land in st-jean from $800,000 to $2.98 million in 11 days of january 1986. the canadian dollar is worth about 79 u.s
oerlikon aerospace inc. contracted to buy the land 13 weeks before the federal government awarded it a $600 million contract to build canada's low-level air defense system
prime minister brian mulroney fired bissonnette, 42, of st-jean a day after reports of the land sales were made public last year. he had been junior transport minister
in ottawa, mulroney's office released a statement saying ``the prime minister is very pleased that mr. bissonnette has been fully exonerated by a jury of his peers.'' the statement said nothing about bissonnette's chances of getting back into the cabinet
the jury was told to decide whether steps taken by ouellette that drove up the price were ``objectively dishonest,'' and whether bissonnette helped him
judge jean-guy boilard of quebec superior court also instructed the jury to determine whether bissonnette knew of methods used by ouellette, who managed his blind trust
prosecutors alleged that bissonnette and ouellette used privileged information to profit illegally from the sale. bissonnette denied in court that half the profit from the final transaction, in which ouellette was involved, wound up in the bank accounts of himself and his wife
bissonnette smiled slightly as the verdict was read. he later crossed the room, patted ouellette on the back and wished him luck
bissonnette, a self-made millionaire, was known as the ``chicken king'' of quebec because one of his companies supplied much of the barbecued chicken sold in restaurants in the province
outside the courthouse, he shook hands with several jurors. he thanked mulroney for supporting him over the past 13 months and said he would leave any decision about his political future up to the prime minister. supplies</head>
the government is reviewing plans for comprehensive screening of blood supplies for aids, since some blood banks were testing only 8 percent of their supplies, the news agency of nigeria reported tuesday
dr. etim essien, chairman of the national adivsory committee on aids, said testing in nigeria's nine blood banks ranged from 8 to 85 percent of supplies
essien said the incidence of aids in nigeria was small, but plans for a comprehensive screening program were under review to guard against the spread of the disease through blood transfusions
essien said there were 20 known cases of aids in nigeria, africa's most populous nation with more than 105 million people, and the chances of getting the disease through blood transfusion were small. he gave no details about the screening program or say when it would be implemented
essien's comments followed the launching of a $1 million national aids education program
meanwhile, a lagos newspaper confirmed the death friday of the country's 12th aids victim, a gambian national living in nigeria
professor idris mohammed, also speaking at the launching of the new aids program, said nigeria's aids victims were mostly low-income farmers who patronized prostitutes
acquired immune deficiency syndrome is a disease in which a virus attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to a wide variety of infections and cancers
aids is most often transmitted through sexual contact. other means of transmission include transfusions of tainted blood or blood products, and the sharing of contaminated hypodermic needles or syringes by drug abusers. aids can also be passed from mother to child at or before birth. wounded in his left shoulder, sted `her'. picks up 8th graf, `according to...'.</note>
a 28-year-old transient was being held tuesday in lieu of $1 million bond, accused of shooting two plainclothes policemen and then barricading himself with hostages in an office building
david johnson was charged with two counts of attempted capital murder in the monday night shooting
authorities alleged that johnson, a familiar figure to officers patrolling downtown, scuffled with police who confronted him, got an officer's gun and opened fire
one of the captives, jerry renaud, said the gunman seemed disoriented and contended he was being framed by police
my understanding is he had some mental problems and it's your typical downtown problem that we've been faced with,'' city manager lou fox said monday night
meanwhile, officer edwin gorrell, 33, a two-year veteran, was in critical condition at brooke army medical center after more than 13 hours of surgery on a head wound, said hospital spokesman robert clark
officer onofre serna, 26, was in good condition at medical center hospital with a wound to his left shoulder, said hospital spokeswoman inez eisazadeh
according to police spokesman sgt. paul buske, the two officers had stopped the man and a female companion who appeared to be intoxicated
a struggle ensued,'' buske said. ``one of the officers lost his weapon. (the suspect) picked up the weapon and several shots were fired.''
the man took a gun, a badge and a police radio and fled into a travis park plaza building, where he took two hostages. he released them and went to a third-floor office, where he took three hostages
renaud, an accountant who was working late with others at deloitte, haskins and sells, said he at first thought the gunman was joking, then decided to listen to the man to calm him down
he seemed disoriented at first, despondent, that he had gotten framed,'' renaud said tuesday. ``he said he wasn't there to hurt us. he said he just needed a place to hide out for the night.''
after a few minutes, he said, he and the man got a soft drink to cool off
right after he got his coke, i decided i needed a drink desperately and poured a little seagram's seven in my coke so i could think,'' renaud said. ``i got interrupted quite a few times by the telephone, but i never really tried to say anything that would upset him.''
renaud and his two co-workers escaped when the gunman walked into another area to take a sixth hostage, buske said. he surrendered an hour later
the san antonio express-news talked to the man by telephone monday night. he told the newspaper he was just walking when he was grabbed by a man with a gun and a badge
the gun just went off ... i didn't mess with nobody,'' he said
gorrell and serna were part of a downtown foot patrol aimed at deterring street crime
last month, a mentally ill homeless man shot and killed a dallas police officer in a downtown parking lot. south dakota win for dole and abc projecting gephardt winner. the 1st add, a0664, should stand</note>
sen. bob dole fought his gop presidential rivals in the south dakota primary and minnesota caucuses tuesday as vice president george bush all but conceded defeat in advance. massachusetts gov. michael dukakis dueled richard gephardt and the rest of the pack for fresh momentum in the democratic race
the two states were billed as the gateway to super tuesday _ a midwestern opportunity to demonstrate electoral strength before the march 8 festival of delegate-rich primaries and caucuses, mostly in southern and border states
dole was rated the heavy favorite in the south dakota republican primary as he bid to rebound from last week's drubbing in new hampshire
as the polls were closing, cbs news and abc news projected that dole would win the republican primary in south dakota. cbs said bush and former television evangelist pat robertson in a tight race for second place in the gop race
abc also projected gephardt as the winner in south dakota. 
the kansas senator also campaigned hard in minnesota, but robertson dreamed of an upset and rep. jack kemp made an all-out effort as well
bush, who finished third in the iowa caucuses earlier this month, made little effort in the two neighboring midwestern states. he spent little money in minnesota and withdrew television advertisements from south dakota stations
democrat dukakis, fresh from a triumph in the new hampshire primary, aimed for a convincing win in minnesota as he bid to demonstrate that his candidacy has appeal outside new england. iowa caucus winner gephardt, sen. paul simon and jesse jackson also vied for support as they sought standing in the race before the primary and caucus calendar turned south
dukakis and gephardt each hoped for a win in a heated south dakota race. sen. albert gore jr. invested heavily in television advertising, as well, hoping for a strong showing outside his native south in advance of super tuesday
simon, who once said he would quit the race if he failed to score a victory in either state, stepped back from that standard late last week and vowed to stay in the race no matter where he finished
gary hart, his comeback candidacy in tatters after poor finishes in iowa and new hampshire, campaigned hard in south dakota
for hart, gore, jackson and robertson, south dakota posed a financial test, as well. each man finished with less than 10 percent of the vote in new hampshire, and a similar result in south dakota would deprive them of federal matching funds beginning in 30 days. a candidate can requalify by gaining 20 percent of the vote in a future primary
the states offered a bewildering array of delegate selection provisions
south dakota's democratic vote was a preferential poll designed to serve as an advisory opinion to a statewide caucus on march 12 that will allocate 15 of the state's 19 delegates
but minnesota's democrats began the selection of 78 of the state's 87 delegates to the party's nominating convention in atlanta in july
south dakota's republican primary voters picked all 18 of the state's delegates to the gop nominating convention in new orleans in august
minnesota's republicans expressed their presidential preferences through a straw vote and selected delegates to begin the process of picking 31 national convention delegates
