serious money,'' caryl churchill's black comedy about high finance and dirty dealing, closed feb. 20 at the royale theater after a run of 15 performances. profession</head>
few people will remember the full name of what was, until recently, the fourth largest law firm in the united states
but few who watched its rise to glory will soon forget the spectacular fall of finley, kumble, wagner, heine, underberg, manley, myerson &amp; casey
as recently as last summer, finley, kumble was a growing, thriving concern, or so it seemed _ 700 of the country's hottest lawyers chasing after business with an aggressiveness and a flamboyance that shook up the profession
its partners included three former u.s. senators, a one-time new york governor and an ex-mayor of new york city. in addition to lavish headquarters on park avenue, it had major branches in beverly hills, miami and washington, d.c., and smaller offices throughout the united states and abroad. its clients included citibank, shearson lehman brothers and real estate developer donald trump
by the end of the year, finley, kumble was gone _ ``vaporized,'' says founder steven kumble _ and its lawyers were hiring lawyers for the battle over what remained: an $83 million debt
the fabric of a law firm is a very delicate thing,'' kumble says now. ``if you tear it, it can unravel very quickly. and that is what happened in this case.''
ambition, jealousy and greed were the instruments of destruction at finley, kumble, where top partners waged internal warfare and borrowed money to pay their own salaries, which were among the highest in the profession
as the yarn unraveled publicly in the legal press last fall, the profession looked on with morbid fascination tinged with glee and a bit of introspection
finley, kumble was never popular among other lawyers and judges. it was too big, too brash, too noisy and didn't play by the old rules. it lacked gentility. but for all its excesses, the firm embodied many of the changes that have been sweeping the legal profession for the last two decades
law firms once operated like exclusive, private clubs
now, large firms are absorbing smaller ones. partners, who once considered a change in firms to be tantamount to divorce, are doing what many married couples have done in recent years _ finding new partners. firms that 20 years ago were unlikely to have even one branch office outside their home city are now spreading around the globe
finley, kumble was among the biggest of the national superfirms. it didn't grow ``organically,'' like the old establishment firms; when it wanted new partners, it went out and bought them. in many respects, finley, kumble operated more like the multinational corporations it served than the law firms it challenged
i do think it's a harbinger of sorts,'' said richard abel, a professor of law at the university of california at los angeles who is studying the development of the legal profession. ``certainly many lawyers are viewing it as a cautionary tale, and a worrisome one.''
finley, kumble was founded in 1968 by eight new york lawyers led by kumble, a graduate of yale university and harvard law school who was 35 years old at the time. kumble says he had no grand plan _ he just wanted to practice law
the firm grew gradually in its first decade. by 1978, it had 70 lawyers, all still in new york. they were doing very well
basically, the firm grew because we ... expanded to meet the needs of our clients,'' says kumble. ``we didn't set out to grow; we set out to build a law practice.''
things began to change in 1978. recognizing the growing importance of los angeles as a financial and corporate center, finley, kumble took on marshall manley as its first california partner and allowed him to begin building the firm's first branch office in beverly hills
as it grew, the california office began to challenge the dominance of new york. in 1983, in a bitter power struggle, manley persuaded management to let him become co-managing partner along with kumble
by then, finley, kumble had 283 lawyers, only 100 of them in new york. there were 86 lawyers in beverly hills, 63 in a new washington office, 26 in miami and eight in san diego. the firm was on the move
in the next four years, finley, kumble would more than double in size and open new offices in chicago, dallas, baltimore, downtown los angeles, baton rouge, la., tallahassee, palm beach and ft. lauderdale, fla., newport beach and sacramento, calif., and london
it would recruit former sens. paul laxalt, russell long and joseph tydings to join former new york gov. hugh carey and former new york city mayor robert f. wagner sr
it would become one of the most high-profile firms in the country, with lawyers and legal publications constantly discussing its aggressive tactics and its philosophy of ``meritocracy,'' in which lawyers were said to be rewarded according to the business they generated, not the years they served
but the battle for control of the firm continued. first it was manley; after he left in 1986, it was a new partner, harvey myerson, who struggled with kumble
the showdown came in february 1987. at a management committee meeting in miami, the firm's officers voted to strip kumble of power, which fell to myerson and robert washington jr., head of the washington office
the expansion continued, but through that spring and summer, unsettling reports made the rounds among lower-level partners. according to these partners, the rumors said the firm was in debt _ deeply in debt
new york partner peter fass says the bottom line for him was the discovery, just a few months after he joined the firm in january 1987, that more than half the firm's profits were borrowed
the ship was already underwater when i got there, but i didn't know about it,'' fass said. ``a lot of people who had been there for a number of years had no inkling what was going on.''
what was going on, many partners later charged, was that the managing partners had hidden the borrowing by creating a separate corporation that took out bank loans to buy up the firm's accounts receivable _ the unpaid bills of clients
this money was then used to pay the generous salaries of the firm's superstar lawyers, many of them lured in the firm's final year of furious expansion. laxalt and long were said to have been offered $800,000 a year
in september, the borrowing scheme was divulged publicly in an extraordinary front-page article in the american lawyer magazine by editor steven brill. it was titled, ``bye, bye, finley, kumble,'' and it was prophetic
it was devastating,'' said one los angeles partner, who, like many people interviewed for this article would speak only on condition of anonymity. ``that article, i think, was really the beginning of the end.''
in it, brill not only laid bare finley, kumble's financial morass in excruciating detail, he also castigated the firm for what he viewed as a misplaced sense of priorities
it has become a place,'' wrote brill, ``where the only corporate culture is money, where things like pro bono (charitable legal work) or collegiality are sissy stuff _ which means that when the money dries up, even temporarily, there's no other glue there, no shared values, to hold the place together.''
toward the end of the summer, lawyers were leaving finley, kumble in growing numbers. after brill's article, the stream turned to a torrent. by the beginning of december, branches were closing and it became apparent that the firm could not survive. on dec. 21, at a sparsely attended meeting in new york, the remaining partners voted to disband as of jan. 4
a four-member liquidation committee is now sorting the firm's accounts, trying to determine how its assets stack up against the $83 million debt. one washington partner estimates that as much as $60 million can be squeezed out of the firm's real estate, accounts receivable and other assets. but he said the process could take years
i'm sure that five years from now there will still be some quivering in the corpse,'' he said
meanwhile, two lawsuits have been filed by california partners richard osborn and david ellsworth, and others are expected. osborn and ellsworth allege that they were misled about the financial health of the firm and should not be responsible for repaying the debt
four banks have sued, charging that all partners are responsible and that some assets have been hidden. some partners who have signed individual settlements with the banks were not named in the suit, and more such settlements are likely
what went wrong at finley, kumble? the consensus is that the firm grew too far, too fast, exercising questionable business judgment along the way
its level of borrowing was ``almost unheard of'' among law firms, according to jack kaufman, chairman of an american bar association committee on law office management and president of hildebrandt inc., the nation's largest legal management consulting firm
in fact, until recently, law firms didn't borrow, period,'' kaufman said
kumble counters that the firm's loans were no different from those employed by many corporations. ``it was a big business, and it borrowed like big businesses do,'' he said
the problem, he said, was that when adversity began driving partners away from the firm, those remaining couldn't support the debt. and as they realized that, they left too
and what of brill's contention that finley, kumble lacked the loyalty, friendship and shared goals that hold law firms together, that it was a place to do business, nothing more?
i've had more conversations with other people in two weeks than i had in 11 months at finley, kumble,'' said fass, now at another manhattan firm. ``there, nobody cared what you did so long as you brought in money.''
still, finley, kumble's basic business strategy _ national growth, corporate-style aggressiveness _ was far from unique
ten years ago, only two law firms in the united states had more than seven branches, according to ucla's abel. in 1987, there were 13 such firms. ten years ago, no firm had more than 300 lawyers. in 1987, there were 38
abel said the growth has been disproportionate among the lowest-paid attorneys, the associates, whose fees help pad the profits of increasingly wealthy partners
others say simply that the growth has been triggered by a new intensity in competition that has forced firms to reach out for new business
it's gotten to be a very tough, competitive marketplace,'' kaufman said
kumble, who is now chairman of lincolnshire management, a firm that arranges and finances leveraged buyouts, prided himself as a seer of the legal profession, often to the irritation of his competitors. he is giving no ground now
i think a lot of firms are emulating what finley, kumble did, in terms of being a national law firm, in terms of lateral recruitment (of partners), in terms of expansion, and i think that will continue,'' he said
the problem we had is that our management committee became very politicized. ... i don't think the concept was flawed. i think the combination of people we had didn't work cohesively. it wasn't the concept _ it was the people.''
despite her opposition to apartheid, despite her work as a u.n. delegate, despite her award-winning efforts for human rights, miriam makeba insists she is an artist _ not a politician
it was as an artist that the empress of african song first spoke out against the system of discrimination in south africa, testifying before the united nations special committee on apartheid in 1963. in retaliation, south africa banned her records
afterward, i tell the press, `i am not a politician or a diplomat,''' makeba writes in her recently published autobiography ``makeba: my story,'' written with james hall (new american library, $18.95)
i am just a singer, i say. but in south africa, when the authorities learn of my testimony, i become something else: a criminal.''
makeba: my story,'' recounts some of the joy and sadness in the life of one of south africa's most acclaimed singers, who has been in exile from her native country since 1959
she decided to write her autobiography five years ago. ``i never really wanted to write a book. besides, i don't know how to write.''
however, makeba said, friends convinced her of the book's importance; she was ``the first artist to leave the country and make some type of impact on the world'' while not forgetting the problems that exist in south africa
they said that if anything should happen to me, others could write whatever they wanted without my being able to say whether it's true or false,'' she said
it was so hard. every time i read it, i just cry. this morning i was looking at the book. ... i looked at it for maybe for 10 minutes and i was crying.''
the book coincides with the release of ``sangoma,'' the singer's first american album since the late 1960s. it is a collection of 19 african songs, sung in three languages. the songs were taught to makeba by her mother, who was a sangoma, the south african term for a healer in close communication with ancestral spirits
`sangoma' is the most personal record i've made,'' makeba said. ``i like the songs because every time i sing them i think about my mother because she sung them.''
born in johannesburg on march 4, 1932, with the xhosa tribal name zensile, makeba has survived bitter personal and career setbacks
when she was just 18 days old, she went to jail for six months with her mother, who had illegally brewed homemade beer to support the family. later, after her mother was released, the family moved to pretoria, where they endured the hardship of apartheid
at a young age, she found joy in singing. some of the songs protested her country's white minority regime: the songs were a way she and others could demonstrate their defiance in school and church choruses
makeba started her professional career in 1952. she was chosen as the female vocalist for one of the country's top bands, the manhattan brothers
in 1955 she accepted a small role in the documentary, ``come back africa,'' based on the life of a murdered black boxer. harry belafonte spotted her in the film, helped her to obtain a visa and then boosted her career when she arrived in the united states in 1959
she writes in her book that belafonte _ or ``big brother,'' as she calls him _ gave her this advice: ``you must always be careful how you conduct yourself on stage and off, because some day you will have a chance to speak on behalf of your people.''
with her ``click'' singing and deep but lilting voice, makeba created a sensation in her first american tv appearances and new york club dates, and she was received by the late ethiopian emperor haile selassie, cuban president fidel castro, the late president john f. kennedy and other world leaders
in 1960, her mother died and she wished to return home to visit her grave and see relatives. she went to the south african consulate in new york
the man at the desk takes my passport. he does not speak to me, but to himself when he says, `miriam makeba,' as if he was expecting this moment,'' she writes. ``he takes a rubber stamp and slams it down on my passport. then he walks away. i pick up my passport. it is stamped `invalid.'''
she has not been allowed to return to south africa since
her troubles were not limited to her native land. she has been married five times, including once to south african trumpet player hugh maskela, but her career in the united states was most affected by her marriage to black activist stokely carmichael
i never had any problems with the officials in this country, it's just that when i married stokely ... many concerts that were booked for me were canceled _ i guess because some people took my marriage so personally,'' she said
and when that happened i had a tour planned in europe, so i just packed up and went to some of my friends in guinea.''
her friendship with guinea's president, sequo toure, led to her work as a guinean delegate to the united nations
more recently, makeba completed six months as a special guest on paul simon's graceland world tour, which included her long-awaited return to the united states
when we went to zimbabwe, it was another experience,'' she said. ``just looking out from the stage and seeing all those people tight in the stadium. black people, white people _ from all walks of life _ just swaying together to the music. it was so beautiful
it made me almost cry, because i said why can't it be like that just next door. because we were right next door from home.''
makeba hopes that one day she will return to south africa
i guess if i stop believing that i will go home, there would really be no purpose for anything,''she said
in 1972, shirley strum found herself alone with a troop of baboons among the spare, scattered acacia trees on the plains of east africa, a jacket knotted around her waist and a clipboard in her hand
a graduate student in anthropology at the university of california, berkeley, strum had been dispatched to kenya to observe the baboons. she knew little about them. and she knew less about survival in the african wilderness
it was only total ignorance of what i was getting into that gave me the courage to go,'' she said recently in an interview
strum was supposed to stay in kenya for 18 months, just long enough to collect the data she would need to write a ph.d. thesis. instead, she made kenya her home
by 1976, her studies had grown into the gilgil baboon project. she now employs six full-time researchers
strum has written a lively, personal account of the project in ``almost human'' (random house, $22.50). she was in new york to promote the book, which synthesizes the ideas she has developed during 15,000 hours of watching baboons in kenya during the past 15 years
in ``almost human,'' she compares the behavior of the olive baboon, papio anubis, to the behavior of homo sapiens. her studies, vividly recounted in the book, challenge the accepted wisdom that baboons are brute, aggressive beasts. in so doing, the studies have changed her thinking about human nature
if baboons were aggressive, then the killer ape was where we started from,'' she said. early baboon studies formed part of the underpinning for the idea widely popularized in the 1960s by the writer robert ardrey that a ``killer ape'' lurks inside each of us. humans are fundamentally aggressive, ardrey wrote in ``african genesis,'' and nothing we do can change that; we can only control it
that is not what strum found, however. she draws an engaging picture of baboons as sophisticated creatures who prefer negotiation and persuasion to aggression
the old picture was of a society in which males held all power and used force to attain dominance. strum found that males were transients and that they did not arrange themselves in a hierarchy with dominant males on top. she found that females were the stable core of baboon troops, and were ranked in a dominance hierarchy. females _ not males _ were the linchpins of baboon society
they did not, however, exert their dominance over the males. ``it turns out to be a society where there is a complementarity of roles,'' strum said. ``even if you have dominance and aggression in the traditional sense, it doesn't explain everything.''
no one suggests that the hominids, or human-like creatures, that gave rise to humans resembled baboons. but, said strum, if baboons had developed to the point where they no longer relied on naked aggression, then humanity's early ancestors probably did too
it's impossible for me to believe that the early hominids were less sophisticated than baboons,'' she said. thus our early ancestors may have abandoned aggressive social practices long ago
strum grew up in san diego, and she had no plans to become an anthropologist when she left home in 1965 for the university of california. but the turmoil of those years in berkeley made a mark on her
as i lived through the free speech movement and the vietnam war protests, i found myself confronting, over and over, questions about human nature, about what was innate and impossible to modify and what was flexible and worth changing,'' she writes
she drifted in and out of the psychology and sociology departments before fixing on anthropology. she fell under the spell of sherwood washburn, a leading american anthropologist who had done some of the first observations of baboons in the 1950s and '60s. it was washburn who said: ``go out and watch baboons.''
that's what she did for six years, keeping careful records of her observations. in june 1978, at a conference on baboon behavior organized by strum, she presented her findings to her colleagues. ``the 10 worst days of my life followed,'' she writes
other baboon watchers at the conference couldn't accept her conclusions, or her methods. when she arrived in kenya, she decided to follow baboons on foot, rather than watching from a van, as her predecessors had done. that was partly what enabled her to learn so much about baboon society. ``rival baboon watchers criticized me,'' she writes. ``i was `interfering,' ruining the baboons!''
it took time, but strum overcame her disillusionment with her colleagues and won many of them over. as that crisis resolved, however, she faced a crisis of a different sort in africa: the baboons she had come to know so intimately were in danger; the undeveloped ranch on which they had been allowed to roam had been sold, and it was being divided into 5-acre and 10-acre parcels. the baboons' wilderness would soon be farmland
strum and her colleagues made preparations to do the unthinkable _ to relocate the baboons to another wilderness area. no one had ever attempted to move a group of non-human primates from one wilderness area to another
the search for a new location proved difficult, but at the last minute a site was found. the animals were difficult to capture. they were being moved to an area where they would have to learn to eat new foods. would they survive?
they would. ``it's been a great success,'' strum said. the animals adapted well, and with strum's help, survived a dry period shortly after arriving at their new home. the success of the move has made translocation an option for conservationists, she said
unwittingly, the baboons had given me much over the years, personally and scientifically,'' she writes. ``now i had been able to reciprocate by giving them a chance for a better future.''
former ``dukes of hazzard'' star tom wopat is battling his spirited ``good ole boy'' image with love songs and a new tv show about modern family issues
wopat is starring in the new cbs-tv drama, ``blue skies,'' and is maintaining a singing career with country music-oriented songs that have a more romantic feel than driving souped-up cars as the adventurous luke duke
blue skies'' is scheduled to begin this spring and the action involves coping with contemporary issues such as aging and alcoholism rather than rural escapades with his blond buddy john schneider
it was a golden opportunity to be involved with fine persons and escape the `good ole boy' stereotype,'' the 36-year-old wopat said. ``i'm a totally different character. in `dukes,' everything was fantasy. in `blue skies,' it's straightforward and as near to life as possible
i feel it's the type of show the public is looking for as shown by the success of `our house,''' he said. ``it's about three generations of family and the problems of the parents and their families.''
wopat and schneider, and their high powered car, the general lee, co-starred in ``dukes of hazzard'' for seven seasons beginning in 1978. since then, both have gone on to country music careers and remained in acting
he and schneider just reunited in a holiday special, ``christmas comes to willow creek,'' which did well in the ratings. he sees schneider six to 10 times a year
i love him dearly,'' he said. ``he's like a brother. we shared so much and we were in so many scenes together. we genuinely liked each other and had the same interests
we decided from the beginning it was going to be fun and we'd enjoy it and i think this came across on the screen. it's not common to have two leading men who got along as we did.''
looking back on the highly rated ``dukes,'' wopat said it was popular because it was different
until then, urban half-hour comedies were on. we were a new rural show that was action oriented with some violence and exciting stunts. it was a calculated approach: a dark-haired boy, a light-haired boy, a mean old man, a nice old man, a comical old man, a pretty girl
it was pure entertainment. kids could watch it with older people. there was no cussing and no sex except for (catherine bach's) legs. there was a little moral message once in a while and it was oriented to family, not like `dallas' or `dynasty
there were imitators, but we outlasted them all. no show will ever be seen again like it. the cost is too high.''
wopat, who directed some episodes of ``dukes,'' is selecting songs now for his second album. the first was ``tom wopat: a little bit closer.'' a cut from the album, ``a little bit closer,'' is the current release and has zipped up the country music charts
two previous songs have reached the top 20 on the charts: ``the rock and roll of love'' and ``susannah.'' he and his band, southwind, do four to eight shows a month
since ``dukes,'' he has performed in two stage musicals, ``carousel'' in washington, and off-broadway in ``olympus on my mind.''
he's not done quite as well musically as schneider, who's had no. 1 country music songs such as ``i've been around enough to know,'' ``what's a memory like you (doing in a love like this)'' and ``country girls.''
it's been a long and frustrating process except when you have a passion for it,'' wopat said about his music career. ``we're looking for a song to make a big difference _ that big hit that changes everything
i'm still in the process of making believers out there in my commitment to country music. i think i can broaden the base of country music because of my visibility on tv. i'm optimistic about my future in country music. i think i'll be here for a long time.''
wopat, who was raised on a small dairy farm in lodi, wis., says he watches very little television these days, mostly ``cheers'' and reruns of ``the andy griffith show.'' he hasn't seen reruns of ``dukes of hazzard'' for a long time
i have them all on tape. i got one out a while ago and looked at how i directed it

serious swingers'' (fantasy) _ bud shank and bill perkins

halfway through this record you swear you've heard this music somewhere before. you have if you listen to side 1
the most noteworthy thing about this album is that it marks only the second time these two longtime studio musicians have recorded together. the first time was in 1954
however, the title is ``serious swingers,'' and this album doesn't pretend to be any more than a good time _ incidental music for a saturday night
in the jungle of over-produced pop jazz and fusion albums, there is a place for people who want to swing, to plow straight ahead in familar fields. yet, this record somehow leaves an empty feeling. all the chops are just right, the solos just free enough that you know they weren't charted, the mix of ballad and swing ever so correct
a solid rythym section drives bill perkins' tenor sax and bud shank's alto
but the bottom line is this material has been done before and better by many. if you want the real thing instead of an homage, check out early miles davis or thelonious monk or charlie mingus

jimmy rowles-red mitchell (contemporary) _ ``i'm glad there is you''

this is a collection of simply played standards, spare in phrase, but beautifully executed
jimmy rowles' lilting piano combines with the delicate brush work of colin bailey on rodgers and hammerstein's ``it might as well be spring'' to create music mindful of the first scents of early april
on the title track, rowles brings out the passion those simple words have exchanged by trusting lovers. stacy rowles' charming trumpet solo to close the piece seconds the emotion
red mitchell shows his style without imposing on any of the arrangements with that need that bass players sometimes exhibit to prove they can do more than keep the beat
there is no flash in this record, only clean playing that sets a pleasant, content mood
two of the nation's biggest and best-known airlines are facing strike threats over wages, benefits and concessions that reflect growing hostility between labor and management in the intensely competitive deregulated industry
pan am corp. and the union representing 4,500 ground employees in 14 cities remained deadlocked monday following the breakup of their talks. union leaders in new york threatened to call a strike at any time and vowed ``guerrilla war'' tactics that included losing passenger bags and canceling reservations
at the same time in minneapolis, flight attendants at northwest airlines voted by a 94.4 percent majority to strike this weekend if a contract dispute over wages and benefits is not resolved
the strike authorization of 94.4 percent refects the deplorable state of labor relations at northwest airlines,'' said jeff musto, spokesman for the teamsters local 2747 representing 6,500 northwest attendants
officials at both airlines said managers would replace strikers in the event of walkouts and predicted minimal disruption. but the threat of a labor rebellion at pan am already appeared to be discouraging potential passengers
it's a very bad situation for everybody,'' said david perlman, president of dms travel in midtown manhattan. ``some people are shying away (from pan am flights).''
perlman said his agency has been using double bookings as an insurance technique for customers booked on pan am flights. for passengers taking pan am from kennedy airport to europe on monday night, for example, he also booked them on flights offered by other airlines to the same destinations
the union threats against pan am came against a background of staggering losses for the eighth-largest u.s. airline, which once dominated overseas travel but has been struggling over the past several years because of high costs and growing competition from other carriers, a partial result of airline deregulation a decade ago
pan am management has demanded $35 million in concessions from the teamsters, who control ground workers at boston, detroit, chicago, seattle, san francisco, san diego, los angeles, honolulu, houston, washington, new york and the florida cities of tampa, orlando and miami
prospects of a strike disruption at northwest were considered less severe, partly because flight attendants are the most easily replaced of all airline workers. but the carrier's machinists and pilots unions have not said whether they would honor a strike by flight attendants
northwest and its major unions have been engrossed in talks on new contracts since the 1986 merger with republic airlines, another result of deregulation, which made northwest the fifth-biggest u.s. airline
many former republic employees are paid less than their northwest counterparts, a cause of friction between the airline and its unions
northwest's latest proposal to the teamsters offers immediate elimination of pay gaps between former northwest and former republic flight attendants. the union claims the company is compensating by reducing vacation pay and retirement benefits. defense</head>
ohio's new anti-takeover law, a key element of federated department stores inc.'s strategy to thwart a hostile acquisition by canadian developer campeau corp., has been invalidated by a federal judge
the ruling monday by u.s. district judge carl rubin was regarded as at least a temporary victory for campeau, which has been pursuing the cincinnati-based retailing giant with a takeover offer valued at $5.4 billion
rubin granted campeau's request for a preliminary injunction against the new statute, which was passed as an addition to the state's existing takeover law. he said the new measure unconstitutionally discriminated against certain businesses and was an improper regulation of interstate commerce
mike webb, a spokesman for the ohio attorney general's office, said state officials had not decided whether to appeal the ruling. a federated spokesman declined comment
federated stock rose 50 cents a share monday to $60.75 in active new york stock exchange trading
the ruling removed one legal obstacle to campeau's efforts to acquire federated, which has been spurning the canadian concern's offers
campeau has a pending $61 a share hostile tender offer, totaling about $5.4 billion. it also has made an alternative offer to acquire the retailer for $66 a share, about $5.8 billion, in a definitive merger agreement
the toronto-based company had indicated the anti-takeover law could prove to be an impediment in arranging financing for the acquisition
campeau also has challenged another recently passed anti-takeover law in delaware, where federated is incorporated
rubin said ohio's law violated federal measures aimed at avoiding inconsistent regulation of commerce among states
the judge said the ohio law is ``discriminatory on its face'' because it regulates only takeovers by certain businesses organized in foreign countries. he said federal law prohibits such discriminatory legislation by states
the judge agreed with campeau attorneys that the canadian corporation could suffer irreparable injury because of the law
federated's board of directors on friday rejected campeau's $66 a share proposal, saying they were not convinced that campeau had solid financing for the deal
federated operates department and mass-merchandising stores in 36 states and had sales of more than $11 billion last year. its divisions include abraham &amp; straus and bloomingdale's of new york, bullock's and i. magnin in california, rich's in atlanta, filene's of boston and burdines of florida. stock</head>
santa fe southern pacific corp. is pondering a proposal from henley group inc. to scrap part of the railroad-energy giant's restructuring and sell $780 million in new stock to the dissident investor
the move, which would boost henley's stake in chicago-based santa fe to 34.3 percent from 15.7 percent, was announced monday and faced an uncertain reaction from santa fe, which has been fending off henley's unwanted overtures since mid-1987
santa fe spokesman robert gehrt said the proposal would be taken up at santa fe's regularly scheduled board meeting later today but would not comment further
henley's proposal called for santa fe to stop the planned payment of $5 per share in high-yield ``junk bonds'' for each of its 157.3 million shares on march 1. santa fe already has made a $25-per-share cash payout
henley has claimed persistently that the pay-in-kind debentures would leave shareholders with a large tax liability because of the way they are structured
instead, henley proposed that santa fe sell henley $780 million worth of new stock at $17.50 per share. proceeds from that deal would be used to make a onetime $5-per-share cash payout to all current shareholders
the proposed deal would mean 44.6 million new shares for henley and would boost santa fe's total shares outstanding to 201.9 million. but henley said the proposal was dependent on santa fe's annulment of a ``poison pill'' takeover defense that would make a hostile acquisition prohibitely expensive
under the measure, if any hostile suitor exceeds 20 percent ownership in santa fe's stock, other santa fe shareholders would be permitted to buy new stock at half price
henley now owns 24.6 million shares, or 15.7 percent, of santa fe, a railroad, land and natural resources concern that has been attempting to restructure because of federal regulatory rulings forcing it to sell one of its two railroads, either the santa fe line or southern pacific line
together, those lines constitute the nation's third-larges rail system extending over of 26,000 miles of main track
henley repeatedly has criticized santa fe's adoption of the ``poison pill,'' saying the measure restricted the ability of major holders to maneuver
in another development monday concerning santa fe, denver-based rio grande industries inc. filed an application with the interstate commerce commission to acquire the southern pacific line for $1 billion
the icc already has approved an expedited schedule for the application, with a final decision expected in six months, rio grande said
rio grande's action threw into question kansas city southern industries inc.'s rival bid of more than $1.25 billion for the southern pacific
l.f. rothschild holdings inc., a venerable investment firm that once served wealthy clients, later became dangerously diversified and was devastated by the october stock market crash, is selling itself to a kansas company despite earlier vows to remain independent
the announcement on monday signaled the latest casualty from the stock collapse and the first major wall street firm to be acquired by a savings and loan company. it also marked the end of an era for the 89-year-old brokerage, which had been hemorrhaging even before black monday, oct. 19
since then, several small firms have been forced out of business, and e.f. hutton group inc., one of the nation's largest investment firms, agreed in december to be acquired by shearson lehman brothers inc
rothschild, which also announced a $128.8 million loss for the final quarter of 1987, previously had sold virtually all its retail stock brokerage operations, cut staff by more than 40 percent and undertaken several other austerity moves
the firm said it would merge with stern brothers &amp; co., an investment bank in kansas city, mo. wholly owned by franklin financial services inc., which in turn is owned by franklin savings of ottawa, kan
the purchase price still was subject to adjustment, but estimated at about $4.40 in cash and securities for each of rothschild's 15.1 million shares, or about $66.4 million
franklin's major subsidiary is franklin savings institution, which had $9 billion in assets at the end of 1987. it also has brokerage, insurance, mortgage banking and financial consulting operations
the merger ... will form a unique investment banking combination,'' said ernest fleischer, chairman of franklin savings, who along with his wife owns just over half of the company's stock. ``it brings together the advantages of a new york trading desk and regional distribution.''
our stern brothers clients will receive expanded underwriting and distribution capabilities. for l.f. rothschild's clients, we will provide risk management and solid financial backing,'' he said
franklin financial will provide a 2{-year, $30 million loan to l.f. rothschild &amp; co., the broker-dealer subsidiary of l.f. rothschild holdings, the announcement said
in a separate announcement, rothschild holdings reported severe losses for both the fourth quarter and all of 1987, reflecting both the impact of the stock market crash and other troubles
rothschild lost $128.8 million on revenues of $32.5 million in the quarter, compared with a net loss of $15.4 million on revenues of $92.4 million in the same period of 1986
for the full year, it lost $129.1 million on $461.4 million in revenues, compared with an after-tax profit of $498,000, or 3 cents per share, on $401.1 million in revenues in 1986
it said approximately $56 million of the losses resulted from arbitrage and over-the-counter trading positions held during the stock market's collapse. an additional $15 million in losses stemmed from the post-crash bankruptcy of haas securities, a correspondent firm of rothchild's broker-dealer subsidiary
in addition, rothchild said quarterly and annual losses reflected at least $28 million in charges related to cutbacks in staff and offices and the sale of its retail brokerage business
once considered a specialty investment banking house that serviced extremely wealthy clients, rothschild later evolved into a publicly held firm that expanded into government bonds, mutual funds, arbitrage and other areas
the company encountered trouble in late 1987, when a management dispute surfaced over whether the company was becoming excessively diversified. two rothschild principals who opposed diversification abruptly quit and the firm foundered thereafter
andrew l. berger, rothschild's president, had said in a statement to the press on dec. 7 that the firm intended to remain independent, ``get our house in order and as quickly as possible return this business to profitability.''
the company has scrapped its public finance and municipal bond activities and agreed to sell its securities brokerage operations in new york, boston, and tampa, fla
it is in the process of closing offices in san francisco, switzerland and liechtenstein and is trimming its activities in london
oil prices started the week by moving lower in aimless trading
we're really trading on no new news,'' said john h. o'connell, an analyst at refco inc. commodities, on monday. ``its just a roller-coaster. up and down. but i don't think we're falling apart here.''
at the new york mercantile exchange, contracts for march delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s.crude, closed at $16.62 per 42-gallon barrel, down 8 cents from friday
among march contracts for refined products, wholesale heating oil settled at 45.79 cents a gallon, down 0.01 cent, while unleaded gasoline closed down 0.11 cent at 46.32 cents per gallon
o'connell said the market had been rife with stories about overproduction and other problems within the organization of petroleum exporting countries. but he said none of the stories have been considered reliable
campeau corp. has extended until midnight friday its $66-a-share offer for a friendly merger with federated department stores inc
meanwhile, a federal judge monday threw out an ohio anti-takeover law enacted to protect federated from the toronto-based developer
campeau said in a statement monday that without a friendly merger it would continue its hostile tender offer at $61 a share, or $5.4 billion. the friendly offer, which previously expired sunday, totals $5.8 billion
a federated representative had no comment on the renewed offer. the cincinnati-based retailer twice last week rejected the $66-a-share bid, saying campeau had not shown it had adequate financing
federated's board has delayed implementing a company shareholder-rights plan until midnight thursday. the rights plan, a so-called ``poison pill'' defense, is designed to make a hostile takeover too expensive
a campeau representative said the retail and real estate company was renewing its offer ``to remind (federated's) board we're very interested in signing a transaction.''
at the same time, chief u.s. district court judge carl b. rubin ruled unconstitutional the state's anti-takeover law enacted feb. 12. federated had no comment when asked if an appeal was planned
rubin said that while states have a role in the regulation of commerce, the new law ``is discriminatory on its face.''
the act required that certain foreign businesses attempting to acquire companies with major operations in ohio inform the state of the acquisition's impact on employment, tax revenues and details of its financing. correct to 2.59 trillion yen sted 259 trillion yen. picks up 5th graf pvs, dentsu said ...</note>
japanese companies spent 3.945 trillion yen, or about $30.34 billion, on advertising in 1987, up 8.1 percent from the previous year and the highest increase in six years, a report released tuesday said
dentsu inc., the country's largest advertising agency, said the increase reflected the recovery of the japanese economy led by rising domestic demand, and japanese firms' efforts to expand their doemstic business activities
the previous highest annual increase was 8.2 percent in 1981, although the standard for the survey was modifieid in 1985 by eliminating advertising for promoting exports, dentsu said
corporate spending on advertisements in newspapers and magazines and on radio and television was 259 trillion yen, or about $19.95 billion, up 7.7 percent from 1986, dentsu said. that accounted for 65.7 percent of total advertising expenses
dentsu said advertising through direct mail, outdoor ad services, inserts and exhibitions was 1.344 trillion yen, or $10.3 billion
eastman kodak co. completed its effort to buy sterling drug co. today by acquiring more than 96 percent of sterling's stock during the 20-day tender offer, a kodak spokesman said
kodak acquired about 54.5 million shares of sterling stock by the midnight monday deadline and will now complete the merger ``in the matter of a few days,'' said kodak spokesman ron roberts
the acquisition, the largest in kodak history, has attracted a great deal of criticism from stock analysts who said kodak was paying too much for the drug and household products company
kodak had agreed to pay $89.50 a share for the 57 million outstanding shares of sterling stock, which is more than $34 higher than the stock was selling for at the end of 1987. the total value of the deal is expected to be $5.1 billion
sterling, based in new york, has 22,000 employees and has annual sales of about $2 billion
kodak, based in rochester, has 124,000 employees and annual sales of about $13 billion a year
the acquisition will help kodak move into the $110 billion pharmaceutical industry and give the company an established pipeline to get drugs to market, said kodak spokesman charles smith
but analysts have cast a wary eye on the deal with several no longer recommending the purchase of kodak stock
on monday, kodak's bond rating was downgraded by moody's investor's service from a2 to aa2 largely because of the impending $5.1 billion loan the company is going to have to take on to pay for sterling
sterling's bond rating was also downgraded from a2 to aa1
with the acquisition, kodak gets a business featuring such familiar brand names as bayer aspirin, panadol non-aspirin pain reliever, lysol disinfectant, d-con rat killer, and phillips milk of magnesia
kodak officials have said they do not plan to sell any parts of sterling and will keep the company's organization intact
matsushita electric industrial corp., one of the world's largest consumer electronics manufacturers, has announced plans to set up a new firm in the united states in april for sales and maintainance of factory automation machines, a japanese news report said
the new firm, panasonic factory automation co., a division of matsushita electric corp. of america, will pave the way for matsushita's further expansion of factory automation business in north america and localization of the development of computer software used for factory automation, kyodo news service said tuesday
matsushita officials did not answer repeated telephone calls to their offices tuesday night
sales of factory automation equipment have been handled by panasonic industrial co., but the rapid growth of the factory automation market in north america led the parent company to set up a new firm dedicated solely to that purpose, kyodo said
panansonic factory automation co., which will sell industrial robots and installation devices for electronics parts, aims to boost its sales of 6.5 billion yen, or $58 million, in the fiscal year ending march 31, 1988 _ and by five times within five years, kyodo said
stock prices were narrowly mixed this morning after pushing to their highest levels in six weeks in the previous session
trading was more active than in monday's session
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, which jumped 25.70 points on monday to its highest level since jan. 7, backed off 1.33 to 2,038.96 after 90 minutes of trading
but advancing issues took a slight lead over losers in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 639 up, 584 down and 512 unchanged
volume on the big board came to 81.94 million shares as of 11 a.m. on wall street compared with 52.26 million shares at the same point on monday
the stock market has benefited recently from indications that the economy may be stronger than had been expected, leading some analysts to take an optimistic view of the outlook for corporate profits
but there is plenty of uncertainty about the economy's prospects
in a new report today, the government said orders to u.s. factories for durable goods plunged 2.8 percent in january, the biggest decline in a year
but that statistic has been volatile, and many analysts expected a decline in january because it had risen by an unusually large 4.1 percent in december
stock traders were also looking to today's congressional testimony by federal reserve chairman alan greenspan
greenspan said the country faces ``formidable challenges'' in keeping the economic recovery alive, urged further progress on reducing the federal deficit and cautioned congress against passing protectionist trade legislation
