federal reserve chairman alan greenspan said today the country faces ``formidable challenges'' in keeping the economic recovery alive, urged further progress on reducing the federal deficit and cautioned congress against passing protectionist trade legislation
greenspan confirmed that the central bank, in an effort to keep the recovery alive, had taken a ``small easing step a few weeks ago.''
the fed chairman said the central bank agreed with the reagan administration that recovery from the 1981-82 recession should last through this presidential election year, but said prospects for growth would be enhanced through further efforts to reduce the huge federal budget deficit, which raises u.s. dependence on foreign investment
we face formidable challenges over 1988 and beyond in meeting national economic goals of sustaining growth and progress toward price stability,'' greenspan told a house banking subcommittee
greenspan's comments came as part of the fed's semi-annual report to congress on the conduct of monetary policy. it was the first time greenspan has delivered the monetary report since he took over as chairman from paul volcker in august
volcker repeatedly lectured congress during his eight years as fed chief over the need to reduce the soaring federal budget deficits and warned that the central bank could not be expected to carry the full burden of keeping the economic recovery going
greenspan, sounding very much like volcker, echoed those same themes, contending in his testimony that the challenge of managing the economy ``cannot be negotiated by the federal reserve alone.''
for the united states, the most direct and beneficial approach would be to address the problem at its major source _ the federal budget deficit,'' he said. ``reducing the deficit further would give us the opportunity to add to domestic saving and reduce dependence on foreign capital, while still encouraging much-needed investment spending.''
since january a variety of interest rates, including home mortgage rates, have declined, leading many economists to speculate that the federal reserve had eased credit conditions
greenspan confirmed the move toward easier money, saying the fed had made the change amid indications of an economy that was slowing as the year began. he said the fed had the leeway to loosen credit conditions because the u.s. dollar had stabilized on foreign exchange markets
for part of last year, the central bank had been forced to push interest rates higher in an effort to support the dollar, which was declining rapidly in value. higher interest rates in this country tend to make dollar-denominated investments more attractive to foreignes
the fed released an economic forecast that was very close to the predictions made by the reagan administration when it released its budget last week
the fed said it believed the overall economy, as measured by the gross national product, would grow at rate of 2.0 percent to 2.5 percent this year, down from last year's growth of 3.8 percent. the administration is forecasting 2.4 percent gnp growth this year while many private economists believe growth will not reach 2 percent
in response to a question, greenspan said that while the fed was expecting sluggish economic growth this year, it saw no evidence that a recession would occur because the economy was not exhibiting the kinds of imbalances that normally start appearing at the end of an expansion
greenspan was asked by rep. charles e. schumer, r-n.y., whether over the next 12 months he saw ``a greater danger of increased inflation or recession?''
greenspan paused a moment and then responded, ``at the moment i would say the dangers are probably equal. it's very difficult to judge.''
at another point, greenspan disagreed openly with a contention by beryl sprinkel, president reagan's chief economist, that the fed had pursued a tight monetary policy during 1987
we did not perceive ourselves as being tight,'' greenspan said. he claimed that sprinkel placed too much emphasis on the importance of monetary growth in foretelling future economic activity. to have controlled the growth in the money supply to the extent that sprinkel advocates would have triggered ``an unduly inflationary environment'' last year, greenspan testified
there is a difference of opinion between mr. sprinkel and myself on this issue. it is an economist's disagreement,'' greenspan said
the fed chief refused under questioning to make a prediction on the course of short and long-term interest rates during the coming year, saying that for him to do so would be ``sheer mischievousness'' in light of the fact that the fed has direct influence over interest rates
the fed predicted that the unemployment rate, because of the more sluggishgrowth, would not show any improvement, holding at around 5.8 percent to 6 percent. the unemployment rate currently is 5.8 percent
on inflation, the fed predicted that consumer prices, as measured by an inflation index tied to the gnp, would rise 3.25 percent to 3.75 percent this year, a slightly better forecast than the administratin, which is looking for a 3.9 percent rise in the gnp price deflator, as the index is called
greenspan also revealed the money growth targets the fed has set for 1988. these targets, while covering a broad range, serve as a policy guide for the central bank as it tries to supply enough money to keep the economy growing at a healthy rate while guarding against pumping out so much money that inflation is rekindled
in one measure of the money supply, m-2, which includes checking deposits plus cash held by the pubic along with savings accounts and money market accounts, the fed said it was aiming for growth of 4 percent to 8 percent. this was the same target set for a somewhat broader measure of money known as m-3
the central bank, as it did last year, decided to set no growth target for m-1, the narrowest guage of money, because of its erratic behavior in recent years
the ranges for m-2 and m-3 were slightly lower than the 1987 targets of 5.5 percent to 8.5 percent
m-2 actually grew much more slowly last year than the target, increasing only 4 percent, a fact that raised criticism inside the reagan administration from some officials who contended that the central bank was pursuig a tight-money policy which was driving up interest rates and threatening a recession
the president's council of economic advisers issued a report on friday which said tight fed money policies were partly responsible for triggering the oct. 19 stock market crash
greenspan, less than a month after succeeding volcker, led the central bank to increase its discount rate from 5.5 percent to 6 percent on sept. 4. the action raising the rate the fed charges to make bank loans occurred as the value of the dollar was falling sharply and causing fears of higher domestic inflation
stock prices pulled back this morning, as the market ran into resistance in active trading after pushing to its highest levels in six weeks in the previous session
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, which jumped 25.70 points on monday to its highest level since jan. 7, was off 12.60 at 2,027.69 at noon on wall street
declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of nearly 3 to 2 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 558 up, 802 down and 480 unchanged
volume on the big board came to 112.65 million shares as of noontime compared with 52.26 million shares at the same point on monday
the stock market has benefited recently from indications that the economy may be stronger than had been expected, leading some analysts to take an optimistic view of the outlook for corporate profits
but there is plenty of uncertainty about the economy's prospects
in a new report today, the government said orders to u.s. factories for durable goods plunged 2.8 percent in january, the biggest decline in a year
many analysts had expected a decline in january, however, because orders had risen by an unusually large 4.1 percent in december
stock traders were also looking to today's congressional testimony by federal reserve chairman alan greenspan, who told a house subcommittee that the country faces ``formidable challenges'' in keeping the economic recovery alive
charles jensen, a technical market analyst for mki securities corp., said the market's decline was ``a reflex reaction after pretty good runup'' over the past two weeks
the market is in a mature rallying phase subject to these short bouts of profit-taking,'' jensen said, adding that he felt the market ``could regroup and work its way higher'' later
