harlan b. strong has seen his share of losers in his work for young america corp., one of the nation's largest handlers of sweepstakes, rebates and product promotions
but strong says it's the winners who stand out, especially when they're as excited as a detroit-area woman he called to inform that she and her family had won a trip to disney world
there was this long pause; then all i could hear was this blood-curdling scream,'' said strong, the company's vice president of sales
the woman put down the receiver and strong said he could hear her running through the house yelling the good news to her family for several minutes before returning to continue their conversation
i enjoyed that. it was a real honest expression of joy at receiving this,'' he said
nationally, there are about 40 companies in the fulfillment industry, which takes its name from its work fulfilling rebate requests and product promotions and conducting sweepstakes
young america corp. is one of five fulfillment companies in minnesota, and its closest national competitor, the maple plain co., is less than 20 miles away in maple plain
this is kind of the mecca of the fulfillment business,'' said strong
the 17-year-old young america corp. has grown from 15 employees to more than 1,000. that's nearly the population of this tiny town, from which the company took its patriotic-sounding name, 40 miles west of minneapolis
business became so brisk that the company had to acquire its own post office a few years ago to handle its up to 2 million pieces of mail a week, ranging from consumers' requests for duracell battery rebates to campbell soup bowls to sweepstakes entries
the 180,000-square-foot plant, which is completing its fourth expansion in 10 years, is highly automated, and that often surprises visitors, strong said
in one room, employees do nothing but feed envelopes into automatic slitting machines to open them
i think people think there are folks sitting around the table opening envelopes,'' strong said
that impression was closer to the reality of the company's earlier days when strong recalls executives taking off their coats and joining workers in packaging watches to keep product promotions on schedule
selecting winners from thousands of contest entries has grown more sophisticated, too
in the old days, we used to dump them on the floor,'' strong said
now, workers randomly select 2 percent to 10 percent of the entries received each day until the contest deadline and place them in numbered boxes. after the contest deadline, workers draw numbered pingpong balls from a lottery drum and then pick the winners from the corresponding numbered boxes of envelopes
but the prizes _ tvs, vcrs, furs and jewelry and other goodies small enough to be stored at the plant _ are still kept locked in a carefully guarded storage area
the privately held company, which does not disclose its financial figures, promotes its security when selling its services to its clients, mostly fortune 500 companies, by touting its computerized tracking of mail and products as they move through the company
the company installed a paper shredder more than two years ago to destroy mailed-in rebate forms after people began digging through landfills to retrieve other companies' discarded ones, strong said
he is proud of the company's record of employee honesty. young america corp. has never had to discipline a worker for trying to influence contest drawings or stealing rebate forms, strong said
young america corp. is the largest single employer in carver county, a dairy farming area that's beginning to give way to the suburban sprawl of the twin cities. many employees have been with the company for years, and up to 20 people a day apply for jobs there
if i left here to get a job with this kind of status and variety, i would have to go to minneapolis,'' said jan feltmann, a senior client service representative who began working for the company 14 years ago a few hours a day at home
i was a young mother and had a college loan to pay and i didn't want to have my husband pay for that,'' said mrs. feltmann, 35
company officials were so impressed with her work that they brought her to the plant, where she now supervises others
about 600 employees are home checkers and home data entry personnel, verifying customers' entries, rebates and order forms and typing the information for entry into the company's computer system, which is capable of canceling multiple requests from the same household
customer service, where 30 people respond to incomplete rebate forms and handle requests for exchanges on product promotions, also is a fast-growing segment. the employees answer toll-free numbers set up to handle customer inquiries. a wholly owned telemarketing subsidiary, young america direct in edina, was formed last year and already employs about 100 people. pictures</head>
a group of japanese gets off a bus chartered by hokubei tours inc. to gaze at the statue of liberty. but these far easterners are not mere picture-taking tourists _ they're entrepreneurs who want to own a piece of america, rather than just eyeball it
hokubei, whose most popular tour shuttles visitors to as many as five cities in pursuit of anything from a ski chalet to a factory to a wide-open prairie, is just one company catering to the swelling ranks of small japanese investors interested in u.s. property
big cash-rich corporations, like mitsui fudosan inc., which bought new york's exxon building in 1986, have been the biggest players in the u.s. market up to now, and experts say they'll likely dominate the $4 billion to $10 billion in purchases expected this year
but smaller investors also are making a mark, quietly traveling the nation, visiting with local business people and getting a feel for the landscape
a recent study by cushman &amp; wakefield, a major real estate company, found that japanese institutional investors rate real estate as their most important investment in the united states, well ahead of government bonds and corporate stock
the new wave of japanese buyers is being drawn to this country by high returns and comparatively cheap property. the average price per square foot for high-quality office space in tokyo is $4,000, while office space of similar quality in new york commands $400 per square foot or less, according to david shulman, director of real estate research at salomon brothers inc
lower interest rates and the dollar's drop against the japanese yen make such bargains too good to pass up for many japanese investors, who stand to reap yields three times higher than in their own country
with their penchant for savings, japanese who have amassed as little as $500,000 are realizing they can own a luxury condominium in the united states and pay someone else to manage it. more ambitious investors might join forces to buy a piece of commercial property
what may be equally noteworthy is that they also are ``spreading out from main-tier cities,'' shulman said. their interest no longer is exclusively focused on a handful of major urban areas
at los angeles-based hokubei, which specializes in promoting japanese-american business relationships, research manager charles laub said the company arranged 30 real estate tours last year and expects to do as many this year, if not more
during the planning stages of a trip, investors are asked what type of property they would like to see and in what geographic regions. then laub makes the appropriate real estate contacts, while others arrange for accommodations, transportation and interpreters
they won't just go to one city,'' he said. ``most want to see four or five cities.'' typically, he said, investors spend ``five to seven days in new york, then maybe they'll fly to chicago, then down to dallas, up to san francisco or los angeles. the whole thing could be two or three weeks.''
most often investors ask to see office buildings, although there is increasing interest in upscale residences like single-family homes or condominiums valued at a minimum $500,000, laub said
when on tour, ``it's all business'' from monday to friday, said laub, who added that arrangements can be made if travelers ``want to go play golf, or if they're in new york and want to go to the empire state building. some want to go to epcot center in florida.''
many of the tours laub arranges are sponsored by big japanese institutions like mitsui bank and nomura securities, which ultimately hope to serve as lenders if deals are consummated. independent investors, who usually travel in small groups, must foot the $3,000-to-$6,000 bill for a two-week trip on their own
on the first trip, they like to get a feel for the area,'' he said. actual deals are negotiated on subsequent visits
despite all the tours laub has arranged, he has no idea how many have actually resulted in definite sales agreements. ``they come in secretly to close on deals ... i don't know what is sold,'' he said
others also have discovered that real estate can be a common language when talking to the japanese
earl bunker, president of hori &amp; bunker inc. of lincoln, mass., puts out newsletters in japanese that list u.s. properties for sale. while several property owners complain of a lack of response to the ads, bunker insists that if he keeps on publishing, he'll penetrate the market
translation is very important,'' said bunker, adding that the japanese ``expect the same preferential treatment they've been giving us.''
cecil ivey, president of piping engineering co. of sand springs, okla., said he has had some nibbles from japanese interested in the shuttered welding plant he is trying to sell in alamo, texas. although he advertised with bunker, he said his contacts came from elsewhere
much foreign interest has centered on southern texas, where investors can cash in on the maquiladora concept, in which companies set up manufacturing facilities in mexico to take advantage of cheap labor while maintaining office operations just miles away in the united states
last year, a full busload of japanese descended upon the southern part of the lone star state, hitting ``every town on the border from laredo to brownsville,'' said peter pranis, who, as vice president of economic development for the council for south texas economic progress, played host when the group reached mcallen, texas
they're like information vacuum cleaners,'' he said. ``they're very courteous and well-mannered, but they've got a very good idea what they're looking for .... they asked very pointed questions.''
elsewhere, a developer who asked not to be named said japanese are among those interested in a package of two buildings that comprise an entire block in baltimore's prime business district
even dean williams, a retired salesman in las vegas, nev., spent a couple of hundred dollars on an ad to sell the 35 acres of land he owns in central nevada to the japanese. at $69,000 for the parcel, he thinks it's a bargain
the president of the nbc television network indicated nbc is unlikely to sell programming to turner broadcasting system inc.'s proposed new cable network, unless nbc owned a portion of the parent company
last year, nbc and tbs discussed the possibility of nbc taking part ownership of atlanta-based tbs. but the companies announced in mid-january that the talks had been halted
nbc president robert wright said monday the network would be interested in helping program the proposed turner network television only if it owned a piece of tbs
we could be very interested in selling programming to it, but i just don't see that happening,'' wright said after speaking to a civic group in atlanta. ``the problem with tnt is that it is very much involved in the organizational, ownership issues'' that blocked nbc's attempt to buy an interest in tbs last year, he added
nbc reportedly had attempted for the second time in three years to purchase up to 25 percent of tbs for $400 million
tbs is hoping to launch the new cable network in july. tnt is proposed as a super cable channel that would compete with the networks by offering first-run mini-series, award shows and major sporting events
arthur emil never envisioned traveling all the way to japan to sell some of the 54 luxury condominiums he developed in lower manhattan
and he was more than a little skeptical when japan's fujisankei communications group approached him about featuring one of the units on a home-shopping broadcast that would air in tokyo, osaka and nine other cities in late january
a fujisankei representative explained that the communications giant's satellite shopping network ``markets high-ticket items,'' emil said. ``they said they sold a chateau in france.''
and what could be more high-class than his condos, which range in price from $500,000 to $1.7 million and feature such amenities as sub-zero refrigerators in the gourmet kitchens, 17-foot ceilings and a 24-hour concierge in addition to the doorman
emil had a hard time with the notion that someone would buy an apartment without ``physically visiting the property,'' although he said it does happen from time to time
but fujisankei promised, after a single broadcast, to present him with 20 to 25 qualified buyers. ``i'm assuming these are real buyers,'' he said shortly before leaving for japan in early february
but 16,000 miles later and one week later, emil was a believer. ``you can sell apartments in the united states by television in japan,'' he exclaimed
while emil said fujisankei introduced him to fewer qualified buyers than promised, he was still pleased
none of the investors signed on the dotted line, but emil said several are coming to new york to see the landmark building in the near future, and he's confident he'll close on more than one deal
emil described the buyers as wealthy executives who do business in and around new york and were attracted by the building's luxury qualities
i expected a number of offshore buyers, but that i would schlep myself over to japan ...,'' he joked
fujisankei's january broadcast proved to be successful not only for emil. a limousine used by pope john xxiii also sold _ to an unnamed bidder for $423,000
japanese who invest in u.s. real estate evoke mixed emotions on this continent, angering americans competing to buy the same properties but pleasing sellers
they have come into the market with a tremendous new source of capital, and prices have gone up on the very small, upper-tier of properties they're interested in,'' said jon minikes, a managing director at jones, lang, wootton usa, an international real estate firm headquartered in new york
among those ``upper-tier'' properties are new york's exxon building, which was sold to mitsui fudosan for $610 million; the arco towers in los angeles, which sold for $620 million to shuwa investments corp.; and the equitable building in dallas, for which nissei realty paid $250 million
whenever more money is chasing a good product, prices have to go up. it's very simple economics,'' he said
but americans who expected to pay less for quality commercial property in major cities ``are upset with the japanese,'' said david shulman, director of real estate research at salomon brothers inc., while ``building sellers are very happy.''
shulman estimated that prices for quality office buildings could drop by as much as 10 percent to 15 percent if the japanese ceased buying property or became less aggressive in their purchases
japanese can afford to pay more because they are guaranteed to reap far greater yields in the united states than at home
for example, a $100 million investment in japan would probably yield 1 or 2 percent a year, said jim montinari, senior vice president of cushman &amp; wakefield, a national commercial real estate firm. yield is what investors earn after they subtract expenses from rent collected
but the yield on the same $100 million investment in u.s. real estate ``is certain to be 6 to 9 percent. comparing oppportunity to japan versus the united states is anywhere from triple to more,'' he said
in japan, high-quality commercial real estate appreciated between 50 percent and 60 percent in price from 1985 to 1986, shutting out potential investors from their domestic market and turning their attention to the united states, where prices for comparable properties rose about 15 percent, shulman said
the fall in the value of the dollar against the yen also has lured japanese investors, but a cheaper dollar can be ``a double-edged sword,'' minikes said
most japanese investors are looking at the rise in value of the yen as a way to make the purchase cheaper, but you realize that if the yen keeps rising, their investment _ which is generating u.s. dollars _ will show a lower yield, he explained
while some americans are miffed at the cash-rich japanese companies that are snapping up top properties at top dollar, real estate companies have adapted to serve a new market
we constantly have groups coming through who want us to tell them about u.s. real estate,'' minikes said. ``we regard them as a continuing source of profitable business.''
national westminster bank plc, britain's largest bank, said tuesday its profit sank 30.1 percent last year, mainly as a result of higher provisions against loans to latin american countries and heavy losses at its investment bank
the bank said its 1987 earnings totaled 429 million pounds, or $759 million, down from 614 million pounds, or $1.09 billion in 1986. on a per-share basis, that worked out to 57 pence, or $1 per share in 1987, compared with 94 pence, or $1.66 in 1986
the bank said its provisions against loans to lesser developed countries, including brazil, mexico and other latin american countries, now total 810 million pounds, or $1.43 billion _ 33 percent of its total exposure of 2.47 billion pounds, or $4.37 billion
natwest raised its provisions against loans to lesser developed countries to 30 percent last summer, and later by another 3 percent, to keep it within guidelines set up by the bank of england
natwest's international banking unit swung to a loss of 339 million pounds, or $600 million, from a profit of 223 million pounds, or $395 million, because of the increased provisions and the lower dollar
the group's investment banking division widened its loss to 116 million pounds, or $205 million last year, from 38 million pounds, or $67 million in 1986. natwest blamed continuing development costs and the effects of the october stock market's crash
national westminster bank usa had a loss of 95 million pounds, or $168 million, after increasing its provision for loans to lesser developed countries to 35 percent. that loss compared with a profit of 68 million pounds, or $120 million, in 1986
natwest said its results were encouraging in the light of the experience of banks worldwide in 1987
mcdonnell douglas corp. shoved aside two competitors last year to reclaim the title of the nation's largest defense contractor, the pentagon said tuesday
releasing its annual rating of the top 100 military contractors, the pentagon said mcdonnell douglas had jumped past general dynamics corp. and general electric co. to win the top ranking for fiscal 1987
the st. louis-based mcdonnell douglas increased its pentagon work by $1.1 billion during the year to a new total of $7.7 billion, easily surpassing general dynamics
general dynamics, ranked no. 1 in fiscal 1986 with $8 billion worth of contracts, fell to no. 2 in 1987 with work valued at $7 billion. general electric also suffered a decline in contract awards, falling from the $6.8 billion it won in 1986 to $5.8 billion in fiscal 1987, the pentagon said
the defense department report covers the fiscal year ending last sept. 30, and is considered the most definitive gauge of how major military contractors are faring each year
the report discloses that the pentagon's contractors were fighting over a smaller pie in fiscal 1987, with prime contracts totaling $142.5 billion being parceled out. that is $3.2 billion less than the total awarded in fiscal 1986
moreover, the top 100 companies, as a group, saw their share of those contracts decline slightly last year. the 100 firms received $95.4 billion of the contracts, or 66.9 percent of the total, compared to $98.6 billion and 67.7 percent in fiscal 1986
according to the rankings, there was only one company in the fiscal 1986 top 10 that failed to stay in that number last year. rockwell international corp., which is winding down its work on the new b-1b bomber, fell from fourth place on the 1986 list to 12th place in fiscal 1987 with contracts worth $2.2 billion
rockwell's spot in the top 10 was claimed by martin marietta corp., which moved from 11th to seventh place in the rankings with work totaling $3.7 billion
the other top 10 rankings involved the same companies as in 1986, but in a different order
the fourth largest defense contractor in 1987 was lockheed corp., which won contracts totaling $5.6 billion. it improved from sixth place the year before, when its military business totaled $4.9 billion
fifth in the rankings was general motors corp. with $4.1 billion. that was a decline from the $5.1 billion in work won by gm in 1986, but still enough to keep it at the same spot in the rankings
rounding out the top 10 were raytheon co., with $3.8 billion in contracts; martin marietta, with $3.7 billion; united technologies corp., with $3.6 billion; boeing co., with $3.5 billion, and grumman corp., with $3.4 billion
mcdonnell douglas' rise to the no. 1 spot is nothing new for the giant aircraft maker. while general dynamics was no. 1 in 1986, mcdonnell douglas was the top-ranked contractor in fiscal 1984 and fiscal 1985
some of the company's larger contracts include the f-a-18 hornet fighter for the navy; the f-15 eagle for the air force; the ah-64 apache helicopter gunship for the army, and the av-8b harrier jump jet for the marine corps
the stock market was drifting at modestly lower levels this afternoon as its recent rally ran into some resistance
trading was moderate
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, which jumped 25.70 points on monday to its highest level since jan. 7, was off 3.82 at 2,036.47 with two hours to go in the session
declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of nearly 4 to 3 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 677 up, 816 down and 441 unchanged
volume on the big board came to 147.77 million shares as of 2 p.m. on wall street with 109.87 million shares at the same point on monday
traders said the market seemed to pause after a sharp runup over the past two weeks
they said traders were also looking for clues in federal reserve chairman alan greenspan's testimony to a congressional panel about the central bank's view of the economy
the stock market has benefited recently from indications that the economy may be stronger than had been expected, leading some analysts to take an optimistic view of the outlook for corporate profits
but there is plenty of uncertainty about the economy's prospects
in a new report today, the government said orders to u.s. factories for durable goods plunged 2.8 percent in january, the biggest decline in a year
many analysts had expected a decline in january, however, because orders had risen by an unusually large 4.1 percent in december
