finance minister edouard balladur indicated monday he was opposed to the planned sale of the french financial newspaper les echos to pearson plc of britain, saying he won't allow the transfer of ownership to proceed automatically
in a statement, balladur said the 886 million franc, or $158 million, deal that was signed jan. 11 between pearson and les echo owner jacqueline beytout ``is subject to the explicit authorization of the french authorities.''
mrs. beytout called the government's position ``exclusively political,'' and the management of les echos said the newspaper wouldn't publish on tuesday in protest
under regulations, takeovers involving french companies and other european entities must be submitted for approval by the french treasury. if no objection is raised after a two-month period, the transaction goes ahead automatically
the ministry noted, however, that a 1986 press law stipulates that individuals or corporate entities that don't reside in the european community can't acquire a stake of more than 20 percent in the capital of a french publishing company without prior government approval
the ministry said ``the european character of the pearson group doesn't appear to be durably established at this time.''
ministry officials said the main stumbling block to the sale is the 20.5 percent stake in pearson held by media magnate rupert murdoch
news corp, murdoch's australian press group, disclosed jan. 13 that it had increased its stake in pearson by purchasing a 4.9 percent block of shares from cerus sa, the french investment arm of italian financier carlo de benedetti
aides to balladur said the government is concerned that murdoch might be tempted to seek a controlling interest in pearson, although murdoch has denied any such plans.   
the supreme court ruled unanimously tuesday that businesses may not be sued in federal court in certain cases involving their contributions to union benefit funds
the court said the federal courts have no authority over cases in which companies refuse to contribute to multi-employer union benefit funds after a collective bargaining agreement expires
in an 8-0 ruling in a case from california, the court rejected reagan administration arguments that barring lawsuits in such cases could undermine the solvency of the multi-employer pension plans
justice john paul stevens, in his opinion for the court, noted that in 1980 congress amended the employee retirement income security act (erisa) to provide a federal court remedy for trustees of the multi-employer benefit plans to collect delinquent contributions
but stevens said the remedy does not extend to ``the employer's statutory duty to make post-contract contributions while negotiations for a new contract are being conducted.''
the federal courts have no authority to determine whether an employer's refusal to contribute to the funds in such circumstances is a violation of the national labor relations act, stevens said
the case stems from a decision by advanced lightweight concrete company inc. in california to withdraw from the union funds on june 15, 1983, when its collective bargaining agreement with its workers expired
the fund managers filed a federal court suit in december that year, seeking to force the company to pay into the pension plans for the period when the old contract expired until bargaining talks over a new contract reached an impasse
the unions said erisa conferred such jurisdiction on the courts
the suit was dismissed on grounds that the national labor relations board has final say. the nlrb had ruled against the unions in november 1983, rejecting claims that advance lightweight failed to bargain in good faith
today's decision upheld a 1985 ruling by the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals
justice anthony m. kennedy, who joined the high court on thursday, did not take part in the decision
the case is welfare trust fund vs. advanced lightweight concrete, 85-2079
in other cases tuesday involving business:
_the court limited the job protection for government workers fired for lacking security clearances
by a 5-3 vote, the justices agreed with the reagan administration that the merit systems protection board lacks authority to decide whether the denial of security clearance is justified
the court ruled against thomas e. egan, who was hired in 1981 as a laborer at the trident naval refit facility in bremerton, wash., on the condition he subsequently receive a security clearance
the facility is used to test and repair trident submarines. all jobs at the facility require security clearance
_the court, in a victory for three midwestern states, limited the secretary of the interior's authority to allocate water stored in missouri river basin reservoirs
the justices ruled unanimously that the interior secretary exceeded his authority when in 1982 he approved a contract authorizing energy transportation systems inc. (etsi) to take water from lake oahe in south dakota for a coal slurry pipeline project
the decision is a victory for officials in missouri, iowa and nebraska, which had blocked the now-scrapped pipeline project. north dakota, south dakota and wyoming took the other side
_the court rejected claims by private landowners and ruled that the state of mississippi owns thousands of acres of oil- and gas-rich land near the state's gulf coast
by a 5-3 vote, the justices said states may claim title to land beneath waters subject to the tie's influence _ and not only land under navigable waters
the ebb and flow of the tide, not navigability, determines the state's ownership, justice byron r. white said for the court. minister</note>
italian financier carlo de benedetti and belgium's economics minister on tuesday called for a truce in the battle for control of societe generale de belgique s.a., the country's biggest holding company
representative shareholders have to sit down at the table to discuss clear-cut principles: an industrial plan, the modalities of efficient management and a revitalization of the company,'' de benedetti said in a statement
de benedetti, the largest independent stockholder, claims to own 43 percent of societe generale's 28.2 million shares outstanding. he has launched a bid for another 15 percent, but the stock price has since exceeded his offer of about 4,000 belgian francs
societe generale hit a new record tuesday, closing at 5,350 francs, or $152.80, up about $7.15 from monday
de benedetti held meetings tuesday with several top government officials, including minister of economy philippe maystadt, caretaker prime minister wilfried martens and vice-premiers guy verhofstadt and philippe maystadt
de benedetti wants to create a pan-european holding company, but the belgian government has maintained it wants societe generale to remain firmly anchored in belgium. the 166-year-old company controls about half of belgium's top 50 companies and has interests in more that 1,200 companies worldwide
as speculation mounts as to whether a brittle alliance of belgian and french financial groups could fend off de benedetti, the italian financier called for a truce
as the most important shareholder by a wide margin, i want to make an appeal to reason,'' de benedetti said. ``there have been enough maneuvers in the corridors, enough artificial coalitions, enough unrealistic share counts, enough projects inspired only on the basis of personal interest.''
maystadt also said that it would be ``desirable that all concerned parties without exception at last sit down around the same table.''
the french cie financiere de suez and about 18 belgian companies claim to hold more than 50 percent of societe generale's shares, but they have not officially agreed to form an alliance
societe generale management has supported a franco-belgian alliance
the british government said tuesday it would relinquish its ``golden share'' in britoil plc, removing a major roadblock to british petroleum co. plc's $4.4 billion acquisition of the north sea oil company
since december, bp has accumulated 79.8 percent of britoil's 504 million outstanding shares in a takeover bid priced at 2.5 billion pounds. the oil giant has been paying 500 pence, or $8.85, for each britoil share
the government retained its special share _ which gives it a controlling vote over the company's affairs _ when it privatized britoil in two stages in 1985 and 1982
the treasury said it would give up the share under certain conditions agreed to by bp
britoil said its board of directors would meet to decide whether to abandon its resistance to bp's offer
britoil's shares rose 1.77 cents to finish at $8.83 (499 pence) on the london stock exchange tuesday. bp's shares finished unchanged at $4.39 (248 pence)
the government doesn't intend to exercise its special share as long as bp upholds promises to maintain headquarters for some of britoil's operations in glasgow, scotland, and meet other conditions, chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson said in answer to questions in the house of commons
scottish politicians had expressed concern that the takeover would mean the loss of jobs in scotland
lawson said control of the golden share will eventually be transferred from the treasury to britain's energy department, where legal moves will be taken to terminate it
an acceptable arrangement has been reached with bp,'' lawson said. ``i am quite sure there will be no backsliding by bp.''
bp chairman peter walters said in a statement that the company was ``pleased that our discussions with the government have produced a successful resolution of the issues surrounding the special share.''
we believe the outcome will enable us to manage the assets of britoil on a proper commercial basis in the interests of both our shareholders and the u.k. economy,'' walters said
but a britoil spokesman, who asked not to be named, said, ``if you look at the statements (by the government and bp) you'll see it's a two-party agreement between the chancellor and bp.''
although britoil officials met with treasury officials concerning the government's use of the golden share, the company wasn't a party to the agreement, he said
labor lawmaker john smith, his party's treasury spokesman, said in the house of commons that bp had ``gobbled up'' britoil and told lawson: ``you have exacted precious little from bp in exchange for handing britoil to them on a plate.''
atlantic richfield co. of los angeles also had pursued britoil, but abandoned its attempt and sold its 24 percent britoil holding to bp last month after bp sweetened its december offer of $7.97 (450 pence) a share
meanwhile, the kuwaiti government, through its london-based investment vehicle, the kuwait investment office, has acquired a stake of more than 19 percent in bp over the last few months
here are the conditions to which lawson said bp has agreed:
_bp will locate both britoil's and bp's north sea exploration and production head offices in glasgow, where britoil currently has its headquarters. the office will control bp's exploration and productio operations in norway and the republic of ireland, as well as in britain
_britoil will be managed and operated as a separate independent subsidiary and will have its own chief executive
_the britoil board is to be headed by a non-executive chairman with no previous bp connections. the appointment will be a joint agreement between bp and the government
bp also agreed to try to achieve an increase of at least 5 percent in recoverable reserves from britoil's north sea oil fields
bp will spend between $531 million and $575 million a year on exploration and development in areas controlled by bp and britoil, a large increase over previous expenditures in the area. index; no pickup</note>
share prices closed higher in london tuesday, but were down sharply from their best levels in concert with weak early trading on wall street
trading volume picked up from its recent slack pace as some good institutional buying interest emerged, dealers said
the financial times-stock exchange 100-share index finished at 1,757.9, 10.7 points or 0.6 percent higher, just 1.2 points above its lowest level for the day. the index rose as much as 25 points in early trading, bolstered by strong gains overnight in the new york and tokyo stock markets
the strong tone was reinforced by news that britain's real gross domestic product rose 1 percent in the fourth quarter of 1987 from the third quarter and was up 5.3 percent from a year earlier
share prices showed little reaction to the gdp news, but dealers said the figures should help sustain a cautious optimism among market participants
dealers said another factor boosting the market was expectations that substantial tax cuts would be included in the budget to be presented next month by the thatcher government
chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson said the government has agreed to give up its golden share in britoil plc, clearing the way for the independent company's takeover by british petroleum co. plc. britoil shares rose 1 penny to 499 pence, while bp was unchanged at 248 pence
stocks traded at modestly lower prices this afternoon as the market's recent rally ran into some resistance
trading was moderate
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, which jumped 25.70 points on monday to its highest level since jan. 7, was off 8.29 at 2,032.00 with one hour to go in the session
declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of about 4 to 3 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 669 up, 846 down and 436 unchanged
volume on the big board came to 165.28 million shares as of 3 p.m. on wall street with 131.66 million shares at the same point on monday
traders said the market was pausing after a sharp runup over the past two weeks
they said traders were hesitant to make big moves while federal reserve chairman alan greenspan was testifying before a congressional panel about the central bank's view of the economy
the stock market has benefited recently from indications that the economy may be stronger than had been expected, leading some analysts to take an optimistic view of the outlook for corporate profits
but there is plenty of uncertainty about the economy's prospects
in a new report today, the government said orders to u.s. factories for durable goods plunged 2.8 percent in january, the biggest decline in a year
many analysts had expected a decline in january, however, because orders had risen by an unusually large 4.1 percent in december
among the most active issues on the nyse were several utility stocks that will soon be paying dividends. philadelphia electric was the most active, and was unchanged at 19~
among the blue chips, eastman kodak was down \ at 40{, american telephone &amp; telegraph was down \ at 29| and international business machines was off \ at 115
moore mccormack climbed 10{ to 34] after southdown disclosed it was offering $31 a share for the company
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks was off 0.86 at 148.10. at the american stock exchange, the market value index fell 0.89 to 282.12
grain and soybean futures prices closed moderately lower tuesday on the chicago board of trade
wheat futures declined in reaction to the agriculture department's announcement late monday that it would replace its weekly auctions of surplus wheat with three weekly auctions beginning march 2, analysts said
sales from the friday auctions have declined in recent weeks, with last week's total of 11 million bushels falling far short of the target of 25 million bushels
the usda set initial targets of 10 million bushels for each of the three new auctions, which will be held on tuesdays, wednesdays and fridays
traders fear that the new auctions could put as much as 30 million additional bushels of wheat onto the open market, which would tend to depress prices, said jerry gidel, an analyst for g.h. miller &amp; co
soybean prices retreated in response to improved growing conditions for the south american soybean crop, gidel said. corn futures drifted lower due to a lack of fresh supportive news, he said
at the close, wheat was 4} cents to 5\ cents lower with the contract for delivery in march at $3.17 a bushel; corn was 2{ cents to 3{ cents lower with march at $1.96 a bushel; oats were 1 cent lower to \ cent higher with march at $1.90\ a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents to 8{ cents lower with march at $6.20 a bushel
a computer magazine has published a story providing confidential details of a long-awaited apple computer still under development
the article appearing in this week's edition of macintosh today was based on a 160-page confidential in-house document given to a free-lance writer by an apple employee, the san francisco examiner said tuesday
the article details the size, appearance and technical specifications of apple computer inc.'s laguna laptop model, which it said would be available in 1989
apple has been hard hit by information leaks before, and even hired a private detective two years ago to find out who was releasing information. the investigator found leaks at firms developing software and accessories for apple products, according to company spokeswoman barbara krause
ms. krause declined to comment on the magazine report
the article describes a 12-pound laptop capable of running macintosh software. it said the computer would have 1 megabyte of internal memory, the same as the macintosh se. it said the computer would have a flat-panel screen and be powered by a five-pound lead-acid battery that will last up to 10 hours before recharging
foreign ministers of the european economic community on monday formally adopted decisions taken at last week's eec summit on limiting farm subsidies and overhauling the group's finances
britain and the netherlands had made their acceptance of the summit agreement conditional on settlement of a relatively minor issue raised by france in the final stages of the feb. 11-12 meeting
officials said the french foreign minister, jean-bernard raimond, told monday's meeting that his government remained unhappy with proposals for placing new controls on eec subsidies to growers of such products as tobacco and wine
but raimond said paris would allow the proposals to go forward without further debate. that cleared the way for the foreign ministers to formally adopt the overall summit agreement
by satisfying british and dutch demands for strict limits on farm spending, the summit accords marked a breakthrough in the eec's budget crisis. the 12-nation group has been operating without a formal budget since the start of the year and faced possible bankruptcy by late summer
eec budget ministers are scheduled to meet tuesday to adopt a draft 1988 budget. the spending plan then must be approved by the european parliament
hans-dietrich genscher, the west german foreign minister and chairman of monday's meeting, told reporters that adoption of the summit agreement was ``an important step forward in the history of the european community.''
genscher said he and chancellor helmut kohl told u.s. officials during a visit to washington last week that the summit agreement will ``strengthen the economic vitality of europe'' by permitting faster removal of trade barriers between eec member countries and by giving more financial aid to the relatively poorer members in southern europe. market changes</head>
the head of the securities and exchange commission said tuesday he did not expect congress to give the agency control of the stock index futures market and stressed the sec is working with futures regulators to prevent a recurrence of the october stock market crash
sec chairman david s. ruder also indicated his agency was examining ways of reducing volatility of stock prices and trading volume, which he attributed partly to the use of margin in the stock index futures markets
in a speech to an economic outlook conference sponsored by the conference board, ruder repeated his agency's call to examine proposals for increasing coordination between the stock and futures markets and expanding the markets' capacity to deal with unprecedented trading volumes
trading strategies involving stock index futures _ representing ``baskets'' of actual stocks _ have been widely blamed for worsening market volatility and contributing to the severity of the oct. 19 market crash
ruder has contended the sec should have final regulatory power over all stock-related instruments, including the ability to overrule the commodity futures trading commission, which now regulates such products
in testimony to the senate banking committee earlier this month, ruder asked for broad new powers over stock-related futures trading, such as increasing margin requirements and ordering temporary trading halts, to help prevent a recurrence of the crash
kalo hineman, acting chairman of the commodities commission, in subsequent testimony resisted the idea of putting the sec in charge of stock index futures trading
during a news conference after tuesday's speech, ruder defended his proposal but said he did not anticipate congressional support for sec authority over stock index futures markets
he said that although he was not supporting a broad congressional revamping of the regulatory system, the sec's proposals would result in ``a more active and aggressive oversight of those markets'' by his agency
that at times could entail pressuring the commodities commission to make market changes, ruder said. but he also said he expected any future regulation to stem from ``cooperative'' proposals, and emphasized his agency's commitment to work closely with other regulators
ruder said he and the sec staff had met with hineman and the staff of the commodities commission to discuss ``a wide range of market-related topics.''
similar joint discussions were held with representatives of the stock and futures exchanges and would continue as the sec attempted to formulate concrete steps for preventing another crash, ruder said
in his speech, ruder again called for higher margin requirements _ the ``down payment'' a buyer must make _ for trading stock index futures and for other measures to improve liquidity in the futures markets. he said the sec would continue considering the effectiveness of delayed futures market openings
ruder said the ``increased velocity and concentration'' of trading within the stock and futures markets and between those markets had increased the probability of wild price swings. he said the increased intensity of trading was due partly to the lower margin levels in the futures markets
initial margin on stock inedex futures for non-market makers should be raised, at least temporarily, to levels harmonious with stock margin levels applicable to stock market professionals,'' he said
the stock market marked time today, finishing narrowly mixed as its recent rally ran into some resistance
analysts said the market had paused after a two-week rally that had driven some major indicators to their highest levels in six weeks
they said traders also appeared hesitant to make a major move while federal reserve chairman alan greenspan was outlining for a congressional panel the central bank's monetary goals and his view of the economy
the analysts found little in greenspan's remarks to encourage them to bid stocks in either direction
the stock market has benefited recently from indications that the economy may be stronger than had been expected, leading some analysts to take an optimistic view of the outlook for corporate profits
but there is plenty of uncertainty about the economy's prospects
in a new report today, the government said orders to u.s. factories for durable goods plunged 2.8 percent in january, the biggest decline in a year
but a decline had been expected in the wake of an unusually sharp 4.1 percent rise in december
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, which rose 25.70 on monday to its highest level since jan. 7, lost 1.17 to 2,039.12
advancing issues narrowly outpaced losers among those listed on the new york stock exchange, with 760 up, 720 down and 482 unchanged
big board volume totaled 192.26 million shares, against 178.93 million in the previous session
the nyse's composite index fell 0.23 to 148.73
at the american stock exchange, the market value index was off 0.29 at 282.72
