firestone tire &amp; rubber co. reported a 27 percent drop in first-quarter earnings monday, but noted results for the year-earlier period were inflated by a $20 million gain from discontinued operations
firestone reported earnings of $30 million or 94 cents a share, on sales of $976 million for the three months ended jan. 31, compared with earnings of $41 million or $1.07 a share on sales of $846 million during the same period a year ago
excluding a one-time gain of $20 million from the december 1986 sale of its north american wheel and rim business, firestone's first-quarter earnings were up 40 percent from a year earlier
the results reflected improved automotive parts and service sales, increased income from credit-card operations, and larger profits from the company's diverisified-products operations due to higher natural-rubber prices and improved building-products sales, firestone said in a news release
during the quarter, firestone repurchased 3.6 million shares of its outstanding stock for $116 million
firestone, which moved its headquarters from akron, ohio, to chicago during the quarter, announced last week it would sell a 75 percent interest in its tire-manufacturing operations to bridgestone corp. for $1.25 billion
pan am corp. and the union representing 4,500 ground employees in 14 cities deadlocked following the breakup of their talks as a teamsters official threatened ``guerrilla warfare.''
william genoese, director of the teamsters' airline division, threatened monday that employees meanwhile would deliberately misdirect baggage and cargo and cancel passengers' reservations
talks in which management was seeking $35 million in concessions from the union broke down sunday afternoon following expiration of the contract. no talks were held monday
flight attendants at northwest airlines have voted overwhelmingly to strike the airline this weekend if a contract dispute over wages and benefits is not resolved, a union official says
disclosure of the strike vote came monday as the two sides readied to resume negotiations for the first time since last month
jeff musto, a teamsters spokesman, said 94.4 percent of the more than 5,000 attendants participating voted to strike
l.f. rothschild holdings inc., an investment firm staggered by october's stock market crash, will merge with a subsidiary of franklin savings corp., a financial services company based in ottawa, kan
rothschild, which also announced a $128.8 million loss for the final quarter of 1987, previously had sold virtually all of its retail stock brokerage operations and slashed its payroll
the purchase price, still subject to adjustment, was about $66.4 million, rothschild said monday
first republicbank corp. has run full-page advertisements in local newspapers blaming shrinking deposits on seasonal factors and foreign withdrawals and repeating denials that it was involved in merger or bailout negotiations
the bank's actions monday were designed to allay depositors' fears raised by its report last month of a $656.8 million annual loss. it said news reports on its financial condition were wrong or misleading
dissident investor henley group inc. has proposed that santa fe southern pacific corp. scrap part of its financial restructuring and instead sell $780 million in new stock to henley
the move monday, which would boost henley's stake in chicago-based santa fe to 34.3 percent from 15.7 percent, was expected to receive a cool reaction from santa fe, which has been fending off henley's unwanted overtures since mid-1987
santa fe directors will take up the plan at a regularly scheduled board meeting tuesday, spokesman robert gehrt said
rio grande industries inc. has filed an application with the interstate commerce commission to acquire southern pacific transportation co. for $1 billion from santa fe southern pacific corp
rio grande's action monday will affect kansas city southern industries inc.'s rival bid of more than $1.25 billion for the southern pacific
the icc is expected to decide on the application in six months, rio grande said
a federal judge has blocked as unconstitutional an ohio takeover statute aimed at thwarting campeau corp.'s attempted hostile takeover of federated department stores inc
toronto-based campeau has a hostile $5.4 billion offer pending for cincinnati-based federated. campeau is offering $5.8 billion if federated agrees to a friendly merger
state officials have not decided whether to appeal monday's ruling, a spokesman said
the federal government posted a rare $16.09 billion surplus last month, primarily because social security checks for january were mailed early, the treasury department says
the early payment inflated government spending in december and lowered spending in january, the department said monday. the december deficit was $24.22 billion
for all of 1988, the reagan administration is projecting the budget deficit will fall to $146.74 billion, down 2.5 percent from last year's deficit of $150.4 billion
the reagan administration has confirmed it is investigating allegations that a u.s. computer system which could help determine optimal targets for nuclear missiles had been illegally shipped to the soviet union
according to a report in monday editions of the washington times, essex marketing co. of los angeles is under investigation for an alleged shipment dec. 21 of the computer to an engineering college in zagreb, yugoslovia
the computer was diverted and wound up in the soviet union instead, the newspaper said
the supreme court has upheld a ruling that sharply curtails the power of communities to regulate cable television
the high court turned away an appeal by palo alto and atherton, calif., which wanted to enforce public access and other rules challenged by cable operator century federal inc
but the court's action apparently was based on narrow procedural grounds and leaves open the possibility of a subsequent appeal
a survey of 226 large and medium-sized american companies found 70 percent have restricted or are prepared to limit smoking in the workplace
i was really surprised at the extent to which this had surfaced as a personnel issue,'' victor lindquist, author of the northwestern university lindquist-endicott report, said monday
the stock market gained broadly monday, extending its recent rally in a mood of increasing optimism about the economic outlook. the dow jones average of 30 industrials climbed 25.70 to 2,040.29
bond prices finished modestly higher. the yield on the treasury's closely watched 30-year issue, which moves inversely to its price, slipped to 8.41 percent from 8.43 percent late friday
the dollar drifted lower. gold prices were narrowly mixed
