a federal judge has issued a temporary injunction blocking eastman kodak co.'s deal to merge its photofinishing operations with those of fuqua industries inc., and the company continues to face questions about its $5.1 billion acquisition of sterling drug inc
kodak announced tuesday that it had been tendered more than 96 percent of sterling shares during the offering period that expired monday, and said it expected to complete the acquisition in a few days
the company has scheduled a meeting with analysts thursday in new york in an effort to convince them of the merits of the sterling deal
kodak's stock rose 50 cents a shre to $41.25 a share tuesday in consolidated new york stock exchange trading. fuqua's stock fell 50 cents a share to $28.50
in the fuqua dispute, u.s. district judge eldon mahon in fort worth, texas, issued his ruling monday in response to a suit filed in december by phototron corp., a san bernardino, calif., wholesale photofinishing company
the suit contended that if the proposed merger went through, kodak and fuqua would control 50 percent of the wholesale photofinishing industry and 80 percent of the total market for photo-related paper and chemicals, said brenda landry, an analyst for morgan stanley and co
the injunction will remain in effect pending a trial on the merits of the case
fuqua spokeswoman donna browning, in arguments supporting the merger, said the merger would result in a new company controlling only 25 percent of the total photofinishing market in the united states
the federal trade commission and the u.s. department of justice antitrust division approved the proposed merger in december and said their investigation did not show any evidence that federal antitrust laws would be violated
on dec. 7, kodak announced plans to merge its wholesale photoprocessing laboratories with fuqua's raleigh, n.c.-based subsidiary, colorcraft corp
several financial analysts have lowered their opinions of kodak in recent weeks on grounds that the company overpaid for sterling
obviously there are pros and cons to this,'' said michael ellmann, a stock analyst with wertheim schroeder &amp; co. ``but i want to hear what management has to say.''
kodak will pay $89.50 for 54.5 million of the 57 million outstanding shares of sterling stock, more than $34 higher than the stock was selling for at the end of 1987. the company will acquire the 2.5 million shares that weren't offered for sale for the same price after the deal is final, roberts said
the total value of the deal is expected to be $5.1 billion
sterling, based in new york, has 22,000 employees and has annual sales of about $2 billion
kodak, based in rochester, has 124,000 employees and annual sales of about $13 billion a year
the acquisition will help kodak move into the $110 billion pharmaceutical industry and give the company an established pipeline to get drugs to market, said kodak spokesman charles smith
on monday, kodak's bond ratings were downgraded by moody's investors service from a2 to aa2 largely because of the heavy borrowing needed to pay for sterling
sterling's bond rating was also downgraded from a2 to aa1
with the acquisition, kodak will immediately realize its ambition of being a billion-dollar-a-year drug company through bayer aspirin, panadol non-aspirin pain reliever, and demerol
kodak will also get a billion-dollar-a-year household products business with such products as lysol disinfectant, d-con rat killer, and phillips milk of magnesia
kodak officials have said they do not plan to sell any parts of sterling and will keep the company's organization intact
the united states announced tuesday that it was supplying $500 million in short-term financing to argentina while the south american country works out arrangements for a longer-term loan with the international monetary fund
the treasury department announced the loan, which would be the second such borrowing argentina has done in the past five months
in november, argentina received another $500 million bridge loan from the united states and 14 other countries which it paid back in january after it received further money from the imf
the treasury said in a statement, ``the willingness of the united states to provide this financing indicates our support for argentina's economic program to achieve sustainable growth and a viable balance-of-payments position.''
the statement said the united states ``commends argentina's efforts to implement stabilization and reform policies with the support of the international financial community.''
news corp. ltd., the worldwide media company controlled by rupert murdoch, said tuesday its profit climbed 45 percent in its second fiscal quarter as its revenue rose 33 percent
the company, based in sydney, australia, cited strong performances by its newspaper division in britain and its magazine division in australia and the pacific basin, including results from acquisitions
it said profits declined in the united states, reflecting a soft advertising market for its seven television stations, disappointing results from the newspaper division including the new york post and lower results from twentieth century fox films
news corp. said its profit rose to $127 million, or 79 cents per american depositary receipt, in the three months ended dec. 31 compared with $87.6 million, or 64 cents per adr, a year earlier
the adrs are traded on the new york stock exchange and each adr represents two of the company's common shares
revenue for the quarter rose to $1.11 billion from $837 million a year earlier
for the first six months, profit nearly doubled to $231.2 million, or $1.42 per adr, from $120 million, or 88 cents per adr, a year earlier
revenue for the first six months rose 26 percent, to $2.09 billion from $1.66 billion in 1986
six-month results were helped by foreign-exchange trading gains and acquisitions in australia and the pacific basin
last weekend, murdoch won concessions from the new york post's labor unions that cleared the way for the sale of the ailing newspaper to real estate developer peter kalikow for $37 million
kraft inc. will pay ambrit inc. $8.5 million to settle a trademark battle over similar ice cream bars made by the two companies, kraft announced tuesday
the 6-year-old case stemmed from kraft's polar b'ar ice cream bars, which ambrit contended were packaged in a manner that infringed on the trademark of its own klondike bar
the supreme court last may let stand a lower court ruling prohibiting polar b'ar from using a wrapper resembling the klondike package and denying polar b'ar exclusive trademark rights to that name
the 11th u.s. circuit court of appeals had ruled in december 1986 that polar b'ars may not have images of polar bears on their wrappers in imitation of the klondike design
the appeals court also said polar b'ars may have the color royal blue on their silver foil wrappers only if it did not make them ``confusingly similar'' to the klondike wrapper
the appeals court also had ordered a federal judge to determine what damages if any kraft must pay ambrit, which is based in clearwater, fla., for imitating the klondike wrapper
kraft said from its glenview, ill., headquarters that the settlement was ``significantly less'' than the amount sought by ambrit but declined to comment further, citing agreements by both parties not to discuss specifics of the case
the appeals court had canceled kraft's polar b'ar trademark because the company had abandoned the name from 1932, when it stopped making a like-named ice cream novelty, until it began marketing a new ice cream bar in 1979
southdown inc., a cement and energy company, launched a $177 million cash tender offer tuesday for moore mccormack resources of stamford, conn
the offer is contingent on the valid tender of a majority of moore mccormack's common stock, the inapplicability of delaware's recently enacted anti-takeover law, the redemption or invalidation of moore mccormack's ``poison pill'' anti-takeover defense and southdown's ability to secure $635 million in financing, of which $500 million has been committed by a major commercial bank
tony doumlele, director of corporate relations for moore mccormack, said the ``tender offer was totally unsolicited.''
on monday, houston-based southdown and its subsidiary, sdw inc., filed a federal lawsuit which seeks to overturn moore mccormack's anti-takeover defenses, including a poison pill provision that would make the acquisition prohibitively expensive
the lawsuit claims that moore mccormack chairman paul r. tregurtha tried to illegally block the tender offer
southdown said in the suit that it will offer $31 a share for moore mccormack, a building materials company. with 5.7 million moore mccormack shares outstanding, the transaction would be worth about $177 million
southdown said in its suit that unless the anti-takeover defenses are removed, it will be deprived of the right to make a bona fide offer and will be subjected to confusion, delay and lawsuits
the suit said tregurtha and moore mccormack's board of directors violated their fiduciary responsibilities by setting up illegal obstacles that allegedly will prevent the company's shareholders from considering the tender offer
the suit also said that merger talks between the two companies were initiated by moore mccormack a year ago and that tregurtha insisted that he hold the posts of chairman and chief executive officer in the combined business. as a result, southdown said, it concluded that its only alternative was to take a proposal directly to the shareholders of moore mccormack
southdown produces and sells cement and ready-mixed concrete and is in oil and gas exploration and development. it announced monday that it has 137.6 billion cubic feet of proved natural gas reserves, up from 111.7 billion cubic feet last year. it attributed the increase to successful exploration in louisiana and texas
moore mccormack produces building materials and is also involved in oil and gas exploration and production, mainly in texas and louisiana
no hearing has been set for the case, assigned to u.s. district judge lynn n. hughes
the dollar firmed against the japanese yen in foreign exchange dealings in tokyo wednesday after a sharp decline the previous day, while share prices on the tokyo stock exchange were mixed
the dollar opened at 128.90 yen, up 0.40 yen from tuesday's close of 128.50 yen. in midmorning dealings, the u.s. currency traded between 128.65 and 128.90 yen
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues, which rose tuesday for the ninth consecutive trading day, took on an additional 0.09 points to end wednesday's morning session at 24,949.54
foreign exchange dealers said the market didn't respond to comments by u.s. federal reserve chairman alan greenspan, who told a u.s. congressional committee tuesday that there were no signs of a recession in the united states
stock trading was described as mixed by traders, who said buyers were not as aggressive after nine straight days of solid gains in the market
the morning volume was estimated at 700 million shares, a level approaching tuesday's all-day volume of 850 million shares
